<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MoneyBags 1stLd-Writethru a1038 03-09 0655</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Money Bags, 1st Ld - Writethru, a1038,0670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Over $700,000 Still Missing After Armored Car Dumps Loot</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with woman turning money in;
PICKS UP 4th graf pvs, `Investigators were ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVE CARPENTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police warned Wednesday that jail sentences
may await opportunists who made off with more than $700,000 after
an armored car accidentally dumped a crateful of cash in the
street, sparking a mad scramble for the loot.
   Three to five people who were driving or walking by when the
truck dropped a reported $771,000 in an industrial area Tuesday
scooped up clear plastic bags full of cash and sped off. Only
$40,100 was recovered, police said.
   ``We've only had one honest man so far,'' said Lt. Barry
Johnson. A TV repairman picked up two bags containing $20,050 each
and took them straight to the nearby offices of Loomis Armored Inc.
   Late Wednesday, a woman identified only as a 30-year-old postal
worker turned gave police two clear plastic bags containing a total
of $28,000.
   ``She said she picked up the money and then got kind of scared,
so she decided to turn it in,'' said Sgt. William Herndon.
   Investigators were tracing license plate numbers and vehicle
descriptions reported by witnesses and trying to compile a list of
the lost bills' serial numbers.
   ``If they turn it in, the company is considering a reward,''
said Johnson. ``The alternative is we trace them down and they go
to jail. It's their choice.''
   The opportunistic motorists or pedestrians could face felony
charges of grand theft if they took $500 or more, police said.
   A spokesman for Oakland-based Loomis declined to comment on the
accident, which occurred at 3:40 p.m. on a busy thoroughfare in the
Potrero District, adjacent to the low-income Hunter's Point
neighborhood that has been plagued by rock-throwing and violence
against city buses this year.
   The armored truck, filled with more than $1.7 million collected
from 20 banks in the San Francisco Bay area, was headed for Loomis'
offices from downtown.
   Johnson said the driver claimed the rear door had been locked,
but the dolly containing a crate of bills slammed against it and
somehow forced it open.
   The driver, whose name was not disclosed, did not learn of the
mishap until a honking motorist pointed it out 2{ blocks away.
   Before the driver could return, a crowd gathered around the
fallen bags. Some people put the money back into the crate and
others hung onto it, including one man who tossed numerous bags
into his pickup truck and drove off despite the urgings of
bystanders.
   ``It was a free-for-all,'' police Officer Harry Soulette, who
was at the scene, told the San Francisco Examiner. ``People were
throwing bags of bills into their cars and taking off. It was
wild.''
   Police declined to be specific Wednesday about the amount
involved, saying only that it was more than $500,000. The Examiner
reported that $771,000 in $10, $20 and $50 bills fell out of the
truck while close to $1 million remained inside.
   The money is ``potentially traceable,'' Johnson said.
   Police said the driver was not a suspect.
   ``We're looking at every possibility, but there doesn't appear
to have been any collusion at this point,'' Johnson said.
   Repairman Luis Lopez who had spent the day working on TV
monitors at Loomis' offices, told police he tried to recover more
money for the company but was was told by the loot-grabbers to mind
his own business.
   The 29-year-old Lopez, who lives in Daly City, does not have a
listed telephone number and could not be reached for comment
Wednesday.
   Soulette was impressed with his honesty.
   ``He was one of a few people who tried to do what was right,''
the officer said. ``While everyone else was busy grabbing what they
could get, he was thinking of getting the money back to its
rightful owner.''
</TEXT>
