<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua 2dLd-Writethru a00808 03-09 0589</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua, 2d Ld - Writethru, a00808,0605</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ortega Cancels Cease-Fire Talks</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with Ortega blaming Reagan for
canceled talks. Picks up 6th graf: Three days ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega canceled truce
talks with rebels Tuesday after the insurgents said they would not
attend a planned meeting in southern Nicaragua.
   Ortega accused both President Reagan and the rebels, known as
Contras, of sabotaging the talks.
   ``This signifies the killing of the possibility of a meeting,''
he said on Voice of Nicaragua radio, but suggested new talks no
later than the third week in March.
   Contra leader Adolfo Calero said earlier Tuesday the
U.S.-supported rebels would not attend the meeting scheduled by the
leftist Sandinistas.
   ``The Sandinista government spoke with the Nicaraguan Resistance
at the last minute (Monday), informing us that they were ready for
the meeting in Sapoa,'' Calero said in a telephone interview from
Miami. ``We are not willing to take part in a unilateral meeting
mounted by the Sandinistas.''
   Ortega said Reagan ``made a virulent speech against Nicaragua
yesterday. He said `No' to the meeting.
   ``So if there is anyone responsible for the meeting not being
held tomorrow and for the the blood that continues being shed ...
it is the president of the United States.''
   Reagan said in Washington Monday that congressional opponents of
further aid to the Contras lacked the courage to fight communism
and the defeat of the rebels would be a ``grave strategic defeat
for the United States.''
   Three days of talks had been scheduled at Sapoa, 90 miles south
of Managua on the border with Costa Rica.
   They would have been the first talks held on Nicaraguan
territory and without a mediator. Roman Catholic Cardinal Miguel
Obando y Bravo mediated previous talks.
   A Contra statement issued in Miami said the rebels wanted
preliminary discussions in San Jose, Costa Rica.
   ``We accept to go to Sapoa but we are asking a previous meeting
to clear up the details,'' said Aristides Sanchez, one of five
Contra directors. ``We have to discuss dates, an agenda, security.
It must all be established beforehand, since there is no longer a
mediator.''
   He said it would be impossible for Contra negotiators to get
together in time to reach Sapoa by Wednesday.
   Ortega publicly called for the talks last week and said Obando y
Bravo no longer would be needed because negotiators would meet
face-to-face.
   The Contras insisted on the presence of Obando y Bravo, a
frequent critic of the government who leads the Catholic church in
Nicaragua, as ``witness, moderator, and guarantor of the talks.''
   On Monday, Ortega asked the cardinal and Joao Baena Soares,
secretary-general of the Organization of American States, to
witness the talks.
   Baena Soares arrived in Managua on Tuesday, and Ortega announced
cancellation of the talks after meeting with him.
   Contra spokesmen also insisted Ortega's government agree to
discuss political points outlined by Obando y Bravo during the last
round Feb. 18 in Guatemala.
   His plan would require the Sandinistas to grant amnesty to
political prisoners, restore full press freedom, reopen talks with
internal political opposition parties and review the military draft
law.
   Sandinista and opposition sources said Obando y Bravo's
proposals caused his ouster as mediator.
   The Sandinistas have refused to discuss internal political
issues with the Contras. They say the only purpose of talks is to
work out a cease-fire in accordance with the regional peace plan
signed Aug. 7 by the five Central American presidents.
</TEXT>
