<1ST_LINE>u a AM-PTL-IRS     03-09 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PTL-IRS,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Overturns Injunction; Would Allow IRS To Revoke PTL
Tax-Exempt Status</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has cleared the way for
the Internal Revenue Service to revoke PTL's tax exemption, which
could affect income for the Fort Mill television ministry.
   U.S. District Judge Karen Henderson on Monday overturned a
preliminary injunction against the IRS that Bankruptcy Judge Rufus
Reynolds issued in December.
   ``This puts the ball back in our court,'' IRS spokesman Les
Witmer of Atlanta said Tuesday. The IRS may revoke PTL's tax
exemption soon, he said.
   The IRS informed PTL Trustee David Clark in December that it
would revoke the exemption, retroactive to May 31, 1981. But Clark
got the injunction, and Reynolds ordered the IRS not to revoke
before May 1, 1988.
   ``The order of the bankruptcy court enjoining revocation of
PTL's tax exempt status was issued outside its jurisdiction and is
therefore reversed,'' Henderson ruled.
   Clark and PTL attorney Bradford Leggett of Winston-Salem, N.C.,
could not be reached for comment Tuesday.
   The IRS granted PTL its tax exemption in 1973.
   Although the IRS can't collect back taxes while PTL is protected
by Chapter 11 bankruptcy laws, the impending revocation may affect
PTL contributors. The IRS calculates the back taxes at between $62
million and $82 million, while PTL's current leaders calculate the
amount owed at about $5 million.
   The ministry is engaged in a March telethon to raise $4 million.
   Henderson ruled that revoking the tax exempt status would cause
taxes to be assessed only against taxpayers who contribute to PTL _
contributors who are not debtors in bankruptcy.
   The IRS said that PTL's former leader, Jim Bakker, his wife,
Tammy, and top aides received excessive compensation that was not
consistent with the ministry's tax-exempt status. The IRS said the
couple received $11 million during their last seven years with the
ministry.
   Bakker resigned a year ago, admitting he had had a tryst with a
church secretary.
</TEXT>
