<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BRF--ShotgunSleeper     03-09 0163</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Shotgun Sleeper,0168</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shotgun Stolen From Beneath Pillow, Cousin Shot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PERRIS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 70-year-old kept a shotgun under his
pillow because of repeated break-ins, but the latest burglar got
the weapon without waking the man and shot the sleeper's cousin
with it, authorities said.
   Wally Newton woke up when he heard the blast and Simpson Brown
yelling after being shot in the leg early Monday.
   Brown, 70, and Newton share a home in Mead Valley, an
unincorporated area about 65 miles southeast of Los Angeles.
   Brown told deputies he was sleeping when he saw a shadow pass
his bedroom.
   He called out, thinking it was Newton, but got no answer, said
Riverside County sheriff's Sgt. John Horton. Brown got up, and
found the burglar holding Newton's shotgun, according to Horton.
   ``He (Brown) grabbed the barrel,'' Horton said. The gun went
off. Brown yelled. Newton woke up.
   Brown was hospitalized in good condition. The burglar escaped
with the gun, Horton said.
</TEXT>
