<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Diplomat Arrest,0159</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>S.African Diplomat Sorry About Hitting Protester</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOUTH BURLINGTON, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A South African diplomat has
apologized for a traffic accident in which his car struck an
anti-apartheid protester and a police officer.
   Vice Consul Duke Kent Brown, charged with simple assault in
Monday's accident and released on his own recognizance, was ordered
to appear in court in April.
   Brown said he had not expected protesters to block his exit
after he took part in a talk show at WJOY-WQCR.
   In an interview Tuesday with the radio stations, he said he did
not see Police Officer Todd Shepard, who suffered bruises on his
leg.
   ``I was very surprised to hear that a policeman had been injured
and I did apologize to him when I saw him,'' Brown said.
   Brown said he was glad to hear that protester Laurie Larson of
Richmond, who suffered minor bruises, was not badly injured.
