<1ST_LINE>u p AM-SUP--Oklahoma 2ndLd-Writethru a0918 03-09 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SUP--Oklahoma, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0918,0336</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Edges Dole in Oklahoma; Gore Wins</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with Bush winning, new totals. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RON JENKINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush humbled Bob Dole
with a Republican primary win in the Kansas senator's backyard,
while Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore triumphed convincingly in
Oklahoma's Democratic contest Tuesday.
   With 2,272 of 2,439 precincts or 93 percent reporting, Bush
edged Dole from with 69,813 votes or 37 percent to Dole's 66,147
votes or 35 percent. Pat Robertson was next with 40,039 votes or 21
percent and New York Rep. Jack Kemp was a distant fourth with
10,170 votes or 5 percent.
   In the Democratic race, with 2,317 of 2,439 precincts or 95
percent reporting, Gore had 154,217 votes or 41 percent, Gephardt
had 78,834 votes or 21 percent and Dukakis had 62,958 votes or 17
percent.
   Jesse Jackson was next with 48,556 votes or 13 percent; former
Colorado Sen. Gary Hart had 13,897 votes or 4 percent; and Illinois
Sen. Paul Simon had 6,460 votes or 2 percent.
   The Democrats were competing for 46 delegates; the Republicans
for 36.
   A poll broadcast by two television stations last week showed
Gephardt, Gore and Dukakis each getting 18 percent of the
Democratic vote. But 27 percent of those surveyed between Feb. 26
and March 1 were still undecided.
   Dole crisscrossed the state in the closing days and stepped up
his advertising campaign in an effort to overtake Bush, the
perceived front-runner who was endorsed by Gov. Henry Bellmon and
most prominent state political leaders.
   Ads for Dole touted his positions on agriculture and reducing
the federal deficit. Dole was supported by U.S. Sen. Don Nickles.
   Matt Seward, Bush campaign director in Oklahoma, said Oklahoma
was ``a special prize'' since it was listed by Dole operatives as
one of the states Dole was counting on to win.
   ``If he can't win in Oklahoma, where can he win?'' Seward asked.
</TEXT>
