<1ST_LINE>u p AM-SUP--StatePrimariesRdp 4thLd-Writethru aityhousingrepresentativesmaybeclosetoputtingupthefirsteffectivebarrierbetweenrailroadtracksandyoungstersfromthreehousingprojects.
03-09 0821</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SUP--State Primaries Rdp, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0985,0839</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Primaries in Three States; Congressional Race in Louisiana</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 14 grafs to update with comment from Molpus, Rep.
Alexander re-elected in Arkansas and updating returns, picks up
after dash, ``Roemer</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BARR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Mississippi Democrats picked a young congressman as their
candidate to replace John C. Stennis in the U.S. Senate, while
Democratic Sens. Paul Sarbanes of Maryland and Lloyd Bentsen of
Texas easily overcame little-known primary opponents Tuesday.
   As the first state primaries coincided with Super Tuesday, Rep.
Wayne Dowdy defeated Secretary of State Dick Molpus for the
Democratic Senate nomination in Mississippi. He is expected to face
a hard fight from Rep. Trent Lott, the House minority whip who was
unopposed in the Republican primary.
   With 90 percent of the vote counted, Dowdy had 167,640 votes or
54 percent to Molpus' 133,547 votes or 43 percent. A third
candidate, pipefitter Gilbert Fountain, had 11,454 or 4 percent.
   Molpus saluted the winner as ``a decent and likable man. He has
conveyed those characteristics to the people of this state and we
pay him tribute.''
   Texas Republicans will need a runoff to choose Bentsen's
opponent, while Republican Jim McCrery advanced to a runoff against
Democratic state Sen. Foster Campbell to fill the U.S. House seat
being vacated by governor-elect Buddy Roemer.
   Sarbanes easily won renomination for a third term and will face
Thomas Blair, a millionaire political newcomer who beat eight other
candidates for the Republican nomination. With 78 percent of the
vote counted, Blair had 54,408 votes or 47 percent while none of
his eight opponents had more than 13 percent.
   In Arkansas, Rep. William Alexander swamped political consultant
Darrell Glascock in the Democratic primary, and won re-election
because there is no Republican opposition. With 56 percent of the
vote counted, Alexander had 54,079 or 66 percent to Glascock's
27,570 or 34 percent.
   Rep. Jamie Whitten, seeking his 25th term, and Rep. Mike Espy,
Mississippi's first black congressman since Reconstruction, were
overwhelming winners in Democratic primaries. There were tight,
crowded races in both parties for the nominations to succeed Dowdy
and Lott..
   In a rematch of the 1982 primary, Bentsen defeated professor Joe
Sullivan of San Antonio by better than 5-1. With 48 percent of the
vote counted, Bentsen had 587,121 votes or 84 percent to 114,946 or
16 percent for Sullivan.
   Houston millionaire Wes Gilbreath and U.S. Rep. Beau Boulter of
Amarillo were headed for a runoff for the GOP nomination to oppose
Bentsen.
   With 39 percent of the vote counted, Gilbreath had 101,292 or 35
percent and Boulter had 96,212 or 33 percent. Former state Rep.
Milton Fox of Austin had 53,481 or 18 percent and businessman Ned
Snead of Georgetown had 41,564 or 14 percent.
   With returns 91 percent complete in Louisiana's 4th District,
McCrery had 30,859 or 30 percent while Campbell nailed down the
other spot in the April 16 runoff with 21,278 or 21 percent.
   Stan Tiner, the former editor of the Shreveport Journal who had
Roemer's support, was third with 15,600 or 15 percent, followed by
June Phillips, the only black in the race, with 13,479 or 13
percent and state Rep. Claude ``Buddy'' Leach with 12,254 or 12
percent.
   Roemer will resign on Monday to become governor.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Roemer said he would vote for Tiner, and even gave his campaign
a check, but insisted he had not formally endorsed anyone.
   Dowdy, 44, stressed his seven years experience as a member of
Congress, while the 38-year-old Molpus pointed to his record as
director of federal-state programs under former Gov. William Winter
and as secretary of state since 1984.
   Mississippi is one of the states where the GOP hopes to reduce
or even reverse the Democrats' 54-46 advantage in the Senate.
Eighteen of the 33 seats at stake this year are held by Democrats.
   Stennis, 86, retiring after 41 years in the Senate, did not
choose sides in the Democratic primary.
   Bentsen, who is seeking a fourth term has said he is prepared to
spend $10 million in November, and didn't care who the Republican
nominee was.
   Gilbreath was the big spender in the Texas GOP race, investing
about $500,000 of his own money.
   In addition to the Mississippi race, Republican hopes in the
Senate this year were spurred by the retirement of Democratic Sen.
William Proxmire of Wisconsin and Sen. Lawton Chiles of Florida.
   However, the GOP is losing Sens. Paul Trible of Virginia, Daniel
Evans of Washington and Robert T. Stafford of Vermont.
   In New Jersey, Republican businessmen Pete Dawkins _ a West
Point football star, Rhodes scholar, decorated combat veteran and
former Army general _ is challenging Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J.,
who is seeking a second term.
   In New York, Republicans had hoped to mount a strong challenge
to incumbent Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, but were disappointed
when high-profile federal prosecutor Rudolph Giuliani ruled himself
out.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
