<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 0112EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LiuKilling     03-09 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Liu Killing,0544</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosector Says Gangster Accused Of Journalist's Slaying Acted On
Orders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>REDWOOD CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Taiwanese gangster accused of
fatally shooting a Chinese-American journalist was acting on orders
from the head of Taiwan's intelligence agency, a prosecutor charged
Tuesday.
   In his opening statements, Assistant District Attorney Bob
Bishop told the jury that Taiwanese Adm. Wang Hsi-ling hired Tung
Kuei-sen to assassinate Henry Liu, whose writings were highly
critical of the Taiwanese government.
   Liu's wife, Helen, also testified before the jury in San Mateo
County Superior Court. Tung, an acknowledged member of the
Taiwanese crime syndicate known as the Bamboo Gang and one of two
alleged triggermen in the slaying, entered a plea of innocent last
June.
   Tung, 35, is serving a 20-year prison sentence for herion
smuggling.
   The 52-year-old Liu was gunned down at his Daly City home on
Oct. 15, 1984. He was a columnist for Chinese-language newspapers
in San Francisco and had just published an unflattering biography
of Taiwan President Chiang Chung-kuo when he was slain.
   Bishop said that Liu was making it known that he was about to
publish memoirs of a former high-ranking Taiwanese official,
something that Hsi-ling feared would be embarrassing and damaging
to President Chiang. Chiang died in January.
   Wang, the admiral, wanted Liu killed before the memoirs were
published, Bishop said. Wang hired Bamboo Gang leader Chen Chi-li,
who surrounded himself with a group of men, including defendant
Tung, to help carry out the assassination plot, the prosecutor said.
   The memoirs contained nothing that would shock U.S. citizens,
Bishop said. But in Taiwan, anything dealing with the personal
lives of the president or his father, Chiang Kai-shek, were
considered treasonous, he said.
   Mrs. Liu testified Tuesday afternoon, tearfully describing her
husband's murder.
   She said that the day before the slaying, she noticed two people
on bicycles surveying their neighborhood. However, their faces were
covered with hooded sweatshirts and she did not think anything of
it until following day, when she noticed they had returned on the
bikes.
   Less than an hour later, she said she sent her husband down into
the garage to load boxes into their car and heard a loud noise. She
went downstairs and found her husband dying on the garage floor.
   She also said that before her husband's slaying, the Taiwan
government had started sending over former friends of her husband's
to try and persuade him to quit his critical writings.
   The suspects in the slaying fled and eventually resurfaced in
Taiwan, believing they had acted on the orders of the Taiwanese
government, Bishop said. The suspects thought they were immune from
prosecution, he said.
   However, the slaying had strained U.S.-Taiwan relations, and the
United States began putting so much pressure on Chiang's regime
that ``something had to be done,'' Bishop said.
   Chen and another Bamboo Gang member were convicted of the murder
in Taiwan in 1985 and given life sentences, and three top Taiwanese
intelligence officers were also separately convicted by a military
court in the alleged murder plot.
   But Tung fled Taiwan and eventually became the only one of Liu's
suspected killers to be brought to trial in the United States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
