<2ND_LINE>AM-SUP--Louisiana, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0960,0420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Jackson Beats Gore; Bush Swamps GOP Field; Runoff In Congressional
Race</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with Jackson victory; runoff to
succeed Roemer in Congress; no pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN SAYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson repeated his 1984 Democratic
primary victory here Tuesday, staving off Sen. Albert Gore Jr.'s
bid for an upset, while George Bush swamped the GOP field.
   In a special election, a Republican former aide to Democratic
Gov.-elect Buddy Roemer led the 10-candidate field to succeed
Roemer in Congress, but was forced into an April 16 runoff with a
state senator.
   In the Democratic race, with 2,903 of 3,272 precincts or 89
percent reporting, Jackson had 194,118 or 34 percent; Tennessee's
Gore had 168,500 votes or 30 percent; Massachusetts Gov. Michael
Dukakis had 83,117 votes or 15 percent; Missouri Rep. Richard
Gephardt had 61,375 votes or 11 percent.
   In Republican voting, Bush left Sen. Bob Dole battling for
second place with Pat Robertson. With 2,857 of 3,272 precincts or
87 percent reporting, Bush had 76,155 votes or 58 percent;
Robertson had 24,052 votes or 18 percent; Dole had 23,354 votes or
18 percent; New York Rep. Jack Kemp had 6,665 votes or 5 percent.
   The Democrats were deciding 63 convention delegates; the
Republicans 41.
   In the closing days of the Democratic presidential primary,
Roemer endorsed Gore, who said he felt his campaign was gaining
steam in the state, but the same claim was made by Kitty Dukakis,
the wife of the Massachusetts governor.
   Backers of former television evangelist Robertson claimed their
work was responsible for most of the 19,000 voters who switched
their registrations from Democratic to Republican. The Rev. Billy
McCormack, Robertson's state campaign director, predicted the
former TV evangelist would carry Louisiana.
   In the 4th Congressional District, Roemer's former congressional
aide Jim McCrery, the sole Republican in the race, was forced into
a runoff with state Sen. Foster Campbell to succeed Roemer in the
U.S. House.
   With 91 percent of the vote in, McCrery had 30,859 votes, or 30
percent, to 21,278 or 21 percent for Campbell; former Shreveport
newsman Stan Tiner was third with 15,600 votes, or 15 percent. June
Phillips, the only black in the race, gather 13,479 votes, or 13
percent and state Rep. Claude ``Buddy'' Leach, who held the seat
for one term until he was defeated by Roemer in 1980, had 12,254
votes, or 12 percent.
   Roemer resigns on Monday to become governor.
</TEXT>
