<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Dukakis Beats Uncommitted in Idaho</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES with Dukakis declared winner; No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BOISE, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis parlayed
a strong statewide organization into a decisive victory in Idaho's
Democratic presidential caucuses on Tuesday.
   With 34 of 45 precincts or 76 percent reporting, Dukakis had 727
votes or 43 percent; uncommitted received 470 votes or 28 percent;
Jesse Jackson had 269 votes or 16 percent; Tennessee Sen. Albert
Gore Jr. had 107 votes or 6 percent; Illinois Sen. Paul Simon had
65 votes or 4 percent; and Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt had 41
votes or 2 percent.
   State party Chairman Mel Morgan and Gov. Cecil Andrus led a
campaign to have as many of Tuesday's caucus participants as
possible remain uncommitted. Idaho has only 18 delegates at stake.
   ``This thing is looking more and more like a brokered
convention,'' Morgan said, ``so we might as well get some power
while we can.''
</TEXT>
