<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 0211EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-TaxCheaters     03-09 0700</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tax Cheaters,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IRS Losing Less to Tax Cheats, Commissioner Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Internal Revenue Service is preparing to
report that Americans are cheating less on their federal tax
returns even though the government is still losing as much as $90
billion a year to scofflaws.
   That figure for the 1987 ``tax gap'' doesn't even include untold
billions that are lost because illegal income is never reported to
the IRS.
   Nevertheless, says IRS Commissioner Lawrence B. Gibbs, ``the
amount of the tax gap has diminished since the last time we did a
study.'' That was in 1983, when the IRS estimated an $81.5-billion
tax gap that would rise to more than $100 billion by 1987.
   Gibbs, defending the IRS's proposed budget before a House
Appropriations subcommittee on Tuesday, said the new tax-gap study
could be released within a week. The new figure will be between $80
billion and $90 billion, he said.
   He attributed the decline in cheating to several actions by
Congress and the IRS to force better compliance with the tax laws,
including enhanced ability to match virtually every tax return with
supporting income statements filed by employers, banks and other
payers. Gibbs also suggested the massive tax revision enacted in
1986 contributed to better compliance.
   In other developments:
   _Gibbs said the IRS is temporarily suspending efforts to collect
back taxes from many students whose colleges paid them stipends for
research or teaching assignments in 1984, 1985 or 1986. The
colleges reported those stipends to the IRS as income but many
students failed to report them on their tax returns.
   ``We've put the word out (to IRS offices) to hold up on any''
such cases until the agency can develop a uniform policy on how to
treat stipends paid in those years, he said. The 1986 tax revision
cleared up any ambiguity for subsequent years; all stipends are
taxable.
   Some IRS field offices are following a 1975 IRS ruling that set
guidelines for taxing some stipends; others follow different court
interpretations.
   Several colleges have reported numerous graduate students
receiving tax-due notices from the IRS because of their stipends.
The Washington Post cited one unofficial estimate that up to 17,000
students might be involved and that several have already filed suit
in Tax Court to contest the assessments.
   Gibbs said the IRS has no campaign to crack down on these
students, but blamed their problems on the fact their tax returns
did not square with their W-2 earnings statements. He said he hopes
the agency can have a clear-cut policy within a month.
   _More than one-third of taxpayers have filed their 1987 returns,
and, despite the sweeping nature of the 1986 tax overhaul, the IRS
is finding only about 2{ percent more errors this year than last,
Gibbs said. ``I'm delighted,'' he said.
   _The IRS issued a reminder that a new tax on certain vaccines is
now in effect. Although it is imposed on producers, it is likely to
be passed on to patients. The tax, which was enacted last December,
will finance compensation for patients who die or are injured
because of vaccinations.
   The tax is $4.56 for a dose of DPT (diphtheria, whopping cough
and tetanus) vaccine; 6 cents for diphtheria and tetanus; $4.44 for
measles, mumps and rubella, and 28 cents for polio.
   The last IRS study of the tax gap, published in 1983, estimated
that individuals and corporations dodged $81.5 billion in taxes on
legal income in 1981 by understating income and overstating
deductions.
   The agency estimated that another $9 billion in taxes was lost
on three types of illegal income: drugs, prostitution and gambling.
The new report will not even attempt to estimate the tax loss from
illegal income that is never reported.
   Since the last tax gap study was published, IRS researchers have
found evidence that taxpayers may be cheating less. In May 1986,
the agency released a preliminary report indicating that a 20-year
trend of declining compliance with the tax laws might have been
reversed.
   That study estimated that voluntary compliance rose to 91.8
percent in 1982, from 91.0 percent in 1979. Compliance had declined
steadily from 94.3 percent in 1965.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880309-0018 </DOCNO>
