<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Nielsens     03-09 0354</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nielsens,0367</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NBC Back On Top; ABC Back To Third</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An episode of NBC's new series ``Day by Day''
placed second to perennial favorite ``The Cosby Show'' and helped
the network climb back to the top of the ratings after ABC's two
weeks as No. 1.
   NBC won the ratings for the week that ended Sunday with an
average prime-time A.C. Nielsen Co. rating of 16.3. CBS had a 15.0
rating and ABC, whose 16 days of Winter Olympics coverage
catapulted it to the top the previous two weeks, fell back to
third, with a 12.8.
   For the season, NBC continues in the lead with a 16.3 overall
rating to ABC's 14.1 and CBS's 13.6.
   A rating is a percentage of the nation's 88.6 million households
with televisions.
   The episode of ``Day By Day'' that ranked second was shown at
8:30 p.m. Thursday, after No. 1-rated ``The Cosby Show.''
   ``Day By Day,'' a comedy about a young couple operating a home
daycare center, also was shown by NBC on Sunday night after
``Family Ties'' and on Monday night after ``ALF.''
   The Sunday night show placed 20th in the Nielsen ratings and the
Monday night show 14th. The show's regular slot will be Sunday
night, where it received its lowest rating.
   The three-hour Grammy Awards show on CBS, which featured a rare
television performance by Michael Jackson, finished eighth.
   ``The Cosby Show'' on NBC was rated No. 1 for the week with a
31.4 rating.
   NBC's ``Cheers'' was No. 3 with a 25.9, followed by NBC's
``Night Court'' with a 24.5.
   ABC's ``Growing Pains'' was No. 5 with a 24.5 rating, and its
``Who's The Boss?'' was next with a 22.0.
   CBS' ``The Golden Girls'' held seventh place with a 21.5 rating,
followed by a tie between the Grammys and CBS' ``60 Minutes,'' at
21.0.
   No. 10 was NBC's ``ALF,'' with a 20.5 rating.
   In the news category, ``The CBS Evening News'' was No. 1, with
an 11.3 rating. ABC's ``World News Tonight'' had a 11.2 rating, and
the ``NBC Nightly News'' 9.6.
</TEXT>
