<1ST_LINE>u p AM-SUP--BadCall     03-09 0135</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SUP--Bad Call,120</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NBC Gave North Carolina to Jackson, Then Gore</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the networks' race to call Super Tuesday
contests, NBC News incorrectly predicted that Jesse Jackson would
win the North Carolina Democratic primary, then switched its pick
to Sen. Albert Gore Jr. about an hour later.
   NBC declared Jackson the winner shortly after the state's polls
closed at 7:30 p.m. EST, said spokeswoman Mary Lou O'Callaghan.
``We made a mistake,'' she said. ``We retracted the projection and
shortly afterward, we called Gore.''
   Gore won with 35 percent, to Jackson's 33 percent.
   O'Callaghan said the projections are based on totals from the
News Election Service, sample precincts and exit polling. ``We used
the same criteria we use in making all our calls, and this one was
just wrong,'' she said.
</TEXT>
