<1ST_LINE>u p AM-SUP--Missouri 3rdLd-Writethru a0474 03-09 0425</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SUP--Missouri, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0474,a0481,0434</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Edges Dole In GOP Primary, Gephardt's Home State His Sole
Victory</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Combines previous, recasts lead to clarify, UPDATES vote
totals first 3 grafs; percentages unchanged.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KAREN BALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush rocked Bob
Dole's presidential hopes with a narrow primary victory in the GOP
senator's back yard, steamrolling to a Super Tuesday sweep.
   And Democratic Rep. Richard Gephardt, an overwhelming winner in
his home state's first presidential primary, found it was his only
victory of the night.
   In Republican voting, with 3,851 of 3,954 precincts or 97
percent reporting, Bush had 169,427 votes or 42 percent; Kansas'
Dole had 164,646 votes or 41 percent; Pat Robertson had 44,379
votes or 11 percent; New York Rep. Jack Kemp had 14,178 votes or 4
percent.
   In the Democratic race, with 3,900 of 3,954 precincts or 99
percent reporting, Gephardt had 290,289 votes or 60 percent; Jesse
Jackson had 83,749 votes or 17 percent; Massachusetts Gov. Michael
Dukakis had 59,132 votes or 12 percent; Illinois Sen. Paul Simon
had 20,095 votes or 4 percent; Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr. had
14,284 votes or 3 percent.
   ``This has been absolutely wild,'' Bush's Missouri campaign
director, Randy Enwright, said of the GOP race. ``No matter what,
we don't lose here.''
   Enwright and Missouri Bush supporter Bill Macon said Dole needed
to win big in Missouri rather than just edge Bush slightly in his
neighbor state.
   ``Sure, if it's close, that's good, but I really wanted to break
Dole's political back here,'' Macon said.
   Dole accused Bush of trying to deliver a ``knockout punch'' in
Missouri by canceling stops in other states while Bush said Dole
probably thought he ``could dust me off'' in Missouri since it was
next to Dole's homestate of Kansas.
   Lee Atwater, Bush's national campaign manager, said Dole would
be in trouble if he lost Missouri.
   ``Bob Dole has repeatedly said Missouri is his most important
state. He's been here more than anyone else and spent more money.
He's practically campaigned as a favorite son candidate. He's sure
going to be rocking and reeling if he loses here,'' Atwater said.
   While Bush and Dole fought for the lion's share of the 47 GOP
delegates at stake, Gephardt, a congressman from the St. Louis
area, overwhelmed the 11 other Democrats listed on the ballot,
competing for 77 convention delegates.
   ``It's been a one-man show from the beginning,'' said Missouri
Democratic Party Chairman Betty Hearnes. ``We just haven't seen
anybody else.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
