<1ST_LINE>r p PM-SUP--Georgia     03-09 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SUP--Georgia,0373</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Another Win For Bush; Jackson Rolls With Giant Black Vote, Some
Whites</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An overwhelming black vote carried Jesse Jackson
to victory over Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore in Georgia's Democratic
presidential primary, while Vice President George Bush crushed
Kansas Sen. Bob Dole.
   With 2,461 of 2,571 precincts or 96 percent reporting early
today, Jackson had 235,088 votes or 39 percent; Gore had 194,824
votes or 33 percent; Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis had 93,442
votes or 16 percent; Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt had 40,658
votes or 7 percent, and former Colorado Sen. Gary Hart had 15,384
votes or 3 percent.
   In the Republican race, with 2,398 of 2,571 precincts or 93
percent reporting, Bush had 188,512 votes or 53 percent; Dole had
81,647 votes or 23 percent; former television evangelist Pat
Robertson had 57,901 votes or 16 percent, and New York Rep. Jack
Kemp had 21,662 votes or 6 percent.
   Gore had won the backing of Sen. Sam Nunn, Gov. Joe Frank Harris
and state House Speaker Tom Murphy.
   But Jackson scored big in Georgia's 5th Congressional District,
composed largely of Atlanta, where he beat both Gore and Dukakis by
better than 8-to-1.
   According to ABC News exit polls, Jackson won 95 percent of
Georgia's black Democratic vote, and added 10 percent of the
state's white Democratic votes. He even picked up 117 votes in
Forsyth County, the virtually all-white site of racial violence and
civil rights marches in 1987.
   Atlanta Mayor Andrew Young, like Jackson a veteran of the civil
rights movement, said the strong showings by Jackson and Gore ``are
probably good for the South. Both Jesse and Al Gore represent where
the South is.''
   The Republicans had 48 delegates up for grabs. The Democrats
offered 77 delegates to their convention in Atlanta in July.
   Robertson, who watched the returns in Atlanta, vowed that he is
still a contender.
   ``This is not the end,'' he told supporters. ``This is just the
beginning. We're going to New Orleans. ... I'm in all the way. I'm
in to see a Republican conservative Congress in 1990, and we're in
for the presidential race in 1992.''
</TEXT>
