<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel-Funeral     03-09 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Funeral,0391</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Attend Funeral of Israeli Victims of Terrorist Attack</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAX NASH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEERSHEVA, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of mourners attended the
funerals of three Israelis killed in a Palestinian terrorist
attack, many sobbing uncontrollably as relatives threw themselves
on the coffins of their beloved.
   ``Such killings ... only strengthen our lust for and link to
this land, to this country,'' Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir told
the 5,000 Israelis who attended the services Tuesday.
   Services were held for the three residents of this southern
Negev desert town who were killed Monday, when three Palestinian
guerrillas hijacked a commuter bus. Nine Israelis were wounded.
   Anti-terrorist police stormed the bus three hours after the
hijacking and 15 minutes after the guerrilla leader shot to death
Victor Ran, 39, a widower and father of three children.
   The guerrillas, from Yasser Arafat's mainstream Fatah branch of
the Palestine Liberation Organization, were killed during the
30-second rescue operation.
   Two Israelis, Rina Shiratzky, 31, a mother of two, and Miriam
Ben Yair, 46, mother of four, were fatally wounded in the rescue.
   The guerrillas were demanding freedom for hundreds of
Palestinians held in Israeli jails on rioting charges.
   ``We have to hold responsible all the countries in the region,
the Arab states from where the murderers came and where you read
and hear today in the media praises for this murder,'' Shamir said.
   ``The war of the Jewish people for their land, the land of
Israel, is not over .... Despite our tremendous longing for peace,
there are still people _ if they might be called human beings _ who
are after our blood,'' he said.
   Family members of the dead threw themselves on the coffins,
screaming in grief and clutching the lids. Many in the crowd sobbed
as they gazed at the coffins, which had been placed on a sunlit
podium.
   Maj. Gen Yitzhak Mordechai, chief of the army's central command
who headed the rescue operation, also spoke at the funerals.
   ``We promise today near their coffins not to rest in continuing
the holy enterprise of mantaining security along the borders of
Israel and within the country,'' Mordechai said.
   ``The murderers have found their death yesterday. Some day we
will reach those who sent them.''
</TEXT>
