<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 0233EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-BlackPatriots     03-09 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Black Patriots,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Panel OKs Siting Plan For Black Revolutionary War Patriots
Memorial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A measure that would let a memorial to the
black veterans of the Revolutionary War be built in the
most-traveled tourist area of Washington has won subcommittee
approval, but the House has just four weeks to act.
   A vote by the House Interior and Insular Affairs subcommittee on
national parks and public lands followed pleas Tuesday by
historians, black activists and the Reagan administration.
   ``The Patriots Memorial is not a war memorial; it is not an
ethnic memorial,'' said Maurice A. Barboza, a Virginia lawyer who
has been the driving force behind the project. ``As a memorial to
the struggle for freedom, it will stand as a universal symbol to
define for generations to come our American nationality, which is
based on principles rather than on pigmentation.''
   The subcommittee also approved, without discussion, locating a
planned Korean War memorial in the city's prime tourist area.
   Last year, President Reagan signed into law a measure pushed by
Barboza that authorizes a black patriots memorial in Washington.
   But Barboza, formerly of Plainville, Conn., and Rep. Nancy L.
Johnson, R-Conn., whom he enlisted to carry on the fight in
Congress, want the memorial in a prominent place, a move that
requires another layer of administrative and legislative approvals.
   Last November, Interior Secretary Donald P. Hodel declared that
Barboza's proposal had ``pre-eminent historical and lasting
significance to the nation.'' That finding is needed to place a
memorial in the city's monument-filled Area I, which includes the
Mall, the Ellipse, Lafayette Park and West Potomac Park.
   The Senate has approved the siting resolution, but the House
only has until April 7 to take action. Without congressional
approval, the memorial cannot be placed in Area I.
   Robert K. Wright, an Army historian, said most history books
ignored the role of the estimated 5,000 blacks who served in the
Continental Army.
   Even if the Area I legislation is accepted, proponents still
would have to go back to the Interior Department, Commission of
Fine Arts and the National Capital Planning Commission to get
specific siting and design approval.
   Barboza, who quit his job as a lobbyist for the American Bar
Association to work on the memorial project full time, envisions a
``modest'' memorial nestled in Constitution Gardens, a grassy area
near both the Lincoln Memorial and Washington Monument.
</TEXT>
