<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 0238EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Licenses-Firefighters     03-09 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Licenses-Firefighters,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Firefighters Angry Over Commercial Licensing Requirement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's firefighters are incensed by a
federal law that could require them to obtain commercial licenses
if they want to continue to drive their equipment.
   The Commercial Vehicle Safety Act of 1986, which is being phased
in starting this year, will require commercial licenses of anyone
who operates a vehicle that weighs 26,000 pounds or more, carries
15 or more people or transports hazardous materials.
   But associations representing many of the nation's 225,000 paid
and 900,000 volunteer firefighters say the law was meant to foster
safety in the commercial trucking business, not impose costly new
rules on their members.
   Tim Butters, a spokesman for the International Association of
Fire Chiefs, said Tuesday, ``The burden on the fire service is
going to be very significant when this law goes through because of
the road test that they're going to have to go through, the
(written) examination, and I think there's going to be a lot of
cost factors.''
   Stanley Hamilton of the Federal Highway Administration said the
licensing regulations won't be ready until July 15, and they will
be phased in through 1992. The law also will affect farmers who
drive heavy equipment, and Hamilton said his agency has been
inundated with protest mail from farm communities.
   Under the law, the secretary of transportation may issue waivers
``with respect to class of persons or class of vehicles,'' but
Hamilton said requests for exemptions would not be considered until
the regulations are written.
   Rep. Sherwood Boehlert, R-N.Y., wrote to Transportation
Secretary James Burnley last week to ask that firefighters be
exempted from the commercial license requirement.
   ``Let's solve the problem with truckers, not create new ones for
firefighters,'' Boehlert said Tuesday. ``Volunteer fire companies
are people who are farmers, lawyers, they work in the factory and
they volunteer their time and services to the fire department. Now
this regulation, if it's enforced, would require these people to
spend about $400 to get a commercial license ... when there's no
evidence whatsoever that firefighters are creating any safety
problems on our nation's highways.''
   Federal legislation introduced last week in the House by Rep.
Jim Slattery, D-Kan., and the Senate by Sen. David Karnes, R-Neb.,
would exempt the drivers of fire trucks and farm vehicles that are
driven less than 15,000 miles a year.
   Francis A. McGarry, New York state fire administrator, estimated
that it would cost $58 million to commercially license 95,000 of
the state's 165,000 firefighters.
   He put test fees at $350, a physical exam at about $150, ``and
that's without even including the time a volunteer has to take off
from work to go and do this.''

</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880309-0032 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 0240EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--China-Bomb     03-09 0144</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--China-Bomb,0146</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Killed When 40-Year-Old Bomb Explodes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 40-year-old bomb exploded and killed a boy and
two other people in central Henan province when the boy tried to
open it, thinking the explosives inside had medicinal value, the
official China Daily said today.
   It said Wei Shuangxi, a farmer living near Sanmenxia city, found
the bomb while digging for medicinal herbs last year.
   On Feb. 19, a boy playing at Wei's home tried to chop the end
off the bomb, thinking the explosives inside could cure diseases,
and the bomb went off, killing the boy, Wei and one other person,
the newspaper said.
   The report gave no details of the bomb. Forty years ago, the
Communist Red Army and the Nationalists were waging a civil war
that ended in 1949 with the Communist forces gaining control of the
mainland.
</TEXT>
