<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 0243EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-SUP--Mississippi     03-09 0476</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SUP--Mississippi,0489</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush, Jackson Win Mississippi; Dowdy to Battle Lott</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN EVEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson, buoyed by a big turnout in
the heavily black Delta, sailed to a decisive victory in
Mississippi's presidential primary, while Vice President George
Bush blew away other GOP challengers like a gulf hurricane.
   Voters on Tuesday also set up a November matchup of two popular
congressmen for the seat of retiring Sen. John C. Stennis.
   With 2,268 of 2,340 precincts or 97 percent reporting, Jackson
had 162,431 or 45 percent and Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr. had
120,708 or 33 percent. Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis had
31,188 or 9 percent; Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt had 19,811
votes or 5 percent; and former Colorado Sen. Gary Hart had 12,748
votes or 4 percent.
   In the Republican race, with 2,249 of 2,340 precincts or 96
percent reporting, Bush had 103,094 votes or 66 percent to Kansas
Sen. Bob Dole's 26,287 or 17 percent. Former TV evangelist Pat
Robertson had 21,017 or 13 percent, and New York Rep. Jack Kemp had
5,782 or 4 percent.
   Based on those returns, Jackson would get 23 delegates to 16 for
Gore and one for Dukakis. Bush would secure 27 GOP delegates, with
two each for Dole and Robertson.
   ``We knew we were going to do well ... but we didn't think we'd
do this well overall, or in Mississippi,'' said Eric Kimbrough,
executive director of the state's Bush campaign. ``We believe this
is a resounding victory for us.''
   U.S. Rep. Wayne Dowdy, a Democrat who jumped in the U.S. Senate
race the day after Stennis, 86, retired in October, defeated
Secretary of State Dick Molpus, 38, by a comfortable margin.
Stennis is retiring after 41 years in the Senate.
   Polls rate a contest between liberal Dowdy and conservative
Republican Trent Lott a toss-up.
   ``It will take a united Democratic Party to beat him,'' Dowdy
said. ``It can be won, and things are ripe for the Democrats to win
in November. Mississippi should have at least one Democrat in the
U.S. Senate.''
   Early polls had shown Dowdy, 44, trailing Molpus, who recently
won re-election to a new four-year statehouse term. The two tussled
over Dowdy's voting record, which Molpus said was among the five
poorest based on attendance in the House.
   ``I think that hurt me a little, and it hurt him a little, too,
but going into the final days we felt very confident,'' Dowdy said.
``We said we would get about 55 percent, and that's the way it
turned out.''
   In lightly contested Democratic primaries, 24-term Rep. Jamie
Whitten and Mike Espy, the state's first black congressman since
reconstruction, were overwhelming winners.
   Runoffs appeared certain in both parties for the 4th and 5th
District seats given up by Dowdy and Lott, respectively. They will
be held March 29.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
