<1ST_LINE>r p PM-SUP--Kentucky     03-09 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SUP--Kentucky,0311</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush, Gore Score Big In Kentucky</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK R. CHELLGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush's lopsided
victory in Kentucky's GOP primary surprised even his staunchest
supporters, while Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr. also won big in
his neighbor state.
   Bush captured 71,912 votes, or 59 percent of the GOP total
Tuesday, according to unofficial returns with 3,235 of 3,237
precincts, or 99 percent, reporting. The vote apparently won 27 of
the 38 delegates up for grabs.
   ``I think Bush is unstoppable after this. I think he clinched
the presidency today,'' said U.S. Rep. Harold Rogers, Bush's state
campaign chairman, who said he had predicted Bush would win 48
percent of the vote.
   Kansas Sen. Robert Dole finished second with 27,844 votes, 23
percent of the total. He apparently won 11 delegates.
   No other Republican crossed the 15 percent threshold to win any
delegates.
   With 3,241 of 3,243 Democratic precincts reporting, Gore
received 150,286 votes, or 46 percent. Because of the way delegates
are apportioned, though, he apparently won 37 of the 55 available
Democratic delegates, or 67 percent.
   ``Al Gore is right for Kentucky; he's right for America. We're
just now starting the momentum in this campaign,'' said Gov.
Wallace Wilkinson, Gore's leading supporter in the state.
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis ran second in Kentucky with
59,457 votes, or 18 percent, and was slated for 12 delegates.
   Only the Jesse Jackson among other Democrats was able to make
the threshold and win delegates. Jackson received 49,655 votes, or
15 percent, to earn six delegates.
   Among other Republicans, former TV evangelist Pat Robertson
received 13,538 votes, or 11 percent. No other Republican broke 2
percent.
   Missouri Congressman Richard Gephardt received 29,048 votes, or
9 percent. No other Democrat received more than 4 percent.
</TEXT>
