<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 0247EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-SUP--BlackVoters     03-09 0701</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SUP--Black Voters,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Near Sweep Of Black Voters For Jesse Jackson</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson built his triumphs in the
South's Super Tuesday primaries by piling a 10 percent share of the
white vote on top of a near sweep of black votes.
   It was Jackson's finest hour in two runs for the presidency and
he said it gave him ``a sense of joy ... and a sense of victory.''
   ``We're now in a dead-heat contest running for the nomination of
our party,'' he told ABC News from Houston Tuesday night. ``It
shows that America is getting stronger and better, but also that in
the South, my message began to break through: stop drugs, save jobs
and invest in our children.''
   Jackson demonstrated anew what he had shown earlier in such
states as Iowa, Maine and Vermont, where only a tiny share of the
population is black: he is now able to attract a significant share
of white votes.
   He has also benefited from changes in the party delegate
selection rules he complained so bitterly about in 1984, when he
won 18 percent of the popular vote but wound up with only 12
percent of the delegates.
   And this time out, Jackson didn't have to share the black vote
with Walter Mondale.
   Blacks made up nearly 25 percent of the electorate in the South,
and exit polls by ABC News indicated Jackson got 95 percent or more
of their votes.
   ABC polls said Jackson had about 10 percent of the white vote in
the South, while the CBS News-New York Times poll said he had 8
percent. NBC figures ranged from 4 percent in Tennessee to 15
percent in Virginia and 19 percent in Massachusetts.
   At a virtually all-black precinct in Mobile County, Ala.,
Jackson got 1,837 votes to second-place Albert Gore Jr.'s 31. In
Macon County, about 90 percent black, Jackson led with 2,540 to
Gore's 43.
   Overall, according to ABC's polls, Jackson got 6 percent of the
white Alabama vote and 96 percent of the black vote. By comparison,
four years earlier, Jackson got 1 percent of the white vote and 55
percent of the black vote in Alabama.
   Likewise, in Florida, where Jackson managed 1 percent of the
white vote and 58 percent of the black vote in 1984, he pulled in 7
percent of the white vote and 82 percent of the black vote Tuesday,
said ABC. Its exit polls had a 5-point margin of error in either
direction.
   Frank Dexter Brown, associate director of communications for the
Joint Center for Political Studies, a black-oriented think tank
based in Washington, said Tuesday Jackson has been defying
expectations all along this year with his showings in New England,
Minnesota and Iowa.
   Jackson got 28 percent of the vote in Maine compared to 1
percent four years earlier. He also got 28 percent in Vermont, 20
percent in a second-place finish in Minnesota, 11 percent in the
Iowa caucuses and 8 percent in New Hampshire.
   Most national polls have given Jackson 4 percent to 5 percent of
the white vote.
   A survey last August by the Joint Center for Political Studies
found 80 percent of blacks and 10 percent of whites supported
Jackson.
   Blacks comprise about 11 percent of all Americans of voting age.
   Since delegates are awarded by congressional district, not
statewide, it is still possible for a candidate to wind up with a
smaller share of delegates in some states than his popular vote.
   But Jackson stood to profit from the lower threshold of votes
needed in each congressional district to gain delegates. It was 20
percent in 1984; now it is 15 percent.
   Voters polled by ABC gave Jackson high marks for his ability to
handle foreign affairs, protect the poor and elderly and hold down
unemployment.
   Among those who voted in Democratic primaries, 29 percent said
they definitely would not vote for Jackson for president; 45
percent nixed Republican Pat Robertson; 37 percent ruled out George
Bush and 36 percent said no to Democrat Gary Hart. His three main
Democratic rivals, Michael Dukakis, Gore and Richard Gephardt, were
ruled out by 12 percent to 14 percent.
</TEXT>
