<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 0153EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-SUP--Republicans 12thLd-Writethru a0501 03-09 0984</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SUP--Republicans, 12th Ld-Writethru, a0501,950</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Sweeps the South, Dole Seeks To Deflect Shock</HEAD>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 10 grafs new with Robertson winning Washington. Picks up
10th graf pvs, ``It isn't. Should stand for AMs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush declared Tuesday, ``I'm going to be
the next president of the United States,'' as he overwhelmed Sen.
Bob Dole in lopsided Republican voting. Dole sought to deflect the
shock while the presidential aspirations of Jack Kemp and Pat
Robertson were dealt shattering blows.
   Robertson kept Bush from a Super Tuesday shutout, winning the
Washington caucuses.
   But it was a small loss for Bush, who was triumphant in the 16
remaining states that held GOP primaries Tuesday.
   Bush was leading for 571 of the 712 delegates up for grabs.
   ``This is a unique political happening,'' an elated Bush told
cheering campaign workers in Houston. ``It exceeded my fondest
expectations.''
   A more subdued Dole told his supporters in Chicago: ``Tomorrow
we will be on the road to recovery.''
   Dole, shutout in the South, turned his sights north, to the
Illinois primary next Tuesday, where he hoped to stage a comeback.
``I want to congratulate the vice president ... He'll probably
sleep better tonight than I will,'' he said. ``We'll take turns.''
   Dole's campaign chairman, William Brock, acknowledged that the
campaign had suffered a serious defeat. ``The psychological hit is
very heavy,'' he said.
   Tuesday's voting appeared to put the other two GOP candidates,
Kemp and Robertson, well out of contention for the party nomination.
   Robertson continued to show strength in state caucuses with his
win in Washington. He vowed to fight on.
   ``It isn't too bad for an amateur, but it's not near what I
expected,'' Robertson said. He suggested he might win the Illinois
primary and asserted, ``I do have resources left. We have the
largest donor base of any candidate and I can carry all the way to
New Orleans.''
   Robertson offered his congratulations to Bush and said, ``He ran
a superb campaign.''
   Bush won decisive victories all over, capturing more than 50
percent of the vote in many states, including delegate-rich Florida
and Texas.
   The vice president also scored big wins in Tennessee, Kentucky,
Georgia, Alabama, Virginia, Mississippi, Louisiana, Arkansas, North
Carolina, Maryland, Massachusetts and Rhode Island. In Oklahoma and
Missouri, the margin was much closer, but Bush hung on to win..
   Dole had pinned his Southern hopes on North Carolina, the home
state of his wife, Elizabeth.
   At stake Tuesday were 712 delegates to the Republican National
Convention. Virginia was alone among the 17 GOP contests holding a
``beauty contest'' that awards no delegates. It takes 1,139 votes
for the nomination.
   Bush led for 571, giving him 698 when combined with the
delegates he won in earlier contests. Dole led for 100, a total of
165. Robertson was getting 10 for a total 18. Kemp led for 4 for a
total 39.
   Bush's national campaign chairman, Lee Atwater, predicted that
Bush would pick up more than 600 delegates _ a gain that would give
him a near-unassailable lead toward winning the GOP presidential
nomination.
   ``I would certainly hate to be in Sen. Dole's shoes after
tonight and especially if he loses in Illinois,'' Atwater said.
   The Dole campaign had sought to keep Bush from picking up more
than 500 delegates.
   Dole hoped to wage a come-from-behind effort in Midwestern and
Western states. He said earlier in Springfield, Ill., ``If we take
a little bath today, I am going to start my road to recovery in
Illinois just like I did 40 years ago.''
   He was referring to his recuperation in an Illinois hospital
from wounds suffered during World War II.
   Kemp and Robertson were far outdistanced by Bush and Dole. Kemp
trailed Robertson in most Southern states, and was expected to drop
out by week's end. For Robertson, the voting throughout the South
was a replay of his third place finish in Saturday's South Carolina
primary, when he could muster no more than about 20 percent of the
vote.
   Bush voted in Houston, and then told reporters, ``If we exceed
our expectations or live up to them, I think we'll be in good
shape.''
   ``It's going to be a little tougher as we go along, but I've
been in tough fights before,'' Dole acknowledged at a morning news
conference in Kansas City, Mo.
   He then traveled to Illinois and immediately challenged Bush to
a series of debates _ ``one-on-one, without moderator'' _ in that
state, which holds its primary next Tuesday.
   ``If Bob Dole was so serious about debating, he would have shown
up for the (Feb. 19) Dallas Morning News debate,'' Bush spokesman
Pete Teeley said. ``We have a strategy which has been highly
successful and we plan to pursue it, and that doesn't include
having one-on-one debates with Bob Dole.''
   The Senate minority leader, a 1980 presidential contender and
GOP vice presidential candidate in 1976, was reportedly spending
$500,000 on television advertising in Illinois.
   A defeat there could all but end Dole's presidential efforts and
a strong showing for the Kanasan was by no means assured. Bush is
backed by Illinois Gov. James Thompson and 93 of the state's 102
Republican county chairmen.
   Kemp, dead last in the South Carolina primary last weekend, had
not been expected to see that flagging effort revived in Tuesday's
voting. Aides said the New York lawmaker and former pro-football
star would reassess his race later in the week. He was expected to
pull out.
   Robertson's chances as a serious contender seemed likely to be
all but ended if his losses in Super Tuesday states were as
decisive as his third-place finish in South Carolina, where he won
only 19 percent of the vote.
   Robertson's candidacy came to life with his strong second-place
finish the Iowa caucuses on Feb. 8. But in the primaries that
followed, his strength ebbed.
</TEXT>
