<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Panama Bjt   03-09 0685</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama, Bjt,0709</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anti-Noriega Protests Sweep Panama City</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By REID G. MILLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Riot police fired birdshot and tear
gas to disperse demonstrators who blocked streets with hundreds of
trash fires to protest the country's military rule and its
tottering economy.
   The demonstrations Tuesday were the largest since President Eric
Arturo Delvalle was deposed Feb. 26, just hours after he tried to
fire Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   Noriega, chief of Panama's 15,000-member Defense Forces, is
considered the real power behind the country's civilian government.
   Reporters saw at least eight protesters captured, beaten with
rubber truncheons and fists and driven away in military vehicles.
   A photographer for the Mexico City newspaper Excelsior was
slightly injured by birdshot fired by police.
   The National Civic Crusade, which has organized demonstrations
calling for Noriega's ouster since last June, said at least 23
people were detained. By late Tuesday, all but two had been
released.
   ``It was another black day for Panama,'' said Aurelio Barria,
president of the Panama Chamber of Commerce, Industry and
Agriculture. ``When the people of Panama go into the streets, they
get repressed,'' he told reporters Tuesday night.
   ``We are in the hands of armed terrorists,'' Barria added,
referring to the Noriega regime.
   Barria is a director of the Crusade, a broad coalition of
business, professional, labor, student and political organizations
opposed to Noriega.
   Small groups of protesters erected barricades across hundreds of
streets in the central and eastern parts of the city Tuesday
afternoon, snarling traffic and forcing many businesses to shut
down early.
   Riot police were out in force, but they could not keep up with
the hundreds of demonstrators, many of whom stepped out of their
homes and shops to hurl plastic bags of garbage into the streets
then quickly ran back inside.
   Other protesters, mostly roving bands of youths, set fire to
piles of debris and built barricades of burning tires, dry palm
fronds, wooden signs, boulders and anything else they could lug
into the streets.
   Some tried to throw rocks at police but could not reach their
targets. When police appeared, groups ran a few blocks then set up
another barricade.
   The stench of burning garbage and the acrid smell of tear gas
wafted over large parts of the city as the demonstrations, and the
government's attempts to halt them, continued into the evening.
   Smouldering rubbish still littered the streets of this tropical
capital late Tuesday night, but demonstrators had dispersed.
   The protests came on the seventh day of a bank shutdown that has
crippled commerce. Most businesses were not accepting checks or
credit cards, only cash.
   Depositors began a run on Panamanian-owned and -operated banks
the day Delvalle was dismissed.
   The 12 locally owned banks closed March 1 during a nationwide
general strike called by Noriega's opponents. The banks opened
briefly but the government ordered them shut again last Thursday
because of a lack of cash.
   In Miami, a U.S. district judge froze Panamanian assets in banks
there after a suit was filed Tuesday to prevent Noriega's
government from withdrawing official monies. A similar order was
issued last week in New York City and another suit was filed
Tuesday in Boston.
   The United States continues to recognize Delvalle as Panama's
president. It has been calling for Noriega's removal since his
indictment in Florida in February on federal drug trafficking
charges.
   Delvalle has been in hiding in Panama since Noriega orchestrated
his ouster by the Legislative Assembly.
   Jorge Abadia, Panama's foreign minister, on Tuesday accused the
United States of conducting ``the prelude of an armed invasion'' by
staging military exercises along the Panama Canal.
   But the U.S. Southern Command said the exercises, involving
nearly 700 soldiers from U.S. military installations in Panama and
U.S. National Guard troops from Florida and Puerto Rico, were
scheduled a year ago. The command said the exercises, which began
last weekend, are ``routine training.''
   Dennis McAuliffe, administrator of the Panama Canal Commission,
said on Tuesday that the waterway was operating normally despite
the strain that the tension between the United States and Panama
has created for canal workers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880309-0039 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 0252EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-SUP--NorthCarolina     03-09 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SUP--North Carolina,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Easily Defeats Dole; Gore Holds Off Jackson</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN FLESHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Support from key Democratic figures pushed
Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr. past Jesse Jackson in North
Carolina's presidential primary, while victorious Vice President
George Bush stressed his ties to President Reagan.
   Gore's victory Tuesday showed voters ``trusted him on defense,
believed he was committed to jobs and economic growth, and they
trusted him to be fiscally responsible,'' said former Gov. Jim
Hunt, who with Sen. Terry Sanford endorsed Gore in January.
   With 2,373 of 2,387 precincts or 99 percent reporting, Gore had
234,595 votes or 35 percent; Jackson had 222,494 votes or 33
percent; Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis had 136,459 votes or 20
percent; Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt had 37,854 votes or 6
percent, and former Colorado Sen. Gary Hart had 16,506 votes or 2
percent.
   In the Republican race, with 2,374 of 2,387 precincts or 99
percent reporting: Bush had 123,781 votes or 45 percent; Kansas
Sen. Bob Dole had 109,678 votes or 40 percent; former television
evangelist Pat Robertson had 26,583 votes or 10 percent, and New
York Rep. Jack Kemp had 11,348 votes or 4 percent.
   Gore was expected to take 34 of the state's 82 Democratic
delegates, with Jackson getting 31 and Dukakis 17. Bush was
expected to take 29 of the state's 54 delegates and Dole 25.
   Bush held off a late surge by Dole, who targeted North Carolina
in his effort to avoid a Southern shutout. During an all-day swing
across the state Saturday, Bush said he was worried because polls
had indicated the contest was neck-and-neck.
   The popularity of Dole's wife, former transportation secretary
Elizabeth Dole, in her native state helped but not enough,
observers said. ``You have to remember that Mrs. Dole is not on the
ticket,'' said Joan Shaffer, co-chairman of Bush's Wake County
organization.
   ``A Republican candidate has to carry the South,'' said Jack
Hawke, the state GOP chairman. ``What George Bush has shown is that
he is strong in the South. ... People are associating him with the
president.''
</TEXT>
