<1ST_LINE>r p PM-SUP--RhodeIsland     03-09 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SUP--Rhode Island,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush, Dukakis Trounce Opposition In Rhode Island</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FLIPPEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis and
Vice President George Bush built vigorous campaigns on already
strong personal ties to score resounding victories in Rhode
Island's presidential primaries.
   ``Our mission has been accomplished,'' said Gov. Edward D.
DiPrete, who repaid Bush's campaign journeys to the state with
strong backing. ``There is really a Bush blastout tonight all over
the country.''
   Bush, a New England native, swept his chief rival, Kansas Sen.
Bob Dole, in 16 states around the country in the Super Tuesday
primaries.
   In the Democratic race, with 100 percent of 320 precincts
reporting, Dukakis amassed 34,159 votes or 70 percent, making his
victory even bigger than that of another Bay Stater, Sen. Edward
Kennedy, in the 1980 primary.
   Jesse Jackson was a distant second with 7,369 votes or 15
percent, followed by Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt with 2,013
votes or 4 percent; Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr. with 1,932 votes
or 4 percent; Illinois Sen. Paul Simon with 1,392 votes or 3
percent and Gary Hart with 738 votes or 2 percent.
   Among Republicans, with 319 of 320 precincts or 99 percent
reporting, Bush won 10,403 votes or 65 percent, trailed by Dole
with 3,637 votes or 23 percent; Pat Robertson with 921 votes or 6
percent and Rep. Jack Kemp, 783 votes or 5 percent.
   Based on those results, Bush would likely capture 15 GOP
delegates and Dole would win six, while Dukakis would gain 19
Democratic delegates and Jackson three.
   Dukakis, as the governor of a neighboring state, was a familiar
face to Rhode Islanders long before he began running for president.
He campaigned here several times and quickly picked up support from
most of Rhode Island's Democratic hierarchy.
   Providence Mayor Joseph R. Paolino Jr., state chairman of the
Dukakis campaign, said the governor's win was even more impressive
than Kennedy's victory over President Carter in the 1980 Democratic
primary.
   Kennedy ``had about 65 to 67 percent of the vote in a two-man
race,'' Paolino said. ``This is a five-man race.''
   Jackson supporters broke out champagne to celebrate their
candidate's strong showing in a state that is only 2 percent black.
</TEXT>
