<1ST_LINE>u p AM-WashCaucuses 1stLd-Writethru   03-09 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wash Caucuses, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0677,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Robertson Wins Washington Caucuses</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES with Robertson winning.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID AMMONS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pat Robertson, supported by troops of energetic
fundamentalists, marched to his sole Super Tuesday victory by
pushing past Kansas Sen. Bob Dole and Vice President George Bush in
Washington state's Republican caucuses.
   With 3,683 of 6,594 precincts reporting, the former TV
evangelist picked up 4,659 votes or 38 percent. Dole had 3,245 or
27 percent, and Bush came in third _ his only loss of the night _
with 2,958 or 24 percent.
   New York Rep. Jack Kemp was a weak fourth with 906 or 7 percent.
   ``We'll take it!'' Robertson's state organizer, Bruce Hawkins,
cried as the results rolled in.
   To claim their share of the state's 41 GOP delegates, the
candidates will have to fare as well in this spring's county or
legislative district caucuses, which precede the July 15 state
convention where delegates will be allocated.
   State Republican chairwoman Jennifer Dunn said the proportions
set caucus night traditionally hold up throughout the delegate
selection process.
   In early results for the Democrats, Massachusetts Gov. Michael
Dukakis, endorsed by Gov. Booth Gardner, had 45 percent and Jesse
Jackson 32 percent. Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr. received the
votes of 7 percent of those Democrats represented in the party's
sample of statewide precinct voting. Ten percent were undecided.
   At stake were 73 Democratic delegates. However, final Democratic
results were not expected for a week.
   As many as 220,000 registered voters, or 10 percent of those
eligible, were expected to take part in caucuses that represented
the first step toward electing the West's second largest bloc of
national convention delegates.
</TEXT>
