<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 0256EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-SUP--AlsoRans     03-09 0670</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SUP--Also Rans,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>The Big Losers: Kemp, Hart, Simon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Super Tuesday rocked the presidential
aspirations of Bob Dole and Richard Gephardt, who just a month ago
were basking in their first-place victories in the Iowa caucuses.
   It also appeared to claim at least one immediate casualty,
Republican Jack Kemp, whose expected withdrawal from the race could
come as early as today. The future of Democrat Gary Hart's campaign
also seemed dim.
   Republican Dole and Democrat Gephardt vowed to press on. But
both were clearly shaken by poor showings in the largest-ever round
of primary contests.
   ``I never told you it was going to be easy,'' Gephardt said
after winning only his home state of Missouri.
   ``I don't give up very easily,'' said Dole, who came away from
Super Tuesday with no wins and few delegates.
   Republican Pat Robertson and Democrat Paul Simon also said they
would stay in the race, at least for now, despite disappointing
showings in their respective primary races on Tuesday.
   Robertson _ who consistently beat only Kemp throughout the
native South that he claimed as his base of support _ said he
``didn't frankly have the concentration I should have had in key
states.'' He didn't come close in any of the 16 GOP primaries, but
did win Washington's caucuses.
   But the former television evangelist, who three weeks ago told a
New Hampshire audience ``I assure you that I am going to be the
next president,'' said his Super Tuesday showing ``isn't too bad
for an amateur.''
   He said, ``I do have resources left. We have the largest donor
base of any candidate and I can carry all the way to New Orleans''
to the Republican convention this summer.
   Democrat Simon was expected to hold on, at least until the
primary next week in his home state of Illinois. He largely stayed
away from Super Tuesday races and declared the outcome a
``gridlock'' with ``no clear winner.''
   ``No candidate is going to win on the first ballot at the
(Democratic) convention,'' Simon suggested. ``It's going to be a
brokered convention.''
   Hart was on the ballot but out of the presidential picture in
all primary states. He failed to get more than single-digit
percentages anywhere.
   But Hart, who declared ``let the people decide'' when he
re-entered the race last December, made no public comment on his
future plans.
   He had said last week that ``so long as I can be treated
seriously, I will continue.'' Hart listened to the returns on
television at his home outside of Denver.
   Dole, who was crushed by Bush in a sweep across the South that
netted the vice president close to 700 new delegates, hoped to make
a comeback effort in the Midwestern and Western primaries that
follow _ beginning with next Tuesday's contest in Illinois.
   ``Tomorrow we will be on the road to recovery,'' Dole told a
group of supporters in Chicago.
   ``I want to congratulate the vice president. ... He'll probably
sleep better tonight than I will,'' Dole added. ``We'll take
turns.''
   A Dole defeat in Illinois could give Bush a nearly unassailable
lead and could all but end Dole's chances for the GOP presidential
nomination.
   Gephardt also sought to look beyond the losses.
   ``Now we go on, to Illinois, to Michigan ... '' he said.
Gephardt claimed, ``I'm far from chucking it in because this is a
long race.''
   Kemp spent the evening with his family in suburban Washington
rather than with supporters.
   The 52-year old former pro quarterback, who had earlier sought
to portray himself as a ``consensus conservative'' who could carry
on the Reagan Revolution, had failed to see his candidacy take off.
   His withdrawal from the race appeared inevitable after his
fourth-place finish in South Carolina last weekend.
   Out of cash, Kemp decided to make one last stand in the Super
Tuesday contests. But in only a single primary, Massachusetts, did
he finish any better than fourth. There he edged out Robertson for
third place.
</TEXT>
