<1ST_LINE>r p PM-SUP--Maryland     03-09 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SUP--Maryland,0379</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush And Dukakis Win In Maryland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM STUCKEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis used a
strong local organization to smash Democratic rivals in Maryland's
presidential primary, while Vice President George Bush won without
even campaigning in person.
   ``We were well organized today. We were the only candidate
really to have extensive poll coverage,'' said Baltimore County
Executive Dennis Rasmussen, one of the organization Democrats
involved in the Dukakis campaign.
   With 1,459 of 1,574 precincts or 93 percent reporting today,
Dukakis had 193,258 votes or 43 percent; Jesse Jackson had 140,025
votes or 31 percent; Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr. had 40,061
votes or 9 percent; Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt had 34,170 votes
or 8 percent, and Illinois Sen. Paul Simon had 13,628 votes or 3
percent.
   In the Republican race, with 1,548 of 1,574 precincts or 98
percent reporting, Bush had 103,899 votes or 53 percent; Kansas
Sen. Bob Dole had 62,721 votes or 32 percent; Pat Robertson had
12,328 votes or 6 percent, and New York Rep. Jack Kemp had 11,579
votes or 6 percent.
   Dukakis was expected to take 27 delegates and Jackson 20. Bush
grabbed the state's 41 Republican delegates.
   Also on the ballot, incumbent Democratic Sen. Paul Sarbanes
easily won nomination for a third term. He will be opposed in the
general election by millionaire businessman Thomas Blair, a
newcomer to politics.
   Bush carried all eight congressional districts even though he
didn't campaign personally in Maryland. Dole spent less than one
day in the state.
   Dukakis benefitted from strong Democratic organizational
support, especially in the populous suburbs around Baltimore and
Washington, D.C.
   U.S. Rep. Kweisi Mfume, Jackson's state chairman, said Dukakis
``ran a good campaign, had a good organization, had a good message,
and people latched onto it.''
   But he said he felt good about Jackson's showing, which was
boosted by strong support in the state's two predominantly black
congressional districts.
   ``The campaign strategy was really to hold onto what we had in
1984 and to slightly increase it, and so we've done better than
that,'' Mfume said. ``Jesse Jackson and Dukakis both were organized
in Maryland. They spent time here, and the voters responded
accordingly.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
