<DOCNO> AP880309-0047 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 0308EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-SUP-Dole     03-09 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SUP-Dole,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dole Vows To Get `Back On The Winning Track' After Super Tuesday
Defeat</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Lead prospects uncertain</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY MASSEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican presidential candidate Bob Dole,
reeling from Super Tuesday losses, says he is ``on the road to
recovery'' in Illinois and that the industrial Midwest will revive
his struggling campaign.
   ``This is going to be Bob Dole's recovery state,'' the Kansas
senator told a crowd of cheering supporters Tuesday night.
   ``It's going to be the turnaround state. It's going to get us
back on the winning track.''
   After Dole's losses in Tuesday's primaries and caucuses, the
March 15 Illinois primary is a make-or-break event for the
senator's candidacy, his aides concede.
   ``We've got to make it happen in Illinois,'' said Thomas D.
Rath, a senior strategist in the campaign.
   Although polls indicate that Vice President George Bush leads
Dole in Illinois, Rath said, the campaign hopes to surge ahead by
focusing on what has become a dominant theme _ Dole's leadership in
the Senate and contrasting that to Bush's record.
   ``If you're looking for somebody who understands the issues,
somebody who deals with the issues every day and somebody who has
made a difference, you can pretty well judge a candidate by what
they've done in the past,'' Dole told supporters in Oak Brook, a
Chicago suburb where he watched the Super Tuesday results on
television.
   The Dole campaign is counting on strong support in downstate
farming areas and in Republican counties near the Illinois-Missouri
border. In addition, the campaign is targeting white-collar
suburban areas around Chicago.
   William Brock, Dole's campaign chairman, acknowledged that
Tuesday's losses dealt a serious blow to the Dole campaign.
   ``The psychological hit is very heavy,'' said Brock.
   Brock attributed Bush's victories to President Reagan's
popularity in the South, and expressed frustration that the Dole
campaign had not been able to make gains by attacking Bush and
focusing the campaign on issues such as the deficit and drug use in
America.
   ``You do the best you can. We did not have time to develop the
one-on-one message that we did in the earlier states,'' Brock said.
``Now we've got a little more time. We'll see if we can do a better
job.''
   On arriving in Illinois on Tuesday, Dole immediately took aim at
Bush when he spoke at a rally at the state Capitol in Springfield,
challenging the vice president to a series of debates.
   Later Tuesday, when it became clear he had suffered a big
defeat, Dole rallied his supporters by recalling that he had come
to Chicago 40 years ago for treatment by a surgeon for crippling
wounds suffered in World War II.
   ``I've been coming to Illinois for a long, long time,'' Dole
said. ``I don't give up very easily. We're going to be on the road
to recovery in the state of Illinois.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
