<2ND_LINE>AM-SUP--Alabama, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0556, a0562, a0567,0489</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Jackson Edges Gore in Alabama; Bush Beats Dole</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Combines urgent series. Picks up 12th graf, `Jackson ran...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KENDAL WEAVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson squeaked out a Democratic
primary win over Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore in the Cradle of the
Confederacy early Wednesday, while Vice President George Bush
drubbed Kansas Sen. Bob Dole in Alabama's Republican race.
   Jackson rallied a phalanx of black voters behind him to defeat
Gore, a white son of the neighboring state. With 3,448 of 4,304
precincts or 80 percent reporting, Jackson had 157,887 votes or 44
percent to Gore's 133,153 votes or 37 percent.
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis was next with 27,846 votes or
8 percent; Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt had 25,825 votes or 7
percent; former Colorado Sen. Gary Hart tallied 6,586 votes or 2
percent and Illinois Sen. Paul Simon had 2,644 votes or 1 percent.
   In the Republican contest, with 3,366 of 4,304 precincts or 78
percent reporting, Bush amassed 123,285 votes or 64 percent; Dole
had 31,279 votes or 16 percent; Pat Robertson had 27,192 votes or
14 percent; and New York Rep. Jack Kemp had 9,458 votes or 5
percent.
   For the Democrats, 56 delegates were at stake, while Republicans
picked 38 delegates.
   Jackson banked on a strong turnout of black voters, but Gore
hoped his appeal as a Southern neighbor and his endorsement by Sen.
Howell Heflin would lift him into the No. 1 spot, despite early
predictions that Jackson would win.
   Jackson made the largest investment of his campaign in TV ads in
the Birmingham area in hopes of nailing down a victory.
   Bush had the endorsement of Alabama Republican Party Chairman
Emory Folmar. But Republican Gov. Guy Hunt remained publicly
neutral, and other party officials joined up with Dole and Kemp,
saying they wanted a tougher, more conservative candidate.
   Robertson, drawing strength from religious fundamentalists, was
given a chance of capturing the No. 2 spot.
   Jackson ran fourth in Alabama in the 1984 primary when Walter
Mondale drew blacks from his camp. But this time black voters
avoided any major split.
   Gore billed himself as the conservative Democrat _ but in 1984
more than 75 percent of the votes went to the liberal Democrats
Mondale, Jackson and Gary Hart.
   The days prior to the election were marked by a new series of
skirmishes over the Democrats' rule against crossover voting, a
rule that ended up bloodying the party in 1986 and leading to the
election of a Republican governor for the first time this century.
   Democratic Party Chairman John Baker said voters who cast
ballots in the Republican primary Tuesday could not come back and
vote in Democratic primaries in June when nominees for hundreds of
local, state and congressional posts are chosen. Critics said
Alabama has no practical way to enforce the rule.
</TEXT>
