<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Iditarod     03-09 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iditarod,0347</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mushers Onto Nikolai In Iditarod</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NIKOLAI, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A decision by three mushers to take a
mandatory 24-hour layover early in the 1,150-mile Iditarod Trail
Sled Dog Race paid off as they sailed into the lead on a trail
packed smooth by other mushers.
   Joe Redington, who helped organize the first Iditarod 16 years
ago but has never won it, found himself in an unfamiliar place
Tuesday _ the lead.
   The Wasilla resident, trailed closely by Herbie Nayokpuk of
Shishmaref and Joe Garnie of Teller, left Tuesday morning from the
Rohn Roadhouse checkpoint, 271 miles into the race.
   The three took their layovers Sunday in Skwentna, just 150 miles
from the start in Anchorage. The race leaders passed them, only to
get bogged down in new snow. They took their mandatory layovers at
Rohn and watched helplessly as Redington, Nayokpuk and Garnie raced
through. They had to wait until Tuesday afternoon to leave.
   ``I kind of have this feeling in the back of my mind that we're
going to see two Eskimos _ Garnie and Nayokpuk _ blazing across
this state,'' said Jerry Austin of St. Michael, one of the mushers
taking his layover at Rohn.
   Joe Runyan of Nenana was the first musher to leave Rohn, and at
4:39 p.m. Tuesday became the first musher to arrive at Nikolai, the
next checkpoint 93 miles down the trail. But he had not yet taken
his 24-hour layover, and so will have to sit in Nikolai for a day
while the caravan of mushers passes.
   Redington left Rohn at 7:20 a.m. Tuesday. Nayokpuk followed two
minutes later, and Garnie left at 9 a.m.
   By Tuesday evening, 49 of the 52 teams racing had reached the
Rohn Roadhouse.
   U.S. mushers from outside Alaska, and their positions at last
report: Frank Teasley of Jackson, Wyo., 23rd; Dan MacEachen of
Snowmass Village, Colo., 25th; Terry Adkins of Mikado, Mich., 26th;
John Patten of Grand Marais, Minn., 27th; Stan Ferguson of
Philadelphia, 35th; and Robin Jacobson of Minnetonka, Minn., 40th.
</TEXT>
