<1ST_LINE>r p PM-SUP--Tennessee     03-09 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SUP--Tennessee,0404</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gore, Bush Win In Tennessee</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISE BICKHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr., three
weeks from his 40th birthday, received an early gift of victory
from adoring constituents in the Democratic presidential primary,
while Vice President George Bush handily defeated GOP rivals.
   ``In 1960, we replaced the oldest president then to serve with
the youngest to be elected,'' Gore said on Tuesday night, comparing
himself with the late John F. Kennedy. ``Today, history is going to
repeat itself.''
   With 2,369 of 2,391 precincts or 99 percent reporting, Gore had
410,202 or 72 percent. Jesse Jackson had 117,152 or 21 percent;
Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis had 18,982 or 3 percent; and
Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt had 8,503 or 2 percent.
   Among Republicans, with 2,298 of 2,391 precincts or 96 percent
reporting, Bush had 141,743 or 60 percent and Dole had 51,239 or 22
percent. Former TV evangelist Pat Robertson had 29,326 or 12
percent and New York Rep. Jack Kemp had 11,490 or 5 percent.
   That should give Bush 28 of the 45 delegates, with 11 for Dole,
one to Robertson and five uncommitted.
   Gore would take 56 of his party's delegates with 14 for Jackson.
   ``This is a fight for the future of the Democratic Party,'' Gore
told 1,000 supporters crowded into a hotel ballroom on Tuesday
night. ``It's a fight for whether we are going to have a viable
Democratic Party and win in November.''
   Gore, who staked his hopes on a campaign concentrated in the 14
Southern states that conducted Super Tuesday primaries, plans to
fly to Chicago today to begin his campaign for the Illinois primary
next Tuesday. The Michigan primary is March 26, five days before
Gore's birthday.
   Jackson supporters said they had expected a better showing in
the Volunteer State.
   ``We were hoping we'd do a little better,'' said state Rep.
Roscoe Dixon, D-Memphis. ``The rain in the West Tennessee area kept
our turnout down, but we feel good about it.''
   U.S. Rep. James Quillen, a Tennessee Republican and a leader of
Bush's Tennessee campaign, said Bush's victory didn't surprise him.
   The victory ``demonstrates that the people realize that he is
fully dedicated and qualified to be next president of the United
States,'' Quillen said.
   Voter turnout across Tennessee was light to moderate, election
officials said.
</TEXT>
