<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Nicaragua     03-09 0635</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua,0656</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ortega Accuses Reagan Of Keeping Contras Out Of Peace Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega accused the
White House of being behind the Contras' pullout from cease-fire
talks that had been set for today, saying the rebels and their
sponsors ``fear negotiations.''
   He said President Reagan should be held responsible for
continued bloodshed caused by the Contras, whom he branded as U.S.
``mercenaries,'' and called for rescheduling the talks, which were
to have been the first in Nicaragua and without a mediator.
   Ortega's comments came after the Contras on Tuesday pulled out
of the talks that were to be held at a post bordering Costa Rica.
The rebels said preliminary meetings should first work out details.
   ``This shows again the lack of political will of the United
States government and the counterrevolutionary leaders, as their
instrument, to end the war of aggression and terrorist acts against
the Nicaraguan people and accept a peaceful solution to the
conflict,'' Ortega said, reading from a prepared statement.
   He suggested the talks be held during the third week of March
and have an open agenda. His leftist Sandinista government had made
preparations for the talks to be held at Sapoa, 90 miles south of
Managua.
   The secretary-general of the Organization of American States,
Joao Baena Soares, arrived in Nicaragua Tuesday, a day after Ortega
invited him to a witness the talks.
   The rebels, supplied and trained by the United States, said
Monday that they would not accept the talks without Cardinal Miguel
Obando y Bravo serving as ``witness, moderator and guarantor of the
talks.''
   Ortega responded by calling on the Nicaraguan Roman Catholic
prelate, who has often criticized the Sandinistas, along with Baena
Soares, to attend the talks but only as a witness.
   In a communique, the Contras said details of the talks needed to
be worked out. It also appeared the rebels would press for more
involvement in the meetings by the cardinal, whom Ortega removed as
mediator last week.
   Ortega said Obando y Bravo's efforts no longer were needed
because the talks would be face to face. But Sandinista and
opposition sources said the cardinal was removed for trying to take
the initiative with a proposal of his own at the last
Contra-Sandinista meeting to end the 6{-year-old civil war.
   In a speech Tuesday night at the Revolution Plaza in honor of
International Women's Day, Ortega said his government was ready to
resume talks ``without conditions.''
   He added, however, ``It is clear we will not discuss the
revolution. We will not discuss the right of the Nicaraguan people
and the legitimate government of Nicaragua to arm itself. This we
won't negotiate.''
   The Sandinistas, who came to power in a 1979 revolution that
ousted dictator Anastasio Somoza, maintain the talks should deal
only with the mechanics of the Contras' disarmament and amnesty.
   Ortega cemented that position last week when he named his
brother, Gen. Humberto Ortega, the defense minister, to head the
government delegation to the talks.
   The rebels named Adolfo Calero, the top political leader of the
Nicaraguan Resistance, the Contra umbrella organization, to lead
their side.
   Obando y Bravo on Feb. 18 called on the Sandinistas to grant
total amnesty, restore full press freedoms, reopen talks with the
internal political opposition and revise the military draft law. He
also called for a 30-day truce to allow the Contras to move into
enclaves to later lay down their arms.
   The Contras accepted Obando y Bravo's proposal. The Sandinistas
hesitated and the cardinal broke off talks, saying the two sides
were at an impasse.
   In his speech Tuesday night, Ortega said Reagan was responsible
for the suspension of cease-fire talks.
   ``Reagan and his mercenaries have not accepted our proposal to
talk tomorrow,'' he said. ``They fear negotiations.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
