<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GolfPasses     03-09 0490</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Golf Passes,0504</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Atlanta City Council Members Abstain All The Way To The Golf
Course</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The practice of flooding city council members
with free passes to municipal golf courses has driven the city's
portion of the profits slicing into the rough.
   A move to end the practice was opposed this week by only two of
the 16 council members present and has landed in the same place.
   ``We have funny rules,'' said councilman Robb Pitts.
   Two years ago, the city leased its four courses to American
Golfing Co. for $80,000 a year. The lease gives each of the 19
council members 10 passes good for unlimited play.
   But the price of each ``free'' round is deducted from the lease
fee, and instead of the $80,000 the city might have received this
year, it will take in only about $14,000 based on projected free
use through May 1.
   The lease fee increases to $120,000 next year.
   With a city budget of some $250 million, that's a not a lot of
money, but for months council members passed it around like a
grenade with the pin pulled.
   ``We lease the golf courses out not only to improve the courses
but to make a profit. I don't think we ought to erode that profit
by giving free passes to people who are able to pay,'' Councilwoman
Myrtle Davis said before the vote.
   Councilman Dozier Smith defended the passes, saying they allowed
elderly constituents on fixed incomes to play.
   Councilman Hosea Williams, who voted to retain the passes and
abstained on a companion proposal to abolish them, said he favored
perquisites such as the passes, claiming council members are not
well paid.
   Most council members, including Williams, who owns a chemical
company, have substantial income outside their $18,400-a-year
council salaries and say they don't use the passes themselves.
   ``Most of them apparently give them to their constituents. The
people who get them the most are those that can afford to pay,''
said Pitts, who led the drive to eliminate the passes.
   ``You would be surprised at the names of the people I have heard
mentioned who have them. It is more of a prestige thing than a
need, to say you have one. It got out of hand.''
   He cited Park and Recreation Department figures projecting a
city loss of more than $670,000 during the first 10 years of the
lease based on current free uses.
   He said he is dropping the fight and knows of nobody eager to
pick it up. ``The results would be the same,'' he said.
   This week's attempt to eliminate the passes was killed through
abstentions, which, under council rules, have the effect of a
``no'' vote. More than half of the members present must vote
``yes'' on an issue to pass it. While only two of the 16 members
present voted against abolishing the passes, nine abstained.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880309-0057 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 0311EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-SUP--Democrats 13thLd-Writethru a0570 03-09 1022</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SUP--Democrats, 13th Ld-Writethru, a0570,950</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Inserts one graf after 14th graf bgng: ``This has ... to
UPDATE with vote total for top three Democrats. Inserts one graf
after numbers 19th graf pvs bgng: He added ... to UPDATE with
Nevada, Hawaii and American Samoa. New delegate totals</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis circled Dixie and claimed a national candidacy
on Super Tuesday, while Albert Gore Jr. looked ahead to a ``long,
hard-fought contest'' after passing his do-or-die Southern test.
Jesse Jackson hailed his ``new Southern message'' that produced
victories in a fractured Democratic field.
   Super Tuesday's loser was Richard Gephardt, who won his home
state of Missouri but fared badly elsewhere. He failed to meet the
15 percent threshold required to win delegates in many states.
   With a splintered outcome, three of the Democratic candidates
could _ and did _ argue they did well on the busiest day of
presidential primaries in history.
   For Jackson it was victories in five states and an impressive
improvement over his campaign four years ago. For Dukakis it was a
display of support outside his native New England and claim to a
national candidacy. And for Gore it was the right to claim wide
support across the South and a spot among the contenders for the
nomination.
   Gore immediately took aim at Dukakis as his chief rival and
compared him to Walter Mondale and the Democrats' 1984 debacle.
   ``I think Mike Dukakis is going to represent for many voters the
same old formula that led to the loss of 49 out of 50 states twice
in the last five elections,'' Gore said.
   He said the race ``is going to be a long, hard-fought contest.
It's also going to be a long, hard-fought contest in the fall. We
need to select the candidate with the best chance of winning.''
   Dukakis, the Massachusetts governor, countered: ``Remember, this
was a place where the guy from Massachusetts wasn't supposed to do
well at all.''
   ``If we can come out of Super Tuesday with the largest
cumulative total of delegates, I think we're going to be on our
way,'' Dukakis said.
   Jackson won Alabama, Georgia, Mississippi, Louisiana and
Virginia; Gore won Arkansas, North Carolina, Oklahoma, Kentucky and
his home state of Tennessee.
   Jackson, the black civil rights leader, savored his Alabama
showing and recalled the violent struggle for equality in Selma,
Ala. 23 years ago.
   ``The same state that wouldn't let us walk across the bridge _
we won that state today,'' Jackson said.
   Dukakis won in his home state of Massachusetts as well as in
neighboring Rhode Island, in Maryland, Idaho caucuses and in the
two mega-states of Florida and Texas.
   ``This has been a great night for us,'' said Dukakis. ``To be
able to take Texas and Florida, the two big ones, and to do well
across the board demonstrates that this is a national candidacy, a
national campaign.''
   Demonstrating the mixed verdict, Jackson, Gore and Dukakis each
collected roughly the same number of votes: 2.4 million votes.
   Jackson's big win in Virginia with nearly half of the vote and
strong showing elsewhere assured he would fare better than his 1984
campaign, when he won only Louisiana.
   ``I've won Southern states today, either number one or number
two, with a new Southern message,'' Jackson said.
   ``And that message is fundamentally, we the people must stop
drugs from threatening our national security and our streets, we
must fight to end economic violence. That message is getting
through.
   ``We've gone from a narrow mainstream to a broad-based river,''
Jackson said.
   He added: ``we're the underdog with the biggest bite.''
   Gore led in the Nevada caucuses, while Jackson led Dukakis in
early returns from Hawaii's caucuses. American Samoa gave one
delegate to Dukakis, one to Gephardt and one to the ranks of the
uncommitted.
   All were vying for a share of the 1,307 Democratic presidential
nominating delegates at stake in 20 states.
   In the crucial delegate battle, Dukakis won 372 delegates out of
Super Tuesday. Gore won 316, Jackson won 353 and Gephardt won 94.
   Gore said he would be among the three candidates going to the
convention _ suggesting Gephardt wouldn't be able to.
   ``I think that three of us are going to go all the way to the
convention,'' Gore said. ``It will be a choice between the politics
of the past and the politics of the future.''
   Gephardt, who was caught in a withering crossfire of negative
television advertisements by Gore and Dukakis, offered
congratulations to all three. He blamed his failure on a lack of
money and vowed to go on to the next round of primaries.
   ``I'm far from chucking it in because this is a long race,''
Gephardt said. ``When we've been able to get my message across, as
I did in Iowa and New Hampshire and South Dakota ... we do well.''
   Democratic Party elder statesman Robert Strauss said the news of
Super Tuesday was grim for Gephardt, .
   He said Jackson, Dukakis and Gore ``are going North now, and
we'll see how it comes out. ... I expect one of those three fellows
will probably be the nominee.''
   ``I think Dick Gephardt's in trouble,'' Strauss said.
``Certainly Dukakis and Gore each have a great deal to be happy
about tonight.''
   Gephardt criticized the Super Tuesday process with 20 states
voting on a single day _ an arrangement that left his
money-strapped campaign hard pressed to keep up.
   ``I think maybe it was a disservice to the voters to put 20
states on one day,'' he said.
   Jackson, a black man born and educated in the South, relied on
his wide support among that region's large black population and
figured to be among the delegate leaders in the Super Tuesday
voting.
   Exit polling said Jackson won nearly all the black vote and 10
percent of the white vote.
   Two other candidates, Sen. Paul Simon of Illinois and Gary Hart,
the former senator from Colorado, weren't factors.
   Simon, looking forward to the Illinois primary, said the outcome
was delegate ``gridlock.''
   ``It's going to be a brokered convention,'' he ssaid.
</TEXT>
