<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Bangladesh     03-09 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bangladesh,0443</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Says Government Arresting No-Show Election Workers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FARID HOSSAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition leaders today accused the
government of arresting and harassing poll workers who refused to
work during last week's violence-marred parliamentary elections.
   Sheik Hasina and Khaleda Zia, the two opposition leaders who led
the boycott of the March 3 balloting, said ``many'' people had been
arrested, but neither woman gave any numbers.
   ``If they are not released, the people will set them free,''
Mrs. Zia said in a statement published by Dhaka newspapers today.
   Ms. Hasina, in a separate statement carried by the press, said
President Hussain Muhammad Ershad's government had once again
displayed its ``autocratic nature.''
   On Tuesday, newspapers in the capital said five people had been
arrested in the southern town of Barisal and 19 teachers in Dhaka
had gone into hiding to avoid arrest.
   School teachers and government employees normally staff polling
places during elections, but many who were slated for duty last
week did not show up, apparently out of fear for their safety.
   At least 13 people were killed and more than 300 injured in
election day clashes between supporters of rival parties. On Feb.
10, more than 100 people were killed during non-partisan elections
for local councils.
   Hasina's Awami League and Mrs. Zia's Bangladesh Nationalist
Party led a score of other political parties in boycotting the
parliamentary election. That left the field clear for Ershad's
Jatiya Party, which faced only token opposition.
   According to incomplete returns, the Jatiya Party has won 238 of
Parliament's 300 seats. Small parties and independents took 41
seats.
   Voting was postponed until Saturday in 20 constituencies because
of violence. In another constituency, voting was delayed
indefinitely after a candidate was killed in pre-election violence.
   Hasina, daughter of President Mujibur Rahman who was
assassinated in 1975, and Mrs. Zia, widow of President Ziaur Rahman
who was assassinated in 1981, have led a 4-month-old campaign to
topple Ershad.
   Ershad, a former army general, seized power in a 1982 coup and
subsequently won a presidential election the opposition says was
rigged.
   Meanwhile, the state-operated news agency Bangladesh Sangbad
Sangstha said the government had ``initiated action'' against those
responsible for preventing a prominent opposition official from
leaving the country.
   The news agency did not say what this action was.
   Former Foreign Minister Kamal Hossain, a member of the Awami
League's presidium, was taken off an airplane Tuesday when he tried
to leave for Sydney, Australia.
   ``It was never the intention of the government to stop his going
abroad,'' the news agency said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
