<DOCNO> AP880309-0059 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 0404EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-SUP--Florida     03-09 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SUP--Florida,0427</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis, Bush Win With Organization</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILL LESTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With their sights set on the White House,
Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis and Vice President George Bush
stalked and bagged a prize apiece in Florida, one of the biggest
catches in the presidential primaries.
   ``You can't win with smoke and mirrors,'' Mike Abrams, a
political strategist for Dukakis in Florida, said on Tuesday. ``You
need people. We knew the organization had to be here. From the way
we put together our phone banks to our wooing of constituent
leaders, it was relentless.''
   With 4,143 of 4,459 precincts or 93 percent reporting, Dukakis
had 466,831 votes or 40 percent; Jesse Jackson had 238,142 or 20
percent. Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt had 171,131 or 15 percent,
followed closely by Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr. with 152,120 or
13 percent.
   In the GOP race, with 4,143 of 4,459 precincts or 93 percent
reporting, Bush had 497,993 votes or 63 percent; Dole had 162,057
or 20 percent; former TV evangelist Pat Robertson had 86,656 or 11
percent; and New York Rep. Jack Kemp had 36,810 votes or 5 percent.
   Bush took advantage of President Reagan's popularity, a
gubernatorial endorsement and family ties in Florida to trounce
Dole and claim the lion's share of 82 GOP delegates.
   ``I'm pretty confident now that he will win the nomination,''
said Bush's son Jeb, Florida's secretary of commerce. ``He got
knocked down in Iowa, changed strategy a little bit and came back.''
   Dukakis, who organized here early, visited frequently and
courted the retirees and condo dwellers who have fled from colder
regions, built an impressive late lead based on polls in the state
that boasted the second-biggest prize of Super Tuesday after Texas:
136 Democratic delegates.
   ``When we first came down here we were told not to expend much
effort, this was a media state,'' said Steve Rosenfeld, Dukakis
state campaign manager. ``Tonight we proved that (to be) obsolete
wisdom. We won with people, we won with organization and we won
with the best candidate.''
   Robertson looked for support in conservative North Florida and
played heavily to Cubans with his assertions about missiles in
Cuba. Dole, who keeps a winter home in Bal Harbour, admitted he was
out-organized by Bush.
   Among Democrats, the state was seen by some as a litmus test of
national appeal, with liberal Democrats in South Florida,
traditional Southern Democrats in North Florida, arch-conservative
Cubans in Miami and Midwestern retirees on the Southwest Gulf Coast.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
