<1ST_LINE>r p PM-SUP--Texas     03-09 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SUP--Texas,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texans Give Bush Big Boost; Democrats Favor Dukakis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL HOLMES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis captured
the top delegate state in the Super Tuesday presidential primaries,
while Vice President George Bush shut out Republican rivals to grab
all 111 Texas GOP delegates.
   ``It has exceeded my fondest expectations,'' Bush told several
hundred supporters crowding a ballroom at at Houston hotel soon
after polls closed on Super Tuesday.
   With 6,079 of 6,933 precincts or 88 percent reporting, Dukakis
had 497,592 votes or 33 percent; Jesse Jackson had 364,242 votes or
24 percent; Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr. had 313,026 votes or 20
percent; Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt had 212,972 votes or 14
percent; former Colorado Sen. Gary Hart had 77,184 votes or 5
percent, and Illinois Sen. Paul Simon had 29,038 votes or 2 percent.
   In the Republican race, with 4,687 of 5,616 precincts or 83
percent reporting, Bush had 542,206 votes or 65 percent; Pat
Robertson had 125,164 votes or 15 percent; Kansas Sen. Bob Dole had
115,119 votes or 14 percent, and New York Rep. Jack Kemp had 40,468
votes or 5 percent.
   Dukakis was expected to get 45 of the state's 183 delegates up
for grabs, Jackson 40, Gore 23 and Gephart 10. Fourteen other
Democratic seats go to party officials.
   Meanwhile, Democratic U.S. Sen. Lloyd Bentsen easily won
renomination in his bid for a fourth term. Top Republican
challengers Beau Boulter, who gave up his congressional seat for
the Senate race, and Wes Gilbreath, a Houston investor making his
first race for a political office, will meet in a runoff. The
winner squares off against Bentsen in November.
   Dukakis, in a televised interview Tuesday from Chicago, said,
``I feel very good about the South. I feel good about tonight,
obviously.''
   Bush, who built an oil business in Texas, rents a motel in
Houston so he can vote in the state. He led in polls throughout the
campaign.
   At the victory party Tuesday night, Tom Loeffler, the former
Texas congressman who is co-chairman of Bush's Texas campaign, gave
the vice president a T-shirt emblazoned with ``Bush in '88 _ Texas
Victory _ Super Tuesday,'' while the crowd cheered and waved U.S.
flags.
   ``It's a wonderful evening, I'll tell you,'' Bush said.
</TEXT>
