<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     03-09 0796</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington In Brief,800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Emergency Shuttle Landing Site Under Construction in Morocco</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the space shuttles begin flying again,
they will have a new emergency landing site at an abandoned
Strategic Air Command base near Ben Guerir, Morrocco.
   The National Aeronautics and Space Administration Tuesday
announced construction of the new site has begun at the base, 40
miles north of Marrakech. It will be the fourth emergency landing
site.
   The former SAC base has a 14,000 foot runway, but its surface
must be rejuvenated to make it usable by shuttles that for some
reason they fail to reach the speeds necessary to get into orbit.
   NASA announced earlier in the week that another airport site in
northwest Africa, in the tiny country of The Gambia, will be
upgraded to accommodate shuttles. The space agency intends to
continue using runways at Zaragoza Air Base and Moron Air Base in
Spain.
   Foundations for shuttle approach and landing aids are being laid
at the new sites and other equipment, including 10 personnel
vehicles, will be shipped.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Jewish Advisers to Reagan Criticize Senators' Letter on Israel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of Jewish advisers to President Reagan
says the 30 senators who wrote a letter supporting the
administration's position that it is time for Israel to exchange
land for peace is acting too quickly and meddling in Israeli
internal affairs.
   The group, known as the National Jewish Coalition, said the
senators ``operated in haste'' and were ``inserting themselves into
the internal politics of Israel.''
   The coalition, formed after the 1984 election to advise Reagan
on Jewish matters, issued its statement after a meeting in the Oval
Office with Reagan. However, Richard Fox, the chairman of the
organization, said the president did not discuss the peace process
or the violence in the Israeli-occupied territories.
   He said the meeting with Reagan lasted only 12 or 13 minutes and
the president's comments were ``really more of a ceremonial
statement. There was no forum for discussion of the issue.''
   On Monday, the White House had said it welcomed the senators'
statement, in which they criticized Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir and his Likud party, suggesting they may be blocking efforts
to reach a peace settlement in the Middle East.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Groups Challenge Provisions of Alien Amnesty Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The eligibility for legalization of hundreds
of illegal aliens may rest on a federal court's interpretation of
four words in the U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service rules
for implementation of the government's amnesty program.
   A class action suit was filed Tuesday in U.S. District Court on
behalf of five illegal aliens to block INS rules defining which
illegal aliens were ``known to the government'' and are eligible
for amnesty.
   INS rules under the Immigration Reform and Control Act of 1986
provide amnesty to aliens who lived illegally in the United States
before Jan. 1, 1982 as well as to agricultural workers who can
prove they lived in this country for at least 90 days in the year
ended May 1, 1986.
   A problem has arisen over individuals who arrived legally _ with
a visa _ but who remained in the country illegally after the Jan.
1, 1982 cutoff date, according to Debbi Sanders of the Washington
Lawyers Committee for Civil Rights, one of the attorneys for the
plantiffs.
   In cases like these, the statute grants amnesty to those whose
illegal status was ``known to the government'' and advocates for
illegal aliens have sought to use Social Security and Internal
Revenue Service forms to prove that aliens in this category were
known.
   The INS, however, maintains that ``known to the government''
meant known to the INS, Sanders said, noting that this difference
of interpretation disqualified hundreds of illegals.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Talks Fail on US Participation in Japanese Contruction Projects</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A week of talks between U.S. and Japanese
officials over participation by U.S. firms in billions of dollars
worth of Japanese building projects has ended in failure.
   And, a U.S. official, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
Tuesday said that President Reagan under the law could retaliate
against Japan for what are considered unfair trade practices.
   ``That is one of the options,'' the official said, adding that
the Reagan administration will decide probably by the end of next
week what its next step will be.
   The official said the U.S. side had exhausted its capacity to
resolve the issues and was not ready to go on talking, given the
differences between the two sides.
   The official said the U.S. delegation to the talks also had
wanted the arrangements on participation by U.S. construction firms
written into a formal agreement, while the Japanese did not want to
be bound and sought only a joint statement that unspecified
arrangements were satisfactory.
</TEXT>
