<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-Markets     03-09 0257</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0266</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Up Against Yen; Stocks Sharply Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose slightly in Tokyo today, while
stock prices gained substantially following an overnight advance on
Wall Street.
   The dollar closed at 128.08 yen, up 0.28 yen from Tuesday's
close. It opened at 127.80 yen and ranged between 127.73 yen and
128.27 yen.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the 225-share Nikkei Stock Average,
which lost 150.85 points Tuesday, gained back 139.66 points, or
0.55 percent, closing at 25,605.39.
   ``Share prices in New York rose yesterday, and the foreign
exchange market has stabilized,'' said Michio Katsumata of Nomura
Securities, Japan's largest brokerage house.
   Today's heavy volume of 1.3 billion shares was concentrated in
steel and heavy industry stocks, which made strong advances, said
Richard Bixon, a trader at Vickers da Costa.
   The market had been apprehensive about the outcome of
presidential primary elections in the United States on Tuesday,
Bixon said.
   ``The main worry there ... was always going to be (Democratic
candidate Richard) Gephardt, because he was widely interpreted as a
protectionist,'' he said. Gephardt fared poorly in the elections.
   Trading was slow on the foreign exchange market as dealers
waited out the final days of the Japanese fiscal year, which ends
March 31, said Shigeki Kawano, a dealer at Mitsubishi Bank.
   Dealers also were awaiting the release of key economic
indicators. Japan's February trade data are to be released
Thursday, and figures for U.S. January trade are scheduled for
release next week in Washington.
   ``It's still a very sleepy market,'' Kawano said.
</TEXT>
