<1ST_LINE>r p PM-SUP--Idaho     03-09 0235</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SUP--Idaho,0242</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis, Jackson Winners In Idaho</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOISE, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis coasted
to victory in Idaho's Democratic presidential caucuses, but Jesse
Jackson surprised party leaders with a strong showing.
   With all 45 precincts reporting early today, Dukakis had 1,516
votes or 38 percent; Jackson had 882 votes or 22 percent; Tennessee
Sen. Albert Gore Jr. had 333 votes or 8 percent; Illinois Sen. Paul
Simon had 280 votes or 7 percent, and Missouri Rep. Richard
Gephardt had 44 votes or 1 percent.
   Dukakis captured 8 of Idaho's 18 delegates, with Jackson winning
four. Six delegates will go to the national convention uncommitted.
   ``Michael Dukakis is foreseen as the frontrunner _ a winner,''
said former governor John Evans, who headed the Dukakis campaign.
``He is perceived as the candidate of the people.''
   The turnout was higher than the number of Democrats who attended
the 1984 caucuses. ``The real message tonight is that we are
getting a lot of people out,'' said Gov. Cecil Andrus, who says he
will go to the convention uncommitted.
   Jackson's strong finish, in a state with a minority population
of less than 5 percent, surprised most campaign leaders.
   ``I didn't recognize where his strength was coming from,'' Evans
said. ``But he (Jackson) is doing better than four years ago.
Obviously he has matured, but it still surprises me.''
   The Republican presidential primary will be held May 24.
</TEXT>
