<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Haiti     03-09 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Haiti,0471</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Warns Media About Critical Reporting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PIERRE-YVES GLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ The government has warned the media
it will not tolerate ``cynical insinuations,'' ``false
accusations'' and ``public insults,'' presumably in reaction to
news reports of high-level corruption.
   The communique issued Tuesday night did not mention specific
cases.
   However, local newspapers and radio stations have relayed U.S.
media reports of charges of drug trafficking made against Col.
Jean-Claude Paul, the target of a U.S. federal grand jury probe.
   The Haitian military said the charges were unfounded.
   Also, the Protestant station Radio Lumiere recently broadcast an
interview in which opposition leader Sylvio Claude accused
President Leslie Manigat of accepting bribes from Philadelphia
authorities for allowing toxic ash from that city to be dumped in
Haiti.
   Claude presented no proof to substantiate his charges.
   ``The Information Ministry has noticed a tendency of the Haitian
media to not control its language when releasing news or
interviews,'' says the communique signed by Information Minister
Roger Savain and broadcast by radio stations.
   ``There is also a tendency to emit erroneous information under
the pretext of citing the foreign news media as a source,'' it says.
   ``Though the Constitution guarantees the freedom of speech ...
its authors also made clear what were the limits beyond which
freedom of speech becomes an abuse,'' the statement continues.
``Cynical insinuations, false or libelous accusations and serious
public insults are intolerable cases of abuse of the freedom of
speech.
   ``The Ministry of Information ... invites the Haitian and
foreign press to respect in the strictest manner the Constitution
and law.''
   The Constitution says a journalist cannot be censored, but has
the ``duty to verify the authenticity and accuracy of his
information.''
   During anti-government strikes and demonstrations in July and
August, radio stations were firebombed and riddled with bullets. At
least four Haitian reporters were shot and wounded by soldiers
during the period, and soldiers shot at foreign reporters in at
least 10 cases.
   On the eve of the the aborted Nov. 29 national elections, in
which gunmen and soldiers killed 34 people at polling stations,
witnesses saw uniformed soldiers blow up the transmittor tower of
the Catholic Church's Radio Soleil.
   Gunmen shot and killed at point blank range a Dominican
photographer, Carlos Grullon, during the election day violence.
   No gunman or soldier has been brought to trial for the shootings.
   Paul's unit, the widely feared Dessalines Barracks, is
responsible for virtually all army repression and killings of
demonstrators last year. Soldiers from the 700-man batallion were
also seen in the streets during the aborted Nov. 29 elections.
   Manigat was elected president Jan. 17 in balloting boycotted by
the opposition and marred by widespread irregularities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880309-0070 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 0421EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-SUP--Polls     03-09 0845</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SUP--Polls,840</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gore's Gain is Gephardt's Loss; Reagan Ties Aid Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Albert Gore Jr.'s do-or-die Southern strategy
succeeded at the expense of Democratic rival Richard Gephardt,
while Republican George Bush's association with the Reagan
administration carried him to his Super Tuesday sweep, pollsters
say.
   Michael Dukakis maintained his Democratic front-runner status on
the strength of victories in Texas and Florida, but Jesse Jackson
bolstered his nearly monolithic black support with additional
backing from whites, the analysts said.
   Gore's campaign did what it had to do in the South. The
Tennessee senator, who eschewed early contests in Iowa and New
Hampshire in favor of the 14 Southern and border states up for
grabs Tuesday, won five of them.
   ``It worked. He cleaned up in the South,'' said Warren Mitofsky,
chief pollster for CBS News. ``But he's got to prove it in the next
couple of weeks in Illinois and Wisconsin. He's got to show support
beyond the South.''
   Gore did well mainly at the expense of Gephardt, the Missouri
congressman, who won only his home state. Gore and Dukakis had
accused Gephardt of waffling on the issues, and exit polls
indicated the charges stuck.
   Gore won among conservative Democrats, with 35 percent, ABC News
exit polls said. He also found help in his Tennessee roots: Of the
52 percent of Southern voters born in the South, Gore was backed by
nearly a third, while Dukakis got 20 percent.
   ``If Gore's going to be the only conservative who goes on, then
he's got a shot,'' said Sheldon Gawiser, poll analyst for NBC News.
``The real question is, can he take his show on the road? The jury
is out on that.''
   One problem for Gore is the relative dearth of conservative
Democratic primary voters outside the South. ABC said conservatives
made up 27 percent of the Southern Democrats, considerably more
than is likely elsewhere.
   But Jackson demonstrated an ability to drain liberal and
moderate votes from Dukakis, possibly leaving Gore an opening to
siphon off a plurality in some states, Gawiser said.
   ``If Jackson continues to cut up the liberal vote with
Dukakis,'' he said, ``Gore can score.''
   Jackson won about 95 percent of the black vote in the South, but
also improved his showing among white voters compared with his
support in the 1984 campaign. ABC said he won 8 percent of white
votes in the region; the CBS News-New York Times poll put it at 9
percent.
   NBC, which gave state-by-state results, said Jackson's white
support ranged from 4 percent in Tennessee to 15 percent in
Virginia and 19 percent in Massachusetts, Dukakis' home state.
   Dukakis stitched together support from older voters, Hispanics,
Jews and moderates for his Southern victories. In Florida, 47
percent of Democratic voters were 60 and over and 52 percent of
them backed Dukakis, the CBS-Times poll said.
   The Massachusetts governor also did well with older voters
across the South. He split the moderates with Jackson, and Jackson
won more liberal Democrats, but ABC said Dukakis won 78 percent of
the Jewish vote across the region, compared with 3 percent for
Jackson.
   NBC said Dukakis was backed by 52 percent of Hispanic voters in
Texas, who made up 18 percent of the Democratic turnout. Dukakis
speaks fluent Spanish and had courted the Hispanic vote.
   Moreover, Dukakis had the best image among the Democratic
candidates, showing a 60 percent favorable rating compared with 31
percent unfavorable, the CBS-Times poll said.
   ``He's demonstrated appeal across the country. He's a very
strong candidate and he's got to be the leading contender at the
moment,'' Gawiser said.
   The hardest hit of the Democrats was Gephardt, whose
get-tough-on-trade message failed to strike a chord. Only 12
percent of Southern Democrats rated the issue as important, the
CBS-Times poll said, and even those went mainly for Gore, 35
percent to Gephardt's 21 percent.
   On the Republican side, Bush benefited from his credentials in
the Reagan administration. In some states as many as 80 percent of
the Republican voters approved of President Reagan, and 60 percent
of them backed Bush, the CBS-Times poll said.
   Bush also maintained favor among conservative Republicans and
among the one-third of GOP voters who rated experience as
important; nearly 80 percent of them went for the vice president,
polls said.
   Dole fared better with independents who voted Republican, a
relatively small group in the conservative-dominated South,
Mitofsky said.
   The Rev. Pat Robertson failed to break out of his core support
of evangelical Christians, and Rep. Jack Kemp of New York fared
poorly in all categories, polls said.
   With the depth of his support, ``It's going to be very, very,
very difficult for Bush to be defeated at this stage of the game,''
Gawiser said. ``Unless he makes some horrendous mistake, he's not
going to lose.''
   Results of the state exit polls had error margins of about 5
percentage points either way; the CBS-Times poll results for the
region as a whole had a smaller margin of sampling error, about 2
percentage points.
</TEXT>
