<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Dukakis, Jackson Lead Hawaii Caucus Poll</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with Dukakis leading in late returns; No
pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis held a narrow
lead over Jesse Jackson in Hawaii's Democratic presidential
caucuses Tuesday.
   With 152 of 284 precincts or 54 percent reporting, Dukakis had
1,152 votes or 48 percent; Jackson had 1,045 votes or 43 percent;
Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt had 55 votes or 2 percent, and
Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr. had 26 votes or 1 percent.
   About 30,000 Democrats were eligible to participate, but fewer
than 5,000 were expected to attend the precinct meetings. And most
of the 2,000 new members signed up by Jackson's campaign were
expected to show up.
   Gov. John Waihee, who earlier had urged that the state's
delegation remain uncommitted, endorsed Dukakis last week, as did
Sens. Daniel Inouye and Spark Matsunaga.
   Twenty delegates were at stake in the caucus voting.
   Jackson was the only candidate to visit Hawaii.
</TEXT>
