<1ST_LINE>r p PM-SUP--Missouri     03-09 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SUP--Missouri,0361</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Missouri Stings to Dole, Gives Gephardt Only Win</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN BALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush stung Bob
Dole with a narrow victory in the Missouri GOP presidential
primary, crushing the Kansas senator's last hope to win a key Super
Tuesday state.
   Democratic Rep. Richard Gephardt easily won his home state with
57 percent of the vote, but it was his only victory of the night.
His closest rival, Jesse Jackson, took 21 percent of the vote.
   The Bush victory in Dole's back yard went down to the wire, with
Bush pulling ahead only when final returns were reported from St.
Louis County, a Republican stronghold.
   ``Being in Missouri, right next to Kansas, I can't tell you how
sweet this victory is,'' said Bush campaigner Sissy Chamberlain.
``I'm not being vindictive, but we wanted to win it for the vice
president and we were able to squeak it out.''
   With 3,878 of 3,954 precincts, or 98 percent, reporting, Bush
had 167,991 votes, or 42 percent, and Dole had 163,394 or 41
percent; Pat Robertson had 44,334, or 11 percent, and New York Rep.
Jack Kemp had 14,125, or 4 percent.
   In the Democratic race, with 3,919 of 3,954 precincts, or 99
percent, reporting, Gephardt had 307,877 votes or 58 percent and
Jackson had 106,619 votes or 20 percent. Massachusetts Gov. Michael
Dukakis had 61,645 votes or 12 percent, Illinois Sen. Paul Simon
had 21,622 votes or 4 percent; and Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr.
had 14,686 votes or 3 percent.
   The News Election Service said Bush received 22 delegates, Dole
received 18 and seven were uncommitted, but state GOP officials
predicted a final tabulation would show Bush with 20 delegates,
Dole with 18 and nine uncommitted.
   NES said the discrepancy resulted from not being able to
reprogram its election tabulation computer to accommodate a change
in the complicated district delegate assignment formula.
   Neither Kemp or Robertson qualified for any of Missouri's 47 GOP
delegates at stake.
   The NES results showed Gephardt with 62 delegates, Jackson with
14 and Dukakis with one.
</TEXT>
