<1ST_LINE>r p PM-SUP--Virginia     03-09 0354</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SUP--Virginia,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Crushes GOP Opponents; Jackson Takes Delegate Majority</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE TAYLOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Jesse Jackson hammered the
opposition in Virginia's first presidential primary, while Vice
President George Bush swept to another easy victory in his 16-state
clean-up.
   Jackson's campaign leaders had expected a sterling performance
Tuesday from their candidate, who carried the state's presidential
caucuses in 1984.
   ``We laid the groundwork,'' said Mary Cox, Jackson's Virginia
coordinator. ``Our goal was to expand at least 10 to 12 percent
beyond our natural black base, and we've successfully done that.''
   With 1,967 of 1,986 precincts or 99 percent reporting, Jackson
had 161,704 votes or 45 percent; Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr. had
81,139 or 23 percent; Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis 78,141 or
22 percent; and Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt 16,082 or 4 percent.
   In the Republican race, with 2,298 of 2,391 precincts or 96
percent reporting, Bush had 141,743 votes or 60 percent; Kansas
Sen. Bob Dole had 51,239 or 22 percent, and Virginia native Pat
Robertson had 29,326 or 12 percent. New York Rep. Jack Kemp had
11,490 or 5 percent.
   Jackson, relying on strong support in Hampton Roads and the
Richmond area, overcame Gore's numbers in southwestern Virginia and
Dukakis' power base in Virginia's Washington, D.C., suburbs.
   With 75 of the state Democratic Party's 85 national convention
delegates riding on the outcome, Jackson appeared to have won 37
delegates to 22 for Gore and 16 for Dukakis.
   No GOP delegates were at stake; the 50 national convention
delegates are allocated through local caucuses and mass meetings.
   Boyd Marcus, state coordinator for the Bush campaign, said he
would have been pleased with a mid-40 percent showing. The 2-to-1
win over Dole ``has been the most surprising thing,'' he said.
   Robertson, a former TV evangelist, placed third even in his home
city of Virginia Beach, a showing his supporters had anticipated.
   Anne Kincaid, Robertson's Virginia coordinator, said the former
evangelist ``expected to run third because we hadn't done anything
to broaden his base of support. ... Pat's going to stay in this
thing right through the convention.''
</TEXT>
