<1ST_LINE>u p AM-SUP--Nevada 1stLd-Writethru a0669 03-09 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SUP--Nevada, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0669,0259</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gore, Jackson in Close Contest</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates throughout with 60 percent tallied</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CARSON CITY, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson and Tennessee Sen. Albert
Gore were tied in an early tally of presidential preferences of
Nevadans attending the Democratic party's Super Tuesday caucuses.
   With 60 percent of about 6,000 expected preference listings
counted, Jackson and Gore had 30 percent each, while Massachusetts
Gov. Michael Dukakis had 25 percent.
   The balance included 13 percent uncommitted, 1 percent for
Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt, and the remaining 1 percent balance
split between Sen. Paul Simon and former Sen. Gary Hart.
   Caucus goers gave Jackson 1,111 votes, Gore 1,102 and Dukakis
951, while 479 were uncommited. Gephardt had 44, Simon 14 and Hart
5.
   Of Jackson's strong showing, state Democratic Chairman Beecher
Avants said, ``It was a real surprise.''
   He had said before the caucuses that he sensed no movement in
the Jackson campaign in Nevada. He noted that Jackson had
considerable support among blacks who represent about 7 percent of
the state's registered voters.
   Gore claimed support from prominent Nevada Democrats such as
Sen. Harry Reid, former Gov. Grant Sawyer and Assembly Speaker Joe
Dini.
   A last-minute mail campaign and telephone blitz were mounted by
backers of Gore and Dukakis. Those two and Jackson made personal
appearances during the campaign.
   Sixteen delegates were at stake in Nevada, to be selected at a
state convention in May. The caucuses were the first stage in
selection of those who will attend the convention.
</TEXT>
