<DOCNO> AP880309-0078 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 0452EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-SUP-Alabama     03-09 0323</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SUP-Alabama,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Edges Gore In Alabama; Bush Wins In Landslide</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KENDAL WEAVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson narrowly beat Tennessee
Sen. Albert Gore Jr. in Alabama's Democratic primary, while Vice
President George Bush outpolled the entire Republican field by
nearly 2-1.
   Bush claimed 35 of Alabama's 38 Republican National Convention
delegates, and Dole the remaining three; Jackson's showing would
give him 30 and Gore would get 26 of the state's 56 Democratic
delegates.
   Both parties drew a record primary turnout.
   With 3,460 of 4,304 precincts, or 80 percent, reporting in the
Republican race, Bush had 124,828 votes or 64 percent; Robert Dole
had 31,562 or 16 percent, Pat Robertson had 27,594 or 15 percent,
and New York Rep. Jack Kemp had 9,525, or 5 percent.
   ``The people of this country appreciate that he (Bush) has
worked shoulder-to-shoulder with President Reagan,'' said Bush's
Alabama campaign director, Doug Adair. ``They want the Reagan
revolution to continue.''
   In the Democratic race, with 3,510 of 4,304 precincts, or 82
percent, reporting in the Democratic primary, Jackson had 159,681
votes or 44 percent to Gore's 134,053 votes, or 37 percent.
Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis got 28,050 votes or 8 percent,
Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt 26,516, or 7 percent, and Gary Hart
6,586 or 2 percent.
   ``We expected it to be close,'' said Youlanda Curtis, Jackson's
state coordinator. Jackson, the lopsided favorite in black
precincts, drew a small but apparently critical number of white
votes in his narrow margin over Gore.
   The Democratic voter turnout for Super Tuesday was expected at
near 450,000; the old record was 423,000 in 1984. The GOP record
for a presidential primary was 211,000 in 1980; more than 230,000
were estimated voting Tuesday.
   Jackson's victory was a landmark in voting rights history in
Alabama, the site of the Selma-to-Montgomery march that led to the
1965 Voting Rights Act, opening the ballot box to blacks across the
South.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880309-0079 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 0513EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-SUP-South Bjt   03-09 0799</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SUP-South, Bjt,780</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gore Strategy Works but South Still Far From Solid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Albert Gore Jr. bet on Dixie and won but the South still
proved anything but solid and allowed two other Democratic
presidential candidates to claim victory as well.
   Jesse Jackson exulted in the success of a ``new Southern
message'' and boasted: ``We've gone from a narrow mainstream to a
broad-based river.''
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis gained bragging rights of his
own with victories in the two biggest Super Tuesday states: Texas
and Florida.
   The result was a fractured outcome that partially served the
aims of the architects of Super Tuesday, who wanted a moderate
Democrat and maybe even a Southern one to emerge from the primaries
across the South.
   Gore ran as that moderate and his victories in five states
propel him to the next round of primaries. ``Super Tuesday
succeeded,'' said a Gore booster, former Gov. Charles Robb of
Virginia.
   But Dukakis' six victories and Jackson's five were potent
reminders of the law of unintended consequences in politics. And
the evening's biggest winner was a Republican _ George Bush, who
won 16 out of 16 primaries to take a commanding lead in the GOP
race.
   ``Super Tuesday is not what I had hoped it would be,'' declared
Charles Whitehead, the Democratic Party chief in Florida. ``If I
had to speculate, I would say that there will be some changes
before the next election four years from now.''
   Sen. Bob Graham of Florida said, ``It's ironic that the governor
of Massachusetts most perceptively figured out the significance of
the new rules in the South.''
   Added Texan Jim Wright, the House speaker: ``If it was designed
to produce a unified conservative Southern candidate, I would say
those who dreamed it up outsmarted themselves.''
   Still, the most dire prediction by Southern Democrats didn't
materialize either: an exodus of disgruntled Democratic voters to
the competing Republican primaries.
   Southern Republicans had hoped to capitalize on the Democrats'
division by attracting Democratic voters in the eight states where
cross-over voting was permitted. The prospect even led Lee Atwater,
Republican George Bush's campaign manager, to taunt before the
balloting that the Democratic designed Super Tuesday would prove
``the political boo-boo of the decade.''
   As it turned out, crossovers to the GOP proved largely
insignificant.
   Gore established himself as a solid contender by winning five
states: Tennessee, Kentucky, Arkansas, North Carolina and Oklahoma.
   Jackson won Virginia, Georgia, Louisiana, Alabama and
Mississippi. With overwhelming black support and a divided white
vote, he moved far beyond his 1984 campaign which won only one
state.
   ``We're the underdog with the biggest bite,'' Jackson said.
   Dukakis won in his home state of Massachusetts as well as in
neighboring Rhode Island, in Maryland, Idaho and in the two
mega-states of Florida and Texas.
   Gore immediately looked ahead to the next round of industrial
states of the North _ where he now must show he is more than a
regional candidate.
   ``I am not a Southern candidate,'' declared the man who ran as a
son of the South in the Super Tuesday contests.
   ``I'm a national candidate who's a Southerner and proud of it,''
Gore said.
   He was leaving today for Chicago before dashing to South
Carolina, where he hopes to pick up delegates at that state's
Democratic caucuses on Saturday.
   After succeeding with a strategy that pummeled rival Richard
Gephardt with a torrent of negative ads, Gore pointed to Dukakis as
his chief rival.
   ``This is becoming a two-person race between Michael Dukakis and
Al Gore,'' Gore said. ``It's a race between the politics of the
past and the politics of the future.''
   Gore began suggesting that Dukakis has an ``electability''
problem _ that despite winning the two biggest states of the South
in the Democratic primary, he is too Northern, too liberal and too
ethnic to carry those states or the region against the Republcans.
   Dukakis scoffed at the claim, noting that he won more delegates
and more votes than Gore on the Tennessean's chosen battlefield.
   With the Democratic field splintered into three parts, Gore,
Jackson and Dukakis all got big chunks of delegates.
   ``This has been a great night for us,'' said Dukakis. ``To be
able to take Texas and Florida, the two big ones, and to do well
across the board demonstrates that this is a national candidacy, a
national campaign.''
   Gephardt blamed his failure on a lack of money and vowed to go
on to the next round of primaries. He criticized the Super Tuesday
process with 20 states voting on a single day _ an arrangement that
left his money-strapped campaign hard pressed to keep up.
   ``I think maybe it was a disservice to the voters to put 20
states on one day,'' he said.
</TEXT>
