<1ST_LINE>r i PM-UN-SouthAfrica     03-09 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-South Africa,0381</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S., Britain, Veto Worldwide Economic Sanctions On South Africa</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and Britain vetoed a
Security Council resolution to impose economic sanctions on South
Africa, saying such mandatory penalties would stifle chances for
internal reform.
   The measure was aimed at putting pressure on South Africa to end
apartheid, that country's system of legalized racial segregation.
It would have imposed mandatory worldwide sanctions, including an
oil embargo, for a year.
   It failed by a vote of 10-2, with France, West Germany and Japan
abstaining.
   Prior to the vote Tuesday, all speakers deplored white
minority-led South Africa's state of emergency and recent
restrictions on anti-apartheid groups.
   But British Ambassador Sir Crispin Tickell and U.S. Ambassador
Herbert Okun both told the council mandatory sanctions would
cripple the chances for an ``internal'' dialogue in South Africa.
   The West German envoy, Alexander Count York von Wartenburg, gave
a similar reason for abstaining.
   But he also warned South Africa that the West German abstention
is ``a signal that my government's patience is not inexhaustible.''
   The French and Japanese envoys did not explain their abstention.
   The resolution called for a one-year ban on export and sale of
oil to South Africa, on iron and steel imports, on the sale of all
South African coins and on investment and loans. It also called for
an end to all promotion and support for trade with South Africa.
   The United States, Britain and West Germany have vetoed similar
measures in the past. The United States and Britain are among the
five permanent members with veto power. The others are China,
France and the Soviet Union.
   African and Asian nations pushed hard for the sanctions to
punish South Africa for its Feb. 24 ban on activities by major anti
anti-apartheid groups, and to force it to dismantle apartheid,
under which the 26 million blacks have no say in national affairs.
   South Africa's 5 million whites control the government and the
economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health
services.
   The council members belonging to the movement of nations
professing non-alliance with either superpower _ Argentina, Nepal,
Senegal, Yugoslavia and Zambia _ sponsored the resolution.
</TEXT>
