<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A Wet Day On The Gulf Coast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy showers drenched the Gulf Coast today from southeast Texas
to northwest Florida, triggering flash flood watches in much of
southern Louisiana.
   Rain also fell from the lower Mississippi Valley to Georgia.
Scattered showers fell along Texas' Rio Grande Valley, the lower
Ohio Valley, parts of Illinois, northern Indiana and southern
Michigan.
   Light rain fell in the Northwest and snow advisories were in
effect for the Cascade Mountains of Oregon and Washington, where
about 6 inches of snow was expected. A gale warning was posted for
the Washington coast, and a wind advisory for gusts up to 50 mph
issued for eastern Washington.
   As the storm moving through the Northwest heads southeast, snow
was expected to return to the central Rockies. A winter storm watch
was posted for tonight for the mountains of northern Utah and
northern and central Colorado.
   Skies were partly cloudy or cloudy in much of the eastern third
of the nation, and clear skies prevailed across the Plains states
and into the Southwest.
   Temperatures early today were in the 50s as far north as Detroit
and Buffalo, N.Y., while 20s were common over the northern and
central Plains states.
   Temperatures across the northern and mid-Atlantic states were
mostly in the 30s, but were near the 60-degree mark in Kentucky. In
southern Florida, temperatures were in the 70s. The western third
of the nation also had mild temperatures, with a 50-degree reading
at Boise, Idaho, at midnight.
   Today's forecast called for rain and thunderstorms from the
central Gulf Coast states and Tennessee Valley to northern Florida,
Georgia and the Carolinas; numerous rain showers from the Ohio
Valley across the middle Atlantic Coast, New York state and much of
New England; freezing rain, sleet and snow in northern New England;
and rain and mountain snow from the northern Pacific Coast through
the northern half of the Rockies.
   Today's high temperatures were expected in the 50s or 60s in
much of the nation; the 30s and 40s from the upper Mississippi
Valley to the upper Great Lakes and from upstate New York to
northern and central New England; 70s and 80s from Southern
California to the desert Southwest and in Florida; and the 70s in
southwest Texas, southeast Georgia and coastal Carolinas.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 7
degrees at Houlton, Maine, to 75 degrees at Key West, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 54 rain; Boston 35 fair; Buffalo 54 windy;
Charleston, S.C. 64 cloudy; Cincinnati 55 showers; Cleveland 56
showers; Detroit 45 foggy; Miami 73 cloudy; New York 38 fair;
Philadelphia 35 fair; Pittsburgh 53 cloudy; Portland, Maine 35
partly cloudy; Washington 40 cloudy.
   _Central: Bismarck 22 fair; Chicago 37 cloudy; Dallas-Fort Worth
46 cloudy; Denver 31 fair; Des Moines 29 fair; Indianapolis 44
cloudy; Kansas City 30 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 35 cloudy;
Nashville 54 cloudy; New Orleans 62 cloudy; St. Louis 41 partly
cloudy.
   _West: Albuquerque 37 fair; Anchorage 35 cloudy; Las Vegas 46
fair; Los Angeles 55 foggy; Phoenix 57 fair; Salt Lake City 36
fair; San Francisco 53 windy; Seattle 43 partly cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 28 cloudy; Toronto 37 cloudy.
</TEXT>
