<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     03-09 0309</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Steadies, Gold Slightly Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar steadied against European
currencies and the Japanese yen today after falling sharply against
a surging British pound. Gold was unchanged to slightly lower.
   In London, the British pound was quoted at $1.8340, compared
with $1.8415 Tuesday, and eased down from a high of 3.09 West
German marks to 3.065.
   ``We think the pound will stabilize around these levels,'' said
a trader with a Frankfurt bank. ``Its rise was too sharp and too
fast.''
   The pound has gained a massive 10 cents this week, powered by
high British interest rates. Although the Bank of England has
intervened to stem the rise, it was strengthened further by Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher ruling out a cut in interest rates.
   In Tokyo the dollar rose 0.28 yen to a closing 128.08. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 128.23 yen.
   A dealer in Rome speculated that Vice President George Bush's
triumph in the Super Tuesday primaries may also have calmed
markets, because he is perceived here as an anti-protectionist.
   The dollar, trading in a narrow range, was little changed from
late Tuesday. Some rates:
   _1.6718 West German marks, up from 1.6668
   _1.3810 Swiss francs, up from 1.3790
   _5.6590 French francs, down from 5.6625
   _1.8774 Dutch guilders, down from 1.8780
   _1.233.00 Italian lire, down from 1,234.00
   _1.2545 Canadian dollar, up from 1.2524
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $435.80 a troy ounce,
compared with late Tuesday's $438.10. At mid-morning today, the
city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of
$436.10.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $435.80, down from $436.50 late
Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose one cent to close at a bid
$438.01.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.28 a troy
ounce, down from Tuesday's $6.36.
</TEXT>
