<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 0627EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-HawaiiCaucus     03-09 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hawaii Caucus,0263</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Wins Hawaii Democratic Presidential Poll</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis rode an
endorsement by Hawaii's top elected Democrats to a narrow victory
over Jesse Jackson in a presidential preference poll at the state's
Democratic Party caucuses.
   With all but about a dozen of 283 precincts reporting, Dukakis
had 2,026 votes, while Jackson had 1,470. None of the other
candidates or the choice of ``uncommitted'' had enough votes to
qualify for any of the state's 20 pledged delegates to the
Democratic National Convention.
   Party officials were analyzing the results today to determine
the allocation of the pledged delegates, but it appeared Dukakis
would get 12 delegates and Jackson 8.
   In endorsing Dukakis, Gov. John Waihee was joined by Sens.
Daniel Inouye and Spark Matsunaga, Rep. Daniel Akaka, Lt. Gov.
Benjamin Cayetano, and the mayors of Hawaii and Kauai islands.
   Waihee said he was not surprised by Jackson's strong showing and
said it was ``healthy for the Democratic Party.''
   Jackson supporters signed up about 2,000 new party members prior
to the caucuses.
   The Jackson campaign claimed victory with their strong showing
against the endorsement of the Democratic establishment.
   ``Jackson's showing in Hawaii puts an end to the belief that
Jesse Jackson is not electable, and to the belief that Jackson can
win only in states with large black populations,'' said Richard
Port, manager of the Jackson campaign in Hawaii.
   The votes of other candidates were Richard Gephardt, 83; Paul
Simon, 46; Albert Gore, 41; Gary Hart, 83; and ``uncommitted,'' 183.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
