<1ST_LINE>r p PM-SUP--Samoa     03-09 0200</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SUP--Samoa,0208</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Samoa Democratic Convention Delegates Split</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PAGO PAGO, American Samoa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Only 36 Democrats took part
presidential preference caucuses in this South Pacific territory,
dividing their support between Massachusetts Governor Michael
Dukakis and Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt.
   The Democrats rejected a call by party leaders in American Samoa
to endorse an uncommitted slate of delegates to the Democratic
National Convention.
   American Samoa was the smallest player in Super Tuesday, with
three delegates available and about 300 Democrats eligible to take
part in the meetings.
   National Committeeman Glenn Jones said 36 Democrats attended the
caucuses. He said few voters turned out probably because the
territory has no electoral votes in the presidential election.
   Of the 36 votes cast, 14 went for Dukakis, eight for Gephardt,
and two for Jesse Jackson. The remaining 12 were uncommitted.
   That means that Dukakis and Gephardt will have one delegate
each, and the third member of the American Samoa delegation will be
uncommitted.
   Jones said that of all the candidates, only Jackson's campaign
had contacted party officials for convention support.
   ``We would rather wait to see where the trend is going ... who
doesn't make the cut,'' said Party Chairman Utu R.M. Sinagege.
</TEXT>
