<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 0715EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MoneyBags     03-09 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Money Bags,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drivers Cash In On Armored Car Mishap</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATALINA ORTIZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least $1.7 million fell into the street
from an armored truck, and when a crowd gathered up the cash at
least three people made off with $500,000, police said.
   Two unidentified men and a woman disappeared Tuesday afternoon
with cash-stuffed money bags scattered from a crate that fell out
of the moving Loomis Armored Inc. truck in the city's Mission
District.
   ``(They) decided they were going to take advantage of what
happened, threw the bags into their cars and left,'' said police
officer Harry Soulette.
   Soulette said he was flagged down by the Loomis truck driver,
who was unaware of the loss until a motorist honked his horn and
told him the door of the truck was ajar, Soulette said.
   Two blocks back, a crowd gathered around the crate, which postal
worker Daniel Higginbotham moved to the sidewalk. Some people
helped him gather the bags, recovering about $1.2 million, police
said. Some didn't.
   ``There was a gentleman from the Post Office grabbing bags of
money out of people's hands and putting them back in the (crate),''
Soulette said. ``At least three people looked at him and told him
what he could do with his suggestion.'' Others may have taken a few
bags and fled on foot, police said. It's not a case of finders
keepers, Soulette said. If caught, the money-grubbers face grand
theft charges. ``That's a felony. My advice to them is to turn it
in,'' Soulette said.
   Witnesses gave detailed descriptions of the two men and the
woman, who each took several bags, and their cars, Soulette said.
   One man picked up two sacks and returned them immediately to the
company, police said. Louis A. Lopez, of Daly City, drove straight
to Loomis to hand over two bags containing $40,100 in cash,
Soulette said.
   Neither Lopez nor Higginbotham could be reached for comment
Tuesday night.
   The money had come from different banks and businesses. The
truck was on the way back to Loomis and was several blocks away
when the door, which may not have been closed securely, sprang
open, Soulette said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
