<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Britain-Panama     03-09 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Panama,0398</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Britain Demands Envoy Waive Immunity, Hints at Expulsion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain demanded today that the Panamanian
ambassador waive his diplomatic immunity and face police
questioning about a raid he authorized to seize control of his
country's London consulate.
   The Foreign Office said it expected an answer from Ambassador
Guillermo Vega by the end of the day, and warned that expulsion
``remains an option.''
   Vega was summoned to the Foreign Office twice Tuesday to explain
Monday night's seizure, an extension of the struggle for control of
Panama's government.
   Representatives of Vega, accompanied by hired security guards,
crashed a Land Rover through the glass doors of the consulate on
Fleet Street and occupied the offices.
   Vega supports Panamanian strongman Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega,
who engineered the ouster of President Eric Delvalle Feb. 26.
Consul Eduardo Arango, whose offices were seized, is loyal to
Delvalle.
   The Foreign Office said it asked Vega and embassy counselor
Jorge E. Constantino to waive their diplomatic immunity so that
police can question them about the incident.
   ``We haven't given him a deadline as such. We made it clear that
we want to hear (a reply) today,'' said a spokesman who, under
British civil service rules, cannot be identified.
   Under international law, accredited diplomats are immune from
police action but can be expelled if the host government believes
them guilty of misconduct.
   Seven Britons were arrested and charged with public order
offenses for alleged roles in the consulate raid.
   The Times quoted Foreign Office Minister Timothy Eggar as
saying: ``What is at issue here is whether any Panamanian Embassy
official has taken the law into his own hands. The British
government will not tolerate any such action.''
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher told Parliament Tuesday:
``Differences of opinion should not be fought out on London
streets.''
   Vega has said the raid had his authority, and that the consulate
was ``full of outsiders to the Panamanian government.''
   Control of the Panamanian Embassy in Washington is also in
dispute.
   Delvalle was ousted hours after he ordered Noriega to step down.
The general was indicted in Florida last month on federal drug
trafficking charges.
   The Reagan administration says it still considers Delvalle
Panama's chief of state. The Thatcher government has not stated a
position on the matter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
