<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 0743EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-ShuttleAward     03-09 0259</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Shuttle Award,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Engineer Who Tried to Prevent The Challenger Launch Hailed For
Integrity</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The engineer who tried to prevent the launch of
the space shuttle Challenger before its fatal 1986 launch has been
honored as nation's the most courageous and most ethical engineer.
   Allan J. McDonald, a vice president of Morton Thiokol Corp.,
received an honorary award Tuesday from Design News magazine, said
Steve Thompson, the publisher of the magazine.
   ``Al McDonald was the one guy who tried to stop it,'' said
Thompson, who presented the magazine's awards at a banquet in
Chicago.
   ``He had the courage to stand up to the whole world and say
`look, you can't do this' _ that's why he's special.''
   A Presidential commission has blamed the Challenger disaster on
a flaw in a booster rocket built by Morton Thiokol. Seven
astronauts died in the explosion.
   During a speech after receiving the award, McDonald, 50, said he
hopes the Challenger disaster does not leave the nation's space
program paralyzed.
   ``My biggest concern is that we've lost the nerve to ever fly
anything again,'' McDonald said. ``We think we have to have
complete safety. I don't think we will ever have that.''
   McDonald said the space shuttle will be ready for its next
scheduled launch in August.
   ``One thing worse than failure is not to try,'' he said.
   Also honored Tuesday was Elbert Rutan, who designed the Voyager,
the first aircraft to fly around the world without refueling. Rutan
was voted best engineer by the magazine's 750,000 readers, Thompson
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
