<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 0804EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-StolenMonet     03-09 0475</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Stolen Monet,0488</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stolen Monet Recovered At Post Office</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MARSHALLTOWN, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man who found what police believe
to be a valuable stolen painting by French impressionist Claude
Monet stolen says the artwork appears to be damaged.
   ``You could see places where it was rolled up very tightly and
maybe flattened. It had lines running down it from that, and some
of the oil paint was peeled off in places,'' said Charles Polley,
postmaster at LeGrand who found the painting Tuesday morning in a
mail drop-off box.
   Local police, the FBI and the international police agency
Interpol have been searching for the oil painting since it was cut
out of its frame at the Fisher Community Center on March 19, 1987.
   The painting, ``Fishing boats in front of the cliffs at
Etretat,'' was insured for $175,000 by St. Paul Fire and Marine
Insurance Co. The canvas was painted by Monet around 1891.
   The painting was rolled up and bound by two rubber bands when
Polley found it mixed in with other pieces of mail. He said it was
dropped sometime after 3 p.m. Monday and before 7:30 a.m. Tuesday
when he opened the mailbox.
   ``I thought it was trash at first _ but it sure wasn't trash,''
Polley said. ``It had the look of canvas, and I looked at the edges
and knew exactly what it was.''
   When the painting was cut out of its frame, which was rigged to
an alarm system in the police department, the thief didn't make a
clean cut along the bottom of the frame, leaving a jagged tear in
the painting.
   ``I called just about everyone but Interpol,'' said Polley.
``You never know what a day will bring.''
   Lt. Darrell Templeton said at a news conference that he unrolled
part of the left edge of the painting _ the side that shows the
cliffs _ and to him it appears the painting is the original.
   He said the FBI will be contacted, and examiners hired by the
insurance company will have to determine for certain that the
painting is the stolen Monet.
   Templeton said it was a frustrating investigation involving
countless telephone calls and false leads. But he said articles
about the theft probably kept it from being sold on the black
market, ``because it was an odd way of getting it back.''
   Templeton said police have no suspects other than a white male,
about 6-foot-2 or 6-3 and weighing about 250 pounds, who was seen
cutting the painting out of its frame.
   Rex Ryden, in charge of the Fisher Foundation, wasn't sure yet
how the insurance company will react, since the insurance was paid.
   He said the painting will have to be inspected for damage and
whether it can be restored.
   ``It will be a drawn-out procedure,'' Ryden said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
