<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ewes imported from Britain, New
Zealand and Australia for breeding are being sheepish about sex,
veterinary officials said.
   Local rams are not interested either, apparently because they
like their mates petite and find the foreigners too big. The coy
ewes may be disoriented by the tropical weather, because they are
used to four seasons.
   Agriculture Minister Sanusi Junid has suggested keeping the
animals in the dark, an idea the Veterinary Services Department is
taking seriously, Director-General Ahmad Mustaffa Babjee said at a
conference today.
   ``The imported sheep should be put in a dark room at a certain
time of the year for some time. When they come out into the light
they may think it is another season and get into the mood to
mate,'' Sanusi said in a speech to the Commonwealth Veterinary
Officers Conference.
   About 20,000 sheep are imported annually for breeding as part of
a government plan to have 1 million head of sheep in Malaysia by
the year 1990.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Italian soldiers will have to brave the weather
without umbrellas, Defense Minister Valerio Zanone has decided.
   Zanone, a Liberal, said equipment issued to Italian soldiers
provides adequate protection in the average climatic conditions of
this Mediterranean country.
   The Radical Party had suggested that Italy follow the U.S.
military's decision to authorize use of umbrellas.
</TEXT>
