<HEAD>Defendant Says He'll Plead Guilty To Seditious Conspiracy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT SMITH, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A white supremacist accused of plotting
to overthrow the government said he would plead guilty after a
judge refused to suppress a statement the man gave to authorities.
   Bruce Pierce had sought dismissal of the statement he gave to
FBI agents after he was arrested in Georgia in 1985. When U.S.
District Judge Morris Arnold refused, Pierce rose in the courtroom.
   ``I'm going to plead guilty, if that's the court's decision,''
Pierce said Tuesday.
   Arnold told him to discuss the matter with his attorney, Bennett
Nolan, and after a conference with Pierce and other defendants,
Nolan said that Pierce would make a final decision this week on
whether to plead guilty.
   Pierce and nine other white supremacists are charged with
sedition. Five defendants are accused of conspiring to kill a
federal judge and an FBI agent, and two are accused of interstate
transportation of stolen money.
   Pierce is serving sentences totaling 250 years in prison _ 100
years for racketeering and 150 years for violating the civil rights
of outspoken Jewish radio talk show host Alan Berg, who was machine
gunned to death in Denver.
   Wayne Manis, an FBI agent, had been scheduled to testify Tuesday
that Pierce confessed several crimes to him while Pierce was in
federal custody in Atlanta.
   Pierce had argued that his statement was not made voluntarily
and should be suppressed. He said agents threatened to have his
wife arrested and put his three children in foster homes if he
refused to make the statement.
   Arnold said he decided the statement was made voluntarily.
</TEXT>
