<NOTE>Eds: Updates in first 5 grafs with Gore comments today, picking up
3rd graf pvs, He was</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore, who vaulted
into the front rank of the Democratic pack with a strong Super
Tuesday showing, said today that ``people were responding to my
message,'' not his Southern background.
   ``We won in the West also, and sooner or later it's going to
stop being a surprise,'' Gore said on ABC-TV's ``Good Morning
America.''
   ``I am not a Southern candidate,'' Gore said Tuesday night in
Nashville, Tenn. ``I'm a national candidate who's a Southern and
proud of it.''
   ``I'm excited about this victory. I thought it would happen
exactly this way ... people were responding to my message,'' Gore
said today.
   ``I think it essentially is a three-person race,'' Gore said.
``Democrats are looking at who can best carry our party's standard
into the fall election.
   He was leaving today for Chicago before heading for South
Carolina, where he hoped to pick up delegates at that state's
Democratic caucuses on Saturday.
   Gore established himself as a solid contender by winning five
states in his native South: Tennessee, Kentucky, Arkansas, North
Carolina and Oklahoma.
   Even as the votes were being counted in Tuesday's races, Gore
was looking ahead to the next round of contests, in the industrial
states of the North.
   After spending much of the Super Tuesday campaign sparring with
Rep. Richard Gephardt of Missouri, Gore began the next round by
pointing to Dukakis as his chief rival.
   Gephardt was one of the big losers of Super Tuesday, winning
only his home state.
   ``This is becoming a two-person race between Michael Dukakis and
Al Gore,'' Gore said. ``It's a race between the politics of the
past and the politics of the future.''
   Dukakis also ran well in Tuesday's contests, as did Jesse
Jackson.
   Gore advisers began making the pitch that Dukakis has an
``electability'' problem _ that he is too Northern, too liberal and
too ethnic to carry the region against the Republcans.
   ``I think Mike Dukakis is going to represent for many voters the
same old formula that led to the loss of 49 out of 50 states twice
in the last five elections,'' Gore said.
   ``We did particularly well with independents and
independently-thinking Democrats and some disillusioned
Republicans,'' he said. ``And that's where the battle ground is
going to be in the general election.''
