<1ST_LINE>r p PM-EnglishOnlyVote     03-09 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-English Only Vote,0398</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Proposal Backed to Make English Official Language</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF AWALT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opponents argued that making English the official
language of Texas was a divisive measure, but state Republicans
spoke with almost one voice in backing the proposal.
   More than nine in 10 GOP voters in Texas' Super Tuesday
elections endorsed a non-binding referendum to make English the
official language of Texas and the United States.
   ``We were hoping for approval between 75 and 80 percent, so the
higher the percentage goes above that the happier we are with the
results,'' said Lou Zaeske, chairman of the Bryan-based American
Ethnic Coalition.
   Zaeske, whose group helped place the proposal on the GOP ballot,
said proponents were not trying to keep people from learning and
speaking foreign languages.
   ``We just think we should have a common language _ like we have
a common currency.''
   Fred Meyer, Texas Republican Party finance chairman, said the
idea behind the proposals is to help all Americans succeed at jobs
and elsewhere in society.
   But Texas Democratic Party Chairman Bob Slagle criticized the
measure, saying it would be more ``politically courageous'' to do
what is right than to capitalize on what polls show to be a popular
notion.
   ``I think it is terribly divisive, and I think it causes Mexican
Americans who already know they must speak English in order to
advance in this society to feel they are being picked on,'' Slagle
said.
   The official-language issue was only on the Republican ballot in
Texas.
   In a June survey, 70 percent of the Texas Democrats surveyed
said they favored the idea of establishing English as the official
language of the state, and 75.4 percent of independents approved of
the proposal.
   On Tuesday, about 93 percent of those voting in the Texas
Republican primary favored the statement, ``English should be
established as the official language of the state of Texas and the
United States of America.''
   Meanwhile in Florida, organizers of a drive to make English that
state's official language said they collected 260,000 signatures on
Super Tuesday. The group needs 342,939 signatures to get the issue
on the November ballot as a referendum.
   The issue is emotional in heaily Hispanic Dade County, around
Miami, where some fear the drive could increase ethnic tensions.

</TEXT>
