<HEAD>Share Prices Firmer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices were firmer in London at midday
today, boosted by previous rises in New York and Tokyo.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was up 6.3
points at 1,821.3 at 12:47, below the day's peak of 1,826.0, up 11
points, at around 10 a.m.
   The index opened 8.2 points higher at 1,823.2 points following
gains in New York on Tuesday, where the Dow Jones Industrial
Average rose 24.70 to 2,081.07, and a rise in Tokyo earlier today,
where the Nikkei Dow index climbed 139.66 to 25,605.39.
   Dealers said prices eased in later trading because the London
price rise was not supported by sufficient buying interest.
   Among the stocks marked up was Hillsdown Holdings, which rose
7.3 cents to $5.57 after announcing that its pre-tax profits last
year doubled to $202.3 million from $100.7 million in 1986.
   Among the banks, Barclays was off 1.8 cents at $9.32, and TSB
Group fell 1.8 cents to $2.05. British government bonds were
opening little changed.
