<DOCNO> AP880309-0109 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 0903EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WritersStrike     03-09 0492</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Writers Strike,0507</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Striking Writers Vote Not To Work On Academy Awards Broadcast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Union writers refused to continue working on
next month's Academy Awards ceremony script and CBS-TV shelved two
new shows as a strike by the Writers Guild of America put a crunch
on Hollywood.
   The Academy Awards ceremony, scheduled for worldwide broadcast
by ABC-TV on April 11, will air without the aid of the striking
WGA, spokeswoman Cheryl Rhoden said Tuesday night.
   The union's western unit board voted unanimously Tuesday night
to reject a request for a waiver from the producers of the Academy
of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences show. A waiver would have
allowed union work despite the strike.
   Ms. Rhoden said the guild's eastern unit didn't vote because the
show is produced in Los Angeles and would only involve members of
the western unit.
   Scriptwriter Mel Shavelson, former WGA president, and Jack Rose
were hired by the academy to write the program.
   ``If there is no waiver, I won't do the show,'' Shavelson said
before the vote. He added that the writing is far from complete.
``Most of the work is done when the cast shows up at rehearsal.
It's rewriting, really.''
   CBS-TV announced Tuesday that two new shows scheduled to debut
later this month have been shelved indefinitely.
   ``The Dictator,'' a comedy starring Christopher Lloyd, was in
its third week of production in New York but didn't have enough
scripts completed to warrant going ahead with next week's premiere,
the network said.
   No scripts had been completed for the other show, ``The Smothers
Brothers Comedy Hour,'' which was to debut March 23.
   CBS said ``My Sister Sam,'' which had been removed from the
network's schedule earlier this year, would return in place of
``The Dictator.'' The network said it would fill ``The Smothers
Brothers Comedy Hour'' slot with special programming.
   On Tuesday, Leonard Farrell of the Federal Mediation and
Conciliation Service brought together negotiators for the
scriptwriters and producers to review differences.
   Both sides outlined differences and issues, but no bargaining
was conducted, said Herb Steinberg, a spokesman for the Alliance of
Motion Picture and Television Producers. Sticking points were
writers' demands for increased fees and creative rights.
   In the early evening, the meeting was recessed until 11 a.m.
Thursday.
   ``This strike is going to be over someday,'' Farrell told
reporters. ``And it might just as well be over now. That's what we
usually tell (the opposing sides).''
   The strike began Monday with a massive picket line in front of
20th Century Fox studios. It followed the writers' rejection Sunday
of the producers' final contract offer.
   Talk shows and soap operas would be the first to feel the
effects of the strike, probably turning to reruns, the union said.
Producers said other shows had stockpiled scripts.
   The WGA strike is the fourth since a 17-week walkout in 1973.
The longest, in 1981, lasted three months.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880309-0110 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 0908EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Japanese-Internment 1stLd-Writethru a0494 03-09 0496</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japanese-Internment, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0494,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Argument Over WWII Internment Centers On Statute Of Limitations</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 3rd graf bgng, `Bybee told,' with 1 graf to include full
quote; PICKS UP 4th graf bgng, `Bybee contended</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government attorney contends that although
the United States committed ``great wrongs'' to the thousands of
Japanese-Americans detained in prison camps during World War II,
the victims shouldn't be allowed to sue now for damages.
   ``The statute of limitations clearly began to run in the
1940s,'' Justice Department attorney Jay Bybee told the U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit during arguments
Tuesday on a $24 billion lawsuit filed in 1983 on behalf of 120,000
Japanese-Americans.
   Bybee told the three-judge panel of Giles Rich, Phillip Baldwin
and Helen Nies, ``There is no dispute that there were great wrongs
done to Japanese-Americans.... But even when mistakes are made,
people must file timely claims for redress.''
   Bybee contended that the six-year statute of limitations on
suits against the government expired decades ago.
   But plaintiffs' attorney Benjamin Zelenko argued that the
statute of limitations did not come into play until the early 1980s
because of ``deliberate concealment and misrepresentation by the
government of critical information regarding its claim of `military
necessity''' for the internment.
   President Franklin D. Roosevelt authorized the internment of
Japanese-Americans and Japanese citizens living in California and
parts of Oregon, Washington and Arizona in the wake of the 1941
Japanese attack on Pearl Harbor, when he was advised by military
leaders that people of Japanese descent could not be trusted.
   The only time the Supreme Court has ruled on the internment
itself was in 1944, when it found the action was a constitutionally
acceptable military necessity. Government documents discovered
later indicate no such military necessity existed.
   The concealment didn't end, Zelenko argued, until the 1980s,
when a congressionally appointed commission found that there was no
military necessity for the internment. The policy was ``driven by
race prejudice, war hysteria and lack of political leadership,'' he
said.
   This is the second time a federal appeals court has heard the
case. In 1986, the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the District
of Columbia ruled that the government must defend itself at trial
against the suit. That ruling overturned a 1984 decision by
District Court Judge Louis F. Oberdorfer, who had ruled that the
statute of limitations had expired.
   But last June, the Supreme Court ruled that the statute of
limitations issue should have been decided by a different court _
the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit.
   The lead plaintiff in the case is William Hohri, a computer
programmer living in Chicago. Hohri, a San Francisco native who
lived in Southern California when the war began, said Tuesday he
was interned at Manzanar camp east of the Sierra Nevada shortly
after his 15th birthday. He left for the Midwest 2{ years later and
never returned to California.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880309-0111 </DOCNO>
