<2ND_LINE>PM-Escape Foiled,0237</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FBI Halts Attempted Helicopter Escape From Federal Prison</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILAN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An inmate at the Federal Correctional
Institute who arranged a helicopter escape with an undercover FBI
agent was seized just as he was trying to make his getaway,
officials said.
   Prison officers grabbed William M. Carroll, 28, on Tuesday after
he used a red apron he was wearing to signal a helicopter pilot
hovering over the facility, said Ray Hooker, executive assistant to
Warden John Gluch.
   ``But it didn't land, and the guy tried to blend into the prison
population,'' said Kenneth Walton, head of the FBI's Michigan
office.
   ``He thought he had it made, and then the guards started coming
out of the woodwork. They arrested him and now he's in
segregation.''
   Carroll, a Georgia native, was serving a 15-year sentence on a
1986 conviction for aiding and abetting in the counterfeiting of
$20 bills, Hooker said. He had been scheduled for parole in October
1992.
   Carroll allegedly offered $1.25 million in counterfeit money for
the escape, and $1 million if the pilot would kill a federal
witness, Walton said.
   Authorities at the prison 45 miles southwest of Detroit learned
of the escape plan through an internal investigation, Hooker said.
They referred the matter to the FBI, which planted an undercover
agent who acted as Carroll's contact and also supplied the
helicopter and pilot, Hooker said.
</TEXT>
