<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Rebels, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0588,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eight Rebels Captured, 2 Killed; Enrile Says Army Disorganized</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with six grafs to UPDATE with second rebel death and
CORRECTS number captured to eight, sted 10. ADDS byline. Picks up
6th graf pvs, `Military and ...'
^By ROBERT H. REID</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Reporter</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eight communist rebels, including a
former regional commander, were captured and two were killed in
separate raids and clashes across the country, the military said
today.
   Also today, opposition Sen. Juan Ponce Enrile, a former defense
minister, claimed the 19-year communist insurgency was
strengthening because the nation's 160,000-member armed forces was
increasingly disorganized and poorly supplied.
   The military said troops killed the leader of the rebel
propaganda unit in Nueva Ecjia province in a clash Tuesday north of
Manila. Government forces, which suffered no casualties, also
captured four rebels, the report said.
   Brig. Gen. Domingo Rio said Nemesio Demafiles, former commander
of the communist New People's Army on Negros island, was captured
Tuesday afternoon in a private home near the local headquarters of
the Philippine Constabulary in Bacolod, 300 miles south of Manila.
   Three others were arrested in the same raid, the military said,
adding that it came a day after Demafiles' bodyguard was arrested
near Bacolod.
   In a separate incident Tuesday, troops killed a rebel officer
near the Mindanao city of Butuan, the military said.
   Military and rebel sources said Demafiles was replaced last year
as the Negros commander of the New People's Army, the armed wing of
the Communist Party of the Philippines.
   In a report to constabulary headquarters in Manila, Rio said
police found a .45-caliber pistol and a map of the constabulary
office in Bacolod during the raid in which Demafiles was arrested.
The report said Demafiles was apparently planning an attack on the
paramilitary police Bacolod headquarters.
   Negros has been a stronghold of the New People's Army.
   In Manila, Enrile told the American Chamber of Commerce that
disorganization in the armed forces and a lack of supplies are
hampering the anti-insurgency drive.
   He said the New People's Army had grown in size to between
25,000 and 30,000 fighters and that they controlled more territory
than at any time during the rebellion.
