<1ST_LINE>u p PM-SUP--Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0590 03-09 0441</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SUP--Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0590,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Says He's ``Halfway to Winning''</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material, editing thruout</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis, proclaiming himself ``halfway to
winning'' the Democratic presidential nomination, said today he was
looking forward to the prospect of facing George Bush in the fall
election.
   But Dukakis, who won in the big Super Tuesday states of Texas
and Florida and generally split the day's spoils with Jesse Jackson
and Albert Gore, said he's not assuming the Democratic contest is
over.
   ``I said when this started this is a marathon and we're going to
have to take it contest by contest,'' Dukakis said on CBS-TV.
   Interviewed on NBC-TV, he said, ``I'd say I'm about halfway to
winning the nomination.''
   He said he expects to gain enough delegates in the final round
of primaries, in California and New Jersey, to secure the
nomination before the Democratic convention.
   Looking past that, he said that ``it looks like the Republican
nominee is going to be George Bush. I'm looking forward to that.''
   Dukakis, here to campaign for next week's Illinois primary,
said, ``It's really a great day'' following his showing Tuesday.
   ``To be a son of Massachusetts and to go into Florida and Texas
and beat some candidates who obviously have some very strong ties
with the South is just a terrific thing, as well as to do well in
Maryland ... and out in the Pacific Northwest.''
   Asked whether he intended to use negative ads similar to those
he has aimed at rival Richard Gebhardt, Dukakis said, ``If people
insist on using this negative stuff, then I've learned,
unfortunately from painful experience, that you have to respond.''
   Kicking off his Illinois primary campaign, Dukakis was playing
up his Greek immigrant heritage. The Chicago area is among the most
ethnically diverse in the nation, with its heavy population of
first- and second-generation Eastern Europeans.
   ``Many of your families, like my parents, came to this land in
search of opportunity,'' Dukakis told cheering supporters on
Tuesday. ``They didn't have much money in their pockets; they
couldn't speak the language, but they believed in the American
dream. ... It was their broad shoulders and strong arms and keen
minds that built the mightiest industrial machine in the world.''
   Despite the cash drain of Super Tuesday with its emphasis on
television advertising, the Dukakis campaign remains financially
well off.
   Campaign finance chief Robert Farmer said Dukakis was raising
half a million dollars a week. Coming out of Super Tuesday, he
said, Dukakis had $2 million in the bank and another $1 million on
the way in federal matching funds.
</TEXT>
