<HEAD>Yale's Cost Up to $18,060 Next Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An undergraduate's bill at Yale
University will rise 6.1 percent to $18,060 for the 1988-89 school
year, the prestigious private university said.
   The percentage rise was the same as last year's, said Yale
President Benno C. Schmidt Jr. said Tuesday. It cost $17,020 to
attend Yale this school year.
   The increase was approved over the weekend by the Yale
Corporation, the school's board of trustees. Tuition will increase
6.9 percent to $12,960, an increase of 6.9 percent, and room and
board will go up to $5,100, an increase of 4 percent.
   Announced increases at other Ivy League schools range from 6.2
percent at Princeton to 6.7 percent at Cornell, said Yale spokesman
Walter Littell. The cost of attending most Ivy League schools will
be in the range of $17,000 to $18,300, according to figures
supplied by Littell.
