<2ND_LINE>PM-SUP--Gephardt, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0552,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gephardt: `Never Said it Would be Easy'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates in top 5 grafs with Gephardt heading for South
Carolina, fresh quotes, picking up 2nd graf pvs, ``This wasn't;
subs 17th graf, To underscore</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard Gephardt headed for campaign stops in
South Carolina today after a Super Tuesday disaster he blamed on
lack of money and a withering crossfire from rivals Michael Dukakis
and Albert Gore Jr.
   ``With 20 states and a million dollars, we just could not get
our message ... in front of the voters,'' Gephardt said in an
interview broadcast today on ABC-TV.
   ``I really think I'm the only one who has talked about the
issues people really care about,'' Gephardt said. ``I just couldn't
get it across in enough Southern states.''
   Gephardt said he's not finished ``if I can get back into the
race in the states coming up.'' To make the point, he was flying to
South Carolina today, campaigning for that state's caucuses on
Saturday.
   Tuesday night, Gephardt told supporters, ``I never told you it
was going to be easy.''
   ``This wasn't the best of days,'' Gephardt told a subdued group
of backers after winning only on his home turf of Missouri and
finishing a dismal third or fourth in most of the 19 other states
up for grabs Tuesday.
   Gephardt's loss was Gore's gain, as the Tennessee senator
decisively won their battle for the mantle of moderate alternative
to Dukakis and Jesse Jackson. Gephardt acknowledged that he was
unable to counter a spate of negative ads aimed at him by both Gore
and Dukakis.
   ``We had a situation where we had about $6 million or $7 million
spent against us by those two candidates, against about $1 million
we were able to spend,'' he said as the voters' verdict became
apparent.
   Later, addressing supporters at his St. Louis headquarters, he
spoke bravely of future victories rather than analyzing his Super
Tuesday losses.
   He insisted there are still ``great days ahead'' for his
campaign, which had jumped out of the starting gates with a win in
the Iowa caucuses but began slipping in successive contests.
   Aides, however, conceded that Gephardt's fourth-place overall
showing would put a pinch on fund raising just when the campaign
needs money the most.
   ``We're not penniless,'' said campaign consultant Bob Shrum.
``It won't be as easy to raise money, but we'll raise money. It's
not a good thing to have happen to you.''
   They pointed to Michigan's caucuses later this month as the next
``clean shot'' of the campaign, downplaying the impact of next
week's Illinois primary.
   But as his spoke of targeting resources in selected tests,
Gephardt told his backers in the city he represents in Congress
that he will campaign everywhere and stay in the race until the
Democratic convention this summer.
   ``We're going to carry our cause to every one of those days in
every one of those states,'' Gephardt said. ``We didn't shrink when
we were behind in Iowa and we're not going to shrink now.''
   Gephardt said he simply didn't have the money to respond to the
advertising blitz by Dukakis and Gore.
   ``Our message got across in Iowa, got across in New Hampshire,
got across in South Dakota,'' Gephardt said. ``But in 14 short days
we were not able to get it across in the 20 states of the South the
way we wanted.''
   Deputy campaign manager Joe Trippi said Gephardt's financial
shape isn't all that bad, because he has debts of only $75,000 and
has $250,000 on hand. In addition, Trippi said, the campaign
anticipates raising $500,000 within two weeks despite the
anticipated financial pinch stemming from Tuesday's showing.
   Gephardt aides spent most of the day Tuesday saying the campaign
will focus on the March 26 Michigan voting, in effect conceding the
large Illinois showdown to home-state favorites Sen. Paul Simon and
Jesse Jackson.
   ``Our intention is to compete in South Carolina, campaign in
Illinois but really focus on Michigan,'' Trippi said.
   To underscore that point, Gephardt made South Carolina his first
post-Super Tuesday appearance.
   He then was heading for Michigan before traveling to Illinois
for two days of stumping. Gephardt is scheduled to take a couple of
days off the campaign trail next weekend, just two days before the
big Illinois primary, and Trippi said that was to allow the
candidate to prepare for Michigan.
   ``This is a long campaign,'' Gephardt said. ``Those who prevail
are those who don't lose their heart.''
</TEXT>
