<1ST_LINE>r i PM-India-Punjab     03-09 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Punjab,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Militant Leader Takes Over Top Sikh Post</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Radical priest Jasbir Singh Rode was
installed as the leader of 25 million Sikhs today and vowed to win
the fight to create a homeland for his people.
   Rode was named by a Sikh committee as chief priest of the Akal
Takht, or the eternal throne within the Golden Temple, the holiest
Sikh shrine and the seat of Sikhism's spiritual authority.
   The post, although religious, wields great political influence.
   Rode was released from jail Saturday in what apparently was a
move by the federal government to involve militant Sikhs in finding
a solution to the violence in Punjab state.
   Militant Sikhs have been waging a five-year war for a separate
homeland in Punjab, claiming that they are discriminated against by
the predominant Hindu community. Sikhs form 2 percent of India's
800 million people but are in a majority in Punjab state.
   Rode said at his installation ceremony that he had not reached
an understanding with the government prior to his release from
jail. He had been held since 1985 for alleged sedition, but he
never was brought to trial.
   ``We will try to reach a solution with the government which will
not amount to a surrender,'' Rode said. ``But we will struggle till
we get our rights.''
   He called for unity among political factions in the Sikh
community. During the ceremony, young men armed with Soviet-made
AK-47 rifles stood guard.
   More than 400 people have been killed in Punjab this year in
attacks blamed on Sikhs. Most of the victims have been Hindus or
moderate Sikhs. More than 1,000 people died last year in attacks
blamed on the extremists.
</TEXT>
