<DOCNO> AP880309-0119 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 0936EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-SUP--Democrats 1stLd-Writethru a0611 03-09 0759</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SUP--Democrats, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0611,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reshuffled Democratic Pack Emerges from Super Tuesday</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates in top 11 grafs with candidate comments today,
revised delegate figures, picking up 11th graf pvs, Gephardt's
money</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Northerner Michael Dukakis declared today he had a ``national
victory'' with wins in Texas, Florida, Maryland and the West but
Southerners Jesse Jackson and Albert Gore Jr. celebrated their own
strong Super Tuesday showings in the Democratic primaries.
   Rep. Richard Gephardt, the Iowa winner, took only his home state
of Missouri and faced a fight to keep his campaign from fading into
oblivion.
   ``This was a good national victory and I feel terrific this
morning,'' Dukakis said on ABC-TV. ``I think that demonstrates who
can win in November.'' The Massachusetts governor won the day's
three biggest prizes: Florida, Texas and his home state. He also
won in Rhode Island, Maryland, Idaho and Hawaii.
   Dukakis scored well among elements of ``the new South,''
collecting heavy support from Jewish voters in Florida, Hispanics
in Texas and Catholics across the region, according to ABC News
surveys of voters as they left the polls.
   The Democrat with the best-financed and probably best-organized
campaign, Dukakis emerged in a strong position for the next round
of primaries in Midwestern and Northern industrial states.
   Poised to challenge him were Tennessean Gore and South Carolina
native Jackson, who divided the day's spoils with the front-runner.
Dukakis picked up 386 new delegates toward the party's July
nominating convention, Jackson collected 366 and Gore 326.
   Gore, who was seen as fighting Gephardt for the more
conservative Southern Democratic vote, suggested that rivalry was
now behind him. ``It's a three-man race, no question about it,'' he
said on NBC-TV.
   He immediately took aim at Dukakis, calling him a representative
of ``the politics of the past'' who lacks the appeal to moderate
voters that Democrats need to win back the White House in November.
   Jackson declined to attack his Democratic rivals. ``I'm
concerned we run a campaign that will serve my party well,'' he
said, contending intra-party bickering had cost Democrats the White
House in the past.
   Gore racked up victories in Kentucky, Oklahoma, North Carolina
and Arkansas, as well as his home state of Tennessee, while Jackson
won in Virginia, Georgia, Mississippi, Louisiana and Alabama.
   The day's big loser among Democrats was Gephardt, who won only
in his home state of Missouri and added just 93 delegates to his
total.
   Gephardt's money-starved campaign was unable to afford the
expensive media buys necessary to blanket the 20 states which had
Democratic contests on Tuesday. He said he was outspent
seven-to-one by Gore and Dukakis and couldn't get his message
across.
   ``It certainly wasn't the best of days,'' Gephardt said in St.
Louis. He vowed to press on, despite comments like those from the
party's senior statesman Robert Strauss, who said the contest had
narrowed to Dukakis, Jackson and Gore.
   ``I expect one of those three fellows will probably be the
nominee,'' Strauss said.
   Jackson demonstrated that he had expanded his political base
somewhat beyond what he established in his 1984 candidacy, doubling
the proportion of white Southern votes he won to 10 percent. He got
virtually all of the black vote. In Virginia, he piled up a
surprising 2-1 margin over Gore, his nearest competitor.
   Jackson, who has campaigned hard on themes like economic justice
and combating the drug crisis, told supporters: ``Our message is
winning. We have the poorest campaign, the richest message.''
   Gore, who sat out most of the early primary and caucus battles
to concentrate his resources on his home turf, made the strong
showing he needed. It remained to be seen, however, whether he
could maintain that strength beyond the South.
   The day had been designed by Southern Democrats from the start
to bring to the forefront a candidate like Gore, whose strong views
on defense and foreign policy have appeal in the South.
   One of those behind the ``Super Tuesday'' southern strategy,
former Virginia Gov. Charles Robb, called the day a success. ``I
think the emergence of Al Gore is the most important development on
the Democratic side,'' said Robb.
   ``The message today is that we're still a part of the mainstream
of the nation,'' said Atlanta Mayor Andrew Young. ``Super Tuesday
probably won't decide anything, but it will take everybody one step
further along the way. Our job is to let the folks in Illinois,
Pennsylvania (which have upcoming primaries) ... sort this all out
for us, and give us a nominee we can get behind.''
</TEXT>
