<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 0950EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Hermit'sDeath     03-09 0572</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hermit's Death,0585</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hermit's Ashes To Be Scattered Next to His Favorite Tree</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bill Britt, who gained fame as the ``hermit of
Chestnut Hill'' before dying alone in the woods, will be cremated
and his ashes scattered next to his favorite tree, his daughter
said.
   ``I think my father would have wanted to return to the
elements,'' Ingrid Boughner said Tuesday. ``I know he would want to
be returned to his favorite tree. I can almost hear him saying
`yes.'''
   Britt, who resisted efforts to move him to a shelter, should
have been more carefully monitored although he was unlike most
homeless people, say city officials who knew him.
   Britt, 52, died of hypothermia two weeks before his body was
discovered Monday by Ms. Boughner and her brother in a makeshift
wigwam in Brookline, the Suffolk County medical examiner's office
said Tuesday.
   ``Homeless people, people like Britt who say they want to be
alone, should be protected in this weather,'' said Dr. Stanton
Kessler, a senior pathologist in the medical examiner's office.
``He had no food in him. He had no sleeping bag. This type of thing
should be prevented.''
   Ms. Boughner said she decided on cremation after talking to her
father's longtime friend William Baird, the birth control activist,
who told her the two had once discussed cremation.
   Officials of the Metropolitan District Commission, on whose land
Britt lived, said they did not object to Ms. Boughner's decision.
   Britt died in the woods in the Chestnut Hill reservoir, near the
affluent community of the same name where he was born and grew up.
He had lived in the woods since 1969 and did not attract much
attention until 1985, when officials began trying to move him out
of the woods and into public or subsidized housing.
   Britt's continual resistance to efforts to help him gained media
attention and led to his nickname ``the hermit of Chestnut Hill.''
At one point, actor Mickey Rooney said he planned to buy the rights
to his story. In May, Britt appeared on ``Late Night with David
Letterman.''
   Boston Chief Housing Court Justice E. George Daher, who tried to
arrange housing and medical aid for Britt despite his lack of
cooperation, said Tuesday he was shocked and saddened by the news
of Britt's death.
   ``He represents in a microcosm what happens to the homeless, the
unfortunates, the eccentrics in this cold society,'' said Daher.
``Someone should have checked in on him, rather than have him die a
lonely tragic death like this.''
   A one-time insurance agent who also worked in Procter & Gamble's
marketing division in New York City 30 years ago, Britt once had
been married with a family.
   Both public officials and friends said he was a paradox; a loner
who loved to chat with Boston College students who went to class
just yards from his shelter; an eccentric who said he wanted to be
left alone but who regularly pitched stories about himself to the
media.
   Mary Callahan, 27, was one of the first to write about Britt as
a reporter on a weekly newspaper.
   ``It seems so sad to me,'' said Callahan, who now works for
Boston College. ``He was a singular person, a very interesting man.
He looked very old but he was so articulate. He talked about
writing poetry, about writing books. It's strange that he decided
to live there.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
