<HEAD>Pilot Dies in Crash of Vintage Warplane</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PINE GROVE MILLS, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Searchers have discovered the
wreckage of a vintage P-51D Mustang warplane and the body of its
pilot, who crashed on of State College had taken off for an air show in
Florida,
authorities said.
   Clark, 67, and his friend Robert Byrne, piloting another P-51,
were ascending from University Park Airport around 9:30 a.m. Monday
when Clark disappeared, airport Manager Robert Dannaker said.
   ``Apparently they went into the clouds, and one came out and one
didn't,'' said Civil Air Patrol Maj. Marilyn Lappe.
   The wreckage was found on Pine Grove Mountain, about five miles
east of Pine Grove Mills in Centre County, said CAP Lt. Col Paul
Rost, who coordinated the air search from Allegheny County Airport
near Pittsburgh.
   Byrne, reached at the Tico Air Show at Space Center Executive
Airport in Titusville, Fla., declined to discuss the accident. He
had called University Park during a planned stop to ask if. The one-seat,
single-engine plane was used as a bomber
escort over northern Europe during World War II.
