<HEAD>Armenians Seek Government Protection; Death Toll At 32 In Sumgait</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: UPDATES thruout with Armenians demanding protection, death
toll put at 32 from Sumgait violence, protest reported in Yerevan.
CHANGES byline. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Armenian nationalists today called on the
Politburo to protect their countrymen from ethnic attacks during a
Moslem celebration next week in the republic of Azerbaijan, a
spokesman said.
   Hovik Vassilian, a nationalist in the Armenian capital of
Yerevan, said Armenians fear that Azeris will launch violent
attacks during Iranian New Year celebrations, observed March 18-23
by Shiite Moslems.
   The republic of Azerbaijan borders Iran, and most Azeris are
Shiite Moslem. Most Armenians are Christian.
   Tension between Armenians and Azeris erupted in violence Feb. 28
in the Azerbaijani city of Sumgait. The unrest was triggered by
Armenian demands that Nagorno-Karabakh, a predominantly Armenian
district in Azerbaijan, be annexed to Armenia.
   Gennady I. Gerasimov, the Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman,
said today the death toll in the Sumgait rioting was 32, one more
than previously reported.
   The government blamed the deaths on hooligans provoked by rumors
of ethnic turmoil elsewhere. Some Armenian activists say the
violence was instigated by Azeris out of ethnic hatred, and they
claim the death toll was much higher.
   Vassilian said Armenian nationalists sent a telegram to the
ruling Communist Partry Politburo today to ask for protection
during the Moslem celebrations.
   He said Armenians also planned an hourlong general strike
throughout Armenia on Friday to underscore their concerns about
security.
   Gerasimov, speaking at a regular briefing, said Sumgait
residents were not allowed on the streets after 6 p.m. to maintain
order in the city.
   ``The situation is normal but passions are still running high
since people still remember what happened,'' he said when asked why
foreign reporters weren't being allowed into the area.
   Vassilian, editor of an underground journal called The Armenian
Cause, said by telephone that several hundred thousand Armenians
demonstrated Tuesday in Yerevan to mourn Armenians killed in the
turmoil.
   They placed flowers at the base of a monument to the estimated
1.5 million to 2 million Armenians killed in a 1915 Turkish
invasion, he said.
   Asked to estimate the crowd size, Vassilian said, ``There was no
room to stand. There must have been several hundred thousand
there.''
   Gerasimov said wreaths were laid at the monument, but he did not
say how many people attended.
   In Moscow, about 300 Armenians gathered Tuesday in a cemetery to
mourn the Armenian victims of ethnic violence and exchange tales of
how their countrymen were killed by Azeris. Their accounts could
not be independently verified.
   One man said he saw a pregnant woman and her unborn baby slain
and mutilated in Sumgait.
   A resident of a village near Sumgait said Azeris roved through
his settlement, looking under beds for Armenian children and raping
Armenian women. Another Armenian said children were thrown from
windows.
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev has indicated the Central
Committee will review the dispute at a forthcoming meeting.
</TEXT>
