<HEAD>Company Removes Offensive Frozen Food Bags</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The parent company of Great Scott Supermarkets
Inc. has removed frozen food bags that an Asian-American group
found offensive.
   The bags, which bore a caricature of a child with slanted eyes
and prominent teeth, carry the words ``Coolee bag for your
purchases of ice cream and frozen foods.''
   Unskilled Asians who worked for U.S. railroad companies in the
middle and late 19th century were called ``coolies.''
   ``Those kinds of things are just stupid,'' said David Fukuzawa,
director of American Citizens for Justice, an Asian-American civil
rights organization.
   Paul Coleman, a spokesman for Meadowdale Foods, Great Scott's
parent company, said Tuesday the bags would be removed from the
chain's 24 metropolitan Detroit stores.
   Raymond Gomez, a spokesman for the bag maker, said the character
was intended to be an Eskimo.
</TEXT>
