<1ST_LINE>u p PM-SUP--Jackson 2ndLd-Writethru a0748 03-09 0734</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SUP--Jackson, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0748,750</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 9 grafs new with Jackson news conference; pick up 7th
graf pvs bgng ``Jackson won big...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson said today that Super Tuesday
proved ``the Jackson message is winning'' and proclaimed the
primary season is erasing Democratic establishment doubts about the
viability of his campaign.
   He said if his cash-poor campaign had spent as much money as the
well-heeled forces of Michael Dukakis, ``it would have been a
different situation'' in the results.
   He acknowledged that the endorsements of white Democratic
politicans, many of them elected with support of the black voters
Jackson has helped register in recent years, went to Dukakis and
rivals Albert Gore Jr. and Richard Gephardt.
   `It would be fair to say that many of them had reasonable doubts
about the success of our campaign,'' Jackson said. ``In these
elections we are removing those doubts ... Our coalition represents
the future of the Democratic Party.''
   He said the white politicians will have to make choices, not
only about who can win, but which candidate ``can help them.''
   He also spoke about party unity and said the candidates should
not ``self destruct'' their chances in November by attacking each
other during the primary season.
   Jackson's rivals thus far have refrained from criticizing him,
but his campaign manager says the Jackson forces are prepared for
the possibility he will come under attack now that he has collected
a sizeable number of delegates.
   Jackson was heading today to Cicero, Ill, where voters go to the
polls next Tuesday. He was visiting the site of a General Electric
plant that is closing down, to show solidarity with workers who are
losing their jobs.
   ``Our campaign is winning,'' Jackson told jubilant supporters
Tuesday night. ``Our message is winning. We have the poorest
campaign, the richest message.''
   Jackson won big in Virginia and also won in the Deep South
states of Georgia, Louisiana, Mississippi and Alabama.
   He also came in second in the home states of his three main
rivals, Massachusetts, Tennessee and Missouri, home of Rep. Richard
Gephardt.
   `We're right where we wanted to be, and now it's on to North
Carolina and Illinois,'' said campaign manager Gerald Austin.
``Tonight Jesse Jackson became a valid candidate for president,
with an organization and with a message, and he just happens to be
black.''
   An exit poll by ABC News indicated that Jackson won 10 percent
of the white vote in the Super Tuesday contests, which included 14
Southern and border states.
   Jackson has vigorously courted sectors of the white population
in his campaign, principally the economically hard-pressed, the
unemployed, students, gays and lesbians.
   On Tuesday night, Jackson recalled the Selma, Ala., civil rights
march 23 years ago that was violently turned back at the bridge
into town by state troopers.
   ``The same state that wouldn't let us walk across the bridge _
we won that state today,'' Jackson said. ``America has won.''
   Jackson was joined at the celebration by his wife and mother and
other family members, and several political figures, including
District of Columbia Mayor Marion Barry and Rep. Mickey Leland,
Jackson's campaign chairman in Texas. His longtime supporter, rock
disc jockey Casey Kasem, was the master of ceremonies.
   Jackson, who spent just $100,000 on Super Tuesday television
ads, contrasted his low-budget campaign to the multimillion-dollar
TV budgets of his opponents.
   He criticized the negative ads aired by his rivals as `party
bloodletting.'' That is ``a way to lose and we want to win,'' he
said.
   ``I'm not running against Gore or Dukakis or Gephardt on Super
Tuesday. I'm runing against George Bush in the Super Bowl in
November,'' he said.
   Austin said Jackson's success means he will now come under
increasing scrutiny by the media and attacks from other candidates.
   ``We are prepared for the slings and arrows of outrageous
fortune that will come our way,'' he said.
   He said he anticipates the campaign will benefit from greater
fund-raising which has been on an upswing since the Feb. 8 Iowa
caucuses. The campaign raised $600,000 in February, a one-month
record for Jackson, he said.
   Decisions will have to be made on buying more media time than in
the past, especially in large states such as New York and
California, he said.
   This month, Jackson took out $400,000 in loans to keep his
campaign afloat for Super Tuesday.
</TEXT>
