<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 1027EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-JudicialMisconduct     03-09 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Judicial Misconduct,0298</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Complaint Filed Against Judge For Remarks Backing Harold
Washington</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A formal complaint has been filed against an
Illinois appellate judge for saying South Side residents who failed
to vote for the late Mayor Harold Washington ``ought to be hung.''
   The complaint Tuesday to the Illinois Courts Commission cited
comments made by Appellate Judge R. Eugene Pincham in a speech at
an Operation PUSH gathering on Jan. 31, 1987.
   Pincham mentioned the hanging of several slaves and white
collaborators during a 1741 slave rebellion in New York, then said,
``Any man south of Madison Street who casts a vote in the Feb. 24th
election who doesn't cast a vote for Harold Washington ought to be
hung as those were hung in New York.''
   The speech before the civil rights group was broadcast over
three Chicago-area radio stations. Washington won the election but
died Nov. 25, only a few months into his second term.
   Former U.S. Attorney Dan Webb filed the complaint on behalf of
the Illinois Judicial Inquiry Board, contending that the judge's
comments violated portions of the Illinois Code of Judicial Conduct.
   The code prohibits judges from participating in political
campaigns or activities unless they are candidates for office or
judicial retention.
   Pincham said his comments were protected by the First Amendment.
To punish him would violate his constitutional rights, he said,
adding that he would continue with his own court challenge to the
complaint.
   Pincham had attempted to avoid action by the Judicial Inquiry
Board by filing a lawsuit on First Amendment grounds in U.S.
District Court, but that suit was dismissed last week. Pincham said
he would appeal that ruling.
   The Illinois Courts Commission will set hearings on the board's
complaint.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
