<1ST_LINE>u p PM-SUP--Republicans 2ndLd-Writethru a0793 03-09 0798</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SUP--Republicans, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0793,790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Leaves Dole Reeling, All But Flattens Kemp and Robertson</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates in top 3 grafs with Dole campaigning in Illinois,
picking up 2nd graf pvs, Robertson said.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush's powerful Super Tuesday punch packed such a wallop
it knocked Jack Kemp and Pat Robertson flat and left Bob Dole
scrambling in Illinois today to regain his footing in the
industrial Midwest.
   Dole was out campaigning today in the western Chicago suburb of
Hinsdale, where he visited a commuter train station and gulped
coffee and a pastry before television cameras at a restaurant
counter across the street.
   ``It will be up to Illinois now to turn it around,'' Dole told
one supporter.
   Robertson said today that Bush ``just ran a fabulous race.'' He
also said, in an interview on ABC-TV: ``I was running against the
ghost of Ronald Reagan, not against George Bush.''
   While Robertson vowed to stay in the race, Kemp was meeting with
his advisers to determine the future of his campaign. A spokeswoman
said that Kemp, who got no better than 7 percent of the vote in any
of Tuesday's primaries, would have a news conference Thursday.
   An exhilarated Bush said Tuesday night that the voters' message
was clear: ``I'm going to be the next president of the United
States.''
   The vice president was victorious in 16 of 17 GOP contests
Tuesday, most of them in the South. He won a shutout in the
primaries, though Robertson did win Washington state's caucuses.
   ``This is a unique political happening,'' Bush told cheering
supporters in Houston as his lopsided victory became apparent. ``It
exceeded my fondest expectations.''
   While Dole hadn't expected to dominate Super Tuesday, he'd hoped
for a better showing than the distant runner-up status to which he
was relegated.
   He began focusing on next week's Illinois primary even before
Tuesday's results were final, telling a crowd of supporters in
Chicago: ``Illinois is getting more and more important as the
evening wears on.''
   ``This is going to be Bob Dole's recovery state,'' he said.
``It's going to be the turnaround state.''
   Robertson, who earlier had predicted he'd emerge from Super
Tuesday as the GOP front-runner, insisted his third-place showing
still was respectable.
   ``It isn't too bad for an amateur but it isn't near what I
expected,'' said the former television evangelist.
   Kemp kept out of public view as Super Tuesday voters designated
him their last choice. Aides said he'd be reassessing his candidacy.
   Super Tuesday's balloting represented a dramatic comeback for
Bush, who just a month earlier had been reeling from a third-place
finish behind Dole and Robertson in Iowa.
   Damaged but not destroyed, Bush managed to hang on to a
slimmed-down lead in New Hampshire a week later, and his
self-portrait as loyal sidekick to Ronald Reagan was well-received
in the South.
   Bush claimed most of the 712 delegates at stake Tuesday, adding
them to the 126 he'd amassed in earlier contests. That put him well
on the way to the 1,139 needed to land the GOP nomination.
   His Super Tuesday victories reached across the nation, including
delegate-rich Florida and Texas. He also triumphed in Tennessee,
Kentucky, Georgia, Alabama, Virginia, Mississippi, Louisiana,
Arkansas, North Carolina, Maryland, Massachusetts, Rhode Island,
Oklahoma and Missouri.
   Robertson conceded he'd been damaged by some unusual comments
he'd made on the campaign trail, such as his insistence there are
Soviet missiles in Cuba, claims his Christian Broadcasting Network
at one point knew the whereabouts of American hostages in Lebanon
and his assertions that disclosure of the Jimmy Swaggart sex
scandal had been timed to hurt his candidacy.
   ``I spoke too much and I should have kept my mouth shut but I
was misinterpreted,'' he said.
   But he shrugged off any suggestion that the damage was
irreparable or that he would join forces with Dole in a stop-Bush
offensive, saying ``it looks like the one that may come out of
Illinois is going to be Pat Robertson rather than Bob Dole.''
   ``I, right now, am going to be the rallying point for those who
don't want George Bush as the nominee of the party.''
   Dole, meanwhile, was challenging Bush to a series of debates
``all over Illinois, one on one, no moderator, no notes, stand up
and have it out.''
   Lee Atwater, Bush's campaign manager, didn't welcome the
invitation.
   ``There just doesn't seem to be any point in following the other
guy's campaign schedule,'' he said.
   Bush, however, was ready to fight Dole for Illinois' 82
delegates. While Dole thus far has dominated contests in the
Midwest and has a strong organization in Illinois, Bush is
supported by Illinois Gov. James Thompson and 93 of the state's 102
GOP county chairmen.
   The vice president planned to fly to Chicago Thursday.
</TEXT>
