<1ST_LINE>u w PM-DeafPresident 1stLd-Writethru a0574 03-09 0654</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>^PM-Deaf President, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0574,650</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDS: UPDATES throughout with information on student withdrawal,
quote from Bonior on possible federal funding cuts.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gallaudet University students threatened to
withdraw from the school for the deaf as a protest over the
appointment of a hearing woman as president entered its fourth day
today.
   Gallaudet board of trustees chairwoman Jane Bassett Spilman said
the decision to hire Elisabeth Ann Zinser will stand, and scheduled
a press conference today for herself and the new president.
   At a campus rally Tuesday night, student leaders said that up to
two-thirds of the school's 2,200 undergraduate and graduate
students might withdraw Thursday if Zinser is not replaced with a
deaf president.
   Psychology professor Neil Reynolds, who chairs two faculty
groups, said they will meet today to discuss the controversy over
Zinser's selection, and could vote to suspend classes.
   ``There has been in the past week an escalation of overt support
from faculty members for a deaf president,'' said Reynolds, who
chairs the school's 21-member faculty senate and a group that
includes the entire faculty. ``This is definitely a change.''
   When school officials announced Sunday that Zinser, an
administrator at the University of North Carolina at Greensboro,
had prevailed over two deaf finalists, students staged protest
marches to the Capitol, forced closure of the school Monday, and
boycotted classses Tuesday.
   Rep. David E. Bonior, D-Mich., a member of Gallaudet's board of
trustees, said Congress might consider scaling back funding for the
school if the conflict over Zinser's appointment is not resolved.
   ``I'm concerned it has the potential to hurt the funding of the
university, especially when you have leaders from both sides going
out of their way to express themselves on this,'' Bonior said.
   Bonior, the chief deputy majority whip in the House, said he has
been meeting privately with university officials, and intends to
ask Zinser ``whether she is indeed interested in coming into an
environment that is as hostile as it is.''
   Gallaudet, founded in 1864 by an act of Congress, is the
nation's only liberal arts college for the deaf. Last year, federal
funding accounted for $62.2 million of Gallaudet's $76 million
operating budget.
   Spilman said the selection of Zinser, a vice chancellor for
academic affairs at Greensboro, ``was a vote cast in the best
interests of the university.''
   Zinser, who prevailed by a 10-4 margin over two deaf finalists,
``was selected for one and only one reason _ she was the best
person qualified,'' Spilman said.
   The students claim that by picking Zinser, who doesn't know sign
language, the board of trustees has shown it has no understanding
of the importance deaf students place on having a deaf leader.
Including Zinser, none of the school's seven presidents has been
deaf.
   ``The alumni sympathize with and support the students,'' Gerald
Burstein, president of the school's alumni organization, said at a
campus rally Tuesday. ``We _ unlike hearing members on the board _
know fully what it is like to be deaf.''
   ``I'm behind the students 100 percent,'' said Prof. Herbert
Maples, chairman of Gallaudet's math department, who is deaf.
``Something has to be done about this situation.''
   Thirty percent of Gallaudet's faculty and 22 percent of the
school's 1,300-member support staff is deaf, according to
university publicist Barbara Dennis.
   The National Association of the Deaf is planning to have state
representatives from the 20,000-member organization meet in
Washington Friday to discuss ways to help the protesting students,
said Fred Weiner, a Washington spokesman for the group.
   Students vowed to continue their protest until they achieve
their goal.
   ``We will not give up until we have a deaf president,'' said
Jerry Covell, a leader of the student protest. ``We will just keep
trying.''
   Students also want Spilman replaced, and a plan to make deaf
persons a majority on the board of trustees. The 20-member board
now has four deaf members.
</TEXT>
