<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Afghan-Americans     03-09 0425</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Afghan-Americans,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Urged to Award Medal to Journalists Killed in Afghanistan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan was urged today to award the
Medal of Freedom posthumously to three American journalists killed
by Soviet troops while covering the eight-year Afghanistan war.
   Rep. Jim Courter, R-N.J., introduced a resolution in the House
urging Reagan to give the nation's highest civilian award to
relatives of Charles E. Thornton, a medical reporter for the
Arizona Republic in Phoenix, and independent filmmakers Lee Shapiro
of North Bergen, N.J., and Jim Lindelof of Sacramento, Calif.
   Thornton was killed in an ambush by Soviet troops on Sept. 19,
1985, while preparing a story on volunteer doctors in Afghanistan.
Shapiro and Lindelof, a paramedic serving as soundman for a
documentary being filmed by Shapiro, were killed Oct. 9, 1987, when
they were strafed by Soviet helicopter gunships and shot by Soviet
soldiers who confiscated their cameras and film. Their bodies have
never been returned from Afghanistan.
   ``The journalists' only `crime' was in bringing a trace of
glasnost to the most brutal war of the decade,'' Courter told a
news conference. ``Unable to completely conquer the Afghan
resistance, the Soviets have committed themselves to a policy of
tracking down and murdering Western journalists in an attempt to
prevent the rest of the world from learning of the Afghans' valiant
struggle for freedom.''
   Courter's resolution is cosponsored by Reps. Bob Stump, R-Ariz.,
and Robert T. Matsui, D-Calif. The same appeal to Reagan will be
introduced in the Senate next week by Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz.,
and Pete Wilson, R-Calif.
   The resolution urges Reagan to award the Medal of Freedom
posthumously to the three journalists at a White House ceremony on
March 21, the Afghan new year which the president designated last
year as ``Afghanistan Day.''
   ``The great courage displayed by these American heroes in facing
the dangers of war and a lethal Soviet threat against them as
correspondents should not go unrecognized,'' Matsui said.
   Linda Shapiro, the filmmaker's widow, said her husband was
``sought out and deliberately gunned down for telling the truth''
about the war. She urged continued U.S. support for the Afghan
rebels, and promised to finish her husband's documentary.
   Bill Lindelof, a reporter for the Sacramento Bee, said his
brother originally went to Afghanistan to provide medical treatment
for Afghan war refugees.
   ``He did so much and unselfishly, and this (award) would be sort
of something in his memory,'' Lindelof said. ``It would say that
Jim did all he could, and it was appreciated.''
</TEXT>
