<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-OilMeeting     03-09 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Oil Meeting,0256</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Non-OPEC Producers Meet To Debate Price Strategy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Experts from non-OPEC oil producing nations met
today to debate moves aimed at halting plunging oil prices, said a
spokesman at the Mexican Embassy, which served as host of the
gathering.
   The meeting was called by Egypt but was held in London because
it was a more convenient location than Cairo.
   Apart from Egypt, the other invited participants were the Soviet
Union, China, Angola, Malaysia, Brunei, Oman, Mexico and Colombia.
   Britain, which rejects group pricing policies for its North Sea
oil, was not invited. Norway, another European producer, declined
to attend.
   ``The meeting is at expert level with no ministers involved,''
said a Mexican spokesman, who declined to be identified. ``They
just want to talk about the situation in the market, although
obviously they are not in any position to take a decision.''
   On Tuesday, Oil Minister Abdel-Hady Kandil of Egypt said the
meeting was not against the 13-nation Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries, ``but is an attempt by non-OPEC producers to
help save the world oil market from further deterioration.''
   There was speculation that OPEC may call an emergency meeting
about the oil price drop, due partly to increased output by
non-OPEC producers and a mild winter in Japan and Europe.
   North Sea Brent crude for April delivery was quoted at $14.20 to
$14.30 a barrel in London today. At its December meeting in Vienna,
OPEC pledged to defend a price of $18 a barrel.
</TEXT>
