<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel 4thLd-Writethru a0782 03-09 0775</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0782,0794</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inner Cabinet Refuses To Endorse Shultz Plan, 1 Killed, 10 Wounded</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with army confirming today's
death, U.N. raises total death toll to 90. Pick up 8th pvs, `Prime
Minister...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel's divided government today refused to
endorse a U.S. plan designed to end more than three months of
violence in the Israeli-occupied lands. Troops killed one Arab and
wounded 10 others in clashes.
   Palestinians staged a general strike in observance of another
``martyrs' day'' to honor the Arabs killed since the
anti-occupation unrest began Dec. 8.
   The death brought the confirmed death toll from the rioting to
85 since Dec. 8. U.N. figures now put the number killed at 90,
including five Arabs who died from tear gas inhalation. However,
there was no independent confirmation that the five Arabs included
in the U.N. count died as a result of the riots.
   Israeli troops shot and killed a Palestinian in the West Bank
village of Silwad, 10 miles northeast of Ramallah, the army said.
   Officials at Ramallah Hospital said Mohammed Ochman Sarris, 22,
died of a gunshot wound to the back. They said another Palestinian
from Silwad was admitted with a gunshot wound to the thigh.
   In clashes in Nablus in the West Bank, officials at Al Ittihad
Hospital said seven Palestinians from the nearby Faraa refugee camp
were hospitalized with gunshot wounds to the legs, hands and side.
   Another Palestinian from the village of Masha, 15 miles west of
Nablus, was treated for a gunshot wound to the left leg, the
officials said.
   Officials at Rafidiyeh Hospital in Nablus said a Palestinian
from Jenin, 20 miles to the north, was shot in the shoulder.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir successfully defeated attempts by
the left-of-center Labor Party to force a vote in the 10-member
inner Cabinet on a peace plan offered by U.S. Secretary of State
George P. Shultz.
   Foreign Minister Shimon Peres, who has accepted the Shultz plan,
attacked Shamir's refusal in a speech in Parliament.
   ``We might miss this historic opportunity, and we won't have an
answer, not for our generation and not for those to coe, as to why
we became afraid of peace,'' said Peres, leader of the Labor Party.
``Why did we reject the outstretched hand because of imaginary
fears?'
   In clashes near Qalqilya in the West Bank, Israeli armored
personnel carriers fired pebbles at demonstrators with a newly
developed riot-control device, Israel radio said. The gravel-firing
gun was used for this first time this week, it said.
   The ``martyrs' day'' strike closed shops throughout the West
Bank and the occupied Gaza Strip and kept most of the 110,000 Arabs
who work in Israel away from their jobs, an army spokesman and the
Palestine Press Service said.
   Army spokesmen said the only exception to the general strike was
the Tulkarem area near the Israeli town of Kfar Saba, where some
workers ignored the boycott.
   In the West Bank town of Halhoul, an empty Israeli-owned bus
used to carry Arab workers to their jobs was burned in front of the
municipal building, the Palestine Press Service said.
   It said Arabs demonstrated at a dozen locations in Gaza Strip
refugee camps and towns and shouted Palestine Liberation
Organization slogans, raised Palestinian flags and threw stones.
   About 1.5 million Palestinians live in the West Bank and Gaza
Strip, which Israel captured in the 1967 Middle East war.
   Ezer Weizman, a Labor minister-without-portfolio, said ``the
government is split 50-50'' over the U.S. peace plan.
   Shultz, who brought the peace initiative to the Arab and Israeli
leaders last week, had asked Shamir to bring Israel's response to
Washington for talks with President Reagan on March 14. Labor
leaders had hoped to commit Shamir to accept before he left.
   Shamir's spokesman, Yossi Ahimeir, said the prime minister
``opposed most of the ideas'' in the U.S. plan and sought to talk
the Americans into making changes.
   Shamir, leader of the right-wing Likud bloc, objects to Shultz's
call for an international conference by May 1. He also opposes a
proposal that talks on the final status of the occupied lands begin
in December, even if agreement had not been reached on Palestinian
self-rule.
   Ahimeir said that for the first time, Shamir will suggest an
agreement with Jordan on a step-by-step plan for implementing
self-rule quickly in a limited area of the West Bank or Gaza.
   ``The idea is to make autonomy work in a limited area such as
Nablus or Hebron and then enlarge it until it is in force in all of
the territories,'' Ahimeir said.
</TEXT>
