<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-GulfWar     03-09 0286</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Gulf War,0297</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Acknowledge Sending Missiles to Iraq</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Iran-Iraq</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet official acknowledged today that his
country had supplied missiles to Iraq, but he said their range was
too short to strike Iranian cities.
   The statement by Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov
was believed to be the first time the Soviet Union acknowledged
shipping missiles to Iraq, Iran's enemy in a 7{-year-old war.
   The Soviets have been Iraq's chief arms supplier.
   Western military analysts say Iraq has been using Scud-B
missiles, fitted with strap-on boosters for added power, in recent
attacks on the Iranian capital, Tehran. The city is 290 miles from
the Iran-Iraq border.
   Iran also uses Scud-Bs in its attacks on Iraqi cities.
   The missiles have a range of 190 miles.
   On Sunday, Iranian media reports blamed the Soviet Union for the
missile attacks on Iran, prompting an angry mob in Tehran to try to
storm the Soviet Embassy.
   Gerasimov, asked about the Iranian charges at a government news
briefing, said Soviet missiles had been shipped to Iraq under an
agreement between the two countries.
   ``The Soviet Union previously delivered a limited shipment of
short-range missiles,'' he said. ``We never gave our permission to
modify those missiles to increase their range, and modernization
was not foreseen by that agreement.''
   Gerasimov said the agreement ``ruled out'' modernizing the
missiles.
   ``This is the basis on which we're insisting that we have
nothing to do with the `war of the cities,''' he said.
   Iraq claims the missiles are Iraqi-made.
   Another Soviet Foreign Ministry official, Vsevolod L. Oleandrov,
was asked at the briefing if he believes the Iraqi claims. After a
long pause he said, ``It's difficult for us to say.''
</TEXT>
