<1ST_LINE>r p PM-SUP--Simon 1stLd-Writethru a0547 03-09 0603</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SUP--Simon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0547,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Simon Says Super Tuesday Results Justify Decision To Stay Home</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates in top 5 grafs with Simon comments today, picking up
4th graf pvs, Simon, his</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES REINDL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Illinois Sen. Paul Simon said today his
presidential hopes are riding on a home-state primary victory next
week, and he said he still can get the Democratic nomination
despite sitting out Super Tuesday.
   ``I'm going to finish first in Illinois,'' said Simon. ``If I
don't I'm going to have to re-evaluate,'' he said in an interview
on Cable News Network.
   Simon said the strong showings of rivals Michael Dukakis, Jesse
Jackson and Albert Gore Jr. on Tuesday showed that the Democrats
won't have a candidate picked before their convention in July.
   ``Nobody's going to have that first-ballot nomination, and then
groups are going to start leaving one candidate or another, going
to someone who is going to be generally acceptable,'' he said. ``I
think I fit that. But, I also have to win in Wisconsin or Ohio or
Pennsylvania or New York.''
   ``There is no question that if I can do it in Illinois, we're
going to pick up some states after Illinois,'' he said.
   Simon, his campaign strapped for cash, sat out the 20-state
Super Tuesday campaign in favor of concentrating on his home-state
primary next week, as part of what he calls a Midwest industrial
strategy.
   The Simon campaign has missed one payroll and is in danger of
missing a second, said spokeswoman Pam Huey. Simon also said
Tuesday the campaign was paying cash for expenses and hoped to
avoid borrowing any more money, but had enough federal matching
funds to cover its existing debt.
   February fund-raisers generated about $932,000 and federal
matching funds totaled $364,000, said Simon spokesman Terry
Michael. The campaign owes about $145,000 but is in ``pretty solid
condition as a result of not going into debt'' for Super Tuesday,
Michael said.
   ``We have a really small payroll, and we didn't make the big TV
buys others did for March 8,'' he said.
   But Simon doesn't plan to spend for television advertising in
Illinois either, again looking to future races.
   ``It would be foolish for us to make a big TV buy when we don't
even know what the other candidates are going to do,'' Michael said.
   ``We need a lift from Illinois. With that help we can raise
additional money so we can be more competitive in the states after
Illinois,'' he added.
   Simon is eyeing his fellow Illinois candidate _ Jackson, who
makes his home in Chicago.
   Some Jackson supporters have called on Simon to get out of the
race before Illinois, contending the Democratic senator will only
siphon votes from Jackson with no hope of victory himself.
   ``I've heard more people say Jesse should get out of the race
because he's hurting me, but I'm not calling for him to drop out,''
Simon countered.
   Simon has pitched himself in recent days as the consensus
candidate, the man most likely to get the nomination in Atlanta if
no clear favorite emerges from the primaries.
   ``Any candidate winning enough of the remaining delegates to
secure a clear first ballot victory is becoming a mathematical and
political improbability,'' he said.
   ``Right now, with no Mr. Inevitable in the race, it's going to
be a situation where the one who gets hottest at the end wil be in
the best possible position to negotiate a first ballot victory,''
Michael said.
   ``So really, you just have to hang in there and hope to get hot
at the end.''
</TEXT>
