<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Koop     03-09 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Koop,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Surgeon General Says Masters and Johnson Irresponsible on AIDS</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Surgeon General C. Everett Koop said today
that claims about the spread of AIDS among heterosexuals by
researchers Dr. William Masters and Virginia Johnson are unproven
and irresponsible.
   Koop, interviewed from London on ABC-TV's ``Good Morning
America'', said the sex experts have no scientific evidence to back
claims that AIDS among heterosexuals is ``rampant,'' that the
disease can be spread by casual non-sexual contact or that the
nation's blood supply is unsafe.
   ``In as much as some very wild claims were made, we have to be
very careful,'' Koop said.
   The government's top medical officer was reacting to widely
publicized findings from a new Masters and Johnson book,
co-authored by Dr. Robert Kolodny, ``Crisis: Heterosexual Behavior
in the Age of AIDS.'' Excerpts from the book appeared in this
week's Newsweek magazine.
   Koop noted that Masters and Johnson did not submit their
findings to scientific review or have them published in a
recognized medical journal.
   ``I think it is irresponsible. It is scare tactics,'' Koop said.
   The couple has published several books based on surveys of
Americans' sexual activities and attitudes. The new book calls for
widespread mandatory testing for acquired immune deficiency
syndrome infections, and estimates there are 3 million or more AIDS
carriers in the United States. The government estimates up to 1.5
million.
   Koop acknowledged that there is an explosion of AIDS among
heterosexuals in Africa but said ``the United States is not like
Africa... That's not going to happen here.''
   He said heterosexuals have accounted for only 4 percent of AIDS
cases in the United States and this is expected to increase to 5
percent by 1991.
   Scientists say the disease is spread most often through sexual
contact, needles or syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood
or blood products, and from infected pregnant women to their
offspring. The chief victims have been homosexual men and
intravenous drug abusers.
   Koop said if there were any truth to the suggestion that AIDS is
spread through other means, the government would be warning against
it. ``We have never gotten ahead of our scientific base, and that's
something the American people can rely on,'' he said.
   He said that among more than 50,000 AIDS cases so far in the
United States, ``not one single one was proven to be transmitted by
casual non-sexual contact.''
   ``AIDS is very hard to catch,'' said Koop.
</TEXT>
