<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Iraq, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0798,0680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran and Iraq Continue Bombarding Capitals</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS last 4 grafs, `The Iranians ... with 4 grafs to UPDATE
with Soviets admitting sending short-range missiles to Iraq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran and Iraq bombarded each others'
capitals with missiles today for the 10th day. Iran said 35 people
were killed in Tehran and Iraq reported Baghdad residents died when
a missile wrecked homes and stores.
   Each side in the 7{-year-old war vowed to continue its missile,
air and artillery assaults on population centers until the other
halts the attacks.
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency, monitored in
Nicosia, said the Revolutionary Guards Corps fired two missiles
into Baghdad, one at 10 a.m. and the second five minutes later.
   Baghdad's official Iraqi News Agency, also monitored in Nicosia,
said only one missile exploded in the city of 5 million. It said
the missile demolished houses and stores, ``killing or wounding
numbers of civilians.''
   The Iraqi army retaliated by firing an Al Hussein missile, named
after the Shiite Moslem saint, into Tehran at 11:24 a.m., the
agency said.
   Iran said it hit a residential district, killing 35 people,
wounding 120, knocking down buildings and burying people under the
rubble. Among the survivors was an 80-year-old woman dragged from
the debris by rescue workers, it said.
   Iran claims to have fired 29 missiles into Baghdad, the northern
city of Mosul and the southern town of Al-Amarah since the missile
exchange began Feb. 29. The Iraqis have acknowledged 24 hits.
   Iraq has reported firing 46 missiles into Tehran, the holy city
of Qom, 100 miles south of the Iranian capital, and the central
city of Isfahan during the same period.
   Iraqi communiques said Iranian artillery pounded the southern
port of Basra and Al-Amarah during the night, killing ``many
civilians.''
   The Iraqi News Agency said the Iranian shells rained down on
densely populated residential areas in Basra. It said that among
the dead were four children buried under the rubble of their home
after it took a direct hit.
   The agency said the shelling spread to Qurnah, 30 miles north of
Basra, and Zubair, south of Basra.
   Gulf-based salvage executives said today that an Iraqi warplane
fired a missile at a Cypriot oil tanker carrying Iranian oil in the
Persian Gulf on Tuesday. The shipping executives, who spoke on
condition of anonymity, said 101,977-ton Felicity sustained minor
damage.
   Baghdad's government-run Al Thawra daily said in an editorial
that Iraq will go on ``hitting new Iranian targets every day to
shatter the lies of the charlatans in Tehran'' until Iran accepts
the U.N. Security Council's July 20 cease-fire resolution.
   Iraq has said it will comply with the resolution, but Iran
demands that Iraq must be branded the aggressor before it will
agree to a cease-fire.
   The commander of the Iranian Revolutionary Guards' air wing,
Mohsen Refan, said that if Iraq continues its ``atrocities in the
war of the cities, we will increase our missile attacks on Baghdad
manyfold and attack other Iraqi cities with our missiles.''
   He said Iraq has suffered more than Iran recently because ``our
missiles have four times the destructive force'' of Iraq's weapons
and are more accurate.
   The Iranians charge that the Soviet Union, Iraq's main arms
supplier, provided Baghdad with the long-range missiles capable of
hitting Tehran.
   Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov
acknowledged today that the Soviets supplied Iraq with missiles,
but he said their range was too short to hit Iranian cities and
that the Soviets never gave Iraq permission to modify the missiles
to extend their range.
   Both Iran and Iraq have Soviet-built Scud-Bs, which have a range
of 190 miles. Baghdad, only 80 miles from the border, is within
easy range of the Iranian batteries.
   To hit Tehran, 290 miles from the frontier, the Iraqis need
longer range weapons. Analysts say the Iraqis attach booster
rockets to the Scuds to give them the range to hit Tehran.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
