<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Bangladesh     03-09 0282</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Bangladesh,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bangladesh Foreign Minister Seeks U.S. Support in Political
Turmoil</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bangladesh's Foreign Minister Humayun Rashid
Chowdhury met today with U.S. diplomats in a bid to recruit their
support for his government against opposition charges of election
fraud, officials said.
   Chowdhury, who came here on his own initiative, met with Deputy
Secretary of State John Whitehead and with another, lower-level
State Department representative, said the officials who spoke on
condition they not be named.
   ``There are all sorts of groups in Bangladesh trying to involve
us in their political process. We're not interested in getting
involved,'' said one official.
   ``What we intend to tell him is that Bangladesh has to solve its
own internal problems,'' he added. The United States favors
political reforms but they have to come from within Bangladesh, he
added.
   Chowdhury's government, headed by President Hussain Muhammad
Ershad, won a landslide victory in last week's parliamentary
elections, but a group of 21 opposition parties boycotted the
balloting and charged that it was fraudulent.
   At least 11 people were reported killed and hundreds wounded in
violence connected with the March 3 elections. Ershad, a former
army general, came to power in 1982 in a bloodless coup and was
elected president in 1986 in elections which the opposition also
declared were rigged.
   The United States is providing Ershad's government with about
$130 million in economic support this year and the same amount for
1989, most of it for food and basic commodities. Bangladesh has a
population of 105 million.
   Chowdhury, who arrived here Tuesday, also discussed economic and
regional developments, the officials said, and he scheduled
meetings with members of Congress.
</TEXT>
