<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 1136EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-SUP--Robertson 2ndLd-Writethru a0772 03-09 0632</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SUP--Robertson, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0772,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Robertson Still In Race But Starting To Talk About 1992</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with news conference, subbing 3 grafs for grafs 2-3
pvs, The former ... ABC-TV.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN S. CARLSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pat Robertson said today he'll keep fighting for
the Republican presidential nomination because ``you never know
what will happen between now and August,'' but a pile of
third-place finishes on Super Tuesday was enough to start him
talking about 1990 and beyond.
   ``The mantle of Ronald Reagan has passed to George Bush,''
Robertson said at a news conference today. ``None of us could have
dreamed that he could be so strong.''
   ``It isn't over yet,'' the former television evangelist added.
``Still half of the delegates are to be selected.''
   In separate comments, on ABC-TV, ``I was running against the
ghost of Ronald Reagan. In the South the love of Ronald Reagan is
so deep with these people, and George Bush is totally identified
with him.''
   Robertson, who said earlier his showing wasn't ``too bad for an
amateur,'' said, ``I'm in it for the long haul, for this time, for
1990, the congressional races, and who knows what will happen in
1992.''
   ``Politics are so erratic in America,'' Robertson said. ``You
never know what will happen between now and August.''
   Robertson conceded Vice President George Bush ``beat the
daylights out of us'' in Tuesday's voting, but he assured several
hundred cheering supporters in an Atlanta hotel ballroom Tuesday
night: ``This is not the end. This is just the beginning.
   ``We're going to New Orleans. I'm going to be the conservative
champion for everyone who wants to rally around the conservative
cause in this nation,'' he said.
   ``I'm in all the way. I'm in to see a Republican conservative
Congress in 1990 and we're in for the presidential race in 1992.''
   Robertson said his campaign has brought thousands of
conservatives into the Republican Party ``for the long haul.''
   ``They're in the process and American politics won't be the same
in this century,'' he promised.
   In this campaign, Robertson said, his supporters have worked the
caucuses and dominated the delegate selection process in many
states. When the Republican National Convention convenes in New
Orleans this summer, there will be many more Robertson supporters
than the numbers might suggest, he said.
   ``For one vote the Georgia delegation is bound (to Bush). Beyond
that, the Georgia delegation will be a Pat Robertson delegation.
The same is true in Oklahoma, North Carolina, the state of
Washington, most likely, and many other states _ Hawaii, Alaska and
Nevada,'' he said.
   Although he gained only a handful of delegates in Tuesday's
voting, Robertson told reporters he had greatly improved ``on my
early ratings 10 months ago when I was laughed at with 3 percent.''
   Robertson called the performance ``not too bad for an amateur,
but it's not nearly what I expected.''
   The former television evangelist said he may have spread his
campaign too thin by running in all the Super Tuesday states.
   ``I didn't have the concentration I should have had in ky
states. I tried to play (to) everyone in the South,'' he said. ``We
just didn't have the resources to compete with George Bush.''
   Robertson admitted his campaign was hurt by controversy over
several statements he had made _ trying to tie the Bush campaign to
the timing of revelations about the sex scandal involving
evangelist Jimmy Swaggart; saying his Christian Broadcasting
Network reporters had known where some hostages were being held in
the Middle East, and proclaiming that the Soviet Union has missiles
in Cuba.
   ``I spoke too much and I should have kept my mouth shut,'' he
said.
   But he blamed the news media for much of the controversy. ``I
was misinterpreted,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
