<DOCNO> AP880309-0146 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 1143EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-AIDS     03-09 0432</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-AIDS,0446</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Researcher Says AIDS Epidemic Causing Increase In TB</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The worldwide AIDS epidemic is causing an upsurge
in tuberculosis in many countries, including the United States, a
researcher from the World Health Organization said today.
   Dr. Gary Slutkin told the First International Conference on the
Global Impact of AIDS that tuberculosis rates are going up in areas
worst hit by acquired immune deficiency syndrome.
   About 1,100 specialists from 20 countries are attending the
conference at London's Barbican Center.
   Slutkin said the reason appears to be that AIDS suppresses
immunity to tuberculosis, a lung infection.
   AIDS attacks the body's immune system, leaving victims
susceptible to a variety of infections and cancers.
   Slutkin, an epidemiologist, said the number of TB cases in the
United States increased between 1985 and 1986 for the first time
since records have been kept on the disease.
   He said the number of TB cases went up from 22,201 in 1985 to
22,768 in 1986.
   The largest increases in TB in the United States occurred in New
York City, where the rate jumped by about 50 percent between 1981
and 1986, Slutkin said. He said there also have been increases in
TB rates in 25 states and in Washington, D.C.
   He said that in Africa, where AIDS is prevalent, 20 percent to
50 percent of TB patients tested positively for the AIDS virus.
That's three to 20 times higher than the rest of the population.
   Slutkin told reporterst the scale of the expected increases in TB due
to
AIDS, Slutkin said, ``I think we should certainly expect to see
increases in the number of cases of tuberculosis in the next five
years. In fact, it's almost certainly already occurring in many
countries.''
   Other speakers at the conference today discussed the economic
and social impact of the AIDS epidemic, which has spread to 133
countries.
   Anne Scitovsky, the chief health economist for the Palo Alto
Medical Foundation in California, estimated that the direct cost of
treating AIDS patients in the United States will probably increase
by eight-fold to $8.5 billion by 1991.
   Indirect costs from lost wages and future earnings could soar to
$55.6 billion by 1991, she said.
   AIDS is spread most often through sexual contact, needles or
syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood products,
and from pregnant women to their offspring.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
