<2ND_LINE>PM-Baker-Panama,160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Baker: Rhode Island National Guard Not Invading Panama</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   White House chief of staff Howard Baker today
denied that the United States is planning an invasion of Panama,
saying American troops there are merely holding regularly scheduled
training exercises.
   ``Panama is the site of National Guard training exercises and
has been for years,'' Baker said. ``And as I understand it, the
Rhode Island National Guard is now holding regularly scheduled
exercises in Panama.
   ``And certainly if the United States was going to invade Panama,
it wouldn't be with the Rhode Island National Guard. So it simply
is not so. It has no connection at all,'' Baker said, talking with
reporters at the White House after seeing President Reagan off on a
trip to Indiana.
   Jorge Abadia, Panama's foreign minister, on Tuesday accused the
United States of conducting ``the prelude of an armed invasion'' by
staging military exercises along the Panama Canal.
   The U.S. Southern Command said the exercises were scheduled a
year ago and were ``routine training.''
</TEXT>
