<1ST_LINE>u p PM-SUP--Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0532 03-09 0565</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SUP--Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0532,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Celebrates `National Victory'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates in top 4 grafs with Bush relaxing in private, Baker
comments, picking up in 3rd graf pvs, Just hours</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush took a breather today
after the landslide Super Tuesday victories that he said made it
virtually sure he'll be the next president.
   Bush was relaxing in private today but planned to rejoin the
campaign Thursday in Illinois, which has its primary next Tuesday.
   In Washington, meanwhile, White House chief of staff Howard
Baker said today ``it would take a major event'' to prevent Bush
from winning the Republican nomination. He said there is no sign
President Reagan is about to endorse anyone.
   Bush, the winner in 16 of 17 states with GOP contests, said:
``This is a unique political happening. It exceeded my fondest
expectations.''
   Just hours after the vice president's top aides said he would
not accede to Sen. Bob Dole's demand for one-on-one debates in
Illinois, Bush appeared before a crowd of supporters to declare ``a
national victory.''
   Bush was getting a respite from the campaign wars today as he
and his wife, Barbara, remained in seclusion at their Houstonian
Hotel condominium while aides held strategy sessions for next
Tuesday's Illinois primary.
   Bush's election performance on Tuesday was stunning. After
winning the South Carolina primary on Saturday, he captured
delegate-rich Florida and Texas, and scored other victories
throughout the South. He pushed his delegate total toward 700,
close to two-thirds the number needed for nomination in New Orleans
next August.
   ``This will probably be the single most smashing win anyone's
ever had from the standpoint of delegates in one day,'' exulted
campaign manager Lee Atwater. ``A Guiness Book of Records day.''
   ``Bob Dole is on the canvas now,'' said Bush's deputy campaign
manager, Richard Bond. ``I don't think he's knocked out, though.''
   Top Bush aides said they saw no benefit in the vice president
meeting Dole in the kind of Lincoln-Douglas face-to-face debates
the Kansas senator demanded on Tuesday.
   Atwater called Dole's maneuver ``an eleventh-hour ploy'' and
Bush spokesman Pete Teeley said: ``We're not going to allow him to
dictate how we run our campaign strategy in Illinois.''
   Bush will fly to Chicago tomorrow to kick off five days of
intensive campaigning. ``We look very strong there,'' Teeley said.
   But on Tuesday night, it was Bush's turn to bask in the glory of
his finest political hour in more than 20 years in public life.
   After watching returns for about two hours with members of his
family and political associates gathered in a 21st floor penthouse
hotel suite, Bush entered a ballroom to the cheers of supporters.
   ``As I said yesterday, whoever wins Super Tuesday convincingly
is going to be the next president, and I'll repeat it. I'm going to
be the next president of the United States,'' he declared.
   ``It's a national victory, not a victory so much for me
personally as for the themes we've been discussing.''
   Bush said he would continue to hammer away at his basic themes
of balancing the budget without raising taxes, ``make progress
toward peace through strength ... and reducing the threat of war.''
   ``This is a big, a major political victory,'' he said. ``My
message is going to continue to be one of hope. America's best
days, I am convinced, lie ahead.''
</TEXT>
