<1ST_LINE>r a BC-EditorialRdp 3Takes   03-09 0649</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 3 Takes,0684</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers
throughout the nation.
   March 2
   Albany (Ore.) Democrat-Herald on the United States and Panama:
   The United States finds itself powerless to do anything about
yet another irritant in Central America.
   The irritant is Manuel (Antonio) Noriega, the National Guard
general and dictator in Panama. ...
   The U.S. government is pussyfooting around partly because it
used to rely on Noriega for occasional help and partly because it
doesn't know what to do. ...
   Many Latin Americans regard the United States as an
imperialistic power, but in fact we can't seem to get rid of a
tinpot dictator who gets rich by funneling narcotics to shiftless
American youth. Some imperialism!
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   March 7
   Lubbock (Texas) Avalanche-Journal on the United States and
Nicaragua:
   The muddled U.S. policy in Central America became even more so
over the weekend as experts pondered the House defeat of
``humanitarian'' aid for the Nicaraguan Contras.
   As a result, not only is the fate of the Nicaraguan rebels
fighting to overturn the Marxist Sandinista regime in jeopardy, but
U.S. policy in the region remains one of vacillation and weakness _
the result of unbelievable on-again, off-again meddling by Congress.
   With no immediate aid in the pipeline, the fate of the Contras
is now in limbo.
   The White House, Congress, the media and the American people can
be faulted for not coming to grips with the issue of what to do
about Soviet expansion into this hemisphere.
   The problem is the same as it has been all along _ fear of
becoming involved in another guerrilla-type war and guilt for not
being able to deal with Third World problems which have no easy
solutions.
   Great nations do not let themselves become enmeshed in such
fuzzy thinking.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   March 4
   The Tennessean, Nashville, Tenn., on Barry Goldwater on Evan
Mecham:
   One thing you have to say for Barry Goldwater, former Arizona
senator: He expresses his opinions forcefully and pulls no punches.
   Another thing you have to say for him: He can admit a mistake.
   Goldwater now says he was mistaken to support the election in
1986 of (Arizona) Gov. Evan Mecham, who is undergoing an
impeachment trial and faces a recall election in May.
   The arch-conservative Goldwater said Mecham should go back to
the job he had before becoming governor _ selling cars. But he
acknowledges that Mecham may not listen to reason.
   ``He is a very obstinate man,'' Goldwater said of Mecham. ``I
used to drive mules and he's a lot like a mule.''
   Goldwater not only expresses opinions forcefully, he tells the
truth.
   Mecham, indeed, resembles a stubborn mule. But with Goldwater's
help, perhaps the state of Arizona won't have to put up with the
errant and arrogant governor too much longer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   March 4
   The Press, Atlantic City, N.J., on the war against drugs:
   ``Just say no.''
   That's what the Reagans have been saying to people who use
drugs. It's not that simple. For thousands of addicts, going
straight is difficult; many need help, but as a result of budget
cuts, the help is often nowhere to be found.
   It should be easy, though, for the president to cut off all
foreign aid and impose severe sanctions against those countries
doing little, if anything, to stop the flow of drugs into this
country.
   The penalties can range from a loss of foreign aid to a 50
percent tax on imports.
   According to congressional reports, wholesale corruption in
Mexico has made that country ``the portal through which flows
one-third of all the marijuana, heroin and cocaine on America's
streets and schoolyards.''
   Yet the administration declined to decertify Mexico and other
nations, citing national security problems. ...
   That means the administration places a higher priority on how
anti-Moscow a nation is than it does on how anti-drug it is.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
