<1ST_LINE>r a BC-EditorialRdp 1stAdd   03-09 0843</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 1st Add,0876</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: it is.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   March 3
   Morning Sentinel, Waterville, Maine, on the Shultz peace mission:
   Secretary of State George Shultz accomplished two things on
(his) peace mission to Syria and Jordan. He spent some of the
taxpayers' money. And he spent some of the taxpayers' money. ...
   The truth is that the Palestinians, though they are falling to
Israeli gunfire at the rate of two or three a day in occupied
towns, see no reason to give up their position at this time. ...
   What the recent skirmishes ... have done is publicize the plight
of the Palestinian refugees, a situation that had existed for so
long that even terrorist acts failed to make it big news. ...
   What the U.S. proposal would do is move the bitter dispute of
Palestinians and Israel to the bargaining table. Such a move would
defuse the explosive situation in the occupied territories, and end
the battle that has been costly in terms of Palestinian lives but a
boon politically.
   If the United States or any other party is going to bring peace
to this troubled land, it will take more than vague promises of
negotiation. Without the ingredients for a real compromise, peace
envoys might as well just stay home.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   March 3
   Carlsbad (N.M.) Current-Argus on George Shultz:
   The man is aging gracefully, just like his boss. Unlike Ronald
Reagan, though, Secretary of State George P. Shultz skips around
the globe on a monthly basis, handling missions of import with
savvy and vitality.
   Nearing the end of a lengthy and distinguished career in
governmental service, Shultz has not only survived in an
administration that has had constant turnover, he has thrived. He
has emerged as the true superstar of the Reagan years.
   A gentleman in the most complimentary sense, Shultz possesses an
iron will and discipline. He has hung tough with an impeccable
dignity through some trying circumstances, ranging from Lebanon to
Ollie North.
   Though he has been off the mark on occasion, he has never
wavered from what he believes. A man of intense patriotic devotion,
Shultz has been the man that has kept things together for Reagan.
   Unlike his whirling dervish predecessor, Al Haig, Shultz exudes
a calm that has made the difference in various situations. He's
everybody's favorite Uncle George.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   March 7
   Los Angeles Daily News on alcoholism firings:
   Last Wednesday, U.S. District Judge Elizabeth Kovachevich ruled
in Tampa, Fla., that the National Marine Fisheries Service's firing
of an alcoholic who missed 14 months of work in a three-year period
constituted unlawful discrimination because the employee was
legally crippled by alcohol.
   Kovachevich's ruling was based on a law that requires federal
agencies to ``make reasonable accommodations'' for handicapped
workers, including alcoholics and drug addicts.
   That law seems part of a trend, one that the U.S. Supreme Court
will fortunately have an opportunity to stop this summer when it
rules on another case. That case involves two veterans who claim
that alcoholism prevented them from taking full advantage of
Veterans Administration education benefits during the 10-year limit
following their military discharges. ...
   There is a big difference between people with incurable medical
problems and people who choose not to fight their thirst for
alcohol. ...
   But legally defining alcoholism as a disease would set a
dangerous precedent that conceivably could lead to the
decriminalization of drunken driving (or make it a prosecutable
offense for social drinkers only). This trend could even spawn the
birth of the alcoholic defense, by which those who can blame their
addiction for their transgressions could escape punishment. ...
   There comes a point at which the legal system must assume that
adults are responsible for their behavior, and that line must be
drawn at excessive drinking.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   March 4
   The Sheboygan (Wis.) Press on how hard Congress works:
   What's this? One of our local congressmen claiming that Congress
doesn't work hard enough?
   What kind of way is that to treat one of your own? Why, the very
thought is almost un-American. It's also a good way for Rep. Thomas
Petri, R-Fond du Lac, to light a fire under his colleagues and then
watch them do a slow burn.
   Petri criticized House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, for
scheduling a ``measly'' 14 legislative working days and calling for
only 10 votes in the first 50 days of 1988. He described it as ``a
stunning absence of congressional activity.''
   That accusation, of course, was enough to send his colleagues
into a tizzy. Before long, several of them were grumbling about how
Petri doesn't know what he's talking about.
   Of course they all work hard, the insulted congressmen said. And
how dare Petri even think of such a thing?
   If Congress is so busy, why do they waste so much time on
foolish proclamations to satisfy their constituents back home and
dream up ways to tack their own pet projects onto bills that have
absolutely nothing to do with each other?
   The only thing Petri is guilty of is calling 'em as he sees 'em.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
