<DOCNO> AP880309-0155 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 1222EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-EditorialRdp 2ndAdd   03-09 0475</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 2nd Add,0493</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: sees 'em.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   March 3
   St. Paul (Minn.) Pioneer Press Dispatch on the Noriega regime:
   It is time for the United States to turn the economic screws as
tight as possible on Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega and his henchmen.
That may be the only way to get them to relinquish their grip on
Panama.
   The State Department is preparing to notify U.S. banks that hold
Panamanian deposits not to engage in any transactions with the
Noriega regime. (Deposed president Eric Arturo) Delvalle's lawyers
also have started lawsuits to block any transfer of funds.
   The United States should refuse to hand over the $8 million
payment of canal revenues due Panama next month. That is part of
the $80 million in revenues for this year.
   The United States also should consider a trade embargo and a ban
against flights into the United States of Air Panama _ which also
might cut down the drug traffic _ and termination of any
humanitarian aid to Panama.
   Applying all available drastic economic pressure now may be the
only way to topple the Noriega regime without widespread bloodshed.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   March 6
   Providence (R.I.) Journal on aid to the Contras:
   On Thursday (March 3), the House of Representatives defeated yet
another proposal to aid the contra rebels in Nicaragua. The vote
leaves the resistance stranded with no American aid whatsoever.
   The issue of peace and freedom in Central America is too
important to lay to rest. President Reagan can be counted on to
press Congress for a new vote on aid. ... But he must act swiftly.
...
   When the tally was complete, it was applauded by Reagan, but
regretted by Speaker (James) Wright _ even though the president
supports the Contras and the speaker opposes them. This ... may
possibly be explained by the cynical purpose of the measure itself.
   The real intent was not to aid the Contras but protect their
opponents on Capitol Hill.
   Reagan wants to give Congress one more chance. ... If Speaker
Wright blocks this effort ... his Democratic colleagues will need
more than a fig leaf to hide behind in November.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   March 2
   Huntington (W.Va.) Herald-Dispatch on IRS accuracy:
   If you've been putting off doing your 1987 taxes, here's a
chilling thought: Money magazine reports it asked 50 tax preparers
nationwide to figure out one family's taxes _ and got 50 different
answers.
   Meanwhile, the General Accounting Office has told Congress that
the Internal Revenue Service is giving incorrect answers to 39
percent of the questions posed by people who call for help with
their tax returns.
   No matter how complex the law, those who turn to the IRS for
help are entitled to a straight answer, and Congress should make it
clear to IRS Commissioner Lawrence B. Gibbs and his staff that it
expects nothing less.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
