<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BytheNumbers     03-09 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-By the Numbers,220</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For release at 6:30 p.m. EST; time set by source</NOTE>
<HEAD>Population Group Publishes Statistical Look at America</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Population growth puts pressure on the
environment and resources, whether it occurs in the Third World or
the United States, a population group says in a new booklet.
   ``USA by Numbers: A Statistical Portrait of the United States,''
was issued Wednesday by Zero Population Growth to show how
increasing numbers of people affect the nation's environment,
economy and society as a whole.
   ``Although Americans are increasingly aware of population
pressures in other parts of the world, many of us do not recognize
the symptoms of overpopulation when we find them in our own
backyards,'' said Susan Weber, executive director of the non-profit
population group.
   The group has compiled statistics from a variety of sources,
many of which also appear in the massive Statistical Abstract of
the United States issued annually by the Commerce Department.
   The new 164-page volume, however, concentrates on the
relationship between population and the quality of life in the
nation.
   Chapters in the volume look at population growth over time, city
and rural relationships, young and old, fertility and health,
sexuality and abortion, unemployment, poverty, water use,
pollution, land use and habitat.
   The paperback volume costs $8.95 plus $1.50 for shipping and
handling and can be purchased from Zero Population Growth, 1601
Connecticut Ave., N.W., Washington, D.C., 20009.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
