<1ST_LINE>u a PM-ThrillKilling 1stLd-Writethru a0667 03-09 0584</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Thrill Killing, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0667,0601</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Youth Who Killed For Thrill Was Begging for Help, Laywer Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs on closing arguments, picking up 4th graf
pvs, ``A local cable xxx</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DEDHAM, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 15-year-old youth charged with murdering
a classmate with a baseball bat for the thrill of it was a confused
youth whose cries for help were ignored, the defense argued in
closing arguments today.
   Defense attorney John Philip White, who urged the jury to
deliver a verdict of innocent by reason of insanity, characterized
Rod Matthews as having a ``diseased intellect'' that made him
unable to act rationally.
   White also said that the Canton youth's attempts to seek help
from teachers prior to the Nov. 20, 1986 slaying were ignored.
   Norfolk County Assistant District Attorney Peter Casey said the
defense's contention that Ritalin adversely affected Matthews was a
``smoke screen.'' He argued that Mathews, who is being tried as an
adult, was a calculating murderer.
   Casey noted testimony from several medical experts that Ritalin
does not permanently alter behavior or trigger violence or
hallucinations in normal doses.
   Matthews, whose eyes were downcast during two hours of closing
arguments on the seventh day of the trial, admitted to bludgeoning
14-year-old Shaun Ouillette of Canton with a baseball bat in a
wooded section of the community south of Boston.
   White depicted Matthews as a highly unstable youth whose use of
the drug Ritalin to control hyperactivity may have contributed to
his violent behavior.
   ``He was working in his own world,'' said White.
   The judge gave final instructions to the jury and said
deliberations would begin in the afternoon.
   A local cable access station has run the trial unedited,
including dramatic testimony by classmates that Matthews plotted
the murder for a month and calmly showed them the body as it lay
for weeks in snow-covered woods.
   ``Nothing has impacted the community more than this case,''
Canton Cable General Manager Tanya Willow said. ``It's what
everyone talks about. It's such a tragedy.''
   Defense experts maintained and prosecution witnesses contested
that Matthews, who pleaded innocent by reason of insanity, had
emotional problems worsened by his use of the prescription drug
Ritalin.
   Coincidentally, Ouillette's mother, Jeanne Quinn, testified that
her son took Ritalin from age 7 through 11 to successfully control
frantic behavior that plagued his childhood.
   Dr. Michael Annunziata, a court-appointed psychiatrist,
testified Tuesday that Matthews suffered from a ``conduct
disorder'' but had not experienced classic symptoms of psychosis,
such as hallucinations.
   Dr. Marcel Kinsbourne, a neurologist at the Eunice Shriver
Center in Waltham, testified that standard doses of Ritalin should
not trigger violent behavior.
   Under cross-examination by the defense, Kinsbourne said the drug
could not totally eliminate Matthews' volatile behavior.
   Dr. Bernard Yudowitz of Belmont's McLean Hospital testified
Monday that Ritalin may have made it harder for Matthews to control
his behavior.
   Matthews said he had plotted the slaying for a month to
experience what killing someone was like, according to testimony
from two classmates. Ouillette's body was discovered in December
1986 after one of the classmates sent an anonymous letter to police.
   Matthews has been held at a Danvers children's facility since
last year.
   The case has been compared to the trial of Anthony Broussard,
18, sentenced to 25 years to life Dec. 3, 1982, in San Jose,
Calif., for killing his girlfriend in 1981. Broussard, who was
tried as an adult, took at least 13 schoolmates to see the victim's
body.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
