<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Soviet-Mideast     03-09 0323</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Soviet-Mideast,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Murphy Heads for Moscow to Brief Kremlin on Mideast Peace Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assistant Secretary of State Richard Murphy
headed for Moscow today to brief Kremlin leaders on U.S. efforts to
bring about Mideast peace talks, the State Department said.
   Murphy will brief Soviet Foreign Minister Edouard Shevardnadze
on the latest U.S. efforts in advance of Shevardnadze's visit to
Washington later this month, said spokesman Charles Redman.
   Secretary of State George Shultz promised to keep the Soviets
updated about his Mideast plans when he conducted a shuttle mission
in the region last week. Shultz personally briefed the Soviets on
the initial phase of his mission when he stopped in Moscow last
month.
   Shultz is seeking to bring Israel and the Arabs to the
negotiating table for talks on Palestinian autonomy starting May 1.
Under the plan Shultz presented to Israeli, Jordanian and Egyptian
leaders, the talks would be launched in an international forum that
would include the participation of the United States, the Soviet
Union, China, England and France.
   Shultz, who initially rejected Soviet involvement in the
process, now views the Kremlin's involvement as necessary to nudge
along the reluctant Arabs who are Moscow's allies. Shultz has asked
both Israel and Jordan for responses to his proposals by next week.
   Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir has balked at bringing the
U.S. plan up for a cabinet debate, and intends instead to present a
plan of his own when he comes here next week. That plan calls for
joint U.S.-Soviet participation in autonomy talks for the 1.5
million Palestinians under Israeli occupation.
   Murphy will also stop in Bonn, Rome, Paris and Brussels to bring
officials there up to date on the U.S. Mideast initiative, Redman
said.
   Western European leaders have praised the U.S. involvement,
which is aimed at resolving the three months of Israeli-Palestinian
bloodshed in which at least 80 Arabs have been killed.
</TEXT>
