<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Georgia     03-09 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Georgia,0352</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Georgia GOP Claims Super Tuesday Primaries Shows New Party
Strength</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republicans claimed victory in Georgia Wednesday
after almost twice as many people voted in the party's presidential
primary as ever before, boosting Vice President George Bush's
campaign.
   Democrats, meanwhile, picked Jesse Jackson, with Sen. Albert
Gore Jr. a surprisingly strong second.
   Secretary of State Max Cleland said the 39 percent turnout _ a
presidential primary record _ helped Bush and Gore, who were
preceived as the moderate candidates.
   With 99 percent of the ballots counted, Bush led with 214,892
votes, or 54 percent, giving him all 48 delegates to the August GOP
nominating convention in New Orleans.
   Sen. Bob Dole of Kansas trailed with 94,121 for 24 percent.
Former television evangelist Pat Robertson had 64,995, 16 percent,
and Rep. Jack Kemp of New York had 23,459, or 6 percent.
   In the Democratic race, Jackson had 247,317 votes, or 40
percent. His plurality victories in two congressional districts,
plus his statewide lead, put him ahead for 37 delegates to the
Atlanta convention in July.
   Gore parlayed endorsements by several top state Democrats,
including Sen. Sam Nunn, into 200,758 votes, or 32 percent, good
for 30 delegates. Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis was a distant
third with 96,881, 16 percent, and received 10 delegates.
   With almost 400,000 ballots cast in the GOP primary, the party
doubled the turnout of 1980, when President Reagan blasted Bush on
the way to nomination.
   Longtime GOP activist Bob Bell, currently chairman emeritus of
the state party, was buoyed by the turnout, claiming it represented
a solidifying of the party in the state.
   Although he agreed that newly active Robertson supporters were
responsible for some of the increase, he said most of the new
voters were oldtime Democrats who ``couldn't find anything in the
Democratic Party to attract their attention, ... so they opted for
Bush.''
   Cleland, a Democrat, agreed with Bell, saying, ``I think it (the
GOP turnout) shows that Georgia is a bonafide two-party state.''
</TEXT>
