<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Gallaudet-Profile     03-09 0297</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gallaudet-Profile,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Most of Gallaudet's Students Deaf</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gallaudet University, currently embroiled in a
dispute over the selection of its new president, is the only
liberal arts institution in the world for the deaf.
   The 99-acre campus in northeast Washington provides education
for 2,200 university students, 400 high school students and 200
elementary school students. Nearly all the undergraduates are deaf.
   The federally supported institution receives 75 percent of its
$76 million budget from Congress, with the rest coming from
tuition, which is about $6,000 per student.
   The school began in 1856, when Amos Kendall, a wealthy
journalist and former postmaster general opened the Kendall School
for deaf and blind children on his 99-acre farm.
   The following year, Kendall persuaded Congress to incorporate
the school as the Columbia Institution for the Instruction of the
Deaf and Dumb and the Blind, with President James Buchanan as its
patron.
   In 1864, President Abraham Lincoln signed legislation empowering
the institution to award college degrees through a new National
Deaf Mute College. Edward Miner Gallaudet, son of Thomas Hopkins
Gallaudet, a pioneer in educating the deaf, became its president.
   Five years later, President Ulysses S. Grant signed the diplomas
of the college's first three graduates, starting a tradition that
President Reagan follows today.
   In 1894, the college was renamed in honor of the elder
Gallaudet, and in 1986, Gallaudet College became Gallaudet
University by an act of Congress.
   The institution today has 274 full-time professors, of whom 30
percent are deaf. In addition, 22 percent of the school's
1,300-member support staff are deaf.
   Professors cannot receive tenure unless they demonstrate their
proficiency in sign language to a panel of students and faculty,
and all professors are required to simultaneously speak and sign
their own lectures in English.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
