<1ST_LINE>r p AM-RhodeIsland     03-09 0251</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rhode Island,0256</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush, Dukakis Trounce Opposition In Rhode Island</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis and
Vice President George Bush cashed in on their New England
connections to win Rhode Island's presidential primary.
   Dukakis was a familiar face to Rhode Islanders long before he
began running for president. He campaigned here several times and
quickly gained support from most of Rhode Island's Democratic
hierarchy.
   ``A year ago, no one was going to say that Mike Dukakis would be
the next president,'' Lt. Gov. Richard A. Licht said Tuesday night.
   Dukakis had 34,159 votes or 70 percent; Jesse Jackson had 7,369
votes or 15.2 percent; Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt had 2,013
votes or 4.1 percent; Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr. had 1,932
votes or 4 percent, and Illinois Sen. Paul Simon had 1,392 votes or
2.9 percent.
   Among Republicans, Bush won 10,403 votes or 65 percent; Kansas
Sen. Bob Dole had 3,637 votes or 22.6 percent; former television
evangelist Pat Robertson had 921 votes or 5.8 percent, and New York
Rep. Jack Kemp had 783 votes or 4.9 percent.
   Based on those results, Dukakis likely would capture 19
Democratic delegates and Jackson 3, while Bush would gain 15 GOP
delegates and Dole 6.
   Jackson supporters broke out champagne to celebrate their
candidate's strong showing in a state that is only 2 percent black.
   ``Given $2 million in TV advertising by Dukakis and $100,000 by
Jackson nationally, it shows good management,'' said Jackson's
state campaign chairman, Walter R. Stone.
</TEXT>
