<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--Brink'sDecision     03-09 0162</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Brink's Decision,0165</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appeals Panel Upholds Conviction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state appeals panel has unanimously upheld the
conviction of a defendant in the botched 1981 Brink's robbery that
resulted in the deaths of two policemen and a guard.
   The state Appellate Division in Brooklyn rejected the appeal by
Sam Brown, 46, who is serving a 75-year to life sentence for his
murder and robbery conviction.
   The charges stemmed from the $1.6 million holdup of a Brink's
truck in Nanuet, north of New York City.
   Kathy Boudin, a former Weather Underground activist, pleaded
guilty to the charges and is serving a prison term of 20 years to
life. Three other defendants were convicted.
   Among the many arguments raised by Brown's lawyer and rejected
by the appeals panel was that the indictment should have been
dismissed because his rights were violated when he was beaten by
prison officials after his arrest and that government officials
interfered with his right to counsel.
</TEXT>
