<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 1346EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-CrashHearing 1stLd-Writethru a0685 03-09 0938</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Crash Hearing, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0685,0965</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rescue Coordinator Operation Went Well</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with new grafs 1-13, rescue coordinator's testimony
today; picks up 6th graf pvs, `The NTSB report...'; SUBS grafs 15,
``One survivor xxx, and 19th graf, ``Two Flight 1713 ^^^^, to
CORRECT, only one passenger saw ice</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DEBBIE NEWBY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The effort to save victims of a Continental
Airlines crash went extremely well even though radio batteries
failed, pens wouldn't write and rescuers weren't dressed for the
cold, the rescue coordinator testified today.
   Continental Flight 1713 crashed while taking off from Stapleton
International Airport last Nov. 15 in a snowstorm and left 28
people dead and 54 injured.
   ``We feel fortunate we had that many survivors,'' said Dr.
Michael Brunko of Denver General Hospital, who was in charge of the
rescue operation at the crash. He was testifying on the second day
of a National Transportation Safety Board hearing.
   ``Obviously, there were people trapped in the wreckage who we
could not do anything for. And to this day, I do not know what else
could have been done,'' he said. The overall operation ``went very,
very well,'' he said.
   Among the problems, Brunko said, were the fact that there were
too many rescue workers and vehicles on the scene and that
Continental employees were questioning survivors at the site, even
though the employees role had been part of an earlier crash
rehearsal at the airport.
   ``We survived by adrenaline,'' he said of the cold and snow.
   Brunko said there were so many emergency vehicles that he had to
run 10 to 15 feet away to escape background noise so he could
communicate with the airport command post.
   The four-day NTSB hearing is expected to lead to a report
detailing factors that may have contributed to the crash.
   Brunko's testimony this morning jibed with investigation reports
released Tuesday by the NTSB that quoted one firefighter as saying
rescue personnel at the crash site were ``10 deep and waiting to
get in to help.''
   ``We had more personnel than we needed,'' Brunko said.
   Rescue workers also said that ``the Continental people got in
the way of medical treatment of the passengers,'' according to the
report.
   Brunko said that at one point at least 15 Continental employees
arrived at the crash site, many of them heading for the nose of the
aircraft, which had flipped upside down on the runway and broken
into three pieces.
   He said he had identified about 20 patients needing treatment
before the Continental employees arrived, and their presence made
him suddenly uncertain who were patients and who were airline
employees.
   The NTSB report outlined several problems found by a review
team, including the lack of a staging area for rescue vehicles that
caused ambulances to arrive an estimated 45 minutes after the crash.
   ``I was shocked at the number of people running around who were
not firemen,'' Ron Fano, director of airport operations, testified
Tuesday.
   Fano, who headed the rescue command post, said some operations
were delayed because of two seriously injured passengers inside the
post.
   He said buses to transport the injured did not show up until
about an hour after the accident and ambulances did not show up for
45 minutes.
   The report also said firefighters were trained to extinguish
fires on older models of aircraft, and had difficulty rescuing
survivors.
   The NTSB team did not directly criticize the rescue effort.
Denver Fire Chief Richard Gonzales said he believed the work ``went
rather smothly.''
   The report said Continental employees may have interfered with
medical treatment of passengers by trying to interview them at a
nearby fire station.
   However, Continental spokesman Bruce Hicks said airline
employees routinely are involved in rescue efforts, and he noted
that Continental workers participated in a crash drill at Stapleton
two months before the crash.
   De-icing and the pilots' experience flying DC-9s were the other
chief issues raised during testimony Tuesday, although government
officials have said their inquiry is not focusing on a single
possible cause.
   One survivor told investigators he saw ice and snow on one of
the wings, but another survivor who also was concerned about ice
said the wings only were wet. A pilot on another plane said the
Continental jet looked clear.
   Wes Zimmerman, a Continental pilot whose 727-300 aircraft was on
the runway at the same time as the Continental jetliner, testified
he saw no ice or snow buildup on Flight 1713.
   ``I felt good about how my de-icing was holding up,'' he said,
explaining that he looked at nearby aircraft to gauge the condition
of his own plane. But he acknowledged that his plane did not sit as
long between de-icing and takeoff as Flight 1713 did.
   Robert Benzon, charge of the NTSB inquiry, said during his
opening statement that officials want to know why 24 minutes
elapsed between de-icing and takeoff when other planes on the
runway took off within 15 minutes.
   Two Flight 1713 passengers, Dr. Fred Helpenstell, 56, of Nampa,
Idaho, and Gregory Wadsworth, 22, an airman stationed in Idaho,
testified they were concerned there might have been ice on the
wings before takeoff.
   ``I wondered at one point, `Is that ice?''' Helpenstell
recalled, ``but I decided it was just wet.''
   Wadsworth, who is stationed at Mountain Home Air Force Base,
said he had a clear view of the left wing.
   ``It had started to snow a lot harder, and it made me real
nervous. It was like the snow was starting to pike up (on the
wings),'' he said. ``I was very concerned, but I said it under my
breath.''
</TEXT>
