<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Florida     03-09 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Florida,0372</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush, Dukakis Impressive in Florida</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENT KALLESTAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, who
called delegate-rich Florida a bellwether state because of its
diversity, swept aside his Democratic opponents in the presidential
primary.
   His well-financed campaign used heavy television advertising to
spread from a liberal base in southeast Florida to win 15 of the
state 19 congressional districts. Jesse Jackson won three and
Tennessee Sen. Al Gore Jr. won only the conservative Panhandle.
   ``This is a diverse group of voters in Florida,'' Dukakis
campaign field director Paul Pezzella said. ``If we can win here,
we can win anywhere.''
   With all 4,459 precincts reporting, Dukakis had 509,248 votes or
41 percent; Jackson 250,579 votes or 20 percent; Missouri Rep.
Richard Gephardt 179,400 votes or 14 percent, and Gore had 158,833
votes or 13 percent.
   Vice President George Bush crushed his Republican rivals,
winning 545,668 votes or 62 percent; Kansas Sen. Bob Dole had
185,179 votes or 21 percent; former television evangelist Pat
Robertson had 93,752 votes or 11 percent, and New York Rep. Jack
Kemp had 40,545 votes or 5 percent.
   Based on those results, Bush was expected to win all 82 of
Florida's GOP delegates; Dukakis would win 90 of the 136 Democratic
delegates at stake; Jackson would get 33 delegates; Gephardt 7 and
Gore 6.
   Florida offered the second-largest batch of delegates on Super
Tuesday, behind only Texas, which Bush and Dukakis also carried.
   Bush capitalized on President Reagan's popularity and his own
familiarity to Floridians. He has visited often on official
business such as heading the South Florida Task Force on Drugs, and
for personal visits to his mother in Palm Beach and to his son,
Jeb, now Florida's commerce secretary.
   The Bush campaign had five full-time paid staffers compared to
16 for Dukakis, and both were bankrolled for a strong television
push to reach the diverse Florida electorate on the final weekend
preceding Tuesday's vote.
   Gephardt's poor showing was the biggest surprise in the
Democratic race. Endorsed by Rep. Claude Pepper and using a
last-minute media campaign, Gephardt had concerned the Dukakis
campaign most. He failed to carry a single district.
</TEXT>
