<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Obit-Kiesinger     03-09 0524</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Kiesinger,0542</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>West Germany's Chancellor From 1966-69 Dead at Age 83</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kurt Georg Kiesinger, who served
as West Germany's third federal chancellor from 1966 to 1969
despite controversy over his Nazi past, died Wednesday of heart
failure. He was 83.
   Kiesinger spent 18 months in a U.S. postwar internment camp with
other Nazi party members, but he staunchly denied any wrongdoing
during Adolf Hitler's Third Reich and never was charged with any
crimes.
   In a widely publicized incident, Kiesinger was slapped in the
face by Nazi hunter Beate Klarsfeld at a conference in West Berlin
on Nov. 7, 1968.
   Mrs. Klarsfeld was convicted of causing bodily injury and
insulting Kiesinger, and after receiving and appealing a one-year
prison sentence, was given four months' probation. She continued
her bitter public criticism of Kiesinger.
   During his three years at the helm of the nation's Grand
Coalition of conservatives and leftist-leaning Social Democrats,
Kiesinger improved contacts with the East.
   The Christian Democratic chancellor also overcame a troubling
recession with a series of economic measures during his term.
   Known as ``King Silver Tongue'' because of his powerful speaking
style, Kiesinger retained his heavy Swabian accent. He was a Roman
Catholic, born April 6, 1904, in Ebingen in Baden-Wuerttemburg.
   As a 29-year-old lawyer, Kiesinger joined the Nazi party in
1933, the year Hitler came to power. He said he became
disillusioned with the party a year later because of the bloody
purge of storm trooper leader Ernst Roehm and his associates.
   During World War II, Kiesinger worked in the radio propaganda
section of the Nazi foreign ministry and served as department head
for part of the war.
   After the war, U.S. forces rounded up thousands of Germans
pending investigations of their membership in the Nazi Party. He
spent 18 months in an internment camp in Ludwigsburg.
   A German court fined him 50 marks, then $12.50, for being a
party member. The fine was returned when the court ruled later that
he had risked his life to get a student out of a Nazi prison.
   Kiesinger's Nazi past brought him much unfavorable publicity
when he became a candidate for chancellor, and the sharp, public
debate continued during his term.
   He always denied any wrongdoing and declared: ``I have clean
hands. I know what I did and what I did not do.''
   Kiesinger was a party member for the full 12 years of the Nazi
regime from 1933 to 1945.
   In 1966, Kiesinger succeeded fellow Christian Democrat
Chancellor Ludwig Erhard, forming the only Grand Coalition of
conservatives and Social Democrats.
   Kiesinger sought more contact with the communist states of
Eastern Europe, breaking with past policy. He established
diplomatic relations with Romania and Yugoslavia, but his overtures
suffered a setback when the Soviets invaded Czechoslovakia in 1968.
   Kiesinger's government remained a resolute ally of the United
States, but he feuded with President Lyndon Johnson in 1967 and
complained that he had not been adequately consulted on a
U.S.-Soviet nuclear weapons treaty.
   He was a symbol of reconciliation, grouping the conservative
Christian Democrats and their Bavarian counterparts with the Social
Democrats.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
