<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland-Opposition     03-09 0264</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Opposition,0272</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wroclaw `Happening' Organizer Receives Two-Month Sentence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court on Wednesday sentenced an activist
to two months in prison because of a ``street happening'' that
poked fun at the government, an opposition spokesman said.
   Waldemar Frydrych, 34, head of the opposition cultural group
Orange Alternative, was arrested by police with five other people
on Tuesday, said Jacek Kuron, a Warsaw opposition activist.
   He said about 50 Orange Alternative supporters, some of whom
carried a banner reading ``Missiles _ no, sanitary pads _ yes,''
handed out cotton pads to women in downtown Wroclaw. Police moved
in quickly and halted the demonstration.
   Feminie hygiene products are in short supply in Poland. Tuesday
was International Women's Day.
   The sentence marked one of the few times since a September 1986
amnesty for political prisoners that a misdemeanor court has
sentenced someone to prison for a politically motivated offense. In
almost all cases, people were held up to 48 hours and released
after being fined.
   Kuron said Frydrych was sentenced on a charge of causing public
unrest.
   Two other Orange Alternative supporters, Pawel Kasprzak and
Krzysztof Albin, were each fined the equivalent of $79 by the
misdemeanor court, Kuron said.
   He said the Orange Alternative members joked with the court by
arguing that Karl Marx, the founder of communism, was actually a
bearded lady.
   Frydrych has been detained at least half a dozen times since
September for organizing various Orange Alternative ``happenings''
in Wroclaw in which demonstrators have dressed up as Santa Claus,
Lenten penitents and even secret policemen to satirize government
policies.
</TEXT>
