<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LehderTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0843 03-09 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lehder Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0843,0482</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lehder Helped Race-Car Driver Identified As Paul Newman Partner</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS two grafs at end, SCCA has no listing for Terry Knight</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A convicted marijuana smuggler
testified in the cocaine-smuggling trial of Carlos Lehder Rivas
that the Colombian had helped finance Terry Knight, identified as a
former auto racing partner of actor Paul Newman.
   The brief mention of Newman came Tuesday as defense attorney Ed
Shohat questioned witness Charles Gregory Von Eberstein.
   Knight lived on the Bahamian island of Norman's Cay. Von
Eberstein testified that he had seen a picture of Knight's car with
the insignia of the Norman's Cay Yacht Club on it.
   When Shohat asked if Newman, the actor, was in the picture, Von
Eberstein answered, ``I knew Terry was his racing partner. I knew
(Lehder) had put some money in it.''
   The witness said he didn't believe Knight was aware of the
smuggling going on at the island.
   Lehder, 38, is accused of conspiring with others to smuggle some
3.3 tons of cocaine into the United States from Colombia from 1978
to 1980 via Norman's Cay in the Bahamas.
   Newman has long taken part in auto races as a sideline to his
acting career. His last partner, Jim Fitzgerald, died last November
when he crashed his car during the St. Petersburg Grand Prix. There
was no elaboration on Knight's career in Tuesday's testimony.
   Von Eberstein testified Tuesday that he had decided not to
return to the United States after Knight played an audio tape which
indicated Von Eberstein and his associate Ed Ward had been
indicted. The source of the tape and how Knight got it were not
disclosed in testimony.
   Von Eberstein, a friend and neighbor of Ward, a convicted
smuggler, testified that he and Ward made several cocaine flights
for Lehder in 1979 and 1980. He said one was into Colombia and
several were from Norman's Cay, Lehder's private Bahamian island,
to Prison Airport near Reidsville, Ga.
   Von Eberstein, who was sentenced to 18 years in prison in 1981
after pleading guilty to three marijuana charges and one count of
income-tax evasion, eventually had his sentence reduced to 15 years
and was released after four years in prison.
   Lehder, reputed to be one of the leaders in the violent
Colombian Medellin cartel, is charged with conspiracy, possession
of cocaine with intent to distribute, importation of cocaine and
operating a continuing criminal enterprise.
   A woman who works in the records department of the Sports Car
Club of America in Englewood, Colo., said the club keeps listings
for racers registered in the last three years and had no listing
for a Terry Knight.
   The woman, who declined to give her name, said there was no way
to be certain who Newman's partner was.
</TEXT>
