<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880309-0183 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 1359EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis     03-09 0694</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Stumps in Rust Belt</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis went from the triumph of his
seven Super Tuesday victories to the scrap-strewn wasteland of
Chicago's southeast corner on Wednesday, seeking votes in the
Democrats' next major campaign test.
   The Massachusetts governor talked to steel workers _ some laid
off, some on the job _ in his first full day of campaigning for
next Tuesday's Illinois primary, when 173 delegates will be at
stake.
   Gone were the condominiums and strawberry festivals of the
Florida primary campaign. Now Dukakis was campaigning for votes
among steel mills, scrap heaps, refineries and belching smokestacks.
   Dukakis did only slightly better on Tuesday than rivals Albert
Gore Jr. and Jesse Jackson. But he quickly tried to stake out a
claim as the only national candidate in the race capable of winning
in the South and the industrial Midwest.
   He said of Gore, the Tennessee senator, ``I'm not so sure he's a
major contender. A guy from Massachusetts beat him in Texas, beat
him in Florida. He wasn't willing to go into the early primaries.
But I still take everyone seriously.''
   With two Illinois residents in the race _ Jackson and Sen. Paul
Simon _ ``obviously it's going to be an uphill battle,'' Dukakis
said. ``I hope when the people of Illinois cast their votes they'll
do so for someone who can clearly win the presidency.''
   In a dig at another rival, he said the failure of Missouri Rep.
Richard Gephardt to win any but his home state on Super Tuesday
proved the futility of negative campaigning. Dukakis, who had
countered with an anti-Gephardt ad of his own, said, ``I think that
what happened to Congressman Gephardt yesterday demonstrates pretty
clearly that when you engage in that kind of campaigning, you're
going to get hurt.''
   Dukakis opened the day at a breakfast meeting at the Lion's Den
restaurant on Chicago's east side where he met with laid-off steel
workers. ``I don't know a great deal about the steel industry as
such,'' Dukakis told the group. But he said he did have experience
in Massachusetts getting labor, management and government working
together.
   Later the governor and his wife Kitty donned hard hats as they
toured the Metron Steel factory in Chicago's hard-hit Calumet
industrial section.
   Aware of Walter Mondale's disastrous showing in 1984, Dukakis
has avoided appearing to be too strong a union Democrat. Rather, he
said he wanted to be ``a full-employment Democrat.''
   Jack Corrigan, Dukakis' campaign operations director, said there
would be no change in the candidate's message now that he is in the
nation's industrial section.
   ``We haven't gotten the AFL-CIO endorsement. We've gotten some
union support and we're proud of it. I don't see it as a problem.''
   Despite the cash drain of Super Tuesday with its emphasis on
television advertising, the Dukakis campaign remains in good
financial condition, aides said. Campaign finance chief Robert
Farmer said Dukakis is raising half a million dollars a week.
Coming out of Super Tuesday, he said, Dukakis has $2 million in the
bank and $1 million on the way in federal matching funds. ``We're
going to be in very good shape,'' Farmer said.
   Dukakis made it clear in a speech to about 1,000 cheering
supporters Tuesday night in Chicago that his Greek immigrant
heritage will provide a key ingredient of his campaign in Illinois.
The Chicago area is among the most ethnically diverse in the nation
with its heavy population of first- and second-generation Eastern
Europeans.
   ``Many of your families, like my parents, came to this land in
search of opportunity,'' Dukakis told the cheering supporters.
``They didn't have much money in their pockets; they couldn't speak
the language, but they believed in the American dream... It was
their broad shoulders and strong arms and keen minds that built the
mightiest industrial machine in the world.''
   ``It was their hard work that built the steel mills and the auto
plants and the foundries and the factories that carried our nation
through two world wars,'' Dukakis said. The phrases were new to an
otherwise standard campaign stump speech.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
