<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Robb     03-09 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Robb,0228</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Robb Recovering From `Very Physical Encounter'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Gov. Charles Robb was recovering
Wednesday from what he described as ``a very physical encounter
with a glass door.''
   Robb was knocked unconscious Tuesday night when he walked into
the closed door in his Washington, D.C., office. Robb said he
``blacked out for a few moments'' but did not require medical
attention.
   ``I haven't had a sensation like that since the last time I
played in a football game,'' Robb said.
   Robb, one of the architects of the Super Tuesday presidential
primaries, said he was talking to a television cameraman as he was
leaving his office. ``I had a pretty good head of steam because I
had a lot of news interviews scheduled,'' Robb said.
   The door normally is open, he said. The glass did not break.
   Minutes later, Robb cut short an appearance on the Cable News
Network. ``I couldn't remember why I was there for a few minutes,''
he said. ``Finally, I said on the air that I wouldn't be doing the
viewers a service by continuing.''
   Robb said he was interviewed by other news organizations
throughout the night, but he asked that the interviews be kept
brief.
   ``People kept trying to get me to go to the hospital, but I was
hard-headed,'' he said.
</TEXT>
