<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Indonesia     03-09 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Indonesia,0401</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suharto Set for Election to Fifth Term as President</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: One name cq for Suharto and Sudharmono.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GHAFUR FADYL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The People's Consultative Assembly
gathers Thursday to elect President Suharto, the only candidate, to
his fifth five-year term.
   The 1,000-member assembly, which meets every five years, began a
session last week to choose the president and vice president and
issue new guidelines for state policy.
   Suharto has led the nation of 170 million people since 1967.
   For vice president, the Moslem United Development Party has
nominated its chairman, Jailani Naro, to run against State
Secretary Sudharmono, chairman of the governing Golkar Party and
Suharto's most trusted aide. The vice president is to be elected on
Friday.
   Naro said that despite advice from several senior assembly
members to drop his candidacy, it was his democratic right to run
for election and ``we will fight 'til the end.''
   Sudharmono was nominated by Golkar and supported by the
military, provincial and Indonesian Democratic Party factions in
the assembly.
   All five factions, including the Moslem United Development
Party, nominated Suharto for president.
   The five factions also approved Suharto's 35-page report on the
state of the nation under his administration in the last five years.
   In his report last week, Suharto said his administration had
been able to overcome unpredictable challenges and difficulties,
including a recession and a sharp drop in the price of oil, a major
foreign exchange earner for Indonesia.
   He said Indonesia's economy was expected to grow by an annual
average of 3.6 percent during the five-year economic period ending
in March 1989. The original target had been 5 percent.
   In elections last April, Golkar won 299 seats in Parliament,
which also has 100 government-nominated members from the military.
The Moslem United Development Party has 63 seats and the Indonesian
Democratic Party 38 seats.
   The 500-member Parliament and 500 provincial and district
officials make up the People's Consultative Assembly, the highest
policy-making body in the country.
   Seats in provincial and district legislatures were decided by
proportional representation based on the total votes each party
received.
   In the assembly, Golkar has 548 seats as well as 151
government-nominated members from the military and 147 from the
provinces. The Moslem United Development Party has 93 and the
Indonesian Democratic Party 61.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
