<DOCNO> AP880309-0186 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 1407EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Hawaii     03-09 0182</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hawaii,0188</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Beats Jackson in Two-Man Race</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hawaii's Democratic caucuses came down to a test
of strength between party leaders' support for Michael Dukakis and
grassroots organizing by followers of Jesse Jackson. The
Massachusetts governor won, but Jackson performed impressively.
   Dukakis received 2,026 votes in the presidential preference
poll, compared with Jackson's 1,470 votes, according to incomplete
returns Wednesday.
   ``This is the first time we've really had a race,'' said Gov.
John Waihee, a Dukakis supporter. ``I don't ever remember this much
excitement.''
   Dukakis was expected to get 12 of the 20 pledged delegates that
were up for grabs, with Jackson getting the rest.
   ``It's incredible,'' said Jackson's state coordinator Richard
Port. ``Jackson showed his appeal to Hawaii's multi-cultural
voters. That's the real story here.''
   Much of Jackson's support was thought to have come from the
2,000 new party members his organization signed in recent months.
   Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt received 83 votes, Illinois Sen.
Paul Simon 46, Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr. 41, and former
Colorado Sen. Gary Hart 83. There were 183 votes for
``uncommitted.''
