<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Panda 1stLd-Writethru a0853 03-09 0183</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Panda, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0853,0182</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farmer Finds Rare Panda Cub Tangled In Branches</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT spelling of Sichuan.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sick and hungry panda cub that a farmer found
tangled in tree branches has bounced back to health, boosting
efforts to save the increasingly scarce animal, it was reported
Wednesday.
   Cun Cun _ or ``Spring Spring'' _ was found in the mountains of
Tianquan county in Sichuan province and rushed to a zoo in the
Sichuan capital of Chengdu, the China News Service said.
   ``When this panda arrived at the zoo, he was in very bad shape.
He had contracted an intestinal virus, was severely dehydrated and
very weak,'' a zoo official was quoted as saying.
   The giant panda, native only to China, has become an endangered
species. The number in China has dropped below 1,000 and scientists
have had limited success breeding them in captivity.
   About 200 pandas are in Chinese zoos, but some experts have
called for a halt their capture, arguing that they live longer and
reproduce better in the wild.
</TEXT>
