<DOCNO> AP880309-0188 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 1408EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Tibet Bjt   03-09 0684</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tibet, Bjt,0707</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Reported Roaming Tibetan Capital After Anti-Chinese Unrest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHENGDU, China (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Truckloads of police and cars with wailing
sirens patrolled the Tibetan capital of Lhasa through the night in
an apparent show of force after an anti-Chinese uprising by
thousands of Tibetans, a Western source said Wednesday.
   The Westerner, a tourist who reached Chengdu from Lhasa, said
the trucks drove past the Lhasa Hotel where he was staying after
midnight.
   A Tibetan source in Lhasa reported similar police movement both
day and night since the Saturday uprising, in which Buddhist monks
and thousands of Tibetans stoned police and built bonfires across
the city.
   Asked if she was frightened, the source said, ``No, I'm not
frightened because _ ,'' but the telephone line was broken in
midsentence.
   The Panchen Lama, Tibetan Buddhism's second-highest leader,
denounced those who participated in the all-day violence.
   ``I represent the Tibetan comrades here and myself in expressing
my indignation ... at the violence committed by the small numbers
of separatists during the riot,'' the Panchen Lama, a loyal
supporter of the Beijing government, said at a special meeting of
Tibetan leaders in Beijing on Wednesday.
   The Panchen Lama called for severe punishment for the rioters,
saying, ``As a Tibetan and a devout Buddhist, I cannot condone this
kind of crime.''
   The evening news devoted nearly five minutes to the Panchen
Lama's remarks and briefly showed footage of Saturday's rioting.
   Doje Cering, chairman of Tibet's regional government, said
official policy toward Tibet would not change because of the
rioting, the official Xinhua News Agency reported.
   Lhasa TV said one Tibetan and a Chinese policeman were killed,
but Western sources in Lhasa said as many as five Tibetans and
three police may have died.
   Western tourists arriving in Katmandu, Nepal, on Wednesday
reported seeing five people dead, including a 10-year-old Tibetan
monk, two Tibetans and two Chinese.
   The Western tourist in Chengdu, in southwestern China, reported
being allowed to visit Sera Monastery on the southern edge of the
city, one of Lhasa's leading monasteries.
   Speaking on condition of anonymity, he said a truck carrying
about 20 armed police was parked along the road to the monastery
and two police officers watched the entrance.
   By contrast, Sera and other leading monasteries were cut off by
police blockades after the last Tibetan protest against Chinese
rule on Oct. 1. At least 14 people died then.
   China sent troops into Tibet in 1950, but it has claimed
sovereignty over the Himalayan region since the 13th century.
   Many Tibetans maintain they were effectively independent for
centuries under the Dalai Lama, their temporal and religious
leader. The current Dalai Lama fled to India in 1959 after an
abortive anti-Chinese uprising.
   Thursday is the 29th anniversary of the uprising.
   There were unconfirmed reports from Lhasa of widespread arrests
in the city. Officials released no figures, however.
   The Western source said police set up two checkpoints along the
road from the Lhasa airport to the city and were stopping vehicles
and asking passengers to get out for a check of their identity.
   Saturday's violence was followed by a small confrontation Sunday
in which Tibetans built barricades and threw stones at police in
Lhasa's central market square.
   Saturday was the final day of the ``moinlam qenmo'' prayer
festival, a more than 500-year-old annual event that is one of the
most important in the Tibetan Buddhist calender.
   Chinese authorities had feared pro-independence Tibetans would
take advantage of the gathering of hundreds of monks and pilgrims
to stage a protest.
   One source said Chinese police in Tibet were put on orders
during the festival to exercise restraint. The source said Tibet's
Communist Party Secretary Wu Jinghua ordered police to retreat from
any confrontation. Reports from several Western sources indicated
police initially did so, then fired tear gas to control the crowd.
   Xinhua reported earlier that no police officers carried arms
while on duty Saturday.
   One Western source reported gunshots being fired after nightfall
Saturday after more than 12 hours of violence. None of the Western
witnesses reported seeing police open fire.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
