<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 1415EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Taxes     03-09 0349</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Taxes,0358</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government to Tax Cooperative Businesses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The growing number of private businesses spawned
by Mikhail S. Gorbachev's economic reforms may soon face an enemy
long familiar to their capitalist counterparts: higher taxes.
   The draft of a new law on private enterprises, published in the
government newspaper Izvestia, outlines plans to tax the profits of
the new ventures as well as the incomes of their workers.
   While the law remains in draft form, it is likely to earn
approval from the nation's nominal parliament, the Supreme Soviet,
at its next session expected in late spring.
   Gorbachev last week cited the taxation plan in an apparent
effort to assure workers in state-run businesses that they should
not feel their private counterparts are getting off easy.
   ``It's understood that we need industrious and honest
initiative, but not of the kind of some cooperatives which exploit
a deficit and engage in outright money-grabbing,'' the Soviet
leader told workers at a Moscow factory.
   Many cooperatives charge higher prices than state-run industries
and services, and complaints about this have appeared in the Soviet
press. Many Soviets say, for instance, that while food quality and
selection are better in cooperative restaurants, the prices are out
of their reach.
   The government, while proposing broader opportunities for
cooperatives, also apparently felt the need to tap the businesses'
wealth, calling this approach ``social fairness.''
   The law does not specify at what rate cooperatives will be
taxed, saying this will depend on the kind of business. It said the
tax rate will be fixed for five-year periods. Cooperatives can
deduct from their taxes contributions to charities, and the
government may give some businesses tax breaks for producing
certain high-demand items, according to the law.
   Personal income taxes will be progressive, the law said.
Currently, a social security tax is deducted from the pay of
workers in state-run enterprises.
   The law on private business that took effect May 1 already
provided for a heavy individual tax structure that gave the
government claim to 70 percent of incomes in excess of 600 rubles,
or $1,000, per month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880309-0191 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 1414EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Reagan-NotreDame 3rdLd-Writethru a0869 03-09 0763</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Notre Dame, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0869,690</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts grafs 12-13, The crowd, with color.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOUTH BEND, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan said today he sees ``a
will to succeed evident in our land'' reminiscent of the spirit of
legendary football coach Knute Rockne, who led Notre Dame to five
undefeated seasons.
   Reagan, unveiling a commemorative stamp to mark the 100th
anniversary of Rockne's birth, reminisced both about Rockne's
storied career and his own role in Hollywood's portrayal of it.
   And the president used the occasion to predict a rosy future for
U.S. business.
   ``American industry is lean and mean and ready to meet the
competition head-on,'' he said. ``I predict that, as this year
progresses, we will see American manufacturing re-emerge as the
leading force in the world marketplace. Exports will, in fact, race
ahead and lead our domestic economy.''
   Reagan said the Rockne legend ``stood for fair play and honor,
but you know, it was thorougly American in another way. It was
practical; it placed a value on devastating quickness and agility
and on confounding the opposition with good old American
cleverness. But most of all, the Rockne legend meant this ... that
on or off the field, it is faith that makes the difference, it is
faith that makes great things happen.''
   Reagan said Rockne recognized ``the fundamental element of the
American character that no tyranny and few of our competitors can
ever hope to match. Knute Rockne knew and appreciated it: The
creative genius and omnipresent optimism of our people.''
   Reagan also reminisced about his own heyday in Hollywood, when
he convinced a producer to allow him to play the part of George
Gipp in the movie ``Knute Rockne: All American.'' Gipp was the
Notre Dame football player whose deathbed request to Rockne _ ``Win
just one for the Gipper'' _ inspired the team to a 12-6 victory
over Army in 1928.
   Reagan called the part ``a young actor's dream'' and he said the
movie still has a message for Americans:
   ``There's a will to succeed evident in our land. I happen to
have always believed in the American people. Don't ever sell them
short. Given the proper tools and a level playing ground, our
workers can out-produce and out-compete anyone, anywhere.''
   He added that ``there are those who see a dark side to our
technological progress'' with the development of more deadly
weapons.
   However, the president said, ``Technology is pointing a way out
of this dilemma'' and cited his ``Star Wars'' space-based missile
defense system.
   The crowd in Joyce Athletic Center was treated to several
minutes of the Rockne film on a giant screen showing the young
Reagan as he portrayed Gipp throwing the ball and hustling with his
teammates.
   At the end of Reagan's speech, he was handed a football which he
hurled toward a group of players seated in the crowd. Heisman
trophy winner Tim Brown caught the pigskin as the crowd roared its
approval.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said ``the Gipper goes
back'' as he announced the trip. During his presidency, Reagan's
supporters have seized upon his movie-inspired nickname to help
build support for his political programs.
   The president himself recalled the emotional movie during his
first visit to Notre Dame's South Bend campus, when he delivered
the commencement address on May 17, 1981.
   Rockne, a graduate of the men's college, was its head football
coach from 1918 to 1931 and compiled a record of 108 wins, 12
defeats and five ties. During his tenure, the ``Fighting Irish''
were undefeated in five seasons and won six national championships.
   An innovator of the forward pass and the ``box formation,''
Rockne taught his players to excel in the classroom as well as the
playing field.
   Rockne was killed in a plane crash on March 31, 1931, an
accident that stunned the nation. His funeral Mass was broadcast
across the nation on radio.
   He won a place in the College Football Hall of Fame's first
group of inductees in 1951.
   The 22-cent stamp produced in his honor bears a portrait of the
smiling, balding coach holding a football. Rockne's name is
emblazoned in blue and gold, the colors of the ``Fighting Irish.''
   It is the sixth in the American Sports series, which has honored
Babe Didrikson Zaharias, Bobby Jones, Babe Ruth, Jim Thorpe and
Roberto Clemente.
   The stamp was a joint effort of designer Peter Cocci and
engraver Tom Hipschen, both of the Bureau of Engraving and
Printing, the White House said.
   The new stamp goes on sale nationally tomorrow.
</TEXT>
