<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Louisiana     03-09 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Louisiana,0425</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Super Tuesday Gets Mixed Review From Party Leaders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN SAYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Louisiana's Super Tuesday primaries won by
George Bush and Jesse Jackson drew mixed reviews Wednesday from
state Republican and Democratic leaders.
   ``We think Super Tuesday was wonderful,'' said Carolyn
Blue-Mikell, a spokeswoman for state Democrats. ``There was much,
much more attention paid to the voters, particularly here in
Louisiana.''
   In 1984, the Democratic candidates virtually ignored the state,
while in the months leading up to Tuesday's voting, the top
hopefuls came to Louisiana more than 100 times, she said.
   But state GOP Chairman Donald Bollinger questioned whether the
big event would be repeated.
   ``The Democrats thought they'd come out of the South with a
conservative Democrat that would make the Republicans look silly.
Where's their conservative?'' he said. ``I think in four years,
they won't want another Super Tuesday.''
   With reports in from 99 percent of the precincts, Bush had
83,585 votes, or 58 percent; former television evangelist Pat
Robertson had 26,227, or 18 percent; Kansas Sen. Bob Dole tallied
25,602, or 18 percent; and New York Rep. Jack Kemp had 7,818, or 5
percent.
   Jackson had 219,960 votes, or 35 percent; Tennessee Sen. Albert
Gore Jr. had 174,458, or 28 percent; Massachusetts Gov. Michael
Dukakis had 95,310, or 15 percent; and Missouri Rep. Richard
Gephardt tallied 66,894, or 11 percent.
   The results translated into 32 delegates for Jackson, 23 for
Gore, six for Dukakis and two for Gephardt. On the Republican side,
Bush nabbed 34 delegates with 7 uncommitted.
   Jackson, who aimed at expanding his ``Rainbow Coalition'' of
support across racial and ethnic lines, captured his second
straight victory in the Louisiana Democratic primary.
   ``We think he's been able to take his message to the people of
Louisiana,'' said New Orleans Mayor Sidney Barthelemy, a key
Jackson supporter. ``His base of support has grown.''
   But Bud Courson, Gore's state coordinator, said that Jackson
should be worried about the Tennessee lawmaker's performance.
   ``We feel that a turnaround has come, and again looking further
down the road we feel that Sen. Gore can pull the Democratic Party
back together,'' said Courson.
   In the 4th Congressional District race to replace Gov.-elect
Buddy Roemer in the U.S. House, former Roemer aide Jim McCrery, a
Republican, and Democratic state Sen. Foster Campbell claimed spots
in an April 16 runoff.
   Roemer gave his backing to Stan Tiner, former editor of the
Shreveport Journal, who finished third.
</TEXT>
