<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea     03-09 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea,0358</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Merger Off: Bid To Form United Opposition Collapses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bid to forge a united opposition to
the government of President Roh Tae-woo collapsed Wednesday, with
one faction accusing the other of sacrificing unity for power.
   Kim Dae-jung, head of the Party for Peace and Democracy, told a
news conference a merger with the rival Reunification Democratic
Party wasn't possible in time for the General Assembly elections,
expected to be held in April.
   Kim said he would not follow the lead of his counterpart, former
Reunification Democratic Party chief Kim Young-sam, and step down
from his party's leadership.
   ``The (Reunification Democratic Party) made unreasonable
demands, including my resignation,'' he said.
   Opposition supporters split ranks last year when both Kims ran
for president, dividing the anti-government vote and allowing Roh
to win the presidency without a plurality.
   Since then, public pressure has been on both to step down. Kim
Young-sam resigned from his party's leadership in February. The
resignation of both were seen as the key to merging the parties.
   Kim Dae-jung vowed to continue Wednesday as supporters shouted
``No resignation!'' But he offered a compromise, saying that the
parties should jointly support National Assembly candidates as an
interim measure.
   The Reunification Democratic Party rejected the proposal, saying
a merger is possible only if Kim Dae-jung resigns.
   ``This is a real betrayal of the people and democratic forces.
At this point, the only and largest obstacle to reunification is
Kim Dae-jung,'' the Reunification Democratic Party said in a
statement following Kim Dae-jung's news conference.
   Kim Dae-jung formed his party just prior to the presidential
elections when he and his supporters bolted from the larger
Reunification Democratic Party.
   At stake in the elections are 299 seats. Under a law adopted
Tuesday, 224 lawmakers must be picked in as many districts by
popular vote and 75 others under a proportional representation
system based on the total votes each party gets.
   Roh was elected on Dec. 16 in the first direct presidential
elections in Korea in 16 years.
</TEXT>
