<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Strike     03-09 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Strike,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>250,000 Demonstrators Call for Gandhi's Ouster</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 250,000 people chanting
``Rajiv must go!'' crowded outside Parliament House on Wednesday
and demanded the resignation of Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi and
midterm parliamentary elections.
   The rally and a day-long strike in the Indian capital were
sponsored by the right-wing Bharatiya Janata Party and the Lok Dal,
a rural-based party.
   Most shops in New Delhi were closed, but government offices,
banks and schools remained open. Traffic was normal.
   The capital's 35,000-strong police force and another 5,000
paramilitary troops were deployed to maintain peace. Police
spokesman Ravi Pawar said no violence was reported.
   Police said at least 250,000 people gathered for the rally.
Organizers claimed there were more than 500,000 participants.
   ``This mammoth gathering ... declares the Congress (Party)
government at the center to be anti-laborers, anti-farmers and
anti-rural,'' said a resolution adopted at the rally. Both parties
called upon opposition groups to unite and form a government in the
next general elections.
   Gandhi's Congress Party also faces a rally and strike sponsored
by two communist parties and leftist opposition groups on March 15.
   The next general elections are not due until December 1989,
although Gandhi could call them earlier. Gandhi's party holds 410
of the 544 seats in the governing lower house of Parliament.
   The opposition has blamed Gandhi's adminstration for failing to
control inflation and impose law and order in northern Punjab
state, where at least 400 people have died this year in violent
attacks by Sikh separatists.
   Gandhi's government also has been accused of corruption in its
arms purchases from foreign companies.
</TEXT>
