<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     03-09 0403</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heigh-ho, heigh-ho, it's off to the
barber we must go.
   Workers at the Disneyland Hotel are now subject to a 31-year-old
dress code established for employees at the amusement park across
the street.
   Facial hair is a no-no, so even the late Walt Disney would have
had to shave his mustache to work at the hotel recently acquired by
Disney Co.
   Six of the seven dwarfs, Uncle Remus, Captain Hook and Pinocchio
toymaker Gepetto would all be renegades working in the real-life
world of Disney.
   And men aren't the only ones bound to conform with the company's
desire for a uniform ``wholesome'' look among employees.
   Women will have to abandon slacks, heavy makeup, gaudy jewelry
and wild hairdos. Men will have to get haircuts, shave, and cover
any tattoos.
   
   When Disney Co. assumed control of the hotel, its 1,600
employees fell under the dress code established for the Magic
Kingdom in 1957. Workers who rebel will be terminated.
   ``The reason that we are doing this is because the Disneyland
Hotel is becoming part of Disneyland Attractions, and we have an
appearance standard. ... It is associated with Disney and is
expected by our guests,'' said Disneyland spokesman Bob Roth.
   Disney officials are explaining the dress code to employees this
week, with compliance expected virtually immediately.
   But some hotel employees said they'll rebel, including engineer
Mike Searles, 40, who wears a handlebar mustache. ``I don't think
it's right, and I'm not going to compromise,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   High school students cooked up what they
hope was the world's largest burrito to feed some of the city's
needy and maybe earn a spot in the Guinness Book of World Records.
   Creating the 1,492-foot Mexican specialty consumed 1,200
tortillas, 461 pounds of meat, 3,400 olives, 32 pounds of tomatoes,
14 pounds of onions, and 71 pounds each of salsa, sour cream and
lettuce, said Betty Swan, cafeteria manager at Lincoln High School.
   It took 400 students all of Tuesday morning to put together the
big burrito, she said.
   Two members of the Portland school board measured the burrito as
it wound around the school's gym. ``I consider this a very solemn
responsibility,'' said Steve Griffth, one of the board members.
   After the burrito was measured, it was divided among
representatives of various social service agencies to be given to
their clients.
</TEXT>
