<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghanistan     03-09 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan,0491</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Afghanistan Blasts U.S. Demand on Ending Military Aid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED AFTAB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghanistan on Wednesday rejected a U.S. demand
that the Soviet Union halt military aid to the Afghan government as
soon as the United States stops aiding the Moslem insurgency.
   The dispute could become a major snag in U.N.-sponsored talks
aimed at ending nine years of fighting in Afghanistan and securing
the withdrawal of an estimated 115,000 Soviet troops.
   Foreign Minister Abdul Wakil of Afghanistan flatly opposed the
U.S. position, explained at a State Department briefing Friday,
that there must be a ``symmetrical cessation'' of U.S. and Soviet
military aid.
   Wakil said at a news conference that Soviet assistance could not
be compared to Western aid to ``terrorist groups.''
   He said Afghanistan had received Soviet assistance for ``68
years'' and would continue to do so ``even after the withdrawal of
Soviet troops.'' But he did not specify what kind of Soviet aid
Afghanistan expected to receive.
   Soviet troops entered Afghanistan in December 1979 and are
helping the Marxist government battle the Moslem resistance.
   The United States is the main supplier of arms to the
guerrillas. Aid reportedly totaled about $700 million in 1987,
including the shoulder-fired ground-to-air Stinger missiles said to
have downed at least 200 Soviet and Afghan aircraft.
   Wakil said the U.S. demand was bringing a new issue into the
talks. He said another was Pakistan's attempt to link a Geneva
settlement to the formation of a broad-based transitional
government replacing the present Soviet-backed one in Kabul, the
Afghan capital.
   He said there had been no important developments in the talks
since ``concessions'' by Moscow and Kabul led to an agreement
Friday on the timetable and logistics of a Soviet withdrawal. U.N.
mediator Diego Cordovez said this completed the main elements of a
settlement.
   Wakil accused Pakistan of ``trying to kill time'' and
maneuvering to ``push the Geneva negotiations toward a stalemate''
by holding out for an interim government. He said the chief
Pakistani representative, acting foreign minister Zain Noorani, had
returned ``empty-handed'' from weekend consultations in Islamabad
with the country's opposition leaders.
   Noorani said early last week that Pakistan would decide after
those consultations whether it was prepared to sign a settlement
with the Afghan government under President Najib, which it does not
recognize.
   Wakil, speaking as the latest round of the nearly 6-year-old
talks entered its second week, said the Afghan government would
continue to push for a speedy settlement. He also stressed that his
country was not setting a deadline after which it would leave
Geneva.
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev said last month Moscow would
bring home its troops starting May 15 if the settlement was signed
by March 15. Wakil said the start of the withdrawal depended on the
date of the signing and suggested the 60-day time span would be
retained.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880309-0199 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 1440EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SeawolfSubmarine     03-09 0569</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Seawolf Submarine,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy Defends Seawolf Attack Sub Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy on Wednesday defended the Pentagon's
planned Seawolf submarine, promising Congress that the latest
generation of attack subs would maintain U.S. undersea superiority
far into the 21st century.
   Vice Adm. Bruce DeMars, assistant chief of naval operations for
undersea warfare, said the SSN-21 Seawolf will have double the fire
power and be faster, quieter and more survivable than the SSN-688
Los Angeles class sub, which the Seawolf is expected to replace as
the nation's chief attack submarine.
   The SSN-21 Seawolf, which has been in the research and design
stage for six years, has been criticized by some lawmakers who fear
the sub is not advanced enough for the Soviet's planned successor
to their Akula attack sub.
   But DeMars dismissed that notion, telling the House Armed
Services sea power subcommittee that the Seawolf is ``the
foundation for far-term submarine superiority.''
   ``Repeated, objective analyses have concluded that Seawolf and
her sister ships will have three times the mission effectiveness of
the improved SSN-688 and will restore the commanding technological
and tactical margin which historically we have enjoyed over the
Soviets,'' Demars said.
   Last year, a House subcommittee tried to delay funds for the
project, but Congress restored the money. Navy officials have
warned that such a delay could severely damage the Seawolf program
and cause massive cost overruns.
   DeMars said the project now is on schedule and on budget.
   General Dynamics Corp.'s Electric Boat Division and the Newport
News (Va.) Shipbuilding and Drydock Co., rival sub makers who
traditionally have split SCAN-688 contracts, have been researching
and designing the Seawolf for the Navy.
   Peter Yeo, an aide to Rep. Sam Gejdenson, D-Conn., whose
district includes the Electric Boat shipyard at Groton, Conn., said
Seawolf proponents do not expect intense opposition again this year.
   Opponents ``made their case last year and it didn't fly,'' Yeo
said.
   The first SSN-21 contract is expected to be awarded later this
year, DeMars said. Delivery is planned for late 1994.
   The first Seawolf will cost $1.6 billion, and following subs
will be about $1 billion, the Navy estimates.
   DeMars said the Seawolf costs about 25 percent more than the
SSN-688, but predicted it would only be about 10 percent more over
its 30-year life span because it has much lower operating and
support costs.
   DeMars dismissed suggestions that the SSN-688 could be improved
significantly. He said since the program began in 1976, the Navy
has ordered 4,600 improvements, and there is simply no more room
left on the sub for new systems.
   He said a lack of room on the new SSN-688s has forced the Navy
to put bunks in the torpedo room and line some floors with canned
goods.
   Suggestions that the sub could be modified further are made by
``people who have obviously never been on these subs,'' DeMars said.
   Meanwhile, DeMars dismissed a scenario posed Rep. Charles E.
Bennett, D-Fla., chairman of the subcommittee, under which funds
for a Trident submarine would be delayed for a year and the savings
would go towards building more ships.
   ``To delay the Trident, which is our most survivable sub and
best deterrent, would be the wrong signal to send to both the
country and the Soviets,'' DeMars said.
   The Tridents, which carry long-range nuclear missiles, are made
by Electric Boat. The government orders one a year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
