<HEAD>Unofficial Journal Protests Afghan Detention of French Journalist</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghanistan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Writers and editors of a dissident publication met
the ambassador to Afghanistan on Wednesday to protest the jailing
of a French journalist in Afghanistan on spying charges, one of the
dissidents said.
   Alexander Podrabinek, chief editor of the weekly
Express-Chronicle said in an interview with The Associated Press
that Ambassador Mohammadulah Subhani Safi met with six writers and
editors for about 30 minutes.
   The dissidents were protesting the conviction of French
journalist Alain Guillo, who on Jan. 4 was sentenced in Kabul to 10
years in prison.
   Reading from a copy of the statement handed to the ambassador,
Podrabinek said, ``incarceration for fulfilling his (Guillo's)
journalistic duty is possible only in a barbaric country that does
not value citizens' or human rights.''
   The group demanded the release of Guillo, 45, and said Afghan
authorities should allow him to leave the country.
   The ambassador accepted the group's statement but told its
members their reliance on Western media reports was giving them an
inaccurate picture of the situation in Afghanistan, Podrabinek said.
   Guillo, a filmmaker, was captured Sept. 12, 1987, after he
entered Afghanistan with guerrillas of the Afghan National Front.
   State-run Kabul radio said in announcing the sentence that
Guillo had entered Afghanistan nine times since 1980 ``to prepare
video films and cassettes, to carry out spying activities and to
stengthen relations with armed opposition groups.''
