<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Gephardt     03-09 0570</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gephardt,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gephardt Says Democratic Race Still On; Attacks Gore, Dukakis on
Trade</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEARWATER, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Richard Gephardt on Wednesday
acknowledged his dismal Super Tuesday showing but insisted ``the
race is still on'' as he attacked two of his Democratic
presidential rivals on the trade issue central to his campaign.
   Standing outside a textile mill threatened with closure,
Gephardt said of Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis and Sen. Albert
Gore Jr. of Tennesse, ``The bottom line is are they really for new
policies.''
   ``The fact is that Gov. Dukakis and Sen. Gore talk tough about
trade,'' Gephardt said, but they don't support policies that would
reduce the nation's trade deficit.
   Aides said Gephardt's comments were a signal that he's sticking
with trade as the central theme of his campaign.
   In the Super Tuesday polling, Gephardt won only his home state
of Missouri. Dukakis, Gore and Jesse Jackson shared the spoils in
the other Super Tuesday contests.
   Still, Gephardt vowed to stay in the race until the Democratic
National Convention in July, and said he had enough money to do
just that.
   ``The race is on,'' Gephardt said. ``I'm not where I'd like to
be but I think I have ample opportunity to make up lost ground and
get back in the middle of this race and to win.''
   Mike Nelson, a Gephardt aide, said campaign is less than
$100,000 in debt. ``Our fund-raising has not let up at any of the
dry points in the campaign,'' he said.
   ``We did not borrow, as others did, to run on Super Tuesday,''
Gephardt said. ``Maybe in retrospect we should have.''
   Gephardt made his comments at the first of a series of stops in
South Carolina, where he was campaigning for that state's caucuses
on Saturday. Deputy campaign manager Joe Trippi said Gephardt hopes
for a second place showing behind Jackson, who was born in South
Carolina.
   Gephardt planned a farm rally later in the day before flying to
Michigan and Illinois on Thursday.
   Illinois holds its primary Tuesday, and the Michigan Democratic
caucuses are March 26.
   But Gephardt's aides said the results in Illinois will be
muddled because of two favorite sons, Sen. Paul Simon and Jackson.
As a result, Gephardt has characterized the Michigan contest as the
next major Democratic showdown.
   He challenged Gore to a contest outside his rival's native South.
   ``Sen. Gore has to show he can win outside of his region,''
Gephardt said. ``He's going to have to go and show he can do well
in Illinois and Michigan and the other states in the North and
Northeast.
   ``Obviously it is clear I need to do well in Michigan,''
Gephardt said. ``When I get my message out to the voter I win.''
   The Missouri congressmen blamed his fourth place Super Tuesday
showing on a lack of money. Gephardt said he was only able to spend
$1 million on television, less than one-third of what was spent by
his rivals.
   Voters, he said, ``didn't hear what I had to say. That was the
problem.''
   ``The cutting question is can I get my message to the voters.''
   The textile plant where Gephardt spoke employs about 500 people,
and officials there said as many as 420 of those jobs could be lost
by next month.
   Plant manager Harold Simmons cited foreign competition and the
depressed local economy as reasons for the potential closure.
</TEXT>
