<2ND_LINE>AM-Washington,0310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Robertson Win Was Round 1, Fight Not Over GOP Officials Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID AMMONS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pat Robertson won Round 1, but Republican leaders
cautioned Wednesday that the results of precinct caucuses could
change at county-level meetings and the state convention.
   Grassroots organizing in Washington helped the former television
evangelist prevent Vice President George Bush from repeating here
the victories he recorded in the 16 states holding GOP primaries on
Super Tuesday.
   A sample of precincts taken by the Democrats showed
Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis with a slight lead over Jesse
Jackson, 40 percent to 38 percent.
   With 71 percent of the state's GOP precinct caucuses reporting,
Robertson led the Republicans with 39 percent, Kansas Sen. Bob Dole
had 26 percent and Bush was third with 24 percent.
   But ``no candidate won a clear majority of delegates
statewide,'' noted John Meyers, executive director of the state
Republican Party. ``This is a three-tiered system, and Super
Tuesday was just the first step.
   ``Now some coalitions will form. People have to start coming
together to get votes for the next two steps. Nobody has 50 percent
of the votes by themselves,'' he said.
   State Democratic Chair Karen Marchioro was blunter, saying she
would be ``very surprised if Robertson came out of this state with
any delegates.''
   But if the proportions held during the later steps of delegate
selection, Robertson would get 16 delegates, Dole 11, Bush 10, Kemp
3 and one delegate would attend the national convention uncommitted.
   Of Jackson's surprisingly strong showing behind Dukakis,
Marchioro said, ``Obviously, it's an organizational effort ... I
think also that people like his message _ and that's everywhere in
the state.''
   Official returns for the Democrats won't be known until next
week, after precinct leaders mail in their results.
