<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-ThirdWorldDebt     03-09 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Third World Debt,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Reserve Vice Chairman Opposes New Body For Third World
Debt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice Chairman Manuel H. Johnson of the Federal
Reserve Board told congressmen Wednesday he opposes their plan for
an international body to lift some of the debt burden from Third
World countries.
   He praised Mexico's effort to exchange old debt for new bonds,
saying it was based on the market and gave creditor banks a chance
to adjust their holdings. Critics have called the results
disappointing.
   The Mexican plan has resulted in a reduction of Mexico's debt by
$1.1 billion, said Rodney Wagner, vice chairman of the credit poliy
committee at Morgan Guaranty Bank. His bank sponsored the plan.
   Mexico's debt is estimated at over $100 billion. Total Third
World debt is expected to reach $1.45 trillion by the end of this
year.
   Johnson was sharply challenged by both Democrats and Republicans
on the House Banking Committee. Two of its subcommittees sponsored
Wednesday's hearing.
   Rep. Bruce A. Morrison, D-Conn., told Johnson to ``stop setting
up straw men and start working with us.'' Rep. Jim Bunning, R-Ky.,
asked how Johnson could say that the debt situation has improved
when the price of Third World debt has been dropping on the world
market.
   Bunning cited quotations that indicated Mexico's debt was
selling at 57 to 60 cents on the dollar last May and 48 to 52 cents
in November.
   Johnson replied that the market is thin, easily influenced by
relatively small deals. He said he expects it to turn upwards as a
result of willingness by Brazil and Argentina to come to agreements
with the International Monetary Fund. With Mexico, they are the
biggest Third World debtors.
   Bunning told Morrison he does not believe that putting public
money into a new international institution would solve the debt
problem, and that public money is already going into the Third
World through the fund and the World Bank. They are owned by 151
governments.
   Morrison was influential in getting a plan for a new world body
into the trade bill passed by the House. The proposed institution
would buy up Third World debt and package it for resale, giving
debtor countries at least some of the benefit of the discount.
</TEXT>
