<HEAD>Pentagon Announces New Assignments For Two Air Force Generals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan has nominated two Air Force
generals for promotions and new assignments, the Pentagon said
Wednesday.
   Maj. Gen. Jimmie V. Adams has been nominated for a third star
and the rank of lieutenant general and elevation to the post of
vice commander of the Tactical Air Command, the Pentagon said.
   Adams, 51, is a native of Prichard, Ala., who is currently
serving as the commander of TAC's 1st Air Force. He will replace
Lt. Gen. James R. Brown, whom the Pentagon said Wednesday would
retire on Aug. 1 after more than 34 years of active service.
   Brown, 57, is a native of Bozeman, Mont., who has served as
TAC's vice commander since September 1986.
   The president also nominated Maj. Gen. Monte B. Miller to
receive his third star and to become the surgeon general of the Air
Force. Miller, 57, is a native of Independence, Mo., who is
currently serving as the command surgeon for the U.S. European
Command.
   Miller will replace Lt. Gen. Murphy A. Chesney as the Air
Force's top medical officer.
   The 60-year-old Chesney is retiring on Aug. 1 after more than 33
years of active service, the Pentagon said. Chesney is a native of
Knoxville, Tenn., who has served as surgeon general since August
1985.
