<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Ethiopia     03-09 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Ethiopia,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fighting Hampers Food Distribution</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department expressed grave concern
Wednesday that northern Ethiopia could face widespread starvation
because of fighting between government and insurgent forces.
   Spokesman Charles Redman said insecure conditions along roadways
in Tigray Province caused an 8,000-ton shortfall last month in
deliveries of emergency food supplies to the people in that area.
The goal was 20,000 tons.
   ``We are gravely concerned that expanded fighting will prolong
road insecurity, further complicating transportation difficulties
and leading to depletion of food stocks and widespread
starvation,'' Redman said.
   He attributed the insecure conditions to insurgent activity and
the inability by the Ethiopian government to control it.
   ``We deplore the militarization of roads in northern Ethiopia
and the politicization of the famine precisely at a time when the
people of the area are most vulnerable,'' he said.
   He said truck convoys are prepared to move when circumstances
permit. Food airlift operations sponsored by the United Nations
will continue, he said.
   Tigray province is one of a number of regions in Ethiopia facing
severe food shortages which were partly caused by a drought last
summer.
   According to U.S. estimates, the lives of between 6.7 million
and 7.2 million people are at risk. The U.S. contribution to an
international food relief effort is about 267,000 tons of food
valued at approximately $108 million.
</TEXT>
