<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Maryland     03-09 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Maryland,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush `Steamroller,' Dukakis Organization Spark Wins In Maryland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANE E. ALLEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush never campaigned in
the state, but ``the Bush steamroller leveled Maryland'' anyway on
its way to a 16-state sweep of Kansas Sen. Bob Dole in the
Republican presidential race.
   In Super Tuesday's Democratic primary, Massachusetts Gov.
Michael Dukakis exploited a superb organization and the backing of
Sens. Barbara Mikulski and Paul Sarbanes to leave Jesse Jackson a
distant second.
   Sarbanes easily won nomination for a third term with 86 percent
of the Democratic vote. He will face millionaire Republican
businessman Thomas Blair, a newcomer to politics who drew 46
percent of the GOP vote.
   Bush's tally of 53 percent or 103,899 votes was stronger than
the 48 percent Ronald Reagan polled in the 1980 GOP primary here,
when Bush had 41 percent, according to Republican officials.
   With all 1,574 precincts reporting, Dole finished with 32
percent or 62,721 votes, former TV evangelist Pat Robertson was
third with 12,891 votes or 7 percent, and New York Rep. Jack Kemp
tallied 11,581 votes or 7 percent.
   ``The Bush steamroller leveled Maryland like the rest of the
South,'' Maryland GOP Executive Director Nelson Warfield said. ``I
think Bush did a little better than expected. The Dole camp had
great hopes.''
   Dukakis took 46 percent of the Democratic ballots with 237,389
votes, while Jackson had 150,129 votes or 29 percent.
   The voting was likely to give Dukakis 47 delegates and Jackson
20 delegates. Bush was expected to receive all 41 Republican
convention delegates.
   ``Dukakis was the best organized. It was a Maryland-oriented
campaign that used Maryland people to organize Maryland,'' said
John Willis, vice chairman of the Maryland Democratic Party.
   Willis said Jackson maintained his base from 1984, improving his
showing from 129,387 votes in 1984 to 150,129 votes in 1988.
   Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore, with 45,138 votes or 9 percent,
finished third among Democrats, followed by Missouri Rep. Richard
Gephardt, 41,268 votes or 8 percent.
