<2ND_LINE>AM-Oklahoma,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush, Gore Big Winners in Oklahoma</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON JENKINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr. poured money
into a television blitz and won nearly double the number of votes
cast for his closest Democratic opponent in Oklahoma's presidential
primary.
   With all 2,439 precincts reporting, Gore had 162,511 votes or 41
percent; Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt had 82,565 votes or 21
percent; Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis had 66,226 votes or 17
percent, and Jesse Jackson had 52,431 votes or 13 percent.
   Vice President George Bush had 78,273 votes or 38 percent;
Kansas Sen. Bob Dole had 72,991 votes or 35 percent; Robertson had
44,146 votes or 21 percent, and New York Rep. Jack Kemp had 11,414
votes or 5 percent.
   Based on those results, Gore would win 23 of 46 delegates,
Gephardt would get 13, Dukakis 7, and Jackson 3. Bush would get 33
of the state's 36 GOP delegates, and Dole would get the remaining 3.
   Gephardt won the endorsement of three of Oklahoma's four
Democratic congressmen, and was locked in a virtual tie with Gore
in pre-election polls.
   But the Missouri congressman was outspent 3-1 by Gore in
Oklahoma, with much of the money going for television advertising,
said Lt. Gov. Robert S. Kerr, Gephardt's campaign co-chairman.
   Gore's biggest victory was in the 3rd congressional district,
where he campaigned in a stop at Muskogee in the final week of the
campaign. The nearby town of Gore is named for Thomas P. Gore, a
former Oklahoma senator who was a distant cousin of the candidate.
   ``Super Tuesday has proven that Al Gore is the candidate for
mainstream Democrats,'' said state Sen. Stratton Taylor,
co-chairman of the Gore drive in Oklahoma.
   Bush emphasized his Texas oil business background and visited
the state a day before the primary. Dole made five stops in
Oklahoma in the final week of the campaign, vising Oklahoma City
and Tulsa twice.
</TEXT>
