<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SuperSamoa 1stLd-Writethru a0898 03-09 0433</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Super Samoa, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0898,0440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Samoa's Precinct Reports</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: DELETES extra ``Jones'' in graf 8.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PAGO PAGO, American Samoa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In ``lavalava'' sarongs,
beneath the thatched roofs of a South Seas hotel, and hours behind
the rest of the electorate, Samoans gathered for their moment in
the Super Tuesday sun.
   No negative ads filled the airwaves. No TV anchorman or
presidential candidate descended. And no exit pollster tapped the
wisdom of the voters, all 36 of them. But an upset was in the
making.
   The local Democratic chairman had urged those attending the
party caucus, choosing a three-member delegation to the Democrats'
convention, to vote ``uncommitted.''
   ``We would rather wait to see where the trend is going ... who
doesn't make the cut,'' said Chairman Utu R.M. Sinagege.
   But American Samoa Gov. A.P. Lutali hailed Masschusetts Gov.
Michael Dukakis for his virtues as a fiscal manager, and American
Samoa's congressional delegate, Fofo I.F. Sunia, endorsed another
presidential hopeful, Rep. Richard Gephardt of Missouri. By the
time the party faithful left the Rainmaker Hotel, at the foot of
lushly green Rainmaker Mountain, Dukakis had one delegate, Gephardt
another, and ``uncommitted'' the third.
   The local party chiefs had scheduled the caucus for Super
Tuesday to gain national attention for their Pacific island
territory, which in Republican eyes does not even rate convention
delegates.
   Polls were already closed in most of the 20 Super Tuesday states
when the three dozen Democrats, many clad in traditional, brightly
hued ``lavalavas,'' assembled here in Pago Pago, six time zones
behind the U.S. East Coast and 2,300 miles southwest of Hawaii.
   It was a light turnout _ only one-tenth of those eligible.
National Committeeman Glenn Jones blamed it on the fact that the
territory of 37,500 people has no electoral votes in November's
presidential election.
   But Samoans are deeply interested, nonetheless, in what goes on
in Washington.
   Most of their local budget comes from the U.S. Treasury, and
government welfare payments, made to Samoans on the U.S. mainland,
often find their way here to the home islands, where few jobs are
available beyond the government and two tuna canneries.
   The Samoans' interest apparently is not reciprocated. Party
officials said Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore had pledged to call, but
didn't. Jesse Jackson sent a box of campaign buttons, but Sinagege
said his son sold them to classmates for about 50 cents _ total.
   The lapel strategy may have had an impact, however. Fourteen of
the 36 votes went to Dukakis, eight to Gephardt, 12 were
uncommitted, and the final two went to the man on the buttons.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
