<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Angola     03-09 0549</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Angola,0567</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Angola Says South African Troops Moving North After 180 Rebels
Killed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK REYNA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUANDA, Angola (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South African troops are moving farther
north into Angola to support rebel forces pounded in a three-day
battle this week, government officials said this week.
   The officials said troops loyal to the Marxist government killed
180 UNITA rebels and captured large quantities of South
African-supplied equipment in the battle near Cuemba in central Bie
province.
   ``This was a major battle and we expect more fighting in the
area,'' said one of the officials, who spoke on condition of
anonymity. He said the battle ``shows the South African incursion
into Angola is still moving north in conjunction with rebel
forces.''
   Angolan government radio said government troops destroyed two
South African-built armored personnel carriers and captured another
along with South African arms and ammunition.
   UNITA, the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola,
also is backed by the United States.
   The action was the farthest north UNITA has engaged government
troops since it began driving them out of their southeastern
strongholds when South African troops entered the area in October
to help the rebels repulse a government offensive.
   Cuemba is 375 miles north of Angola's border with South
African-ruled South-West Africa, also known as Namibia.
   In a statement in Lisbon on Wednesday, UNITA said rebels were
enagaged in heavy fighting around Cuemba. It said guerrillas killed
11 Angolan soldiers and four Cubans on Monday in an attack on the
nearby town of Catabola.
   Three weeks earlier, UNITA overran Munhango, 40 miles east of
Cuemba.
   Both Cuemba and Munhango are along the east-west Benguela
railroad, southern Angola's vital transport link to landlocked
Zaire and Zambia. UNITA has targeted the railroad during its
12-year bush war to press President Jose Eduardo dos Santos'
government for a power-sharing accord.
   ``Our troops are holding Cuemba,'' the official said.
   Angolan Defense Minster Gen. Pedro Maria Tonha said Monday in
Lubango, capital of the southern province of Huila, that to take
the strategic city of Cuito Cuanavale, South African forces
fighting with UNITA ``have resorted to bombardment of our positions
with long-range artillery because of the failure of their air
attacks on the city.''
   Angolan authorities announced last month their forces fought off
the third major South African-UNITA offensive against the garrison
city of Cuito Cuanavale in three months.
   Dos Santos said an estimated 7,000 South African troops were in
position around the city, with another 2,000 South African soldiers
scattered around south-central Cunene province.
   South Africa acknowledged in November it was sending troops into
Angola to aid UNITA and has reported casualties among its forces in
Angola in the past two weeks.
   In December and January, the U.N. Security Council called for a
total withdrawal of South African forces from Angolan territory.
   The Angolan officials confirmed Cuban support troops are in
place in the southern war zone but remain behind Angolan front line
positions. ``They are there if needed,'' one official said.
   Cuba has said its has 40,000 troops in Angola and has agreed
with the government to withdraw the Cubans from Angola when South
Africa pulls out of the country, stops aiding UNITA and begins
implementing a U.N. plan for Namibian independence.
   South Africa has demanded a Cuban withdrawal first.
</TEXT>
