<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BRF--NavyLaunch     03-09 0144</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Navy Launch,130</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy to Launch New Guided-Missile Cruiser Next Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy said Wednesday it would launch a new
guided-missile cruiser later this month in Bath, Maine.
   The USS Normandy, a so-called Aegis cruiser, will be launched
during ceremonies on March 19 at the Bath Iron Works, the service
said in a statement.
   Retired Army Brig. Gen. John S.D. Eisenhower will deliver the
principal speech.
   The Normandy, named after the massive Allied landings in France
that led to the defeat of Germany in World War II, is 567 feet
long, 55 feet wide and displaces 9,500 tons.
   The Aegis cruisers are considered the most advanced air-defense
ships in the world, carrying a variety of missiles and gun systems
for use against enemy aircraft and a wraparound radar system that
allows them to ``see'' in all directions at once.
</TEXT>
