<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Idaho     03-09 0206</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Idaho,0212</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Support: Anti-Establishment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOISE, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis won the lion's share of
delegates at Idaho's Democratic caucuses, but Jesse Jackson did
surprisingly well in what Gov. Cecil Andrus saw as a protest vote.
   ``There are a lot of people who are turned off by the so-called
establishment in any way,'' said Andrus, who remains an uncommitted
delegate and urged others to remain uncommitted.
   ``In this case, that is to his (Jackson's) benefit,'' Andrus
said.
   In a state with only a tiny minority population, Jackson waged a
limited campaign but captured four of the state's 18 uncommitted
delegates to the national convention. The Massachusetts governor
won eight delegates, and six will go to the convention uncommitted.
   Party officials were pleased with the turnout, which in most
cases was sharply higher than four years ago when the county caucus
process was used for the first time.
   In Ada County, two caucuses that drew less than 800 people
between them four years ago attracted about 1,700 Tuesday night.
   Former governor John Evans, who was state chairman for Dukakis,
said he felt Dukakis was gaining recognition for his
accomplishments, including the economic revitalization of his state.
   ``That's the message: it can be done,'' said Evans.
</TEXT>
