<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-Macbeth,0596</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Director, Sets, Costumes Ordered for Broadway-bound Macbeth</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: All dollar figures U.S.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BRADLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Glenda Jackson and Christopher Plummer have
avoided broken legs and other major disasters traditionally
associated with the staging of ``Macbeth.''
   But their Broadway-bound production of Shakespeare's
blood-soaked tragedy hasn't been without problems.
   Five weeks before the play arrives at the Mark Hellinger Theater
in New York for a 12-week run, the original director, Kenneth
Frankel, has been dismissed and new sets and costumes at a cost of
$250,000.
   ``We decided we had to make some moves,'' said co-producer Garth
Drabinsky of Toronto, owner of the Cineplex Odeon movie theater
chain.
   The new director, Robin Phillips of Canada's Stratford Festival,
agreed to rescue the production but doesn't want his name on the
program.
   There also are rumors of strife between the two stars _ although
they appeared amiable enough upon arrival March 8 in Toronto for 16
performances at the O'Keefe Center, where $1 million in advance
sales set a box office record.
   ``When we found Robin was free, it was a miracle,'' said
Plummer, a Toronto native and Hollywood veteran who earned critical
acclaim for his Iago in a 1982 Broadway production of ``Othello.''
   ``It saved our necks,'' he added.
   ``We have been working almo  Critics said Frankel, an off-Broadway
Obie award winner, lacked
a cohesive vision of what ``Macbeth'' was all about.
   Miss Jackson is tackling Lady Macbeth for the first time and
finds passionate, erotic bonds between the murdering king and his
ambitious wife.
   ``Undoubtedly part of the attraction each has for the other is
they both have largish sexual appetites. I've never thought that
Lady Macbeth breathed life into a man of straw _ what would be
attractive to her in a man like that?
   ``It was a time when people were infinitely more passionate than
they are now ... they see no alternative to what they are doing,''
she added.
   ``The challenge always is to make it clear to an audience that
Shakespeare is about real people. He's probably the most
contemporary dramatist there is. I'm sure there's a Mr. and Mrs.
Macbeth walking around now.''
   Working with Plummer for the first time, Miss Jackson repeated
her old saw that it's not necessary to like fellow actors in order
to put on a play.
   Asked if he had done anything to make his co-star dislike him,
Plummer smiled and said: ``I constantly do.''
   She chimed in: ``This is true.''
   The production will be seen at Boston's Colonial Theater from
March 22 to April 3 and the Shubert Theater in New Haven April 5-10
before one week of previews in New York. Opening night is April 21.
</TEXT>
