<HEAD>Greek Media Trumpets Dukakis Victories</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis was a big winner on Super
Tuesday and a hit in his ancestral country on Wednesday, picking up
the sort of television and newspaper coverage reserved for a native
son.
   ``Dukakis Triumphs, All Consider Him A Certain President,''
screamed a second edition banner headline in Messimvrini, a
conservative daily newspaper.
   Dukakis, the Massachusetts governor, won Democratic primary
victories in his home state, Florida, Texas, Rhode Island and
Maryland and caucuses in Idaho and Hawaii.
   ``The name Dukakis has a great deal of recognition and the fact
that he is a Greek-American draws intense interest here,'' said
Messimvrini's chief editor, Giorgos Bertsos.
   Dukakis' showing also was one of the top items on the state-run
TV news.
   The conservative afternoon daily 24 Hours, a national tabloid,
ran a large color picture of a smiling Dukakis on its front page.
The left-wing Eleftherotipia said he was ``the main winner among
the Democrats.''
   The Dukakis campaign has been closely followed by the Greek
press and many newspapers have run long interviews with the
candidate.
   On Tuesday, Messimvrini ran four pages on the Super Tuesday
contest under the headline ``The Test of Victory,'' with color
pictures of Dukakis taking up two pages in the middle of the
newspaper.
   Wednesday's left-wing newspapers also had in-depth reporting of
the Democratic and Republican campaigns.
   ``Dukakis and Bush Advancing Steadily,'' headlined the left-wing
afternoon daily Proti above a half-page story.
   Many newspapers played down the fact that Dukakis had split the
vote with Sen. Albert Gore Jr. and Jesse Jackson in the South.
Instead, they highlighted the governor's big wins in Texas and
Florida.
