<1ST_LINE>u w AM-CleanAir     03-09 0737</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Clean Air,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Clean Air Act Could Cost 600,000 Jobs, Business Group Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bill revising the Clean Air Act most likely
would cost the economy $32 billion and 300,000 to 600,000
manufacturing jobs, a business group told Congress on Wednesday.
   In the worst case the cost could reach $73 billion and a million
jobs, about 5 percent of the nation's manufacturing payrolls, the
group said. The minimum cost was put at $14 billion, without a jobs
estimate.
   ``We can't afford to be exposing ourselves to 30 to 70 billion
(dollars) a year and expect to be part of the solution to the trade
problem'' characterized by a $170 billion annual trade deficit,
said David M. Roderick, chairman of USX Corp., in presenting a
study of the air pollution bill approved by the Senate Environment
and Public Works Committee.
   The bill would require tighter pollution controls in several
areas, including new controls on the precursors of acid rain from
old power plants, and stricter requirements for motor vehicles.
Passage is by no means certain.
   Roderick, who is chairman of the environment committee of the
Business Roundtable, an organization of chief executives of large
companies, told a news conference, ``A very high proportion of the
money wouldn't do anything.
   ... It would be the least cost-effective of all our nation's
environmental laws'' as well as the most costly.
   He said Congress should design measures targeted to areas of the
country that don't meet clean-air standards.
   Roderick used an example from his company's steel-making
subsidiary, U.S. Steel Corp., saying the bill would ``go after your
coke ovens in a horrendous way, it would go after your blast
furnaces in a horrendous way ... you could not justify retrofitting
some of those plants.''
   Though the company would have to spend $1.5 billion to $2
billion on compliance, some ovens and furnaces would be closed and
``we would import more semi-finished product.'' One of the
company's most efficient plants found it would have to raise prices
$25 to $40 a ton or roughly 6 percent to 8 percent.
   The company only recently resumed exports, which earn profits of
5 percent to 8 percent on sales. ``This would just wipe that out,''
Roderick said.
   As for weaker steel companies, some of them operating under
protection of the bankruptcy laws, ``they're dead; they're
history,'' Roderick said.
   Manufacturing industry spending of $6 billion a year on air
pollution control would rise to $26 billion, the study said.
   The study by R.M. Dowd & Co., a Washington consulting firm,
pulled together findings from trade association and government
agency studies. No estimates were possible for 22 of 43 provisions
in the bill, Roderick said.
   Those omitted costs included costs to auto makers and their
customers, already paying by some estimates $1,600 a car for
pollution control equipment. ``The technology doesn't exist'' to go
further. ``How are you going to estimate the costs?'' Roderick said.
   Richard Ayres, chairman of the Clean Air Coalition of
environmental and other groups, said Roderick's study was ``An
elaborate, thick stack of back-of-the-envelope calculations ...
probably two to four times too high.''
   ``There is no estimate given here of the benefits'' of the bill,
Ayres said, adding that in his opinion a cleaner environment and
less respiratory disease would be worth $32 billion a year.
   Among estimates from the study of spending requirements:
   _By industry as a whole except utilities, $10.4 billion on new
controls of sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxides, raw materials for
transformation into acid rain, and on compounds that help form
ozone.
   _By utilities, $9 billion on additional control of sulfur
dioxide and nitrogen oxides.
   _By industry, another $3.7 billion limiting emissions of highly
toxic chemicals.
   _By petroleum refiners, $4.3 billion in changing fuel
characteristics.
   _By local governments, $1.3 billion in auto pollution
inspections.
   Some expenditures like inspections would be necessary even if
Congress does nothing. The Environmental Protection Agency has
estimated its plans for ozone control could cost $8 billion a year.
   The study's $32 billion estimate was not out of line with
earlier studies, which made different assumptions and omitted some
provisions included by Dowd.
   EPA estimated the bill would cost $16 billion to $24 billion in
addition to the $8 billion the agency's plan would require. The
Congressional Research Service estimated $14 billion to $28
billion. The Senate committee report estimated costs at $16.87
billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
