<DOCNO> AP880309-0223 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 1610EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Anschluss     03-09 0720</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Anschluss,0743</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Youth Confronting Past And Future As Elders Never Did</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 50th anniversary of Austria's
annexation to Nazi Germany finds Austria's youth beginning to
question the country's past, the validity of democratic
institutions today and prospects for the future.
   Political leaders, analysts and historians have called on
members of the World War II generation to teach Austria's youth
about the events that led up to the Anschluss on March 11, 1938,
and Austria's involvement in the war and the Holocaust.
   Over the two years since the first disclosures that President
Kurt Waldheim had covered up his service with the Nazi army, a
nationwide debate has raised political awareness among Austria's
youth and often pitted young against old.
   In a strongly hierarchical society that has traditionally ducked
conflict, youth began in the late 1970s to question the maxims they
inherited from their parents.
   These included the silent consensus of postwar generations to
keep quiet about the war and not to provoke open conflict.
   For some young people, the Waldheim debate has sharpened their
growing political awareness and unwillingness to accept things just
as they are.
   Many young Austrians who voted for Waldheim in 1986 now say they
made a mistake in voting for him and in failing to inform
themselves about the candidates.
   A panel of historians appointed by the Austrian government
issued a report last month that said Waldheim was ``in close
proximity'' to Nazi atrocities when he was a lieutenant in the
Balkans, knew they were going on and made no attempt to prevent
them. It left open the question of whether he was guilty of any
crime.
   Whole generations were not taught about the 1930s and 1940s in
school. Even many Austrians under 30 say that by the time they
finished school their history teachers had reached only the end of
World War I.
   By contrast, many teen-agers today receive comprehensive and
objective lessons on the events that led to World War II and the
Holocaust from teachers young enough to be distant from those
events.
   Socialist Chancellor Franz Vranitzky told foreign journalists
recently that his teen-age children ``do not find it embarrassing
or painful'' to discuss the war years because they are not
preoccupied with their own involvement.
   Austria's youth ``has read more, traveled more, is more open,
more liberal and more tolerant'' than earlier generations, said
Josef Figl, head of an 11,000-member Catholic student group.
   Sociologist Silvio Lehmann said the level of education rose
tremendously in the 1970s and 1980s, increasing interest in
politics. He cited protests against the Zwentendorf nuclear
facility, which led to a 1978 referendum in which Austrians voted
against nuclear power.
   In December 1984, demonstrators clashed with police in Hainburg
on the Danube to protest a planned hydroelectric plant
environmentalists say would destroy a unique natural landscape.
   The clash shocked and outraged many Austrians in a country where
confrontations with authorities have been rare since the street
battles between Socialists and conservatives in the 1930s.
   Memories of that violence prompted all political parties to bury
their differences after World War II in public consensus and
reconciliation.
   Psychologist Erwin Ringel, author of ``The Austrian Soul,'' said
that after the war Austrians ``threw themselves into rebuilding the
country to avoid rebuilding the soul.'' He said Waldheim symbolizes
that suppression of the past.
   Robert Koschin, 27, of Innsbruck, said the younger generations'
growing interest in the past has reversed the parent-child role.
   ``The children are giving their parents their experiences and
knowledge,'' making older generations more willing to discuss the
``blocking'' of the past, he said.
   Many Austrians perceive their country as Adolf Hitler's first
victim, but many leading Nazis were Austrians.
   As in West Germany, Austria's parents have struggled to shelter
their children from the deprivation they knew immediately after the
war, showering them with the benefits of a rebuilt consumer society.
   Now the economy and an extensive social welfare system are
beginning to falter, with 6.7 percent of youth unemployed and much
of the state-owned industry running heavy deficits.
   ``It is depressing for a generation that was born into having
everything to have to fight for things that were taken for
granted,'' Koschin said. ``It is the first time people are
confronted with having to do something themselves.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880309-0224 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 1615EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CubanConnection     03-09 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cuban Connection,0414</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Secret Drug Case Tape Talks of `Fidel' Payoffs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The alleged chief of a smuggling ring that imported
cocaine through Cuba was ordered held without bond Wednesday after
prosecutors played a tape of the defendant saying ``the money went
in Fidel's drawer.''
   Reinaldo Ruiz, 50, a Cuban-born U.S. citizen, was indicted along
with 16 others last month on charges of flying drugs from Colombia
through Cuba and other Caribbean islands.
   It was the third Miami drug indictment involving alleged Cuban
connections since October.
   On a secretly recorded videotape played for U.S. Magistrate
William Turnoff during a pre-trial detention hearing, Ruiz is heard
telling an informant, ``I am the only one that has connections'' in
Cuba.
   Then, apparently referring to payoffs, Ruiz states, ``The money
went in Fidel's drawer.''
   Ruiz never identified Cuban President Fidel Castro as the
``Fidel'' he was referring to, and prosecutors refused to comment
on the statement.
   Castro has strenuously denied any involvement in drug smuggling.
   But last month's indictment of Panamanian strongman Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega here alleges the Cuban leader mediated a drug
payoff dispute between the general and the Medellin Cartel, a
Colombian ring responsible for up to 80 percent of U.S. cocaine
imports.
   And an indictment in October charged that another drug ring
routinely used Cuba as a waystation for cocaine shipments.
   No Cuban officials were indicted in the most recent case. But
prosecutors say the conspirators used a Cuban military base to ship
drugs, and promised an informant an escort of Cuban coast guard
vessels for a cocaine shipment.
   The indictment accuses Ruiz of heading the smuggling ring which
allegedly imported cocaine from Colombia through Cuba, Haiti and
the Bahamas to Mexico and the United States.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Thomas Mulvihill asked that Ruiz be held
until trial, contending he is a danger to the community and may
flee. Ruiz faces trafficking charges and a continuing criminal
enterprise count that carries a maximum life sentence.
   Turnoff agreed to hold Ruiz, over objections of defense attorny
Alvin Entin.
   ``The government appears to have a very strong case,'' said
Turnoff.
   Besides Ruiz, the tapes showed a woman named Rosa and Ruiz's son
Rubin, who is also a defendant in the case. A cooperating informant
was out of camera during the part of the tape shown in court.
   The elder Ruiz has not entered a plea in the case.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
