<1ST_LINE>r i AM-EmergencyLanding     03-09 0238</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Emergency Landing,0245</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Aircraft En Route To Falklands Makes Emergency Landing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTEVIDEO, Uruguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British transport plane headed to
the Falkland Islands for military exercises had engine trouble and
made an emergency landing in Uruguay after reportedly being denied
permission to land in Brazil.
   In neighboring Argentina, the government news agency Telam
reported the emergency landing and said the aircraft contained ``a
shipment of bombs and explosives.'' It did not elaborate.
   Both Telam and Radio Montecarlo in Uruguay reported that the
plane landed at Montevideo's Carrasco International Airport on
Tuesday night after Brazil refused to let it land there.
   British officials said only that the aircraft encountered engine
troubles while heading to the islands and requested emergency
authorization to land.
   The Hercules C-130 aircraft, carrying a crew of seven, was en
route to the Falkland Islands for military exercises that have been
denounced by Argentina, which has claimed the islands since 1833.
   Argentina calls the islands the Malvinas and fought a 74-day war
with Britain over them in 1982 before surrendering.
   Telam said without elaboration that Argentine Foreign Minister
Dante Caputo was ``in telephone communications with his Uruguayan
counterpart, Luis Barrios Tassano.''
   The aircraft was in protective custody of Uruguayan soldiers at
Carrasco airport, said an air control tower spokesman who would not
give his name.
   The British exercises, which simulate an Argentine attack on the
islands, are scheduled to last until March 31.
</TEXT>
