<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Virginia     03-09 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Virginia,0297</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Buoyed by Virginia's Black Vote; Robertson Humbled</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY O'DELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pat Robertson was humiliated by a
third-place finish in his Southern backyard, while a strong black
showing boosted Jesse Jackson to victory as many white voters
shunned Virginia's primaries.
   Robertson lagged far behind Super Tuesday's super winner, Vice
President George Bush, who captured the Republican primary with
103,743 votes or 53 percent to Kansas Sen. Bob Dole's 50,191 votes
or 25 percent, with 93 percent of the 1,986 precincts reporting.
   Jackson's easy win in the Democratic primary with 162,355 votes
or 45 percent was based on a large turnout by black voters, who
cast 40 percent of the ballots in the Democratic primary, said
Larry Sabato, a political scientist at the University of Virginia.
   ``Whites virtually boycotted the Democratic primary,'' he said
Wednesday.
   Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore was next with 80,650 votes or 22
percent, followed closely by Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis
with 78,141 votes or 22 percent. Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt was
fourth with 16,082 votes or 4 percent.
   Jackson captured 38 delegates, Gore had 22 and Dukakis won 15.
   Sabato said the ``abysmal'' voter turnout _ about 21.5 percent
of the 2.6 million Virginians eligible _ should have helped
Robertson. The former Virginia Beach television evangelist was
believed to have the most committed followers of all the GOP
candidates, but their impact was not felt at the polls.
   ``No one thought Robertson would do so poorly,'' he said. ``This
is a real humiliation for him.''
   Robertson captured only 29,556 votes or 15 percent. New York
Rep. Jack Kemp was next with 8,696 or 4 percent. No delegates were
selected in the non-binding Republican primary.
</TEXT>
