<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 1633EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ChemicalWeapons     03-09 0230</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chemical Weapons,0235</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Depot To Resume Chemical Weapons Disposal Year After Gas Leak</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOOELE ARMY DEPOT, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Incineration of obsolete chemical
weapons will resume this week at this remote desert installation,
where disposal operations were shut down after a nerve gas leak 13
months ago.
   Work began Tuesday to prepare equipment for renewed destruction
of M-55 nerve gas rockets at the Chemical Agent Munitions Disposal
System, said depot spokesman W. Allen Kenitzer. Disposal operations
were to begin by week's end, he said.
   The Army is using the facility to test equipment and procedures
it eventually will use to destroy the nation's aging chemical agent
stockpile. The size of the chemical arsenal is classified but has
been estimated at 30,000 tons.
   On Jan. 28, 1987, a small quantity of deadly liquid nerve agent
leaked from an incinerator. No injuries were reported, but the Army
closed the plant pending an inspection and review of management
problems that allowed the leak to occur.
   Corrective actions included increased quality control, tougher
requirements on plant filter units and stricter emphasis on
monitoring and maintenance, Kenitzer said.
   The Tooele facility has disposed of 38,000 missiles, shells or
bombs filled with nerve or mustard agent since operations began in
1979.
   The depot is one of nine chemical storage sites officials plan
to use for incineration of old chemical arsenals using the Tooele
model.
</TEXT>
