<DOCNO> AP880309-0231 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 1635EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-SuperTuesday     03-09 0607</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Super Tuesday,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Was Super Tuesday A Super Success?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The splintered results of the South's regional
primary gave both its architects and its detractors room to claim
they were right about Super Tuesday.
   ``Super Tuesday succeeded,'' said one who was present at its
creation, former Gov. Charles Robb of Virginia. He saw his state go
to Jesse Jackson but his own candidate, Albert Gore, establish his
candidacy in much of the rest of Dixie.
   ``Super Tuesday is not what I hoped it would be,'' said
Florida's state Democratic chairman, Charles Whitehead. His state
and Texas, the two big delegate prizes of the South, went to
Northerner Michael Dukakis.
   The sharp, three-way division of Democratic winners means no one
will likely clinch the nomination before the convention in Atlanta,
former President Jimmy Carter said.
   ``I was surprised at how well Gore did,'' Carter said. ``I
thought (Richard) Gephardt would do better in the South.''
   Twenty states held Democratic primaries on Super Tuesday,
including the 14 Southern and border states and six others,
including Dukakis' own Massachusetts.
   In total popular vote, the result was a near-equal division
among the three winners. Jackson, the black candidate, won the most
votes with 2.54 million, or 27 percent. Dukakis got 2.51 million,
or 26 percent, and Gore got 2.46 million, also 26 percent.
   ``Super Tuesday pretty much guarantees a protracted struggle for
the Democrats,'' said Merle Black, political science professor at
the University of North Carolina. None of the candidates, he said,
displayed the strength needed to defeat the Republicans in November.
   Super Tuesday was largely a Democratic creation, led by Southern
Democratic legislators. But it was the Republicans who got the
decisive winner, George Bush.
   ``The great Republican fear was that Pat Robertson would emerge
as a strong, divisive force,'' Black said. ``That possibility has
pretty well dissipated.''
   Texas state Sen. Chet Edwards, one of the sponsors of the bill
that created Texas' entry into regional primary, declared the day
``a real success story.''
   ``I think the biggest myth that non-Southerners have about Super
Tuesday was that it was set up to assure the nomination of a
conservative Anglo Southerner,'' said Edwards.
   Instead, he argued, Super Tuesday had wide support among
Hispanic and black minorities in Texas. The goal, he said, was not
to nominate a conservative or a Southern candidate but to give the
South a voice early in the nominating process, before the choices
had been too narrowed.
   ``It speaks well for the South and for Michael Dukakis that the
governor of Massachusetts can come to the South and address the
issues and win,'' said Edwards.
   But even some of its boosters acknowledged Super Tuesday may
have been a bit of overkill, with 20 states voting. If the idea
survives, some say there may at least be a reduction in the number
of states holding primaries on the same day.
   The wide battleground, coming just three weeks after New
Hampshire's primary, put a premium on television advertising and
the money it takes to buy it.
   Candidates fell back on the one proven method of moving large
numbers of voters in a short time span: negative advertising.
Dukakis and Gore blistered Richard Gephardt with tough negative ads
that took their toll.
   ``Each of the other three beat expectations,'' said former party
chairman Robert Strauss. ``It came out of Dick Gephardt's hide.''
   And Super Tuesday also said something about the hoopla
surrounding Iowa's caucuses, the first event of the season and the
one that seemed to get the most attention. Its winner was Gephardt,
the big loser of Super Tuesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
