<DOCNO> AP880309-0232 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 1639EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-FailedCoup     03-09 0522</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Failed Coup,0536</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Links South Africa to Failed Coup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Africa may have aided canoe-borne
raiders who staged an abortive coup attempt in the West African
island nation of Sao Tome and Principe, it was reported Wednesday.
   Officials said security forces captured 43 armed men who landed
in fishing canoes before dawn Tuesday on beaches near Sao Tome, the
capital of the Marxist nation 100 miles west of Gabon.
   President Manuel Pinto da Costa said in a national radio
broadcast that soldiers, police and militiamen were searching for
two remaining members of the assault force. He appealed for calm
and vigilance against renewed attacks.
   The Portuguese news agency Lusa said Celestino da Costa, prime
minister of the two-island nation, identified one of the captured
assailants as Afonso Santos. It said he was leader of an opposition
group that sought asylum two years ago in South African-ruled
South-West Africa, also known as Namibia.
   Lusa said 76 Sao Tome exiles arrived by boat in South
Africa-ruled Namibia in May 1986 and sought South African aid to
overthrow the government of Pinto da Costa.
   The agency said a South African Foreign Ministry spokesman,
speaking on condition of anonymity, acknowledged the South African
government had granted asylum to the refugees. But he denied
reports that it trained about 100 refugees from Sao Tome and
Principe to overthrow the government, Lusa said.
   Da Costa, whose Sao Tome and Principe Liberation Movement has
governed since independence from Portugal in 1975, blamed the
opposition National Resistance Front. The front is based in
Libreville, the capital of pro-Western Gabon.
   The Lisbon-based secretary-general of the front, Quintiliano
Amado, denied it was behind the attack. But he said it may have
been carried out by dissidents within his movement.
   Earlier Wednesday, informed sources in Sao Tome and Principe
told The Associated Press that government opponents, possibly based
in Gabon or South Africa, were suspected in the raid, which left
two attackers dead and one assailant and a policeman wounded.
   The sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
investigators would seek information about Sao Tome exiles expelled
from Gabon to South Africa two years ago.
   They said the attackers were armed only with light weapons and
that Angolan troops stationed on the islands were not called to
assist in capturing the raiders. They said the army was no longer
securing key facilities and life had returned to normal.
   The two volcanic islands of 110,000 people are known chiefly for
their white sand beaches, coffee and cocoa plantations, and
brightly colored tropical birds.
   But attention was focused on their strategic position in the
Gulf of Guinea in 1978 when rumors of an imminent invasion swept
the country. Cuba, Angola and Guinea-Bissau sent troops to help
defend the islands.
   The invasion never happened, but the country since has
strengthened its ties with Angola, Cuba and the Soviet Union. News
reports in 1984 said about 2,000 Soviet and Cuban troops were
operating two radio stations and a submarine port in the area.
   An estimated 1,000 Angolan troops also are stationed in Sao Tome
and Principe to support the regular army.
</TEXT>
