<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Phone Outage,0213</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cave-in Damages Phone Cable, Cuts Long-Distance Service to 2
Counties</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Long-distance telephone service for
more than a quarter-million customers in Santa Barbara and part of
San Luis Obispo counties was cut off Wednesday after a cave-in at
an excavation project damaged a major phone line, officials said.
   GTE California Co. said it has 196,000 residential and 68,000
business customers in the affected area.
   The excavation accident in Los Angeles kinked the only major
long-distance line into the affected region, said American
Telephone & Telegraph Co. spokeswoman Kelly Williams. AT&T owns the
line, but rival long-distance carriers MCI and Sprint lease space
on it, she said.
   Telephone customers in the affected area could not call out to
or receive calls from other areas of California or out of state,
officials said. Calls within the affected area weren't affected.
   Ms. Williams said the line was expected to be repaired by
mid-afternoon. The accident occurred about 9:30 a.m.
