<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 1639EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-RustBeltProspects     03-09 0542</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rust Belt Prospects,500</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For Release at 6:30 p.m. EST; time set by source</NOTE>
<HEAD>Study Sees Short-Term Prosperity for Northeast, Midwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's industrial heartland will prosper
in the next few years, but lagging population growth threatens the
region's political clout and share of federal programs, a public
policy group said Wednesday.
   The hemorrhage of jobs from the region was another point of
weakness in the 18 northern states stretching from Minnesota to New
England, the Northeast-Midwest Institute said in its study, ``The
State of the Region.''
   ``The short-term economic outlook for the entire region is
positive,'' the report said. The region shared in the national
return to prosperity from 1983 to late 1986, with New England
benefiting the most and the Midwest the least.
   However, the study warned that the region's well-being is
endangered by the failure of its population growth to keep pace
with the rest of the nation's.
   ``The trend is expected to continue through the turn of the
century,'' the study said. ``Government researchers expect
population in the Northeast and Midwest to grow at only 3.8 percent
throughout the 1990s, about half the national average.''
   The Sunbelt states in the South and West will show population
increases of 10 percent in the 1990s, the study said.
   The lagging population gains in the Northeast and Midwest result
both from lower birth rates and migration to southern and western
states, the study said.
   Slower population growth translates into less clout in Congress,
with the region expected to lose 14 House seats after the 1990
census. The region lost 15 seats after the 1980 census, for a total
projected loss in representation of 13 percent in the 1970s and
1980s, the study said.
   ``Political influence, from the selection of the president in
the electoral college to appropriation fights in the House of
Representatives, will shift further to the South and West,'' the
study said. ``Moreover, because billions of dollars are allocated
by formulas based on population, the Northeast-Midwest region can
expect reductions in its share of federal funding.''
   Although unemployment dropped below the national average in
parts of the region, it was unlikely to regain many of the 1.3
million manufacturing jobs lost between 1980 and 1986, the study
said.
   The South and West for the first time topped the Northeast and
Midwest in manufacturing employment in 1986. The Sunbelt had
9,542,500 employees on manufacturing payrolls, compared with
9,394,000 in the Northeast and Midwest.
   Other points made by the study were:
   _Per capita personal income increased faster in the Northeast
and Midwest than in the South and West.
   _The Northeast and Midwest invested more in public school
education than did other regions.
   _The trend toward an older population was more evident in the
Northeast and Midwest than in the rest of the country.
   The study covered these states: Connecticut, Delaware, Illinois,
Indiana, Iowa, Maine, Maryland, Massachusetts, Michigan, Minnesota,
New Hampshire, New Jersey, New York, Ohio, Pennsylvania, Rhode
Island, Vermont and Wisconsin.
   The privately funded Northeast-Midwest Institute was formed in
1977 at the request of members of the House and Senate from the
region. The study was also sponsored by two legislative groups: the
Northeast-Midwest Congressional Coalition and the Northeast-Midwest
Senate Coalition.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880309-0235 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 1640EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Tennessee     03-09 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tennessee,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gore, Bush Win In Tennessee</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL RAWLINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Albert Gore Jr. swamped his fellow
Democrats in his home state and on Wednesday predicted that his
victory in five presidential primaries proved his campaign can
survive a national contest.
   ``Two or three days ago, the conventional wisdom ... through the
country was that Super Tuesday was going to see the end of Al
Gore's campaign. The conventional wisdom was wrong,'' Gore said.
``Sooner or later, it's going to stop being a surprise.''
   With all 2,391 precincts reporting, Gore had 414,569 votes or 72
percent; Jesse Jackson received 118,615 votes or 21 percent;
Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis had 19,268 votes or 3 percent
and Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt had 8,657 votes or 2 percent.
   In the Republican race, Vice President George Bush had 151,130
votes or 60 percent; Kansas Sen. Bob Dole had 54,493 votes or 22
percent; former television evangelist Pat Robertson had 31,402
votes or 12 percent, and New York Rep. Jack Kemp had 10,871 votes
or 4 percent.
   Based on those results, Gore would take 56 Democratic delegates
and Jackson would get 14. Bush would capture 29 of Tennessee's 45
GOP delegates, Dole 10 and 6 would go to the national convention
uncommitted.
   Gore predicted his Super Tuesday showing would propel him to the
Democratic nomination to face Bush in November and ``bring the
party back to the grass roots and make a fresh start for America.''
   Gore, who will be 40 on March 31, likened himself to the late
John F. Kennedy.
   ``In 1960, we replaced the oldest president then to serve with
the youngest to be elected,'' he said. ``We have a chance to do it
again.''
   About 150 Jackson supporters cheered as they watched election
returns Tuesday night in Nashville.
   ``I think it's a victory,'' said Jackson's Tennessee chairman,
state Rep. Lois DeBerry. Jackson would have carried Tennessee if
Gore hadn't been in the race, she said.
</TEXT>
