<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Alabama     03-09 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Alabama,0343</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Camp Says White Votes Made Difference in Alabama; Bush
Routs Dole</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KENDAL WEAVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   White voters who joined ranks with Jesse
Jackson in a state once known as a bastion of segregation helped
put him over the top in Alabama's Democratic primary.
   In the Republican contest, Vice President George Bush swept to
victory atop a record turnout on Super Tuesday. Bush picked up an
estimated 35 of the state's 38 GOP delegates, with Kansas Sen.
Robert Dole apparently getting the other three.
   Among Democrats, Jackson gained an estimated 30 delegates, but
Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr. ran stronger than expected in his
neighbor state and appeared to be pulling the remaining 26
delegates.
   For the Jackson forces, the victory was particularly sweet in
the Cradle of the Confederacy, where blacks were routinely denied
the right to vote before the 1965 Voting Rights Act.
   ``Jesse Jackson's message has touched the hearts of many in the
South,'' said his state coordinator, Youlanda Curtis. The victory
``shows that Alabama is progressing. Alabamians should be proud,
both black and white.''
   Al LaPierre, executive director of the Alabama Democratic Party,
estimated that Jackson received as much as 5 percent of the white
vote in addition to overwhelming black support, helping to give the
former minister the margin of victory.
   With 3,788 of 4,304 precincts or 88 percent reporting Wednesday,
Jackson had 165,570 votes or 44 percent to Gore's 139,892 votes or
37 percent. Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis was next with 28,949
votes or 8 percent and Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt had 27,997 or
7 percent.
   The GOP turnout appeared headed toward 230,000, defeating the
1980 record of 211,000 for a Republican presidential primary in the
state.
   With 3,713 of 4,304 precincts or 86 percent reporting, Bush had
127,937 votes or 64 percent, Dole followed with 32,274 or 16
percent, Pat Robertson was third with 28,174 or 14 percent and New
York Rep. Jack Kemp had 9,739 or 5 percent.
</TEXT>
