<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 1645EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Kerrey     03-09 0690</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kerrey,0713</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kerrey Says He Has More Experience, But The Same Style</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED HOWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Bob Kerrey burst onto the
political scene in 1982 by winning the governorship in a state
dominated by Republicans, then made the gossip columns with his
romance with actress Debra Winger.
   The free-wheeling style that carried him to the governor's
mansion in his first political campaign won't change much as he
seeks election to the U.S. Senate, Kerry said.
   Unopposed for the Democratic nomination in the May primary,
Kerrey has been campaigning for several months but planned to
formally announce his candidacy Thursday.
   Two Republicans, incumbent Sen. David Karnes and Rep. Hal Daub,
are battling for the GOP nod. Karnes was appointed by Gov. Kay Orr
to fill the seat after the death last year of incumbent Democrat
Edward Zorinsky.
   Despite his frequent assertions when he left the governor's
mansion in 1986 that he didn't know if he would again seek public
office, Kerrey was regarded by political observers as a possible
Senate candidate. When Zorinsky died of a heart attack, Kerrey was
seen as his party's best hope.
   ``I had to decide if I would enjoy this, if I wanted to serve
and whether I wanted a public or private life,'' Kerrey said.
   A war hero who earned the Medal of Honor and lost part of a leg
as a Navy commando in Vietnam, Kerrey became a successful
entrepreneur who owns several restaurants and then a successful
politician.
   He became an intregral part of the Democratic scene when he
worked for Gary Hart in 1984, and was instrumental in Hart's
victory in the Nebraska primary.
   Part of his personal notoriety came from his relationship with
Winger, who married actor Timothy Hutton a few years ago.
   Kerrey, 44, is ready and willing to discuss his campaign, but he
usually deflects questions about Winger.
   ``We are friends,'' he said recently. ``I don't know that there
is anything else to be said.''
   He is divorced and the father of two children. Ben, 13 and
Lindsey, 11, live in Texas with their mother.
   An interview with Kerrey is often peppered with off-the-record
asides, some self-deprecating and some reflecting that he doesn't
appear to take himself too seriously.
   Kerrey chose not to seek a second term as governor, saying it
was time to seek other challenges.
   The former governor admits he doesn't have a list of proposals
and solutions.
   ``I learned as governor you don't solve problems from the top,
down. What you do is engage the citizens in an effort to find out
what we are willing to do about a problem.
   ``My sense is that we are afraid sometimes to try something
different, to get in there and say, `Hey, we're going to try to
make a difference here.'''
   Part of the political process, he says, is to ``select that part
of the status quo we want to hold on to, and that part which we
want to change and that's where the fun of it is.''
   The cost of campaigning keeps many out of the political arena,
according to Kerrey. The Nebraska Senate race could cost each
candidate as much as $6 million, he said.
   ``If you don't conclude after this race that campaign spending
restraints are needed, you've got a pretty warped sense about how
democracy should operate.''
   In Kerrey's first political outing, he defeated incumbent
Republican Gov. Charles Thone.
   During that campaign, he often spoke of the ``hopes and dreams''
of Nebraskans and his vision of the future, and to some, he seemed
a living symbol of determination. Despite the loss of his right leg
below the knee, he runs five miles every day.
   A troubled farm economy led to four years of tight budgets, and
Kerrey's readiness to trim state spending didn't endear him to some
Democrats or to state employees.
   ``No one tells you that everything will go your way just because
you have good plans and good intentions,'' Kerrey said. ``That's
because things don't always go your way. So you do the best you can
by facing the realities of the problems.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
