<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Massachusetts 1stLd-Writethru a0965 03-09 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Massachusetts, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0965,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis, Bush Capture Massachusetts Primaries</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to CORRECT Gore title from Gov. to Sen.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DUNCAN MANSFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Michael Dukakis beat Jesse Jackson by a
nearly 3-1 margin to win on home turf in Massachusetts' Democratic
presidential primary, but fell short of the victory margin
predicted in pre-election polls.
   ``It just goes to show you the only polls that count are the
ones on election day,'' said Steve Akey, a Dukakis spokesman. ``We
are very pleased with the landslide victory here in Massachusetts.''
   With 2,114 of the 2,140 precincts or 99 percent reporting,
Dukakis had 413,806 votes or 59 percent; Jackson had 130,643 votes
or 19 percent; Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt had 72,053 votes or
10 percent, and Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr. had 31,575 votes or
4 percent.
   Vice President George Bush had 137,639 votes or 59 percent;
Kansas Sen. Bob Dole had 61,266 votes or 26 percent; New York Rep.
Jack Kemp had 16,331 votes or 7 percent, and former television
evangeleist Pat Robertson had 10,779 votes or 5 percent.
   Based on those results, Bush would get 30 of Massachusetts' 52
GOP delegates to the national convention; Dole would get 13; Kemp
3; Robertson 2, and 4 would be uncommitted. Dukakis would get 79 of
the state's 98 Democratic delegates, and Jackson would get 19.
   U.S. Rep. Chester Atkins, the state Democratic party chairman,
said he had hoped Dukakis would win at least 60 percent of the
vote, but added, ``59 is close enough.''
   Dukakis may have been hurt by some of the ``tough positions (he
has taken) over the years on things that were important for the
state,'' Atkins said.
   ``I also think that it's really a factor that in Massachusetts,
politics is a favorite contact sport and we're probably tougher on
elected officials in Massachusetts than any other state in the
country,'' he said. ``We are the most critical electorate I think
there is in America, which I think is positive.''
</TEXT>
