<DOCNO> AP880309-0242 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 1705EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-SuperTurnout     03-09 0707</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Super Turnout,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Some Had `Super' Reasons For Not Turning Out on Super Tuesday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There were a lot of reasons why some voters
didn't bother to make Super Tuesday a Super Turnout day. Some of
the best came from Massachusetts and American Samoa.
   The biggest primary-caucus day in history had been billed as a
battle ``south of the Mason-Dixon line and the drive to Dixie,''
according Rep. Chester Atkins of Massachusetts, the state
Democratic chairman.
   ``People in Massachusetts,'' he observed, ``just don't think of
themselves as part of the drive to Dixie.''
   In American Samoa, where 300 Democrats were eligible to take
part in the caucuses, only 36 bothered to do so. National
committeeman Glenn Jones provided a reason: residents of the U.S.
territory can't vote in presidential elections.
   In many states, officials were jubilant over the numbers who
cast ballots in primary elections, which traditionally get a far
lower voter turnout than do the general elections in November. This
year the turnout was higher because there was spice in the
contested elections of both parties.
   The voting in Florida fell short of the 50 to 55 percent
predictions made last week, but still came to a respectable 42
percent of eligible Democrats and 43 percent eligible Republicans.
   ``I would presume a lot of the (George) Bush supporters felt it
was not necessary to go to the polls because he was leading by such
a majority anyway,'' said Dot Joyce, state supervisor of the
division of elections.
   It was that certainty for the outcome that also held down the
turnout in Massachusetts, said Susan Pye, a spokeswoman for the
secretary of state.
   ``The biggest reason why people don't turn out and vote is
because they feel that their vote doesn't matter,'' she said. Only
about a third of Massachusetts' 2.9 million registered voters cast
ballots, and Ms. Pye said it was confidence among Democrats that
Gov. Michael Dukakis was a shoo-in in his home state. Republicans
assumed Bush would win.
   Taking a nose count in some of the 20 Super Tuesday states:
   Maryland: Higher than predicted, but less than the 48 percent in
the 1976 Jimmy Carter-Jerry Brown contest. Of 1.3 million
Democrats, more than 500,000 or 38 percent cast ballots. Of 520,000
registered Republicans, 195,000 or 37.5 percent voted.
   Hawaii: ``This is the first time we've really had a race; I
don't remember this much excitement,'' said Gov. John Waihee,
delighted that Jesse Jackson put up a strong challenge to Dukakis,
whom Waihee supported. Around 4,000 party members _ double the
usual turnout _ attended Democratic caucuses.
   Texas: ``It's very clear Super Tuesday has been super for
Texas,'' said Secretary of State Jack Rains. ``When I stop and
think about the potential for this fall, I can get very excited.''
The turnout in Texas was 35 percent of the 7.9 million registered
voters _ more than 1 million Republicans and 1.75 million Democrats.
   ``Wouldn't it be wonderful if we could bump our registration
totals up to 8.5 million and get 50 percent of those or better to
the polls, which would mean 4.25 million plus in November,'' Rains
said. ``I believe that's an achievable goal.''
   Arkansas: State Auditor Julia Hughes Jones had predicted a
turnout of 514,000. It was 50,000 higher.
   Georgia: The Jimmy Carter primary in 1976 had set a state
record, but the mark was broken Tuesday when 1 million of the
state's 2.5 million registered voters cast ballots ``I love it when
a plan comes together,'' said Georgia Secretary of State Max
Cleland, one of the architects of Super Tuesday. ``This shows that
a regional primary can focus time, attention, money and
organizational talent on one particular goal.''
   Rhode Island: ``Some people might have thought it was a fait
accompli _ that the vice president was going to win and that
Governor Dukakis was going to win,'' said GOP Chairman J. Michael
Levesque. The turnout was was 12.6 percent, best since the 14
percent in 1976.
   Oklahoma: Lee Slater, secretary of the election board, had said
anything over 500,000 would be a good turnout. By unofficial count,
more than 600,00 voted. ``It's a wonderful turnout, it's a super
turnout,'' Slater says now.
</TEXT>
