<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 1706EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GeneticFingerprints     03-09 0513</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Genetic Fingerprints,0528</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Witness: Fetus' Genes Match Those Of Rape Suspect</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An alleged rapist whose genes match
those of a rape victim's fetus may as well have left ``a full set
of fingerprints, Social Security number and a signature'' at the
scene of a crime, a medical expert testified.
   Circuit Judge Marvin Mounts is presiding in a hearing to
determine whether genetic tests should be admitted in the trial of
George Forrest, charged with raping eight women between December
1986 and October 1987.
   Four genetic tests on DNA molecules from Forrest's blood, a rape
victim's blood and tissue from the fetus she aborted indicate that
the fetus shared common genes.
   The tests showed a 99.99 percent probability that Forrest
fathered the child, said Michael Baird, laboratory manager of
Lifecodes Corp., the Elmsford, N.Y., company that performed the
tests.
   Mounts has not ruled if the tests described Tuesday will be used
during Forrest's trial.
   ``That's a narrow possibility, albeit a possibility,'' he said
of the test results.
   Forrest, 34, of Boynton Beach, is being held in the Palm Beach
County Jail. He was arrested as police sought a man they dubbed
``The Congress Avenue Rapist,'' after the area in which the attacks
occurred.
   He was charged with eight counts of sexual battery with a deadly
weapon, six counts of sexual battery with force likely to cause
serious personal injury, 4 counts of kidnapping, two counts of
attempted sexual battery and one count of burglary while committing
assault or battery.
   Dr. Karl Muench, a professor of medicine at the University of
Miami, testified that DNA tests are revolutionizing legal
proceedings across the country. He said the results were as
convincing as ``a full set of fingerprints, Social Security number
and a signature'' left at a crime scene.
   The tests use blood, semen or human tissue and semen in a
200-step process that determines whether the genes of an alleged
father match those of a child.
   DNA, deoxyribonucleic acid, is the protein that carries an
organism's genetic information. Each DNA molecule consists of four
amino acids arranged in a code that is unique to each person.
   Forrest's genetic code was determined through a blood sample and
compared with that of a fetus aborted by a white woman he is
accused of raping.
   The genetic code of the fetal material is so similar to that of
Forrest, who is black, that 533,790 other blacks would have to be
chosen at random before one would be found with almost identical
coding, Baird said.
   Asked by Forrest's attorney, James Cassidy, whether two brothers
could produce the same test results because of similar genetic
blueprints, Baird said the possibility was remote unless they were
identical twins.
   Test results have been used in New York, California and Virginia
courts to link defendants to crimes, and Lifecodes is working with
the FBI to develop DNA testing at its laboratories, Baird said.
   In other cases, when DNA tests have indicated that a defendant
is not linked to a crime, the charges have been dropped, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880309-0244 </DOCNO>
