<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BRF--TaxReturns     03-09 0141</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Tax Returns,140</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tax Refunds Averaging 6.2 Percent More Than Last Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal tax refunds are averaging 6.2 percent
more than last year, the Internal Revenue Service said Wednesday.
   Through March 4, said spokesman Wilson Fadely, 12.66 million
refunds had been certified, up slightly from the 12.6 million at
this time a year ago. Refunds averaged $802, up from $755 for the
same period of 1987.
   The IRS has processed 22.1 million of the 36.7 million returns
received so far. The number of returns filed was 2.4 percent below
last year's pace, although the gap was considerably less than four
weeks ago.
   The IRS has processed about 1 percent fewer returns than at this
time last year. The backlog of unprocessed returns totals 14.6
million, down from 15.3 million last year.
   The filing deadline is April 15.
</TEXT>
