<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CourthouseShooting     03-09 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Courthouse Shooting,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gunman Killed After Shooting Up Courtroom Day After Conviction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By E. SCOTT RECKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man apparently bent on revenge against a
deputy city attorney who had successfully prosecuted him a day
earlier opened fire Wednesday in a courtroom, wounding a bailiff
before he was killed, officials said.
   Jeremy Sigmond, 35, of Woodland Hills was killed in the shootout
at Los Angeles Municipal Court in suburban Van Nuys at 10:15 a.m.,
said Ted Goldstein, a spokesman for the city attorney's office.
   The bailiff, county Deputy Marshal Cliff Wooford, 30, of
Palmdale, was shot in the abdomen and was undergoing surgery at St.
Joseph's Medical Center in Burbank, said hospital spokeswoman Linda
Roberts.
   The prosecutor, Jessica Silvers, 48, was ``shaken'' but
unharmed, Goldstein said.
   Sigmond ``came looking for her today,'' Goldstein said.
   ``I heard one shot, and then all the doors flew open and people
started streaming outside,'' said Becker Mubani, who was outside
the courtroom.
   Sigmond was convicted in the same courtroom 24 hours earlier of
four misdemeanor counts stemming from an Oct. 22 chase by
California Highway Patrol officers, Goldstein said. He was
eventually arrested in front of his Woodland Hills home, Goldstein
said.
   Goldstein said he did not know what on charges Sigmond was
convicted or the sentences he received, but he said Ms. Silvers had
not been threatened.
   ``He walked into the courtroom and (later) opened fire,'' said
marshal's Cmdr. Clyde Gatlin.
   Mubani said that after the shooting he saw the bailiff running
from the courtroom, ``his left hand covering the wound.''
   The officer staggered down some steps to the sidewalk as other
officers ran to assist him. Mubani screamed, ``Watch, watch, he's
wounded.''
   ``Then the wounded officer began shouting, `Where is the
ambulance, where is the ambulance?''' Mubani said.
</TEXT>
