<HEAD>Soldier Killed While Practicing Parachute Jump</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT BRAGG, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 19-year-old soldier practicing a
parachute jump became entangled in the doorway of an airplane and
fell to his death, Fort Bragg officials and a newspaper said
Wednesday.
   The incident happened Tuesday afternoon as the soldier was
taking part in a training exercise over the base, said base
spokeswoman Carol Jones.
   Officials refused to give details of the accident, but the
Fayetteville Observer quoted unidentified sources Wednesday as
saying a strap from the soldier's parachute gear begame entangled
in the doorway as he exited the aircraft, and he fell out without
opening the parachute at the proper time.
   He was pronounced dead where he landed, said Master Sgt. Michael
Hartt. The soldier, a member of an airborne infantry regiment of
the 82nd Airborne Division, was not identified pending notification
of family.
   The death is the second fatal parachute accident in six years at
the military base, Ms. Jones said.
</TEXT>
