<1ST_LINE>r p AM-ExitPolls-Robertson     03-09 0590</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Exit Polls-Robertson,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Juggernaut Includes Southern Fundamentalists</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pat Robertson finished poorly in Super Tuesday
primaries because George Bush won the votes of the conservative
Christian community considered most likely to support the former
television evangelist, analysts said Wednesday.
   Exit polls said Robertson failed to win majorities or even many
pluralities of the fundamentalist, evangelical or born-again
Christian vote in the Southern states.
   ``That's his group, and he didn't get them,'' said CBS News
pollster Kathleen A. Frankovic. ``The core support that Robertson
expects to get clearly wasn't there.''
   Robertson finished second in Iowa last month by drawing
Christian supporters to the caucuses. They made up 36 percent of
the GOP vote there, and he won half of the caucuses. In New
Hampshire, they made up just 9 percent, but again Robertson won
half.
   It was different in the South. In Mississippi, where 24 percent
of the GOP voters said they were fundamentalist or evangelical
Christians, Bush won with 49 percent of the group, to 31 percent
for Robertson, Frankovic said.
   Bush also won the fundamentalist vote in Alabama; Robertson won
it in Georgia and the two men split it in North Carolina, the
CBS-Times polls said.
   Other network polls used other gauges but found similar results.
ABC News said 34 percent of the GOP voters in the South said they
were born-again Christians and 40 percent of them backed Bush, to
35 percent for Robertson.
   NBC said the born-again Christian vote ranged from 28 percent in
Alabama to 63 percent in Tennessee. Bush won it in Alabama,
Louisiana, Tennessee and Texas and split it with Robertson in
Arkansas, NBC polls said.
   ``It's pretty tough to put together a winning coalition if
that's his secret army. He's not getting more than a third of them
anyplace,'' said Sheldon Gawiser, an NBC poll analyst.
   Frankovic said overwhelming approval in the South for Vice
President Bush and the Reagan administration cut into Robertson's
support, and he may have been damaged by negative publicity.
Robertson last week dropped his libel suit over charges that he
shirked combat duty in Korea, still maintaining that the allegation
was untrue.
   ``There was something pulling people to support Bush and there
wasn't something pulling fundamentalists to support Robertson,''
Frankovic said.
   But Claibourne H. Darden Jr., a pollster in Atlanta, had another
view: He said Robertson never had support from more than a hard
core within the ranks of fundamentalists, who make up a much larger
group in the South than elsewhere.
   ``So many people consider themselves fundamentalists in the
South that it gets out of the core group and becomes the norm,''
Darden said. ``He's got the hard core. He doesn't have any more
than that and he never did.''
   In Iowa, where voter turnout is low, and in New Hampshire,
Darden said, the fundamentalist vote was made up largely of the
small central core of Robertson supporters. ``Anywhere you get a
large turnout'' _ as in the South _ ``that core shrinks in
percentage,'' he said.
   The Robertson campaign took a similar line. ``Part of the
problem has been the perception that this group is a monolithic
group,'' said campaign spokeswoman Teresa George. ``We've been
telling people they aren't.''
   As the race moves north, said George, ``I don't think there's
any doubt that Pat Robertson is going to try to reach those
people,'' even he tries to build new support in other groups.
   The margin of sampling error for the polls was about 5 points.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880309-0248 </DOCNO>
