<1ST_LINE>r i AM-PLOClaims     03-09 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PLO Claims,0485</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Conflicting Claims on Bomb Planted Near Shultz's Hotel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Responsibility for the car bomb
discovered near the hotel where Secretary of State George P. Shultz
was staying remained a matter of conflict Wednesday within the
Palestine Liberation Organization.
   Hours after the bomb was found and removed by Israeli police on
March 5, a spokesman in Beirut for Yasser Arafat's Fatah faction of
the PLO claimed responsibility for the bombing attempt and said
Shultz was the target.
   The spokesman is well-known to Beirut news organizations and
often is in telephone contact with correspondents. The claim was
widely reported and the various PLO factions did not challenge it
immediately or in subsequent days.
   But when an Associated Press correspondent contacted another PLO
spokesman in Tunis on March 7, he denied the PLO had planted the
bomb. Ahmed Abderrahman, a member of Fatah's central committee,
blamed Mossad, Israel's secret service.
   Abderrahman claimed Israel was trying to harden anti-Palestinian
sentiment in Washington and prevent the possible acceptance of the
PLO in any peace talks.
   The AP then asked Bassam Abu Sharif, a close Arafat aide, and he
also denied Fatah involvement in the bombing attempt.
   ``It is nothing to do with Palestinians whatsoever,'' he said by
telephone from Tunis. ``The car bomb was a clear Israeli trick to
make it look like the Palestinians wanted to blow up Shultz and to
make the Israeli security services look good by discovering this
so-called bomb.''
   It is not unusual to receive several claims by competing
Palestinian groups. And some Palestinian sources say that is done
on purpose to confuse Israeli and Western intelligence services
about which group is behind attacks.
   But on other occasions, PLO and Fatah officials have denied
their fighters were involved when they considered claiming
responsibility would harm their cause.
   On Monday, when an Israeli bus was hijacked by three Palestinian
guerrillas there was agreement that Fatah had carried out the
action that ended with the deaths of the three guerrillas and three
passengers on the bus.
   Again, the Beirut source issued the initial claim that Fatah was
responsible. This time, Abu Sharif confirmed the claim, saying:
``Fatah carried out the attack on the bus.''
   So did Azam al-Ahmad, the PLO representative in Baghdad, where
Arafat has his military headquarters. Al-Ahmad, who also is a
senior Fatah official, said the guerrillas hijacked the bus
carrying workers from Israel's top-secret Dimona nuclear power
plant in the Negev with the aim of holding them hostage.
   On Wednesday, however, Hekmat Zaid, chief of the PLO mission in
Budapest, told reporters: ``The aim of the Palestinian commando
action ... was not to take hostages, the plan of the PLO's armed
men was to enter the strictly guarded complex by overpowering the
bus that carried the workers of the Dimona nuclear center.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
