<DOCNO> AP880309-0250 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 1725EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Tunisia     03-09 0310</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tunisia,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>National Assembly Approves New Constitution In First Reading</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GOLDSMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUNIS, Tunisia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Assembly has approved
unanimously a new constitution that will do away with the concept
of ``president for life.''
   The new constitution, approved Tuesday night on its first
reading, will take effect after its approval by two-thirds of the
National Assembly. The vote is expected later this year.
   Former President-for-Life Habib Bourguiba, who ruled Tunisia
without interruption for 32 years following the end of French
colonial rule in 1956, was ousted Nov. 7 by his prime minister,
Zine el Abidine Ben Ali.
   Ben Ali justified the bloodless coup on grounds that the
84-year-old Bourguiba had become senile and unable to exercise his
duties and that Tunisia needed to revert to genuine democratic rule.
   Bourguiba, who formerly controlled 100 percent of the National
Assembly, had himself named president-for-life by assembly members
in March 1975.
   The former leader has remained confined in his chateau near
Tunis since the coup. All mention of his name has been banished
from the media in this North African Arab nation.
   But the former leader, whose photograph for years was featured
prominently in every television broadcast and on the front page of
every newspaper, remains an unspoken factor in Tunisian politics.
   Tunisian sources said he has steadfastly resisted pressure from
the government to issue a public endorsement of Ben Ali as
Tunisia's president.
   Yet no voice was raised in tribute to him when the National
Assembly, exclusively composed of members of the ruling
Constitutional Democratic Rally, debated the new constitution.
   The Constitutional Democratic Rally is the new name of
Bourguiba's ruling Destourian Socialist Party. The name change was
approved Feb. 28.
   Under the new constitution, the president will be elected for
five-year terms. The president can be reelected but must face
voters every five years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
