<HEAD>Authorities: Pay Stub Bank Note Helped In Man's Arrest</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Misspellings in note in 3rd graf are cq.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man authorities said used his own paycheck
stub to write a holdup note at a bank was indicted Wednesday on
federal robbery charges.
   Kevin D. Thompson, 26, was accused in the robbery of $8,000 from
a Bloomfield branch of Midlantic National Bank on June 22. He was
being held in lieu of $75,000 bail at the Metropolitan Correctional
Center.
   According to a criminal complaint, the money was handed over
after a teller received a note saying, ``This is a stickup, keep
clam I have a gun give me some $100, 50, & 20 keep clam and no won
will get harm. Thank you.''
   The note was written on a stub from Systems Maintenance Corp. of
Fairfield, where Thompson had worked and was absent on June 22, the
complaint said. The stub had no names on it, but listed specific
pay figures.
   The government's complaint said an anonymous caller last month
described the getaway car, identified Thompson, gave Thompson's
address and gave other details.
   But the defendant's attorney, Lawrence Lustberg, said his client
was innocent.
   ``He has no idea how his stub came to be used and was ``educated
enough to know to spell not like the note is spelled,'' Lustberg
said.
</TEXT>
