<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Sweden-Reunion,0178</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Defector Reunited with Wife in Sweden</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet opera singer who defected to
Sweden was reunited with his wife Wednesday after almost seven
years, auguring improved Swedish-Soviet relations.
   ``During all these years, the hope never left me,'' Vera Morozov
told Swedish Radio after arriving by ship at a Stockholm harbor.
   Alex Morozov, who was living in Leningrad, defected in June 1981
during a concert stop in Goteborg.
   In January, he protested to press for his wife's visa during an
official visit of Soviet Premier Nikolai Ryzhkov to Goteborg.
   Soviet approval of her visa resolved the last of 21 human rights
cases raised by Prime Minister Ingvar Carlsson on a visit to Moscow
in 1986.
   ``We have ... noted a pronounced thaw in the ice, a change, from
before'' in the Soviet attitude, said a spokeswoman for the Swedish
Foreign Ministry.
   The two countries have resolved three other asylum issues since
Carlsson's 1986 visit. The Foreign Ministry spokeswoman was unsure
if other cases were pending.
</TEXT>
