<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ChanceReunion     03-09 0307</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chance Reunion,0314</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cousins Meet By Chance After 60 Years Apart</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMARAC, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two cousins who hadn't seen each other in
60 years had an unexpected reunion in a hospital waiting room,
where one had gone to have a shoulder injury examined and the other
was seeking treatment of lung congestion.
   Elmer Gnau, 73, on vacation from La Grange, Ky., wound up
sitting just one seat away from Kenneth Gnau, 63, of Margate, at
HCA University Hospital on Tuesday.
   When the nurse came out and called `Gnau,' both men stood up.
   ``I looked at him and asked him his name,'' said Elmer Gnau, a
retired tool and dye maker. ``I knew if he said Kenneth, he would
be my cousin. Not many people are named Gnau.''
   The chance meeting was emotional for the first cousins, who last
saw each other when they were children in Louisville, Ky.
   ``I never thought I would have recognized him,'' said Kenneth
Gnau. ``But I looked up, and my stomach came right up to my throat.
He has the face of my father. I almost cried.''
   Elmer Gnau was in Florida to visit his son, Jerry Gnau, in North
Lauderdale. Still suffering from congested lungs after a bout with
pneumonia a month ago, he went to the doctor for a prescription to
clear up the infection.
   Kenneth Gnau, who retired to Margate with his wife, was waiting
to have an X-ray taken of a shoulder injury.
   Jerry Gnau's daughter, Teresa, said her family had tried to find
Kenneth Gnau three years ago when they saw a picture of his
motorboat in a newspaper. The boat had exploded in a canal in
Margate, but Kenneth Gnau's phone number wasn't listed.
   The cousins planned to visit each other later this week after
Kenneth Gnau undergoes an operation for his injured shoulder.
</TEXT>
