<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 1746EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-AIDS-Vatican     03-09 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS-Vatican,0306</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Major Statement on AIDS Calls for Virtue, Criticizes Condoms</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-AIDS Conference</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANCES D'EMILIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The only effective way to prevent the spread
of AIDS is to halt sex outside marriage and to end intravenous drug
abuse, the Vatican newspaper said Wednesday in a major statement on
the disease.
   ``The prevention of AIDS has moral implications of a reach
greater than what it seemed at first,'' said the unsigned editorial
on the front page of L'Osservatore Romano, the Vatican's daily
newspaper.
   ``The responsibility for the battle against the evil does not
fall only on the shoulders of some doctors and researchers, but, on
the contrary, must be shared by everybody,'' it said.
   The Vatican newspaper said the defeat of AIDS ``requires an
effort extended to modify and to overcome ethically aberrant
behaviors.''
   ``The only really effective measure is prevention ... avoiding
the causes of contagion, which means, in 95 percent of the cases,
abstaining from sexual practice outside marriage and from consuming
drugs,'' the editorial said.
   It said medical and ethical prescriptions have coincided before,
such as the campaign against smoking and calls for moderation in
diet.
   The newspaper said trying to prevent AIDS ``by promoting the use
of condoms ... is not only scarcely trustworthy from the technical
point of view, but also and above all inacceptable from the moral
point of view.''
   In December, a report by the administrative board of the United
States Catholic Conference said instruction about condoms in AIDS
education programs could be permitted in the context of church
teaching advocating ``abstinence outside of marriage and fidelity
within marriage.''
   Cardinal John J. O'Connor of New York called the report a ``very
grave mistake'' and said he will not allow such instruction.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
