<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 1618EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0964 03-09 0676</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0964,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Camp Gets Ready for Illinois</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 9 grafs new with prospects in Illinois, picking up in 7th
graf pvs, ``His strength</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush paused briefly Wednesday to savor the
fruits of his stunning Super Tuesday success while his aides toted
up the vice president's advantages in next week's Illinois primary.
   Campaign manager Lee Atwater cautioned against overconfidence
following Bush's 16-state primary sweep. But the vice president
enters his Illinois campaign with the support of Gov. James
Thompson and most other state party officials, as well as the lead
in public and private polls.
   The vice president's aides also have mapped their largest
single-state television advertising effort of the campaign in the
days before Illinois votes.
   Bush's Super Tuesday showing left him with roughly 700 of the
1,139 delegates needed to win the nomination, and Illinois offers
the possibility of another 92.
   Aides agreed that his close identification with President Reagan
helped Bush on Super Tuesday. But a key strategist said it would be
``clearly an oversimplification'' to credit Bush's lopsided victory
to Reagan's popularity.
   Bush himself rested Wednesday before plunging into his campaign
in Illinois on Thursday. His aides tried to avoid sounding
overconfident the day after his string of victories.
   ``I'd rather be more like Ronald Reagan and be cautiously
optimistic,'' said deputy campaign manager Rich Bond. ``It's a
marathon and we've got to play this thing through until we're
mathematically certain that we're going to win the nomination.''
   Atwater had said late Tuesday, ``The second in this business you
start resting on laurels ... is the second you start getting in
trouble.''
   The vice president's aides said they could not quarrel with exit
polls showing Bush benefited handsomely from his association with
Reagan. But Lanny Griffith, who was Bush's Southern regional
political director, said he thought the coattail effect was
exaggerated.
   
   ``His strength was the work that was done in the 14 months
leading up to Super Tuesday,'' Griffith said in an interview. ``The
real heroes were the people that put this thing together.''
   Griffith said that Bush's ties to Reagan helped, ``but that's
clearly an oversimplification. The vice president has shown that he
is as strong on the issues as any candidate.''
   A CBS-New York Times exit poll said that in some states, as many
as four out of five Republican voters approved of Reagan and that
three out of five of them backed Bush.
   ``He stayed away from political rhetoric as usual. He stayed
away from name-calling,'' Atwater said. And he said Bush's
association with ``a very successful administration'' played a big
role in his victories.
   Rep. Lynn Martin, R-Ill., co-chairman of Bush's Illinois
campaign, attributed at least part of Bush's Super Tuesday success
to mistakes by Sen. Bob Dole of Kansas.
   ``I think he's terrific. I think he's funny. I think a lot of
him,'' she said of Dole. ``But Bob Dole did himself in'' by seeming
too ingracious after losing the New Hampshire primary to Bush, she
said.
   In a telehone interview, she said Bush is being perceived as
sending a more positive message.
   ``I don't think it's because George Bush suddenly became so
charismatic that you couldn't take your eyes off him,'' she said.
   Bush carried all but the state of Washington Tuesday, winning
around 600 delegates, the largest one-day collection in the history
of presidential nomination politics.
   By refusing to meet Dole in one-on-one debates in Illinois, and
by hewing closely to a campaign regimen that has Bush mixing
frequently with people and posing for pictures, the vice
president's strategists signaled they plan no change in campaign
style.
   ``The vice president is going to go and do in Illinois what he
did in New Hampshire and in South Carolina, and that is, go through
all corners of the state, campaign directly and forthrightly and
get his message out,'' Atwater said.
   Bush is scheduled to campaign nonstop in Illinois from Thursday
through Monday, including a one-day flying tour of the state.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
