<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Kentucky     03-09 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kentucky,0350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush, Gore Get Help from A President and Governor in Kentucky</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES WEBB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFORT, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opponents of Vice President George Bush
credited his huge Kentucky win to President Reagan's popularity,
while Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr. got help in the Democratic
primary from the state's governor.
   Bush's 16-state primary sweep over Kansas Sen. Bob Dole in the
South and elsewhere on Super Tuesday ``will practically cinch the
Bush nomination,'' said U.S. Rep. Harold ``Hal'' Rogers, who led
Bush's state campaign.
   ``George Bush is not just whistling Dixie, he's got the full
orchestra behind him,'' Rogers said Wednesday.
   Gore emerged from Kentucky's primary with less than half the
popular vote, but with the backing of Gov. Wallace Wilkinson he
could control more than two-thirds of the state's 62 delegates.
   With all of the 3,243 Democratic precincts reporting, Gore had
145,201 votes or 46 percent, followed by Massachusetts Gov. Michael
Dukakis with 59,424 votes or 19 percent and Jesse Jackson with
49,659 votes or 16 percent.
   Gore won 37 of the 55 pledged delegates, Dukakis had 12 and
Jackson, six. Wilkinson, however, will be able to control at least
four of the party's unpledged official delegates, giving Gore a
solid two-thirds of the total delegation.
   ``Al Gore is right for Kentucky; he's right for America. We're
just now starting the momentum in this campaign,'' Wilkinson said
Tuesday.
   In the Republican race, with 100 percent of the vote counted,
Bush had 71,954 votes or 59 percent, to 27,845 votes or 23 percent
for Dole.
   State Sen. John Rogers, of the Dole campaign in Kentucky, said
there had been hopes of getting up to 40 percent of the vote for
the senator, but ``a security vote'' brought the Republicans out
for Bush.
   ``He was just more closely associated with Reagan and the
majority of people _ Republicans anyway _ liked what Reagan's done
for the last eight years,'' Rogers said.
   Bush won 27 of the state's 38 delegates and Dole captured the
other 11.
</TEXT>
