<1ST_LINE>r a AM-JetBlowout     03-09 0197</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jet Blowout,0202</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FAA Investigates Jet Landing, In Which Two Tires Blowout</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Continental jetliner that had two tires
blow out while landing at Newark International Airport was flying
without a special braking device that prevents such incidents,
authorities said.
   The Federal Aviation Administration is investigating the trouble
with the landing Monday of DC9 Flight 612 from Rochester, N.Y.,
said FAA spokeswoman Kathleen Bergen.
   Legally the airline could fly the jet without the braking device
for three days before fixing it, Ms. Bergen said.
   None of the 29 passengers or crew was hurt when both tires on
the main landing gear under the left wing failed, Ms. Bergen said.
   Passengers were taken to the terminal by bus, said Rick Scott, a
Continental spokesman.
   The device is called an ``anti-skid'' braking system, which is
supposed to prevent pilots from applying the brakes too hard,
officials said. If the brakes are applied too hard they can lock
and cause blowouts, officials said.
   Scott said the inoperable braking device had nothing to do with
the tire blowouts. He said the pilot reported the tires blew
``immediately upon landing'' and before the brakes could be applied.
</TEXT>
