<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Carlucci     03-09 0653</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Carlucci,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Considering Ways To Help Non-US-Flagged Ships In Persian Gulf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States is considering ways to help
merchant ships which aren't flying the U.S. flag in the war-torn
Persian Gulf, Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci said Wednesday.
   ``We are examining a number of options in this regard, but
serious policy, legal, economic and force level issues remain,''
Carlucci told the House Foreign Affairs Committee.
   Since last July 22, the Navy has been protecting 11
Kuwaiti-owned tankers which were reflagged with the Star and
Stripes. The large-scale convoy operation increased the number of
Navy ships in the area from six to about 30.
   The Kuwaiti ships are being protected against attack by Iran,
which has been at war for seven and one-half year with Iraq, an
ally of Kuwait.
   The Reagan administration has been asked for aid by U.S.
shipowners using so-called flags of convenience, such as Panama and
Liberia. The Navy has consistently refused, citing U.S. policies of
helping only American-flagged ships.
   U.S. shipowners ``continue to ask us to provide protection to
their non-U.S. flag vessels,'' Carlucci said. ``Despite our
humanitarian desire to be helpful, our longstanding requirement for
ships to be flying the U.S. flag remains very persuasive.''
   ``Absent a U.S. flag, we believe a substantial foreign force
operational commitment would be mandatory,'' he noted.
   Carlucci did not explain, nor was he asked, what other measures
are being considered.
   However, some shipowners have pushed to have the U.S. Navy freed
to protect shipping under attack if the Navy warships are in the
vicinity. There have been a number of incidents where Navy warships
were nearby when non-U.S.-flagged vessels were under attack.
   The Navy has actually decreased the number of ships in the gulf
area, Carlucci noted, after the battleship Iowa and helicopter
carrier Okinawa were withdrawn earlier this year.
   The withdrawal ``does not represent any change in our policy or
any weakening of our capability,'' Carlucci noted. ``The numbers
will continue to fluctuate somewhat, but our steadfast commitment
along with our capabilities will remain a constant as long as our
presence is required.''
   American allies in Europe are providing a wide range of help for
the Navy in the Persian Gulf, Carlucci noted.
   Most of that aid comes from allied minesweepers, which were sent
into the region after the first of the reflagged Kuwaiti tankers
hit a mine last July 24 and other mines were found in the following
months.
   Japan is also providing financial help, Carlucci noted, but is
prohibited by its U.S.-written laws from sending ships to the
region.
   Carlucci said the Pentagon is considering the sale of four Aegis
defense systems to Japan for use in the Japanese navy. Each would
cost about $1 billion.
   The Aegis, with its sophisticated electronics, is considered the
world's most advanced air defense system and plays a key role in
Navy plans to defend American ships in wartime.
   Rep. Olympia Snowe, R-Maine, noted that the sale could be ``a
serious problem'' if any of Aegis equipment were resold to American
enenies. She noted that a Japanese company, Toshiba, reported
helped sell sophisticated equipment to the Soviet Union which the
Soviets then used to make much quieter submarines.
   ``There has never been a compromise by the Japanese
government,'' said Carlucci, noting that the previous incident
involved a private company.
   But Snowe noted that ``even though the Japanese government was
not involved in the Toshiba case, there have been a series of
problems with other nations.''
   Carlucci said, ``we have no reason to question the sincerity of
the Japanese government.''
   Adm. William Crowe Jr., chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff,
noted calls in Congress for Japan to do more in its own defense.
Selling the Aegi systems to Japan ``would buttress our position in
the northwest Pacific'' and improve the Navy's ability to operate
with the Japanese navy, he noted.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
