<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 1820EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Baker-Fed     03-09 0698</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Baker-Fed,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Baker Says Fed Should Be Independent, But Not Sheltered</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Treasury Secretary James A. Baker III said
Wednesday that the need for an independent Federal Reserve did not
mean the central bank should be ``totally sheltered from outside
advice or criticism.''
   Baker defended the administration against charges that it had
sought to bring undue political pressure on the central bank to
insure that the economy continues growing without a recession
during this presidential election year.
   Testifying before the Joint Economic Committee of Congress,
Baker was asked specifically about a letter that Assistant Treasury
Secretary Michael Darby sent to the central bank on Jan. 28 in
which Darby warned that slow growth of the money supply was
threatening a recession.
   Darby's letter was sent to every member of the Federal Open
Market Committee two weeks before a crucial meeting in which the
group was to set monetary growth targets for this year. The central
bank seeks to provide enough money to the banking system to promote
healthy economic growth while guarding against supplying so much
money that it threatens higher inflation.
   Sen. William Proxmire, D-Wis., said that in 30 years in Congress
he had never seen such ``overt, direct interference with the
independent Federal Reserve.'' Proxmire, chairman of the Senate
Banking Committee, asked whether Darby faced any disciplinary
action for his letter.
   Baker said the Darby letter had been sent without his knowledge
and when he learned about it, he told Darby not to do it again. But
Baker denied that Darby's letter, which he characterized as raising
academic questions about monetary growth, was an example of
administration pressure.
   On Feb. 24, Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan issued a
rare public warning to the administration to stop pressing the Fed
to lower interest rates, contending that further pressure might
force the central bank to demonstrate its independence by doing
exactly the opposite.
   Greenspan specifically cited the Darby letter, saying he had
objected to the letter strongly with an administration official,
later identified as Baker.
   Administration critics charged that the Darby letter was just
one example of administration pressure on the Federal Reserve to
keep the economy expanding as a way of boosting Republican chances
of holding onto the White House.
   Baker denied these accusations and said he had never engaged in
``Fed bashing'' since becoming Treasury secretary in 1985. He said
he had worked closely with both Greenspan and former Fed Chairman
Paul Volcker in an effort to coordinate policies on a whole range
of economic issues including international debt, currency exchange
rates, the government's tax and budget policies and monetary policy.
   ``The Federal Reserve ought to be independent, but that does not
mean that they should be totally sheltered from outside advice or
criticism,'' he said. ``It is my view that the administration has a
right and a responsibility to advise the Federal Reserve on all
elements of economy policy, just as we welcome their advice to us
on all elements of economic policy.''
   Baker added, ``The Federal Reserve is independent and it ought
to remain independent, but it is independent within this government
and it is not independent of this government.''
   On another matter, Baker said he did not view the big rise in
the value of the British pound in recent days as a breach of the
currency stabilization agreement between the United States, Britain
and five other top industrial countries reached last December.
   Baker said British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher had not
informed the United States beforehand of her government's decision
not to intervene in currency markets to stop the rise of the pound
against the U.S. dollar and other currencies.
   Baker said he did not see the rise in the pound as jeopardizing
the Dec. 22 accord between the United States and other top
industrialized countries to stabilize the value of the dollar
around current exchange rates.
   ``We don't see this as in any way running counter to that
agreement or being somehow a repudiation of it,'' he said, adding
that the recent increase in the British pound had more to do with
British interest rates and monetary policy decisions in that
country.
</TEXT>
