<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Nevada 1stLd-Writethru a0858 03-09 0292</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nevada, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0858,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gore Backer Says Caucus Win Puts Him in ``Excellent Shape''</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Leads with four grafs with updated figures; picks up graf 4,
``That left''
^Associated Press Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CARSON CITY, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tennesseee Sen. Albert Gore Jr.'s
victory in Nevada's Democratic caucuses was important because it
showed he could win outside the South, according to Sen. Harry
Reid. But most of the state's top Democrats said they were
impressed with Jesse Jackson's third-place finish.
   ``The good news is how well we've (Gore's campaign) done all
over the country,'' Reid said.
   With all but a handful of precincts uncounted Wednesday, state
party leaders said Gore won with 33 percent or 693 of the 2,101
delegates, followed by Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis with 548
or 26 percent, and Jackson with 460 or 22 percent.
   Fifteen percent or 329 of the delegates were uncommitted, 2
percent or 39 were for Rep. Richard Gephardt of Missouri, and 2
percent was divided between Sen. Paul Simon of Illinois and former
Sen. Gary Hart of Colorado.
   That left Gore leading for 7 delegates, Dukakis for 5 and
Jackson for 3 with 1 uncommitted.
   Bill Wasserman, Dukakis' state coordinator, said he was pleased
with the results but called support for Jackson was ``stunning. It
has got to be a phenomenon that makes any Democratic candidate
think seriously about his campaign effort.''
   Jackson spokesman Joe Neal, a state senator, said the turnout of
Jackson supporters at the caucuses exceeded expectations. ``The
people we contacted went to the caucuses.''
   State Democratic Chairman Beecher Avants agreed that Jackson's
showing was a surprise, adding that he didn't think Jackson had
been doing the pre-caucus mailing and telephone work that
supporters of Gore and Dukakis had.
</TEXT>
