<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland-Students 1stLd-Writethru a0975 03-09 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Students, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0975,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Walesa Upbraids Police for Breaking Up Student Protest</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS penultimate graf, ``Zygmunt Lenyk ... with 1 graf to
UPDATE with government figures on detentions; SUBS 3rd graf, ``On
Tuesday ... with 1 graf to conform.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa criticized
police on Wednesday for using force to break up student
demonstrations in Warsaw and Krakow.
   Walesa made his remarks one day after club-wielding riot police
clashed with youths demonstrating for more academic freedom on the
20th anniversary of student protests against censorship and
political repression.
   On Tuesday, police charged into hundreds of demonstrators in
Warsaw and Krakow and made scores of arrests.
   The leader of the outlawed labor federation said he expected
authorities eventually to admit error in using force against
students this year.
   ``I don't have a detailed account of what happened, but I think
that in a few years' time there shall be great efforts to disavow
all that took place,'' Walesa said before meeting with Austrian
Foreign Minister Alois Mock in Warsaw.
   The authorities use ``such a method of disavowing things that
should not have taken place at all,'' he said.
   A commentary by the official Polish news agency PAP said that in
Warsaw and Krakow ``attempts were made to take advantage'' of
anniversary observances to hold illegal demonstrations.
   ``The attempts were abortive owing to the lack of wider support
and thanks to the determined attitude of the forces of law and
order,'' PAP said.
   The students were calling for restoration of academic freedoms
won during the 1980-81 Solidarity labor upheaval and for
legalization of the Independent Students Union, which was outlawed
under martial law was imposed in 1982.
   Zygmunt Lenyk, a Krakow opposition spokesman, said at least 64
people were detained in the southern Polish city, but everyone was
released later Tuesday. An aide to government spokesman Jerzy Urban
said a total of 83 people were detained in Tuesday's demonstrations
but less than 15 people remained in custody, awaiting appearances
in misdemeanor courts.
   The student protests of 20 years ago were violently broken up by
police and worker activists. But the communist Polish United
Workers Party recently disavowed repressive measures used against
reform-oriented intellectuals 20 years ago.
</TEXT>
