<1ST_LINE>r p AM-WhiteHouse-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0880 03-09 0544</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-White House-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0880,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Stays Neutral But Staff Chief Says Bush Close to Victory</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Leads with 3 grafs with Reagan comment. Picks up 3rd graf
pvs., ``Vice President ...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan renewed his vow of neutrality
in the Republican presidential race Wednesday, while White House
Chief of Staff Howard Baker said ``it would take a major event'' to
deny George Bush the nomination.
   ``I will remain neutral,'' Reagan told inquiring reporters as he
returned to the White House from a trip to Notre Dame University in
South Bend, Ind. He seemed bouyant, dribbling a basketball he got
at Notre Dame and passing it back and forth with a woman
well-wisher.
   Baker, talking with reporters earlier, said, ``The president is
still neutral and I expect will continue that way for the
foreseeable future.''
   Vice President Bush scored a sweep of the Super Tuesday
primaries, moving within reach of the GOP presidential nomination.
   ``He was the front-runner before and clearly is the front-runner
now,'' said Baker. ``I think it would take a major event to deny
him the nomination. He's certainly got the momentum.''
   Baker, who dropped out of the presidential race a year ago to
lead Reagan's staff, said the last word he had from Reagan was that
as the titular head of the Republican Party, he intended to remain
neutral.
   ``And whether he would re-address that in light of other
circumstances, we'll have to wait and see but I have no indication
of it,'' the former senator said.
   Baker said Reagan was ``awful pleased with the exit polls,''
which showed an 84 percent approval rating for the president among
Republican voters in the South.
   ``I told him this morning ... he was really the one who swept
the South,'' Baker said. ``I think that was a matter of pride for
the president.''
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater, traveling with Reagan
aboard Air Force One to South Bend, Ind., also described the
president as ``very impressed with the Republican turnout.''
   ``We have a strong movement toward the Republican Party in the
South,'' Fitzwater said. He called it a ``strong indication of the
realignment that's taken place'' in the region.
   Citing Texas as an example, Fitzwater said that 500,000 persons
voted on the GOP side during the primary season in 1980 and 900,000
voted in the GOP ranks in 1988.
   Baker said the overall Republican voter turnout was about 44
percent of the total vote cast Tuesday.
   ``So that's a far cry from the old Democratic solid South and
that may be the most significant single aspect of Super Tuesday,''
Baker said.
   He said the GOP turnout ``indicates that the Reagan revolution
and the Republican growth in the South is not a transient
phenomenon but is a permanent fixture in the American political
system.
   Commenting on the outcome on the Democratic side, Baker singled
out the success of fellow Tennessean Albert Gore Jr., who won his
own state and four other Souther primaries.
   ``Al Gore may have demolished the theory that you've got to run
in Iowa and New Hampshire. He is a very credible candidate and he
did not make a major effort in Iowa and New Hampshire,'' Baker said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
