<DOCNO> AP880309-0272 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 1855EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LaRoucheTrial     03-09 0732</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-LaRouche Trial,0747</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Declassified Documents Indicate CIA, FBI Infilrated LaRouche
Groups</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   FBI files declassified Wednesday quoted three
intelligence operatives as saying they had been directed by
high-level FBI and CIA officials to infiltrate the political
organizations of Lyndon LaRouche.
   Excerpts from the files, surrendered to defense lawyers in the
fraud and conspiracy trial of LaRouche, six aides and five of his
political groups, showed that one of the three refused to discuss
his LaRouche-related dealings with low-level FBI officials, saying
he had been instructed by ranking officials at the agencies not to
do so.
   That man, retired Army Sgt. Maj. Fred Lewis, also was referred
to in a memo from retired Air Force Maj. Gen. Richard Secord to
Marine Lt. Col. Oliver North in which Secord indicated Lewis had
collected evidence against LaRouche.
   Both the declassified FBI material and the Secord memo were
dated in May 1986 and refer to giving Lewis a polygraph to
determine if his information was valid.
   Lawyers for LaRouche, a political extremist who has accused such
international figures as Queen Elizabeth II of drug trafficking,
have obtained growing evidence in recent weeks of infiltration of
LaRouche groups by the FBI and CIA. They contend the effort was
directed by North, the former National Security Council aide fired
for his role in the Iran-Contra scandal. Secord worked with North
to set up a private network to aid the Contra rebels in Nicaragua.
   The defense lawyers, who have requested thousands of other
documents from the FBI, CIA and NSC, contend the records will prove
their claim that charges of credit card fraud and conspiracy
against LaRouche and his followers were concocted as part of a
government plot to ruin LaRouche because he refused to support aid
to the Contras.
   ``This was an activity that was headed up by Oliver North and
Mr. Secord in a political attempt to stop the LaRouche people,''
defense attorney Michael Reilly said Wednesday.
   The defense lawyers also have said they believe they have
grounds for dismissal of the case because of prosecutorial
misconduct, contending the government has deliberately withheld
evidence of FBI and CIA penetration of LaRouche groups.
   The three men referred to in the declassified FBI material are
Lewis, Gary S. Howard and Ron Tucker.
   ``Lewis, Tucker and Howard indicated they have a very high level
source in the federal government who advises them regularly
concerning cooperation or lack thereof between Lewis and his
associates and the federal government,'' the document said.
   ``When asked about their possible ties to LaRouche, they claimed
to have been previously been requested by the FBI and CIA to
penetrate the LaRouche organization,'' said the document, which was
excerpted from an unidentified FBI file.
   According to the material, Lewis said he had been instructed by
contacts in CIA and FBI headquarters not to discuss his LaRouche
ties without authorization from top officials at the agencies.
   Defense attorney Daniel Alchorn, who represents LaRouche aide
Paul Goldstein, said during Wednesday's hearing that Lewis was a
principal in a Dallas-based group known as Peregrine International,
which he said was tied to Secord and helped carry out covert
activities for the U.S. government.
   In the North-Secord memo, there is a reference by Secord to
``our man.'' The defense lawyers said they have been informed by
the government that the reference is to Oliver Revell, an FBI
assistant director invovled in counterintelligence.
   Tucker, a former Texas Department of Public Safety Narcotics
Agent, and Howard, a former border patrol agent, claim in a suit
against the Customs Service that they have been government
informants since 1979.
   In the suit, filed in Washington in August, Tucker and Howard
say the government owes them $1.4 million for their expenses in a
sting operation that led to the arrest of a man allegedly buying
arms for Iran. They claim the government lost interest in
prosecuting the case because it would have revealed the Reagan
administration's arms shipments to Iran and the diversion of
profits from the sales to the Contras.
   The FBI document also said that during interviews with FBI
agents in Texas, Tucker and Howard said they had approached family
and friends of Soviet dissidents Andrei Sakharov and his wife,
Yelena Bonner, claiming they could free the couple from the Soviet
Union for $2 million. ``No further information was available
concerning this matter,'' the document said.
</TEXT>
