<1ST_LINE>r p AM-NorthCarolina     03-09 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-North Carolina,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan's Popularity Helps Bush; Endorsements Boost Gore</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN FLESHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr. narrowly
defeated Jesse Jackson in a North Carolina presidential primary
that observers said showed the changing face of Southern Democratic
politics.
   ``It shows there are many Souths _ no solid South,'' said Merle
Black, political science professor at the University of North
Carolina. ``It's too diverse.''
   Meanwhile, Vice President George Bush's lopsided victory in the
Republican primary showed his links with President Reagan were
stronger than Kansas Sen. Bob Dole's ties to North Carolina. Dole's
wife, Elizabeth, is a native of Salisbury, N.C.
   ``What George Bush has shown is that he is strong in the
South,'' said Jack Hawke, state GOP chairman. ``People are
associating him with the president.''
   Bush held off a late surge by Dole, who targeted North Carolina
in his effort to avoid a Southern shutout. Bush had said he was
worried because polls had indicated the contest was neck-and-neck.
   With all 2,387 precincts reporting, Gore had 235,345 votes or 35
percent; Jackson had 223,207 votes or 33 percent; Massachusetts
Gov. Michael Dukakis had 137,755 votes or 20 percent, and Missouri
Rep. Richard Gephardt had 37,483 votes or 6 percent.
   In the Republican race, Bush had 124,028 votes or 45 percent;
Dole had 109,999 votes or 40 percent; former television evangelist
Pat Robertson had 26,747 votes or 10 percent, and New York Rep.
Jack Kemp had 11,364 votes or 4 percent.
   Based on those results, Bush was expected to win 29 GOP
delegates and Dole 25. Gore would capture 34 Democratic delegates,
Jackson 31 and Dukakis 17.
   Gore carried North Carolina becuse he ``has a lot of appeal to
middle-of-the road, common sense Democrats,'' said former Gov. Jim
Hunt, who with Sen. Terry Sanford endorsed Gore in January.
   Black, however, said the closeness of the race indicated many
conservative Democrats had not voted.
   ``I don't think Gore would have made any showing if Jim Hunt and
Terry Sanford had not gotten active in his campaign like they
did,'' said Dan Blue, a black state representative who was state
chairman for Jackson.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
