<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Robertson     03-09 0543</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Robertson,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Robertson Won't Rule Out 1988, But Looks To Future</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Pat Robertson said Wednesday that
Super Tuesday showed the ``mantle of Ronald Reagan has passed to
George Bush'' but he refused to write off his own presidential try,
saying his political agenda now extended beyond 1988.
   ``In the South, where I thought I would be strong, Ronald Reagan
and his mantle was a lot stronger, but there are other parts of the
country that maybe don't feel this way,'' said Robertson, who took
a drubbing at the hands of George Bush.
   Most of Tuesday's contests were in the South, where Robertson
had expected to do well. But he won only nine of the 712 delegates
at stake, losing all 16 primaries and winning only the caucuses in
the state of Washington. Bush won all the primaries.
   ``None of us could have dreamed that (Bush) could be so
strong,'' Robertson said. ``The mantle of Ronald Reagan has passed
to George Bush.''
   Exit polls showed Bush picked up more votes from conservative
Christians than the former television evangelist, and Robertson
blamed himself.
   ``I talked too much up in South Carolina,'' he said, referring
to statements there which seemed to suggest Bush's campaign was
responsible for revelations about questionable sexual practices by
television evangelist Jimmy Swaggart.
   ``Some of the things I said, unfortunately, were misinterpreted
by the press, at least spun in a different way than what I
intended,'' he said.
   Robertson also stood by a controversial statement he made during
the New Hampshire campaign. ``I still think there are (nuclear)
missiles in Cuba,'' he said, restating a claim denied by the Reagan
administration.
   Robertson, who also finished behind Bob Dole, said he would
continue the race until the New Orleans nominating convention as
``a rallying point for conservatives.''
   ``I will probably go into the convention with a number of
delegates that are at least mine in heart,'' Robertson said at a
morning news conference in Atlanta, where he watched election
returns Tuesday night.
   He said he would take a day off before continuing to Illinois to
campaign for next week's primary there.
   ``It isn't over yet. There're still half of the delegates left
to be selected,'' he said. ``My goal this year is to win the
presidency. I haven't given that goal up. I am in for principle.''
   Robertson said his candidacy has helped expand the Republican
Party and that will leave him with a reservoir of support he could
tap later, perhaps in 1992.
   ``I will have people favorable to me in key party positions ...
in a lot of (state parties),'' he said, estimating as much as 40
percent of the GOP structure in some states is loyal to him.
   ``That would be a significant base for something in the
future,'' he said.
   If he doesn't win this year, Robertson said, ``my role (in 1990)
will be what George Bush's role was in '86. He went to many, many
congressional districts, helped raise ... about $17 million for
party candidates during that cycle.
   ``I could help a number of good men and women be elected,'' he
said. ``I want to build the Republican Party and make it the
majority party.''
</TEXT>
