<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Children'sSpending     03-09 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Children's Spending,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lobbying Group Calls for Increased Spending on Children's Programs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CRISPIN Y. CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Children's Defense Fund urged its
supporters on Wednesday to press the presidental candidates to
increase funding for children's welfare and education programs.
   ``It is now time to reverse course and invest in the future, to
invest in our children, if we as a nation are going to save
ourselves,'' the fund's President Marian Wright Edelman said at a
news conference at the organization's annual meeting.
   Edelman called on supporters to ``urge those seeking and holding
public office this year to commit themselves to making preventive
investment in our children and families the cornerstone of national
domestic policy in the coming political era.''
   The fund will press for immediate enactment of legislation
providing safe daycare and establishing minimum health care
coverage for poverty-level mothers and children, she said. The
group's long-term priorities include five-year incremental
increases in the minimum wage and in funding for educational
programs for poor and handicapped chldren.
   The fund, a non-profit lobbying group for children's issues, has
produced briefing books and a list of questions for its members to
quiz the candidates and eventually elicit support for its
legislative agenda.
   Edelman said she was optimistic about the success of the agenda
because of the ``new and powerful allies'' it has found in
corporate leaders, who want to ensure an educated work force.
   ``What we see now is a new coalition of those who worry about
the health and social welfare of children and those in the business
community who recognize the economic connection in investing in
children who are at risk in this society,'' said Donna Shelala, the
fund's board chairman.
   She referred to the Committee for Economic Development's Report
for 1987 in which the business community spoke ``in terms of
investing in children early on, in prenatal care, in early
childhood programs, and Head Start programs, as ways of ensuring
the economic future of the country.''
   This is the eighth year the fund has produced a children's
budget and provided analysis of the administration's fiscal
proposal. As in the past, the organization criticized the Reagan
administration's emphasis on defense spending over funding for
social programs.
</TEXT>
