<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LionKilled     03-09 0196</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lion Killed,0202</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Game Wardens Kill Cougar Stalking Residential Area</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YORBA LINDA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mountain lion was shot dead
Wednesday after he was spotted stalking a residential area where
children were waiting for school buses and adults were leaving
their homes for work, officials said.
   The 120-pound male mountain lion was spotted in this northwest
Orange County community below the Chino Hills, said Patrick Moore,
spokesman for the state Fish and Game Department in Long Beach.
   Police cornered the lion outside a house, and a fish and game
warden shot it, Moore said.
   ``These animals are extremely shy and normally don't come in
residential areas,'' Moore said. ``We like to remove the animal
permanently from those situations.''
   Moore said the animal was killed rather than tranquilized
because the drug takes 10 to 20 minutes to take affect and animals
sometimes have a violent reaction to it.
   ``There was fear that he would run amok in the area and threaten
children,'' he said.
   The cat's body was taken to the fish and game laboratory in
Victorville for a necropsy.
   Mountain lions are common to the hillside areas of Southern
California but rarely attack humans.
</TEXT>
