<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-China Bjt   03-09 0647</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-China, Bjt,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US To Liberalize High-Tech Sales; China Positive On Accepting
Peace Corps</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Relations between the United States and China
brightened Wednesday with a U.S. decision to liberalize the sale of
high technology to the Chinese and Beijing's agreement in principle
to accept Peace Corps volunteers.
   The Reagan administration announced that it lifted a five-month
suspension on the transfer of new technologies after receiving
assurances from Chinese Foreign Minister Wu Xueqian that his
country was not sending Silkworm anti-ship missiles to Iran.
   This removed a major irritant in the relationship.
   Then, during a question-answer session at the National Press
Club after three days of talks with U.S. officials, Wu said of the
Peace Corps that ``China has adopted a positive attitude on this
matter,'' though many details still need to be resolved.
   The agency, established in 1961 by President Kennedy to put a
grassroots and people-to-people stamp on U.S. overseas aid,
currently has programs in 64 countries.
   Alexander Sinclair, a Peace Corps spokesman, said
representatives from the two countries will discuss China's
development needs and how the agency can help.
   As for how large the program will be, when it will start and how
many volunteers will go to China, ``It's too early to tell,''
Sinclair said.
   ``We welcome the opportunity to enter in discussions with the
People's Republic of China about a future Peace Corps program
there,'' Sinclair said. ``We expect to have more information about
such a program in the weeks ahead.''
   The presence of Peace Corps volunteers in a country has for many
years been a significant measure of the warmth of its ties to the
United States. The most populated country that has ever accepted
the Peace Corps was India, which invited volunteers from 1962 until
1976, when it shut down the program.
   After more than two decades of years of emnity, including
several years of war in Korea, the United States and China
normalized relations in the late 1970s and have steadily increased
trade and defense ties.
   There have been some rough spots in the relationship recently,
however, and one of the major ones appears to have been smoothed
during Wu's three days of talks with U.S. officials, including a
40-minute session with President Reagan on Tuesday.
   Last autumn, to protest what it said was continuing Chinese sale
of Silkworm anti-ship missiles to Iran, the administration froze a
decade-old process of liberalizing the list of high technology
items China is permitted by buy from U.S. companies.
   China denounced the decision and in his press club remarks, Wu
reiterated Chinese denials of ``direct'' arms sales to Iran. He
also said that since July, Beijing has made efforts to stop the
flow of Chinese weapons sent through other countries.
   He said that in his talks with Secretary of Stte George P.
Shultz and other administration figures, complaints about Chinese
arms sales to Iran were voiced ``20 times.''
   Without commenting on the truth of Wu's denials about arms
sales, administration officials said after meeting the foreign
minister they had no reason to believe Chinese arms are now flowing
from China to Iran.
   ``We are encouraged by Chinese statements and actions regarding
Iran's acquisition of Chinese anti-ship missiles, Silkworms,''
State Department spokesman Charles E. Redman said.
   ``We have therefore decided to resume the export control
liberalization process for China,'' he said.
   The administration also announced during Wu's visit that he
assured Reagan his country would not stand in the way of a United
Nations resolution calling for an arms embargo against Iran.
   The United States has been trying for months to line up support
on the U.N. Security Council for an arms embargo against Iran
designed to stop the 7-year-old Iran-Iraq War. The ban on weapons
sales would be the second installment of a U.N. resolution last
July calling for a truce in the war.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
