<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Pot-Blindness     03-09 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pot-Blindness,0381</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nearly Blind Woman Arrested For Using Marijuana To Ease Glaucoma</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nearly blind glaucoma victim whose
doctors vainly sought legal permission for her to use marijuana to
help her see now faces up to a year in prison for allegedly growing
her own.
   Elvy Musikka, 43, was arrested Friday and charged with felony
possession of almost a pound of marijuana. She was freed on $1,000
bail.
   Ms. Musikka is sightless in her right eye and retains little
vision in the other.
   ``I don't think I'm above the law,'' she said Tuesday. ``I've
always resented being a criminal to protect my sight. It's a scary
situation.''
   Born with cataracts, she was diagnosed as suffering from
glaucoma in 1976. By 1980 she had to retire from her job as a bank
switchboard operator because of poor vision.
   Glaucoma is characterized by increased pressure inside and
hardening of the eyeball. It can gradually lead to blindness.
   Dr. Paul Palmberg of the Bascom Palmer Eye Institute of the
University of Miami Medical School said 80 percent of glaucoma
patients responded to legal drugs.
   Ms. Musikka, however, did not, and Pamberg said he neither
recommended nor discouraged her use of marijuana to help her see.
   In Ms. Musikka's case, marijuana lowered the pressure of fluid
in her eye while not lowering her blood pressure, allowing the
optic nerve to be nourished with blood, Palmberg said.
   Dr. Richard Parrish, also of the eye institute, said he did not
recommend marijuana, either, but had tried to obtain it legally for
her when he realized it was helping.
   Norman Kent, counsel to the Florida chapter of the National
Organization for the Reformation of Marijuana Laws, said it was
extremely difficult to legally obtain marijuana for medical reasons.
   ``To secure that right, you need a scientist, engineer,
physician, lawyer and magician on your side,'' he said.
   Police spokesman Jim Rabbitt said officers did ``what they had
to do.''
   ``We had a violation,'' he said. ``She's going to have her day
in court.''
   A man who rented a room at her home turned her in for growing
four marijuana plants after the two argued, police reports said.
</TEXT>
