<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Missouri     03-09 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Missouri,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Missouri Hands Narrow Loss to Dole, Only Win to Gephardt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN BALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Missouri voters dealt Bob Dole a narrow
but embarrassing loss blamed on a tidal wave of Southern support
for George Bush, while Rep. Richard Gephardt tolled his only Super
Tuesday win in his home state.
   Supporters of Dole, a senator from neighboring Kansas, said
polls that showed the vice president with commanding leads in the
Southern states prior to Tuesday prompted Missouri's uncommitted
voters to side with the vice president.
   ``Everything in the past two weeks has been Bush is sweeping the
South, Bush is going to win the nomination, Bush is the next
president,'' Roberta Capps, Dole's Missouri campaign chairman, said
Wednesday.
   With all precincts reporting, the vice president had 168,823
votes or 42 percent and Dole had 164,452 votes or 41 percent.
   On the Democratic side, Gephardt garnered 305,159 votes or 58
percent. Jesse Jackson trailed with 106,287 votes or 20 percent.
Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis had 61,557 votes or 12 percent.
   Results showed Gephardt with 68 delegates, Jackson with 14 and
Dukakis with one.
   ``I don't think we have done as well as we'd hoped.'' Gephardt
said in St. Louis after finishing poorly in the 19 other Super
Tuesday states.
   Bill Macon of the Missouri Bush campaign said the victory, along
with the vice president's triumph in Oklahoma, was especially
gratifying because it showed Dole could be beaten in states
neighboring his own.
   ``I'm certainly not trying to humiliate any good Republican but
I think this shows he ought to go back to being the Senate minority
leader and quit cluttering up the race,'' Macon said.
   Bush was expected to capture 22 delegates and Dole 18. Pat
Robertson and New York Rep. Jack Kemp failed to attract enough
Missouri Republican votes to receive any delegates.
</TEXT>
