<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 1930EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FishWars     03-09 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fish Wars,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Department Under Fire Over Japanese Fishing In US Waters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A State Department official said Wednesday the
administration would talk to the Soviet Union about reports of
Japanese vessels fishing illegally in waters off Alaska, but a
House committee chairman demanded more action.
   Ed Wolfe, the State Department's ambassador for oceans and
fisheries, told a congressional hearing that the Reagan
administration was still pressing the government of Japan for an
official explanation of an incident in which Japanese trawlers were
videotaped apparently fishing in American waters in the Bering Sea.
   ``I am personally disappointed that I am not able to provide the
subcommittee with a full report of the Japanese investigation,''
Wolfe said.
   Wolfe said an interagency task force was developing a ``U.S.
government position to help avoid a recurrence of this problem in
the future.''
   He said the United States will be holding bilateral talks with
the Soviet Union, which has its eastern-most tip on the Bering Sea,
later this month to discuss fisheries problems in the area.
   ``It's a good exercise,'' said Wolfe.
   ``It's a good exercise Mr. Ambassador,'' replied Rep. Don
Bonker, D-Wash.. ``But good grief, we want more than an exercise.
   ``It's been three months since the alleged illegal activity took
place and I'm wondering how long we will have to wait before
something is forthcoming.''
   Bonker, chairman of the subcommittee on international economic
policy and trade of the House Foreign Affairs Committee, called on
the State Department to ``greatly accelerate it's actions.
   ``I can promise you, if you don't do something we will.''
   American fishermen and the U.S. Coast Guard have suspected for
more than a year that foreign trawlers were entering the 200-mile
U.S. fishing zone under cover of darkness or in stormy weather to
fish illegally.
   Seven foreign trawlers, most of them thought to be Japanese,
were videotaped with their nets down 38 miles inside the U.S. zone
off Alaska. The tapes were taken from a private plane chartered by
a fishing industry group in early January.
   Bonker said he was considering legislation that would require
that foreign fishing vessels inform U.S. authorities before they
enter American waters.
   Wolfe said the administration would probably finish formulating
a policy within a month, but said the best deterrent to illegal
foreign fishing might be increased surveillance and enforcement by
the Coast Guard.
</TEXT>
