<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MultipleSlayings     03-09 0545</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Multiple Slayings,0561</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Witnesses Interviewed In Attempt To Identify Two Suspects</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police in three states interviewed witnesses
Wednesday as they tried to identify two men sought in a
cold-blooded rampage that left four people dead, including a woman
whose throat was slit while she struggled with her assailants.
   Another victim, an 85-year-old man, was shot in the back of the
head, and his son was shot in the face. The fourth victim was shot
three times and then dumped by the side of an Arkansas road after
he gave two men a ride, authorities said.
   ``By all indications, it was overkill,'' said Cooke County
Sheriff John Aston, where the first of the victims, a 23-year-old
woman, was found in her Gainesville mobile home.
   Vehicles stolen from the victims turned up in lakes in Oklahoma
and Arkansas, authorities said, and items found with vehicles
linked the four killings.
   ``We do not have a motive at all,'' Aston said.
   ``We don't know where they are, not now,'' said Sgt. Anthony
Hancock of the Collin County sheriff's office. ``I would not say a
search is under way because we don't know where to look. We're
trying to compile information, compile artists' sketches. We're
trying to make an identification on these guys. We just don't know
which way to go.''
   Deana Andrews Woodard was killed Monday morning in her home in
Gainesville, just south of the Texas-Oklahoma line. Aston described
the slaying as cold-blooded.
   ``These people were there the whole time she was bleeding to
death,'' he said. ``There are indications there had been a
struggle. She was hit in the head.''
   Her infant son was in the home but was not harmed. The suspects
stole her gun and apparently drove her car to the Collin County
community of Farmersville, north of Dallas. There, the bodies of
Cecil Floyd Morrison and his son, Cecil Leonard Morrison, 62, were
found Monday night in their home, Hancock said.
   They had been brutally beaten with a tire iron or other tool,
and shot in the head or face, Hancock said.
   The men are believed to have abandonded Mrs. Woodard's car near
Farmersville and to have stolen the Morrisons' pickup truck. Mrs.
Woodard's car has not been recovered.
   They then drove the pickup truck to the Hope-Saratoga, Ark.,
area and drove it into a lake, Hancock said.
   The men went to a home in the area to ask for assistance after
dark Monday, and the fourth victim offered them a ride, Hancock
said.
   The body of Kenneth Olden, 34, of Arkansas, was found about 9
a.m. Tuesday on a rural road outside Saratoga, authorities said.
   ``They left him on a roadside and drove his vehicle back to
Marietta, Oklahoma, where that vehcile was discovered somewhere
before noon Tuesday,'' Hancock said. Marietta is just north of the
Texas-Oklahoma line.
   A checkbook taken from the men in Farmersville, two gold
necklaces and a prescription bottle with Mrs. Woodard's name on it
were found with the vehicle in Arkansas, Hancock said.
   Authorities said they were trying to determine whether the
killings were linked to the robbery by three men of a Seminole,
Okla., bank Monday. The FBI recovered most of the stolen cash in
Muskogee, Okla.
</TEXT>
