<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Dingell-InsiderTrading     03-09 0431</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dingell-Insider Trading,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dingell Says Congress Won't Define Insider Trading</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the House Energy and Commerce
Committee says Congress will not enact a bill to define insider
trading, although the securities industry is seeking such
legislation.
   ``The definition that has developed in case law is clear,'' Rep.
John Dingell, D-Mich., said in a speech this week to the Securities
Industry Association.
   Reporters were not invited to the lobby group's meeting in
Washington on Monday, but Dingell's office released a copy of his
remarks on Wednesday.
   The offense of insider trading has developed over the years
through court and regulatory interpretations of fraud and
securities laws.
   The securities industry has been pushing Congress to write a
definition into the law, arguing that traders need to know
beforehand what constitutes insider trading in order to avoid
violating the law.
   Sens. Donald W. Riegle Jr., D-Mich., and Alfonse D'Amato,
R-N.Y., in June introduced a bill with a definition. They have been
working with the Securities and Exchange Commission, which favors
legislation but has suggested changes in the Senate bill to broaden
the definition.
   However, in the House, Dingell told the lobby group flatly,
``There will be no definition of insider trading.''
   He said his committee is drafting a bill that would ``implement
needed reforms'' and promised ``we will work toward passage this
year.''
   He did not elaborate what reforms would be in the bill, beyond
advising the association that ``you will probably dislike some of
them.''
   Dennis Fitzgibbons, a spokesman for Dingell, said the chairman
favors additional penalties for insider trading. He also wants
harsher treatment for violations of internal ``Chinese wall''
barriers designed to prevent executives in a securities firm
involved in mergers and aquisitions from communicating with traders
in the same firm, Fitzgibbons said.
   Fitzgibbons said Dingell is not philosophically opposed to
legislating a definition, but recognizes the difficulty of getting
Congress to agree on one and is comfortable with the definition
developed by the courts.
   Donald J. Crawford, a senior vice president for the securities
association, said the group has endorsed a statutory definition but
believes there is some validity to Dingell's arguments.
   In a related matter, Dingell critized a bill passed last week by
the Senate Banking Committee that would permit banks to underwrite
most securities, except corporate stocks.
   Dingell said the bill provided insufficient safeguards against
conflicts between banks' role as lenders and what would become
their new role as a securities underwriters.
   The bill ``has emerged ... with firewalls as thin as rice
paper,'' he said.
</TEXT>
