<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Election-WorldReax 1stLd-Writethru a0945 03-09 0701</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Election-World Reax, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0945,0719</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Makes Super Tuesday Splash Overseas</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds, SUBS 15th graf ``A front-page ... in November'' to make clear
that Izvestia is Soviet newspaper. SUBS 20th graf ``But the . ..
this way:'' to show that Le Monde is French newspaper.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK FRITZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush grabbed the lion's share of the overseas headlines
after his string of Super Tuesday victories, with much of the press
portraying him as a low-key Reagan loyalist with one foot in the
White House door.
   ``Why is Bush so popular? The answer comes easily,'' said the
independent tabloid Expressen, Sweden's largest-circulation paper.
``Party people see him as Ronald Reagan's loyal aid _ loyal to the
grave _ and therefore his natural successor.''
   The vice president's Republican primary victories in 16 states
grabbed more media coverage than the more muddled outcomes on the
Democratic side, although Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis got
huge display in his ancestral country, Greece, and Jesse Jackson
drew strong coverage.
   ``Jesse Jackson, the one-time `leftist radical,' has become a
... kingmaker with a strong influence on the Democratic program and
on the ultimate choice of the presidential candidate,'' the
independent Amsterdam newspaper, Het Parool, noted in an editorial.
   Poland's state-run radio, in a commentary read during the midday
news, drew parallels between Bush and Sen. Albert Gore, D-Tenn.
   Gore, it said, ``originates from a well-to-do family, graduated
from elite universities, and his life, including the political one,
has been happy,'' it said.
   ``This moderate conservative from the South describes himself as
the toughest among the Democrats as far as military issues are
concerned. His political profile therefore offers no contrast to
Bush's...''
   Prevailing foreign sentiment attributed Bush's big day to
President Reagan. The British papers seemed ready to announce an
inauguration.
   ``White House Here I Come,'' shouted the the banner headline in
the Standard of London, which ran a photo of an exhilarated Bush
waving to supporters.
   Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole was shown rubbing his brow in a
photograph captioned ``Feeling the Pain.''
   ``By a stunning series of triumphs, grinding his rivals to dust
beneath his chariot wheels in the Super Tuesday primaries, George
Bush emerged almost invincible as the next presidential candidate
of the Republican Party,'' the Standard rhapsodized.
   In West Germany, the Bonn-based newspaper Die Welt said:
``George Bush's impressive victory is without doubt the most
important event of the primary elections.
   ``This was not just a victory for George Bush, it was a triumph
for Ronald Reagan.''
   In Greece, where the Dukakis campaign has been followed closely,
the media trumpeted his victories in five Democratic primaries.
``Dukakis Triumphs, All Consider Him A Certain President,'' said a
banner headline in the conservative daily Messimvrini.
   A front-page article in the Soviet-government newspaper Izvestia
in Moscow said Super Tuesday appears to have decided the Republican
contest, but only raised more questions about who will emerge as
the Democratic contender in November.
   Dukakis, Jackson and Gore ``practically split up among
themselves the states where elections were held,'' the newspaper
said.
   Izvestia quoted ``a prominent Democratic figure who didn't want
his name used'' in speculating that his party might run a ticket
pairing Dukakis with Jackson.
   In contrast with past coverage, reports issued this week by the
official Tass news agency were notable for their balance and
clarity.
   Both Tass and Izvestia noted the poor showings by Republicans
Jack Kemp and Pat Robertson, ``who had been conducting their
campaigns from extreme right positions.''
   But the leftist French daily Le Monde of Paris, in an editorial,
summed up the whole process this way:
   ``It will take hundreds of millions of dollars, thousands of
kilometers, countless hours of television, to realize (that) hopes
have been disappointed, careers destroyed and contestants
hopelessly plunged into debt before there is the slightest idea or
the vaguest program'' put forward by the candidates.
   Le Monde said there was an ideological vacuum on the Democratic
side, with the exception of Jackson and his ``out-of-date
liberalism.''
   Rome's moderate Il Messsaggero, said in its headline: ``Bush Did
It. Beating Dole, He Has Become the Political Heir of Reagan.''
   State-run RAI-TV spent nearly five minutes explaining the
process before giving the results Wednesday morning.
</TEXT>
