<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 1959EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SoilSlurper     03-09 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soil Slurper,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Absorbent Material Helps To Counter Citrus Root Weevils</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An absorbent material called super slurper is
helping tiny worms to kill root weevils that threaten citrus trees,
the Agriculture Department said Wednesday.
   William J. Schroeder, an entomolgist in the department's
Agricultural Research Service, said the super slurper keeps soil
moist so that the microscopic worms, or nematodes, can survive and
kill weevils which chew the tree roots.
   In tests, 60 percent of the weevils were killed, compared with
only 25 percent without the help of the worms. Schroeder said that
weevils can kill up to 30 percent of the trees in a grove if not
controlled.
   The nematodes haven't been used before as a natural weevil
control because they die quickly if soil dries out, Schoeder said.
   Other agency scientists are looking into the use of super
slurper and nematodes to see if they can control pests of corn and
vegetables.
   Agency scientists in Peoria, Ill., invented the cornstarch-based
super slurper 14 years ago. It has been successfully used in dozens
of commercial products, including body powder, medical dressings
and many other items.
   Schroeder, who works at the department's horticultural research
laboratory in Orlando, Fla., said he thought of super slurper in
1985 when he observed nematodes dying in dry soil.
   Companies could mass-produce nematodes and ``package billions of
them alive'' for sale to growers, who then could mix the worms with
super slurper for application on tree roots before planting, he
said.
   For citrus groves already inhabited by the beneficial nematodes,
Schroeder said he is looking into the possibility of injecting
super slurper into the soil with a nozzle.
   The tiny worms, which survive as long as the soil is kept moist,
penetrate the weevils and release lethal bacteria, which don't harm
plants or other organisms, Schroeder said.
</TEXT>
