<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Jackson     03-09 0675</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Returns to Chicago, Predicts Hot Illinois Race</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Pr</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   ss Writer=
   CHICAGO (AP) _ Jesse Jackson returned to his home base on
Wednesday, fresh from his strong showing on Super Tuesday, and
predicted a ``hotly contested race'' in next week's Illinois
primary.
   ``I will do well in Illinois,'' he told reporters. But he also
said he anticipated a tough fight with Illinois Sen. Paul Simon,
who sat out the Super Tuesday primaries and caucuses across 20
states.
   Jackson reaped more than 300 delegates, coming in second overall
to Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis.
   Jackson placed first in the popular vote for the day, with 27
percent to 26 percent each for Dukakis and Sen. Albert Gore Jr. of
Tennessee.
   But that was a total for all the states. The delegates are
alloted state-by-state depending on the votes each candidate wins
in each state, not how many they win regionwide.
   Jackson's campaign staff pointed to exit polls showing he had
won the Hispanic vote, the women's vote and the 18-to-21 age group.
   The exit polls indicated Jackson won about 95 percent of the
black vote and about 10 percent of the white vote across the Super
Tuesday states.
   Jackson came in third in Texas, and to put the best face on that
showing in a state where he campaigned vigorously, his aides said
he had spent only $30,000 on TV there, a fraction of what was spent
by his opponents.
   Campaign official Steve Cobble said polling showed that Jackson
did well in the places that he appeared personally, as in the case
of Beaumont, Texas, where he went to show solidarity with striking
oil workers.
   Jackson talked repeatedly Wednesday about how he was outspent by
the multi-million dollar TV campaigns of Dukakis, Gore and Rep.
Richard Gephardt of Missouri.
   ``My opponents have money, and money is powerful, but we the
people are more powerful,'' he told a rally of plant workers in the
Chicago suburb of Cicero. ``We get stronger every day.''
   His campaign manager, Gerald Austin, said the Jackson campaign
will be buying TV ads as new money comes in. Jackson spent $100,000
on TV in the Super Tuesday contests.
   In South Carolina, Jackson's boyhood state where voting occurs
Saturday, Austin said the TV budget is about $20,000. In Illinois,
Austin anticipates a total budget of $200,000, with about $30,000
for television.
   Jackson has been a political force in Chicago for many years
starting when he worked with the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. for
open housing and other civil rights causes. Jackson makes his home
here, and his Operation PUSH, People United to Serve Humanity, is
based here.
   Upon arriving home Wednesday, Jackson went to Cicero to speak at
an outdoor rally of about 150 General Electric workers who are
upset because of plans to close down a refrigerator plant where
more than 1,000 people work.
   ``Jesse, help us save our jobs,'' their placards read.
   Jackson said he was challenging GE to meet with workers and him
to discuss ways of converting the plant to other uses.
   Earlier, at a news conference in Houston, he said the primary
elections are muting Democratic Party establishment doubts about
the viability of his campaign.
   But he said many white Democratic politicians who were elected
with support from black voters he helped bring into the party had
failed to endorse him.
   ``It would be fair to say that many of them had reasonable
doubts about the success of our campaign,'' he said. ``In these
elections we are removing those doubts. ... Our coalition
represents the future of the Democratic Party.''
   He said white officials must assess not only who can win, but
which candidate ``can help them.''
   He decried the negative ads his opponents ran against one
another, and said the Democrats must not ``self-destruct'' their
chances for winning the White House in November.
   Although Jackson so far has not been attacked by his rivals,
Austin said the Jackson camp is prepared to face ``slings and
arrows'' now that he is amassing delegates.
</TEXT>
