<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Texas     03-09 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Texas,0400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Supporters Hope Texas Win Dispels `Wimp' Image; Dukakis
Prevails</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH SHANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis organized early and spent big to
tell Texas voters that the economic program dubbed the
``Massachusetts Miracle'' could mean jobs and tax breaks for them.
He succeeded, convincingly.
   Supporters of Vice President George Bush, meanwhile, said they
hoped the former Texas resident's sweep of all 111 state Republican
delegates on Super Tuesday dispelled the ``wimp'' issue.
   ``He's the best of what Texas is,'' said Margaret Wolf, who
served as Bush's secretary in 1977-78. Bush, a Massachusetts native
who keeps a voting address at a Houston hotel, was ``gutsy'' for
starting his own oil business in Texas in 1953, she said.
   Dukakis, who says he helped spur his state's economic revival as
governor, ``ran a good campaign'' to defeat Jesse Jackson by 33
percent to 24 percent of the primary vote, said George Christian, a
former press secretary to Lyndon Johnson and an Austin political
consultant.
   ``He had the strategy of finding his constituency and organizing
it. His constituency was the Hispanics and liberals. That was a
sufficient number to put him at the top,'' Christian said.
   In contrast to a Dukakis advertising blitz that cost hundreds of
thousands of dollars, Jackson spent about $20,000 on Texas ads but
used volunteers to build his No. 2 spot among Democrats, said his
campaign secretary, Steve Coble.
   With 6,534 of 6,933 precincts or 94 percent reporting, Dukakis
had 533,076 votes, Jackson had 387,440, Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore
received 334,365 or 14 percent and Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt
finished with 225,770 or 14 percent.
   Dukakis earned an estimated 45 delegates and Jesse Jackson was
expected to capture 44. Gore had 26 delegates and Gephardt tallied
9.
   In the Republican primary, with 5,238 of 5,616 precincts or 93
percent reporting, Bush amassed 588,081 votes or 64 percent.Former
TV evangelist Pat Robertson was a distant second with 141,444 votes
and Kansas Sen. Bob Dole had 125,702 or 14 percent.
   In other races, Democratic Sen. Lloyd Bentsen easily won
renomination in his bid for a fourth term. Top Republican
challengers Beau Boulter, who gave up his congressional seat for
the Senate race, and Wes Gilbreath, a Houston investor making his
first race for a political office, will meet in a runoff on April
12.
</TEXT>
