<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0434</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heavy Rain in Louisiana, Washington; Record Warmth in N. Dakota</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A slow-moving cold front set off showers Wednesday through the
Ohio and Tennessee valleys and along the Gulf Coast, where more
than 3 inches of rain drenched central Louisiana in 24 hours.
   Heavy rain also fell in the Pacific Northwest, and up to 5
inches of snow were expected in Washington's Cascade and Olympic
mountains.
   Temperatures climbed to record highs in North Dakota, while much
of Texas had readings in the 60s and 70s.
   Rainshowers were scattered from western New England into the
upper Ohio Valley and from Virginia through the eastern Carolinas
into northern Florida.
   Northeast Michigan got a dusting of snow.
   In Louisiana, more than an 3 inches of rain were measured in 24
hours at Oakdale, Bunkie, Eunice and Alexandria. Lake Charles got
more than an inch.
   More than 3 inches were recorded in 24 hours in Washington at
Spada Lake and Verlot.
   Snow and blowing dust hindered travel across northwest Nevada,
reducing visibility to less than a mile. Winds gusted to 36 mph at
Tonopah, Nev.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 1 p.m. EST
included 0.70 inch at McComb, Miss., 0.65 inch at Gainesville,
Fla., and Charleston, S.C., 0.49 inch at Crescent City, Calif.
   Temperatures at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 26 degrees at Limestone,
Maine, Gunnison, Colo., and Elko, Nev., to 83 degrees at Avon Park,
Fla. The morning low for the nation was 5 degrees below zero at
Gunnison, Colo.
   Record high temperatures included 58 in Bismarck, N.D., 60 in
Dickinson, N.D., and 56 at Williston, N.D.
   Thursday's forecast called for rainshowers along the middle and
southern Atlantic Coast, with showers and a few thunderstorms
across the Florida Peninsula; rain across the northeast Plains and
the central Intermountain region; snow across the northern Rockies
and high Plains into the Colorado Rockies, and gusty wind from the
desert Southwest into the southern Rockies and from the Carolinas
into northern Florida.
   High temperatures were expected to reach the 50s or 60s across
much of the nation, with readings in the 30s and 40s from the
northern Plateau and central Intermountain region through the
northern Rockies, the northern Plains, the Great Lakes and upper
Ohio Valley into New England; in the 70s across the southern coast
of California, the southern Plateau, the southern Plains and the
lower Mississippi Valley as well as much of Florida, and in the low
to mid-80s across western and southern Texas.
</TEXT>
