<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CitiesConference     03-09 0541</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cities Conference,0556</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>International Conference on Cities Opens</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The world's cities must be more than
simply places to do business: They must strive to meet the higher
human aspirations of their citizens, experts attending an
international conference on cities agreed Wednesday.
   ``It's more than a tax base. It's more than buildings. It's
aiming to make the city enjoyable for those citizens who have the
least,'' Charleston Mayor Joseph P. Riley Jr. told the
International Conference on Making Cities Liveable.
   About 300 experts from around the globe are attending the
conference which runs through this weekend. Social policy and
values as they apply to cities were the topics of the opening
session.
   ``If we can give homes rather than housing projects, if we can
create types of beauty everyone can enjoy ... then we are on our
way to making cities liveable,'' said Riley, who showed slides of
rehabilitation and restoration projects he said has given
Charleston an international reputation.
   Eduardo Salzano, a professor at the University of Venice in
Italy, said modern cities are confronted with ``a cluttered mass of
individual interests.''
   He suggested planning should be in the hands of local boards
that have adequate citizen input, and residents of cities must
agree ownership of urban land does not automatically give the owner
the right to build anything he wants.
   ``A sense of place is a human hunger'' which many modern cities
don't satisfy, said Don Robert Johnson, a New York scholar. He
added that ``individuals without a sense of history are incapable
of planning the present and the future in an informed manner.''
   The mayor of Erlangen, West Germany, Dietmar Hahlweg, said
cities need strong planning authority and the right to take land
when needed for public purposes.
   Cities also need enlightened leadership and ``people who have
the necessary knowledge and have a feeling for the wishes, needs
and problems of the people,'' he said.
   Planners must also consider the needs of the elderly and
children, said Suzanne Lennard, one of the organizers of the
conference.
   She said liveable cities have some sort of unity. Cities in the
United States ``have grown cancerously'' with a wide separation of
shopping areas and neighborhoods and ``a lack of order or reason in
the sequence of streets and places,'' she said.
   ``A community cannot be said to exist in a series of pockets of
persons wishing to know only those in their own group and shunning
contact with others,'' she said.
   William Whyte of the American Conservation Association in New
York suggested many American cities fear ``undesirables'' and
``bustle with distrust'' of some of their citizens.
   He noted that in some cities, park benches are cut short to make
it hard for people to sleep on them. In other metropolitan areas,
it's virtually impossible to find a public rest room in the center
of the city, he said.
   In some large downtown development projects featuring hotels or
shopping arcades, benches are omitted to discourage
``undesirables,'' he said.
   Many such projects are financed in part through tax money, he
said.
   ``These things the public has an equity in and it should be
mandatory they can be used by the public,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880309-0298 </DOCNO>
