<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Delegates     03-09 0610</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Delegates,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prospects Dim For Democrat To Lock Up Nomination During Primary
Season</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democratic presidential candidates on
Wednesday found themselves stuck in a logjam of delegates in which
nobody was likely to lock up the party's nomination when the
primaries end in June.
   ``Mathematically and politically this process is in gridlock,''
said Terry Michael, spokesman for Illinois Sen. Paul Simon, who
suffered a shutout in Super Tuesday's round of primaries and
caucuses.
   Simon, who held just 35.5 delegates both before and after
Tuesday's balloting, is banking on nobody being able to gain the
2,082 delegates needed to win the Democratic presidential
nomination when the primaries conclude on June 7, with California
and New Jersey, two of the largest states with a total of 423
delegates at stake.
   ``The person or persons with the greatest potential to negotiate
his way to a first-ballot victory will be the candidate who is
hottest at the end,'' Michael said.
   The odds are growing longer that any candidate can come up with
the magic number needed to win on the first ballot at the
Democratic convention in Atlanta.
   The Democrats have yet to allocate 2,524 of their national
convention delegates, and another 258.65 delegates list themselves
as uncommitted. Thus the available pool of delegates to be won
between now and early June would be 2,782.65.
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, who was leading the field of
Democratic candidates with 456.5 delegates, needs to win another
1625.5 delegates to wrap up the presidential nomionation. Or, put
another way, he has to win more than 58 percent of all the
delegates that are still left to be won _ roughly twice as well as
he's done so far.
   Dukakis was followed in the delegate count by Rev. Jesse Jackson
with 395.55 and Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore with 346.8.
   The three-way tie in the Democratic race prompted former
President Jimmy Carter to observe that ``I think it's accurate to
say the chances are less likely that one of the candidates will
arrive in Atlanta with a clear majority.''
   New York Gov. Mario Cuomo said Wednesday he wanted to see his
party hold a ``quiet convention,'' although he conceded it would be
difficult for any of the current candidates to secure a
first-ballot victory based on results of the primaries and caucuses.
   Cuomo said he had talked to Democratic National Committee
Chairman Paul Kirk about the problem last week.
   ``I believe what you, Paul Kirk, should do is try, right after
California and New Jersey, the last primaries, to take whoever is
ahead and make that person the concensus choice,'' Cuomo said as he
recalled the conversation.
   Michael said if no candidate holds a majority by the time the
primaries conclude, the rule of conscience that binds delegates to
the candidates will begin to bend and break.
   However, Jude Barry, an aide to Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt's
presidential campaign, disagreed, saying, ``I think there's going
to be loyalty and commitment. We're prepared to protect what we
have, as I'm sure the other candidates will as well.''
   Gephardt, who had 143 delegates after Super Tuesday, is hoping
to hang on with a strong showing in the Michigan caucuses on March
26 and the congressional Democratic caucuses on April 19 and 20.
Gephardt is planning on winning big when his House colleagues pick
210 of their own to be national convention delegates. Another 43
delegates will be picked by Senate Democrats.
   ``Our hand certainly will not be weak with that wild card,''
Barry said.
   Simon, meanwhile, is hoping to score a victory next Tuesday in
his home state of Illinois.
</TEXT>
