<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Unrest 1stLd-Writethru a0982 03-09 0630</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Unrest, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0982,0644</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Meets With Ethnic Leaders to Discuss Unrest</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4 grafs for grafs 5-6 pvs: `The Tass ...' to UPDATE with
report of meeting in Yerevan.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev and other Kremlin officials
met Wednesday with leaders of the republics of Armenia and
Azerbaijan to discuss how to resolve ethnic unrest that has killed
at least 32 people, Tass said.
   The report said party leaders Kyamran Bagirov of Azerbaijan and
Karen Demirchyan of Armenia met with the Soviet leader, Soviet
President Andrei A. Gromyko, Premier Nikolai I. Ryzhkov and two
other influential Politburo members, Yegor K. Ligachev and
Alexander N. Yakovlev.
   The conference involving the party's top echelon illustrated the
Kremlin's concern over the ethnic strife that has cracked the
facade of cohesion among the Soviet Union's more than 100
nationalities.
   In its report on the meeting at the party's Central Committee
headquarters, Tass said the situation in the republics ``is
returning to normal, although it continues to have its
difficulties.''
   Meanwhile, an Armenian who described himself as a city official
loyal to the Soviet government called The Associated Press from the
Armenian capital of Yerevan to report that city officials from
throughout the republic had gathered Wednesday to appeal to
authorities in Moscow for support.
   ``This is not a nationalist or an extremist action,'' said
Gamlet Kocharyan, who said he was a member of the governing council
of the city of Kafan. He said the Armenians' effort to annex a
section of the neighboring republic of Azerbaijan was legal and
deserved the central government's attention.
   He said the appeal was adopted unanimously by 1,500 delegates at
the meeting in Yerevan and would be sent to Moscow. It also asked
the national party Central Committee to reprimand Soviet media for
inaccurate and incomplete reporting on the ethnic disturbances, he
said.
   The Tass report on the Kremlin meeting, which was the top item
on the national news program ``Vremya,'' said public order was
being observed and that schools and businesses were open in
Azerbaijan and Armenia.
   Tass said the officials discussed ``the situation taking shape
in these republics in connection with the events in
Nagorno-Karabakh.''
   Nagorno-Karabakh is an Armenian-dominated region of Azerbaijan
that Armenians want to be annexed to their republic.
   Tensions between Armenians and Azeris erupted in violence Feb.
28 in the Azerbaijani city of Sumgait. Foreign Ministry spokesman
Gennady I. Gerasimov said 32 people were killed in the rioting.
   At a news briefing, Gerasimov said ``the situation is normal,
but passions are still running high since people still remember
what happened.''
   The Soviet government has blamed the killings on ``hooligans''
provoked by rumors of ethnic turmoil elsewhere. But some Armenian
activists claim the death toll is much higher and that the violence
was instigated by Azeris out of ethnic hatred.
   Gorbachev issued an appeal last month to both ethnic groups to
cease fighting and work together to resolve the territorial dispute.
   Tass said the Armenian and Azeri officials who met with
Gorbachev declared their peoples' support for an orderly approach
to determining the fate of Nagorno-Karabakh.
   Earlier, Armenian nationalists called on the Politburo to
protect their countrymen from attacks by Azeris and said they plan
a general strike later this week.
   Hovik Vassilian, a nationalist in Yerevan, said Armenians fear
their Azeri neighbors will resort to violence during a March 18-23
holiday observed by Shiite Moslems.
   Azeris are predominantly Shiite Moslem, while most Armenians are
Christian.
   Vassilian also said that hundreds of thousands of Armenians
staged a demonstration Tuesday in Yerevan to mourn countrymen
killed in the ethnic turmoil.
   Gerasimov confirmed that a demonstration took place at Yerevan's
memorial to Armenian victims of the 1915 Turkish invasion, but said
he did not know how many people participated.
</TEXT>
