<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Panama     03-09 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Panama,0462</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panama Ambassador Waives Diplomatic Immunity Over Raid</HEAD>
<HEAD>WWith AM-Panama-Future, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bowing to a British demand, the Panamanian
ambassador agreed to waive his diplomatic immunity Wednesday and be
questioned by police over a raid he authorized on his country's
consulate, the embassy said.
   ``We haven't done anything wrong,'' embassy spokesman Geronimo
de Obaldia said of the Monday night raid, in which British security
guards hired by the embassy crashed a Land Rover through the glass
doors of Panama's London consulate and occupied it.
   ``No one was hurt, there was some glass broken and that's it,''
de Obaldia told The Associated Press.
   An embassy statement said Ambassador Guillermo Vega told the
Foreign Office in a letter Wednesday he ``and relevant members of
his staff ... are ready to be interviewed by the authorities in
respect of the events of March 7 at the consulate.''
   The Foreign Office, however, considered Vega's response
``unclear and inadequate,'' summoned him for the third time in two
days and gave him 24 hours to provide a ``definite response,'' said
a spokesman, who under British procedure declined to be identified.
   Vega supports Panamanian military leader Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega, who arranged the ouster of President Eric Delvalle on Feb.
26. Consul Eduardo Arango, whose Fleet Street offices were seized,
is loyal to Delvalle.
   The Foreign Office had set a deadline for the Panamanians to
waive diplomatic immunity and hinted that Vega might be expelled if
he refused.
   De Obaldia told the AP the embassy announcement meant the
ambassador waived diplomatic immunity for himself and other
diplomats.
   Under international law, diplomats cannot be charged with
criminal offenses or questioned by police unless they waive
immunity.
   Besides Vega, the Foreign Office said police want to question
embassy counselor Jorge E. Constantino, who allegedly accompanied
the raiders or was nearby, and any other diplomats involved.
   Seven Britons employed by the security firm which Vega hired for
the raid were arrested and charged with public order offenses. They
have no diplomatic protection.
   Panama's ambassador to the European Economic Community, Angel.
E. Riera, also a Delvalle loyalist, meanwhile said Noriega
supporters broke into his office in Strasbourg, France, on
Wednesday.
   Riera said the raiders, led by a Panamanian colonel, smashed the
office door, searched for money and left when they found none.
   The tough British response to the London raid underlined
Conservative government insistence that London streets not be
turned into battlegrounds for internal disputes in foreign
countries.
   Control of Panamana's Washington embassy is also in dispute
following Noriega's takeover.
   Delvalle was ousted hours after demanding that Noriega resign
following his February indictment in Florida on drug trafficking
charges.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
