<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Soviet-Mideast 1stLd-Writethru a0958 03-09 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Soviet-Mideast, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0958,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Official Going To Moscow For Talks On Mideast</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 3rd graf bgng ``Murphy's talks'' to include full
reference to Shultz.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top State Department official headed for
Moscow Wednesday to explain to Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard
Shevardnadze what the United States is doing to get peace talks
started in the Middle East.
   The State Department said that Assistant Secretary of State
Richard Murphy left Washington Tuesday night headed for Moscow,
with a brief stopover in Brussels to brief the U.S. NATO allies on
the American Mideast peace plan.
   Murphy's talks in Moscow are designed to prepare Shevardnadze
for his visit to Washington on March 22, when he and Secretary of
State George P. Shultz will discuss how best to advance the Mideast
initiative.
   The two men already discussed the Mideast situation when Shultz
visited Moscow last month prior to undertaking a shuttle between
Jordan, Egypt and Israel to present his plan.
   The plan reportedly calls for Israel and its Arab neighbors to
launch talks by May 1 on a three-year autonomy period for the 1.5
million Palestinians living under Israeli occupation. The sides
would begin talks on a long-term solution to the occupied West Bank
and Gaza Strip in December.
   The United States is seeking Soviet support for the plan in an
effort to enlist the backing of the Arabs, especially those closely
allied with the Kremlin like Syria.
   The Shultz plan calls for the Soviets to join England, France,
China and the United States in overseeing the talks.
   Murphy is also scheduled to stop in Rome, Paris and Bonn as part
of the U.S. effort to ensure a broad base of support for the
initiative which was sparked by three months of Israeli-Palestinian
clashes which have left more than 80 Arabs dead.
   Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir is due in Washington next
week, but he is not expected to bring an Israeli response to his
plan, despite such a demand from Shultz.
   Shamir, leader of the right-wing Likud bloc, objects to an
international conference out of concern that such a forum will
pressure Israel into giving up occupied lands.
   Instead, Shamir will propose an agreement with Jordan on a
step-by-step plan for implementing self-rule quickly in a limited
area of the West Bank or Gaza.
</TEXT>
