<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dole 2ndLd-Writethru a1002 03-09 0786</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dole, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a1002,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dole Says It's Now ``Up to Illinois'' to Revive His Campaign</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs, Bush telegram refusing debates; picks up
10th graf pvs, bgng: Dole contended</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY MASSEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican presidential candidate Bob Dole,
conceding he must win in Illinois, renewed his call for a series of
one-on-one debates in the state with Vice President George Bush.
But Bush rebuffed the request, saying it was time to look ahead to
the general election.
   ``I respectfully decline your invitation to debate in
Illinois,'' Bush said in a telegram to Dole, reminding his rival
that the two have already been in six GOP debates together. ``I
believe it is now time to look ahead to the issues which
distinguish us from the Democrats.''
   ``Good luck,'' added the vice president, who trounced Dole in
the big round of Super Tuesday contests. Dole was all to mindful of
that as he kicked off his Illinois effort on Wednesday.
   ``I've got to win Illinois,'' he said. ``And if I can do that
then ... I think people will pause to reflect.''
   Dole spoke outside a hospital where he had surgery 40 years ago
for crippling wounds suffered in World War II. He said he came to
visit Wesley Hospital, now part of the Northwestern Memorial
Hospital complex, because ``I walked out of these doors and started
back on the road to recovery.''
   ``After taking a bath yesterday, I've got to start down that
road again,'' Dole said.
   Bush won 16 of 17 Republican contests on Tuesday, while Dole won
none.
   The Kansas senator said ``it would not be easy'' to overtake
Bush but he maintained that he could do it ``the hard way _ one
state at a time.''
   At Northwestern Law School, Dole renewed his call for Bush to
participate in a round of Lincoln-Douglas style debates without
moderators.
   ``I just appeal to George Bush. Here's a chance, George, to
finish me off right here in Illinois,'' Dole said.
   Dole contended that past debates featured too many candidates
and prevented a clear comparison of his record with the vice
president's.
   He also began airing a TV commercial in which he links Bush to
U.S. arms sales to Iran.
   Dole projected a confident, come-from-behind theme and
repeatedly told audiences that he was a ``strong person'' who had
overcome past personal difficulties.
   ``I'm here after a rather difficult day,'' Dole told the law
students. ``I feel like I've just taken the finals, and I didn't
flunk but I didn't do too well either.''
   Dole aides contend that the senator can survive if he wins a
large share of the 82 Republican delegates at stake in the March 15
Illinois primary. But even if he does well in Illinois, he would
face an uphill fight with Bush all the way to the nominating
convention in August.
   Asked if Illinois is a do-or-die contest for Dole, Thomas Rath,
a senior campaign strategist, said: ``If it's not, it'll do until
the real thing comes along. We have to view this campaign in short
bursts, and clearly the next burst for us is Illinois.''
   Assessing the impact of Tuesday's defeats, William Brock, Dole's
campaign chairman, would only say: ``That causes a lot of problems
for us.''
   Rath said the Dole campaign will begin to step up its attacks on
Bush with television ads to start running on Thursday in some
areas, drawing a comparisons between Bush and Dole's records.
Similar ads were used in the Super Tuesday states.
   In addition, Rath said the campaign is considering a new TV spot
to raise the ``electability issue.'' Dole frequently cites polls
that he says show him the strongest GOP nominee against any
Democrat in the general election.
   By focusing on issues, the Dole campaign can ``cut the umbilical
cord'' that links Bush to President Reagan and gives him a
popularity boost among Republicans who favor the administration,
Rath said.
   Dole campaigned in the Chicago area on Wednesday beneath leaden
skies and in a damp chill _ weather that seemed to match the gloomy
aftermath of Super Tuesday for his campaign.
   But in contrast to his defeat in New Hampshire, when Dole
angrily lashed out at Bush, the Kansas senator tried to project an
upbeat image and repeatedly declared that he was ``on the road to
recovery'' in Illinois.
   At a suburban commuter train station, Dole shook hands with a
few people as they hurried off to work.
   One man, who identified himself as a Dole supporter but declined
to give his name, summed up the political landscape for a reporter:
``I guess it's all over for him unless he wins Illinois. That's too
bad.''
</TEXT>
