<1ST_LINE>r i AM-PLO-WorldCourt     03-09 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PLO-World Court,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>World Court Orders Hearings in PLO Office Dispute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The World Court on Wednesday
ordered hearings on a United Nations attempt to block the United
States from shutting down the PLO's office in New York.
   Anti-terrorism legislation passed by the U.S. Congress on Dec.
22 calls for the Palestine Liberation Organization U.N. observer
mission to be closed by March 21.
   The United States defied a 143-1 U.N. vote last month that
called for the dispute to be submitted to an independent
arbitration panel.
   U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar last week asked
the court for a ruling on whether the United States has a right to
refuse arbitration, which is called for in the 1947 headquarters
treaty.
   On Wednesday, the 15-member World Court ordered hearings April
11 in the case.
   The court also ordered the United Nations and the United States
to submit written arguments by March 25. Other U.N. members are
also entitled to file arguments, a court statement said.
   The World Court, formally known as the International Court of
Justice, has no enforcement powers and depends on voluntary
adherence to its rulings.
   The PLO was granted non-voting observer status at the United
Nations in 1974 and has maintained an office in New York ever since.
   The U.S. State Department and the United Nations say the United
States is obliged by the 1947 headquarters treaty to allow the
observer mission to remain. But Attorney General Edwin Meese III
reportedly said he plans to enforce the measure anyway. He is
expected to announce his decision later this month.
</TEXT>
