<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 1855EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Candidates-Wright     03-09 0245</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Candidates-Wright,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Speaker To Democratic Candidates: Tone Down Negative Ads</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, said he had
sent telegrams Wednesday congratulating all the Democratic
candidates who won delegates on Super Tuesday and asking them to
eschew negative ads from now on in the campaign.
   ``Candidates with viable ideas and strong ideals do not need to
rely on negative campaigning which only tarnishes and muddles the
processes of democracy,'' Wright said.
   Wright said the use of negative ads had become a ``vogue,''
intensified by the short time between the New Hampshire primaries
and Tuesday's 20-state extravaganza.
   The rush left ``no time to make a sensible ... appeal,'' Wright
said, and led candidates to ``succumb to the wicked blandishments
of those in the advertising fraternity'' who specialize in attack
ads.
   Super Tuesday, Wright said, ``put a great premium on having an
enormous amount of money to spend in little quickie TV spots'' and
denied candidates the chance to be evaluated by voters on the
merits of their ideas.
   He said Rep. Richard Gephardt, who was strongly supported by a
long list of his House Democratic colleagues ``basically ran out of
money'' but had not been eliminated from the race.
   House Majority Leader Thomas Foley, D-Wash., agreed that the
idea of a large regional primary could use at least some
fine-tuning.
   ``It might be better if Super Tuesday were a little smaller and
not quite so soon after New Hampshire,'' Foley said.
</TEXT>
