<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New in first eight grafs to UPDATE with Torrijos statement,
resignation of envoy to Mexico; Picks up 6th graf pvs bgng: They
said ..., editing to conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nephew of Omar Torrijos, national hero in
Panama for negotiating the Panama Canal treaties, disclosed
Wednesday he has broken with his country's military-dominated
government, accusing it of plunging Panama into a political crisis.
   Meanwhile, the Panamanian Embassy made public the copy of a
letter by Panama's Ambassador to Mexico, Emilia Arosemena
Vallarino, in which she announced her resignation because she was
``in disagreement with political events'' in her country. She had
served in Mexico for 18 years and was dean of the diplomatic corps
there.
   Santiago Torrijos, about 40 years old, left his post Tuesday as
chief of Panama's consulate in Los Angeles and flew to an
undisclosed location in Washington to join forces loyal to ousted
President Eric Arturo Delvalle.
   Telephone calls to the consulate Wednesday afternoon were not
answered.
   Santiago Torrijos is the son of a brother of Omar Torrijos, the
former head of the Panamanian National Guard, now known as the
Panamanian Defense Forces.
   He said in a type-written statement distributed to news
organizations Wednesday night the Defense Forces have not lived up
to a pledge made by Omar Torrijos to establish constitutional
democracy in Panama.
   ``The political, financial, moral and social crisis in Panama
must be rectified,'' he said.
   Diplomatic sources, insisting on anonymity, said Santiago
Torrijos is the first member of the Torrijos family to break ranks
with Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, the commander of the Defense
Forces who orchestrated Delvalle's ouster two weeks ago.
   They said the defection is considered significant because of the
close identification of the Torrijos family with the Defense Forces.
   Word of the defection came as the Reagan administration prepared
for a high-level inter-agency meeting Thursday at which a series of
economic sanctions against Panama will be considered.
   U.S. officials, who asked not to be identified, said that it is
almost certain that the United States will withhold a $6.5 million
payment due to Panama on March 15 for canal-related operations.
   Also being considered are measures that will have the effect of
making some Panamanian products less competitive in U.S. markets.
State Department figures show that Panama's U.S. exports totaled
$342 million last year, but Commerce Department statistics list
that category at $388 million.
   Meanwhile, White House chief of staff Howard Baker denied
Wednesday that the United States is planning an invasion of Panama,
saying American troops there are merely holding regularly scheduled
training exercises.
   ``Panama is the site of National Guard training exercises and
has been for years,'' Baker said. ``And as I understand it, the
Rhode Island National Guard is now holding regularly scheduled
exercises in Panama.
   ``And certainly if the United States was going to invade Panama,
it wouldn't be with the Rhode Island National Guard. So it simply
is not so. It has no connection at all,'' Baker said, talking with
reporters at the White House after seeing President Reagan off on a
trip to Indiana.
   Jorge Abadia, Panama's foreign minister, on Tuesday accused the
United States of conducting ``the prelude of an armed invasion'' by
staging military exercises along the Panama Canal.
   As part of his effort to survive mounting protests in Panama
against the new government, Noriega from time to time has invoked
Omar Torrijos' name.
   Omar Torrijos was killed in a plane crash in July 1981. A former
deputy of Noriega, Col. Roberto Diaz Herrera, caused a political
stir in Panama last June by alleging that Noriega was responsible
for Torrijos' death by arranging to place a bomb aboard the
aircraft.
   Torrijos, the key figure in Panamanian politics from 1968 until
his death, is a revered figure in Panama for persuading President
Jimmy Carter to agree to a treaty that will revert the Panama Canal
to Panamanian control at the end of 1999.
   Santiago Torrijos is said to be an engineer who headed a
government-owned cement plant in Panama before becoming consul
general in Los Angeles about four years ago.
   Delvalle attempted to fire Noriega on Feb. 25 but was fired
himself hours later by the National Assembly, which is dominated by
Noriega loyalists.
   The Reagan administration has refused to recognize the successor
government, nominally headed by President Manuel Solis Palma, and
instead continues to recognize Delvalle as the constitutional
authority in Panama. Noriega has been indicted by two federal grand
juries on drug smuggling charges.
</TEXT>
