<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LaRouche-NBC     03-09 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-LaRouche-NBC,0460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Upholds Order For Outtakes Of NBC Interview</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-LaRouche Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court Wednesday upheld an order
requiring NBC to surrender outtakes of an interview with a former
consultant for Lyndon LaRouche who said a top LaRouche aide
discussed killing Henry Kissinger.
   The 1st U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, which also affirmed a
contempt citation against the network, said videotape of the entire
interview should be given to the judge at the trial of LaRouche,
six aides and five political organizations.
   LaRouche, a candidate for the 1988 Democratic presidential
nomination, is charged with conspiring to obstruct a federal grand
jury investigation into an alleged scheme to finance his 1984
campaign through loan and credit-card fraud.
   Floyd Abrams, an attorney for NBC, said no decision had been
made on whether to appeal. He said the ruling ``does not sufficient
recognize the First Amendment rights of broadcasters.''
   NBC had contended that surrendering outtakes, or portions of the
interview not broadcast, violated a First Amendment right against
judicial intrusion into newsgathering and editorial decisions.
   U.S. District Judge Robert E. Keeton ruled in December that the
rights of the defendants to access to the interview with Forrest
Lee Fick outweighed NBC's rights.
   ``At stake in the defendants' side of the equation are their
constitutional rights to a fair trial,'' the appeals court wrote in
concurring with Keeton, who planned to review the tape and
determine which portions, if any, were relevant to the case.
   Keeton had issued a similar order requiring CBS to surrender
outtakes of an interview with another LaRouche aide. CBS complied.
   Fick, of Reading, Pa., worked as a LaRouche security consultant
and is expected to be called as a witness at the trial.
   NBC interviewed Fick for 100 minutes and in April 1986 aired a
one-minute portion in which Fick said he and LaRouche aide Paul
Goldstein discussed a plot to assassinate Kissinger, the former
secretary of state.
   Goldstein is a defendant in the case now on trial.
   Defense lawyers argued for access to the entire NBC interview.
They contend Fick was among scores of operatives planted in
LaRouche organizations by the FBI and CIA to gather information and
cripple LaRouche's fund-raising network.
   The contempt citation against NBC carried with it a $500-a-day
fine, which Keeton had stayed pending the appeal.
   LaRouche has attended most of the trial since in began in
December. He was allowed to travel last week to West Germany, where
his wife lives, to have surgery for glaucoma.
   He is accused of ordering fund-raisers to flee the country and
destroy records to stymie the grand jury investigation.
</TEXT>
