<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Arkansas     03-09 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Arkansas,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush and Gore Win Arkansas Primaries</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL SIMMONS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr. ran
strongly throughout Arkansas to rack up nearly double the number of
votes cast for Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis in the Democratic
presidential primary.
   With all 2,762 precincts reporting, Gore had 184,729 votes or 37
percent; Dukakis had 93,532 votes or 19 percent; Jesse Jackson had
85,047 votes or 17 percent, and Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt had
59,471 votes or 12 percent.
   In the Republican race, Vice President George Bush had 31,327
votes or 47 percent; Kansas Sen. Bob Dole had 17,359 votes or 26
percent; former television evangelist Pat Robertson had 12,232
votes or 18 percent, and New York Rep. Jack Kemp had 3,405 votes or
5 percent.
   Based on those results, Gore would capture 19 Democratic
delegates, Dukakis 10 and Jackson 9. Bush would get 15 GOP
delegates, Dole 7, Robertson 5 and Kemp 1.
   Also on the ballot, U.S. Rep. Bill Alexander crushed the bid of
political consultant Darrell Glascock in the race for the
Democratic nomination for Congress in the 1st District. Alexander
won by a 2-1 margin. There is no Republican nominee.
   Dukakis was the choice of much of the state's Democratic
establishment, but Gore had strong support that ranged from farm
districts to cities throughout the state. Jackson wiped out his
Democratic opposition in areas where blacks were in the majority,
but finished third or worse in most other places.
   Arkansas had a large voter turnout for the primary election;
more than 55,000 people cast ballots, roughly double the state's
norm.
</TEXT>
