<1ST_LINE>r i AM-ManitobaVote     03-09 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Manitoba Vote,0451</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Premier Quits, Calls Election After Losing Confidence Vote</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Howard Pawley of Manitoba,
head of the only socialist government in North America, resigned as
leader of his party and called a provincial election Wednesday
after losing a vote of confidence.
   Pawley, 53, leader of the New Democratic Party, had ruled with a
one-seat majority until the unexpected defeat in a budget vote
Tuesday night.
   When renegade New Democrat Jim Walding sided with the
opposition, the government fell by 28 votes to 27.
   Pawley, elected to a second five-year term in 1986, waited
overnight before meeting with his party and announcing his decision
to call an April 26 election in Manitoba, a large central province
with just over 1 million people.
   An election was expected, in accordance with Canadian
parliamentary tradition following defeat on a budget vote.
   But Pawley stunned colleagues by also announcing his plan to
step down after nine years as leader. A leadership convention will
select a successor who will be thrust immediately into the election
campaign.
   ``This would not have been a time of my choosing,'' said the
premier.
   There was speculation Pawley might switch to federal politics by
running for the New Democrats in the next national election, due
within 18 months.
   Ed Broadbent, national leader of the New Democratic Party, said
in Ottawa Wednesday he would welcome Pawley aboard.
   The upheaval in Winnipeg has other national ramifications.
   Latest polls indicate the Conservative Party in Manitoba is
twice as popular as the New Democrats, with a good chance of
winning the provincial election.
   That would please Conservative Prime Minister Brian Mulroney's
federal government because Pawley was the most outspoken provincial
opponent of the free-trade agreement Mulroney negotiated last year
with the United States.
   Pawley also has reservations about the Meech Lake constitutional
accord fashioned last year to recognize French-majority Quebec as
``a distinct society'' and to share federal powers with the 10
provinces.
   National opinion surveys put the New Democrats in a dead heat
with the Conservatives and opposition Liberal Party. Pawley could
help Broadbent convert that popularity into seats.
   The New Democratic Party has its origins in the Cooperative
Commonwealth Federation, a socialist political group founded in the
Canadian prairies in the depression 1930s. It introduced
unemployment benefit and socialized medicine to Canada.
   Walding, a former speaker of the Manitoba legislature who felt
overlooked by Pawley, explained his defection by saying he was
under too much strain keeping the government afloat with his one
vote.
   ``It is time for the people of Manitoba to decide whether this
government still has a mandate,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
