<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka,0192</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Six People Killed by Pro-Sinhalese Group</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group that opposes a peace accord
with minority Tamils killed six people from the Sinhalese ethnic
majority, including a government official and two family members,
military officers said Wednesday.
   The officers blamed the outlawed People's Liberation Front, a
Sinhalese group, for the killings near Beliatta, 85 miles southeast
of Colombo.
   They said the official, P.K. Dissanayake, and two members of his
family were abducted Tuesday night by men wearing police uniforms
and their bodies were found early early Wednesday. Three other
Sinhalese were shot dead Wednesday, the officers said, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   Authorities blame the Sinhalese group for more than 150 killings
since July 1987 in its campaign against a peace agreement designed
to end a 4-year-old Tamil separatist war that has taken more than
8,000 lives. The Front claims the July 29 agreement grants Tamils
too many concessions.
   Tamils, most of whom are Hindus, make up 18 percent of Sri
Lanka's 16 million people and claim discrimination by the majority
Sinhalese, a predominantly Buddhist ethnic group that controls
government and military.
