<1ST_LINE>r w AM-HijackingSuspect     03-09 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hijacking Suspect,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government To Appeal Judge's Ruling On Confession</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department filed a notice
Wednesday that it would appeal a federal judge's decision to
suppress the confession of a former Lebanese Shiite Amal militiaman
accused of leading an airline hijacking.
   The government's move to appeal the ruling by U.S. District
Judge Barrington D. Parker stays the March 22 trial of Fawaz Younis
pending a ruling by the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals here.
   Parker ruled last month that the FBI illegally obtained a
confession from Younis when he was arrested in the Mediterranean
after being lured into an FBI-chartered yacht.
   The judge ruled that prosecutors could not use the confession as
evidence that Younis led four other hijackers who seized a Royal
Jordanian airliner on June 11, 1985 at Beirut International Airport.
   The plane was destroyed a day later after the passengers and
crew were taken off the aircraft.
   Parker criticized the FBI's four-day interrogation of Younis
aboard a Navy munitions ship following his arrest last Sept. 13 in
international waters off Cyprus.
   Younis, whose wrists were broken when two FBI agents slammed him
to the deck of the yacht, suffered throbbing pain and seasickness
that left him in no condition to rationally waive his
constitutional right to remain silent, the judge said.
   Parker said the four-day cruise aboard the Navy ship was
conducted solely for the purpose of obtaining a confession.
   The notice of appeal was filed even though prosecutors have not
received permission from Solicitor General Charles Fried to take
the case to the appellate court. It can be withdrawn if Fried
decides the government has no ground to appeal Parker's decision.
   The notice was filed as a protective measure to preserve the
prosecution's right to appeal, according to government sources who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Although they want to use the confession, federal prosecutors
have other evidence, including a videotape of Younis reading a
statement to reporters before the plane was blown up in the
background. In addition, two Americans who were aboard the plane
when it was seized by heavily armed hijackers have identified
Younis as being one of their captors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
