<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BRF--ParksHospitalized     03-09 0153</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Parks Hospitalized,0157</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bus Boycott Leader of 1955 Gets Pacemaker</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rosa L. Parks, whose refusal to give up her
seat to a white man on a segregated Alabama bus sparked the 1955
Montgomery bus boycott, was in satisfactory condition Wednesday
after receiving a pacemaker.
   Mrs. Parks, 75, of Detroit, entered Johns Hopkins Hospital on
Sunday and the procedure was performed Tuesday, said hospital
spokeswoman Ghita Levine. Mrs. Parks is expected to be discharged
within a couple days, Ms. Levine said.
   Mrs. Parks in Baltimore for medical tests and to help plan a
birthday tribute to her in June, said spokeswoman Ghita Levine.
   Nearly 33 years ago, Mrs. Parks was arrested for refusing to
give up her bus seat. The black community retaliated by boycotting
the buses.
   Buses in Montgomery and other Southern cities ultimately were
desegregated. Her action was heralded as a watershed in the
mounting civil rights movement.
</TEXT>
