<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Song,0198</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Radio Bans Song Attacking Catholic Birth Control Policies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MUNICH, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bavarian Radio on Wednesday banned a
song that links the Roman Catholic Church's opposition to birth
control to the plight of millions suffering starvation in the world.
   Udo Reiter, director of Bavarian Rundfunk's radio division, said
in a statement the song by popular West German entertainer Udo
Juergens would not be broadcast because its lyrics ``would offend
religious feelings.''
   A station official said station managers concluded that the
lyrics ``simply go too far.''
   He spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The song ``Go Forth and Multiply,'' which plays on a well-known
Bible passage, attacks church prohibitions against using artificial
birth control.
   Referring to problems caused by overpopulation, Juergens wrote:
``The creator will become the destroyer if he continues on this
way.''
   Bild newspaper on Wednesday quoted Juergens as saying, ``I don't
want to offend anyone's religious beliefs, but the 50 million
starving people in the world deserve a forthright voice.''
   Bild quoted a spokesman for Augsburg Bishop Josef Stimpfle as
saying the lyrics contained ``hateful filth.''
   Conservative Bavaria state has a large Roman Catholic population.
</TEXT>
