<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 2134EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Peru     03-09 0241</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru,0249</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Peru Extends Anti-Rebel Emergency Measures in Jungle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Peru extended a state of emergency Wednesday
in parts of two states in the eastern jungles, where leftist
guerrillas are reported to be collaborating with drug traffickers.
   The government says that for the past year, Mao-inspired Shining
Path rebels have offered traffickers protection from police in
exchange for money.
   A decree published in the official gazette and signed by
President Alan Garcia prolonged emergency measures for two months
across most of San Martin state and two adjoining counties in
Huanuco state.
   The region lies on the eastern slopes of the Andes, where most
of the coca leaf, the raw ingredient of cocaine, is harvested. The
drug is partially processed and then smuggled into Colombia for
refining.
   A state of emergency suspends constitutional rights to travel
and meet freely. It permits government forces to conduct searches
without warrants and hold suspects for long periods without filing
charges.
   ``Since the acts of violence continue ... it is necessary to
maintain measures aimed at re-establishing public order,'' said the
decree Wednesday.
   The Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement, a smaller leftist
guerrilla band considered less violent than Shining Path, expanded
its urban insurgency to northern San Martin state late last year.
   The government responded by declaring a state of emergency.
   Parts of seven states, home to more than half of Peru's 20
million people, are under states of emergency to fight guerrillas.
</TEXT>
