<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PoliticalRdp 3rdLd-Writethru a1104 03-09 1038</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Rdp, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a1104,960</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Looks Ahead to Illinois; Three-Way Democratic Race</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: New graf 4 with Dole saying Kemp will drop out, won't endorse
anyone; DELETES graf 10 pvs, bgng: Rep. Jack; minor editing to
conform. Also restores material from a1037, which dropped from last
writethru. Note a1104, with Hart said ready to quit, should have
been slugged a 2nd Ld-Writethru</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican resistance to George Bush's bid for the White House
began crumbling Wednesday as the impact of his fabulous Super
Tuesday showing sank in. Democrats Michael Dukakis, Albert Gore and
Jesse Jackson savored their own successes while aiming for next
week's showdown in Illinois.
   Massachusetts Gov. Dukakis and Sen. Gore of Tennessee agreed the
nomination struggle would last until the convention next summer.
But they quarreled long-distance over which one of them could
attract the most voters to the Democratic banner in a campaign
against the Republicans.
   Bush spent the day in Houston savoring his 16-state primary
sweep and the roughly 600 delegates they brought. The outlook for
Illinois wasn't bad either, as Gov. James Thompson was backing the
vice president and Sen. Bob Dole's own campaign polls gave Bush the
lead.
   Dole, meanwhile, said Rep. Jack Kemp had telephoned him to say
he would drop out of the race Thursday, without endorsing either of
his Republican rivals. Kemp, who has scheduled a morning news
conference in Washington, had been expected to bow out after weak
finishes in all the contests so far.
   ``He (Kemp) wanted me to know he was going to get out
tomorrow...He's not going to endorse anybody...He's going to stay
neutral,'' Dole told reporters in Chicago.
   The vice president, for his part, sounded like he was trying to
nudge Dole from the race. He declined his rival's challenge to
debate him in Illinois in a telegram that said the time had come to
``look ahead to the issues which distinguish us from the
Democrats.''
   ``Good luck,'' he wrote.
   Dole awoke to a campaign in shambles after losing all 17 Super
Tuesday states and conceded, ``I've got to win Illinois'' to save
his candidacy. The Kansas senator visited the hospital in Chicago
where he was treated 40 years ago for his crippling World War II
wounds, while his senior aides met to discuss wholesale staff
reductions.
   Republican Pat Robertson signaled he knew the game was all but
over, although he said he would stay in contention.
   ``None of us could have dreamed that he (Bush) could be so
strong,'' said Robertson. He said the vice president had run a
``fabulous race,'' and added, ``The mantle of Ronald Reagan has
passed to George Bush.'' The former television evangelist said he
would remain in the race, but talked in terms of expanding his
support for a campaign rerun in 1992.
   On the Democratic side, Gary Hart was apparently poised to quit.
He put travel plans on hold and scheduled a news conference on
Friday in Denver. A Denver TV station, KUSA, said he had told his
staff he would abandon his bid for the nomination.
   The former Colorado senator, who has garnered few votes in any
contest since re-entering the race in December, failed to win a
single delegate on Tuesday, and home state Gov. Roy Romer endorsed
Dukakis. Hart had dropped out of the race in May amid reports of
his relationship with a Miami model.
   At the White House, Chief of Staff Howard Baker said Reagan
would remain neutral in the race for a while longer. But then he
added that it would take a ``major event'' to deny Bush the
nomination. ``He's certainly got the momentum,'' said Baker, who
once harbored White House ambitions of his own.
   If anything, the Democratic race looked like it was just
beginning. Delegate leader Dukakis stood only about a quarter of
the way toward the 2,082 convention votes needed to be nominated.
   Jackson was the early favorite to win the South Carolina
caucuses on Saturday, while he and Sen. Paul Simon looked like
favorite son front-runners for next Tuesday's Illinois primary.
   Jackson said he was ``overcome with a sense of history and joy''
after winning primaries in Alabama, Georgia, Louisiana, Mississippi
and Virginia and second-place finishes in Massachusetts, Rhode
Island, Maryland and elsewhere.
   Gore said Dukakis was the embodiment of ``the same old formula''
that has led Democrats to 49-state defeats in two of the last five
presidential elections, and said he was the man to gain the
allegiance of independent voters. ``This is a battle for the future
of the Democratic Party,'' said Gore, who won his home state of
Tennessee as well as Arkansas, Kentucky, North Carolina and
Oklahoma and Nevada's caucuses.
   Dukakis, the leader in national convention delegates with 455,
said polls show him running ahead of Bush in Florida and Texas. The
Massachusetts governor said he had won a ``national victory,'' and
pointed to wins in every corner of the country as evidence.
   He won primaries Tuesday in Texas, Florida, Maryland, Rhode
Island and at home in Massachusetts, and was the winner in the
Idaho caucuses and the leader in Hawaii's caucuses.
   ``Al hasn't won a primary outside the South,'' he said of Gore.
   Dukakis said he was the man with the message for the voters in
the industrial state voters yet ahead. ``I'm a chief executive.
I've balanced budgets, I took a state that was in desperate shape
12 years ago and today it's one of the great success stories,'' he
said.
   Simon, who sat out Super Tuesday, waited for his rivals in his
home state. He said he fully expects to win both the popular vote
and the plurality of the state's 187 national convention delegates,
even though he won't be advertising on television. If he fails to
win, he said, he will be reassessing his campaign.
   Rep. Richard Gephardt, who won only his home state of Missouri
on Tuesday, insisted the ``race is on'' as he attacked Dukakis and
Gore on trade issues during a campaign stop in South Carolina.
   Despite his vow, aides said Geophardt would make a minimal
effort in Illinois and hoped to conserve his resources for a major
battle in the Michigan caucuses on March 26.
</TEXT>
