<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brown     03-09 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brown,0388</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Joyce Brown Collects $7,000, Says She Won't Panhandle Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A formerly homeless woman who successfully
fought her forced hospitalization by the city said Wednesday she
went back to the streets to panhandle for money over the weekend
because she was broke.
   ``I'm not insane for having panhandled,'' said Joyce Brown, who
has been living at a halfway house for women since her release from
a psychiatric ward Jan. 19. ``It's not a sign of insanity _ it's a
sign of trying to survive.''
   The 40-year-old Miss Brown, who called herself Billie Boggs on
the street, said she won't panhandle again because she had just
received Social Security checks mailed to her sister's New Jersey
home.
   The checks, totaling $7,000, were turned over to Miss Brown on
Tuesday, said her lawyer, Norman Siegel of the New York Civil
Liberties Union. Miss Brown said she needed $10 over the weekend
for cigarettes and food.
   Miss Brown also acknowledged shouting obscenities at passers-by
outside her hotel Sunday, but only at those who taunted her.
   ``Because I am known as a figure, people were being smart and
sarcastic: `Billie, didn't I see you on TV?' So I did use profanity
to make them leave me alone, and it worked,'' she said, calmly
answering questions.
   Miss Brown, after her release, had worked as a temporary
receptionist at the ACLU's office, and had given several interviews
and made talk show appearances and speaking engagements, including
one at Harvard Law School.
   She lived for months over a hot-air grate on Manhattan's East
Side and was the first homeless person picked up and forcibly
hospitalized when the city began clearing mentally ill people from
the streets Oct. 28.
   She was released after a judge ruled she could not be forced to
take medication.
   Dr. Robert Gould, whom Miss Brown visits weekly for
psychotherapy, said she eventually will return to work but needs
time to adjust to her freedom.
   ``Her celebrity status in the last couple of months is not an
easy thing to handle,'' he said.
   Mayor Edward I. Koch said Wednesday, ``She left the hospital
against the will of the doctors. Had she stayed there, she might
have received medical treatment that might have stabilized her.''
</TEXT>
