<HEAD>Slaying Marks Violent Basketball Season in NJ High Schools</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf pvs, `Robert Lindsey ...' with two grafs to
CORRECT first name to Richard, caliber of gun to .25 sted .22 and
ADD suspect's ID; A version moving on sports wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY HELEN GILLESPIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WOODBURY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials blamed gang members and
non-students Wednesday for violence at high school basketball games
in New Jersey, where a 16-year-old boy was fatally shot after one
contest and another match was played in secret to avoid threatened
trouble.
   ``Parents shouldn't have to worry about their kids being beaten
up or stabbed or shot at a basketball game,'' said Richard
Luttrell, former past president of the state athletic directors
association.
   On Tuesday, a former student at Paterson's Kennedy High School
was fatally shot following a regional championship contest at
Hackensack High School between Kennedy and Passaic County Technical
and Vocational High School of Wayne.
   A 19-year-old Hackensack man was charged with the slaying,
police said.
   The shooting followed a disagreement in the school parking lot
between boys from Paterson and Hackensack over a girl, said
Hackensack Police Lt. Anthony Leggieri.
   Richard Lindsey of Paterson, who was stranded with three other
youths after the game without a ride back to Paterson, was killed
by one shot in the face from a .25-caliber gun as he walked along
the street five blocks from the school, Leggieri said.
   The suspect, Troy Frazier, an unemployed dropout of Hackensack
High School, was charged with homicide and jailed on $250,000 bail,
McClure said.
   Also on Tuesday, the threat of gang violence forced officials to
move a game between longtime rivals Atlantic City High School and
Camden High School to a location 30 miles away.
   Luttrell, who also is athletic director for Willingboro schools,
said authorities moved the game from Willingboro High School after
receiving word that non-students from Atlantic City and Camden
planned a fight with automatic weapons over a shooting several
months ago.
   The game was played under police guard at Overbrook High School.
Coaches learned of the location only as they boarded team buses and
were handed envelopes with directions to the school.
   On Dec. 27, a woman was shot and four men were slashed or
stabbed during a fight in the crowd at a tournament in Absecon,
disrupting a game and forcing cancellation of the last two days of
the tournament.
   Holy Spirit High School refused to play host to the tournament
again. Next year it moves to St. Joseph's University in
Philadelphia.
   A month later, a game between Atlantic City and Egg Harbor
Township High School was postponed when a freshman on the Atlantic
City team was arrested for having a weapon in his locker.
   In Willingboro, teen-age girls from rival gangs started a fight
following a game earlier this season between Willingboro High and
crosstown rival John F. Kennedy High School, Lutrell said.
   The fight could have been worse had school authorities not used
metal detectors to scan the crowd, Luttrell said.
   Such security precautions have helped reduce troubles at
Willingboro schools, Luttrell said.
   Tensions could be further reduced by keeping non-students away
from the matches, he said.
   ``Let's have the games be good wholesome fun by limiting the
spectators to the student body and their immediate family. The
hangers-on, the dropouts, the gang members, they don't get in,''
Luttrell said.
   Kennedy High Principal William Toole said details of the
Tuesday's fatal melee remained unclear. The victim was a dropout,
he said.
   There were no incidents during the game, which 2,000 spectators
attended, said Hackensack High principal Harold Bloom.
   But Bloom said he planned to re-evaluate whether more
championship games would be played this season at Hackensack High
School.
   Robert Kanaby, the director of the New Jersey State
Interscholastic Athletic Association, was out of town and
unavailable for comment Wednesday. The association oversees boys
and girls high school sports in the state.
</TEXT>
