<2ND_LINE>AM-Spain-Strike,0161</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Public School Teachers Strike For More Pay</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most of Spain's 270,000 public school
teachers stayed out of the classroom Wednesday in the first of two
days of strikes to demand pay increases.
   The strike disrupted classes for more than 6 million students in
elementary, secondary and technical schools in most parts of the
country, union and Education Ministry officials said.
   Spain's two largest unions, the Socialist-led General Workers
Union and the Communist-oriented Workers Commissions, and three
smaller teachers' unions called the strike.
   Workers Commissions spokesman Javier Doz told Spanish Television
the teachers wanted the Socialist government to end ``pay
discrimination'' against teachers.
   He said grade school teachers earn an average $930 a month and
want $1,170 while secondary and technical school teachers seek to
increase their average monthly pay of $1,080 to $1,380.
   Education Ministry official Joaquin Arango told reporters the
teachers' demands were ``economically unfeasible'' due to budget
constraints.
</TEXT>
