<2ND_LINE>AM-Writers Strike,0367</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pickets Up in New York; Talks To Resume Thursday on West Coast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking film and TV scriptwriters were
active on both coasts Wednesday, picketing outside the MGM building
in New York and preparing to resume negotiations here under the
guidance of a federal mediator.
   Script shortages because of the strike begun Monday have forced
CBS to shelve indefinitely two programs set to debut this month,
``The Dictator'' starring Christopher Lloyd, and ``The Smothers
Brothers Comedy Hour.''
   The walkout by 9,000 members of the Writers Guild of America
also has forced ``Late Night With David Letterman'' and ``The
Tonight Show'' into reruns.
   Writers have refused to continue working on the script for the
Academy Awards ceremony, scheduled for worldwide broadcast April 11
on ABC. Soap operas have stockpiled scripts for several weeks and
have not been affected.
   Negotiators for the guild and the Alliance of Motion Picture and
Television Producers were scheduled to meet Thursday at the
producers' headquarters in Sherman Oaks.
   ``It's a mediation session and that's all I can say,'' WGA
spokeswoman Cheryl Rhoden said. ``It's important that those topics
on the table be kept there rather than be aired in the media.''
   The strike began after the scriptwriters rejected a final offer
from the producers. Main points of contention were writers' demands
for higher fees from reruns and greater creative control.
   About 100 scriptwriters Wednesday marched outside the MGM
building. Three writers of Letterman's show, wearing jackets with
the program name on the back, walked the picket line with about 125
other strikers and supporters.
   William Peter Blatty, who wrote ``The Exorcist,'' was on the
line, as was Screen Actors Guild member Barbara Feldon of ``Get
Smart'' fame.
   Carson's show will be in reruns the remainder of the week, but
his production company applied for a waiver that would allow the
talk show's writers to resume work next week, spokesman Jim Mahoney
said Wednesday.
   The guild was expected to consider the request this weekend. A
similar waiver was granted in 1981
   The WGA strike is the fourth since 1973. The longest, in 1981,
lasted three months.
</TEXT>
