<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Turkey-Emergency     03-09 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Turkey-Emergency,0251</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parliament Extends Emergency Rule in Nine Provinces</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Parliament extended emergency rule
Wednesday in nine provinces where the government has been fighting
Kurdish guerrillas, including Istanbul, the country's largest city.
   Under emergency rule, civilian governors can impose curfews,
issue search warrants, halt strikes and ban meetings and rallies.
   Wednesday's vote extends the emergency rule for four months.
   Interior Minister Mustafa Kalemli told Parliament that Kurdish
guerrillas in eight southeastern provinces killed 100 civilians and
30 soldiers over the past six months. He said 53 people believed to
be terrorists were killed during the same period and 1,761 others
were arrested.
   In the same period in Istanbul, two terrorists were shot dead
and 168 terrorist suspects were arrested, he said.
   The Kurdish Labor Party seeks to set up an independent Marxist
state in parts of eastern and southeastern Turkey. It has been
fighting the government since August 1984.
   About one-fifth of Turkey's 52 million population are ethnic
Kurds.
   Also on Wednesday, a parliamentary commission approved a draft
bill that would allow individuals to apply for a court order to
halt or prevent publication of a story deemed an invasion of
privacy.
   Columnist Oktay Eksi wrote in the liberal daily Hurriyet that
the bill, introduced by members of the governing Motherland Party,
meant plain censorship.
   The government disclosed that it has drafted legislation which
would penalize the press for reporting false news, permitting fines
up to $100,000.
</TEXT>
