<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-QueenMum     03-09 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Queen Mum,0402</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Queen Mother Expresses `Much Distress' In Closure Of Hospital Ward</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Queen Mother Elizabeth made a foray Wednesday into
the hottest issue in British domestic politics _ the ailing,
tax-funded National Health Service.
   Her office said that in a letter to Health Minister Tony Newton,
the 87-year-old mother of Queen Elizabeth II expressed ``much
distress'' at the closure last December of a ward for the elderly
in a south Wales hospital.
   She had presided at the reopening of the hospital eight months
earlier after its renovation.
   ``Although I am sure you appreciate the queen mother has no
jurisdiction whatsoever over the affairs of the National Health
Service, I have at Her Majesty's command written,'' the letter said.
   George Boulton, the general manager of the Mid-Glamorgan Health
Authority, told reporters the royal intervention was unlikely to
reopen the six-bed ward at St. Tydfil's Hospital in Merthyr Tydfil.
   ``No one takes interest from the royal family lightly,'' he said.
   ``But we are facing a deficit of about 4 million pounds ($7.3
million) this year because we haven't got enough money from the
government and prices are going up all the time. We made cuts to
save 1.2 million pounds ($2.2 million).''
   Boulton said closing the ward would save about $73,000. He said
more wards at the hospital may be closed.
   National opinion polls report that the state of the health
service is the biggest worry among Britons.
   Nurses are quitting in protest over their pay and conditions,
wards are closing and the more than 700,000 patients wait months
and sometimes years for operations.
   The service now costs $39.3 billion a year and critics say it
urgently needs another $3.6 billion to $9.2 billion.
   The royal family traditionally stays out of politics, although
Prince Charles, heir to the throne, has expressed anger at
inner-city poverty.
   Robin Cook, social services spokesman for the opposition Labor
Party, which has repeatedly condemned the government for not
spending more on the National Health Service, said: ``This is a
dramatic intervention by the queen mother which demonstrates the
state of the National Health Service.''
   Tony Wilkins, an official of the National Union of Public
Employees in Merthyr Tydfil, said: ``Perhaps the queen mother
should be allowed to open every hospital _ it might be a good way
of protecting our health service.''
</TEXT>
