<DOCNO> AP880309-0333 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 2146EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CrashHearing     03-09 0600</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crash Hearing,0619</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Problems In Rescue Operation Recounted At NTSB Hearing</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Copters Collide, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBBIE NEWBY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Enough snow fell while Continental Flight
1713 awaited takeoff at Denver's airport Nov. 15 for ice buildup on
the wings to have been a possible factor in the crash, an airplane
engineer testified Wednesday.
   Ralph Brumby, manager of aerodynamics and acoustics for
McDonnell Douglas Corp., which manufactured the DC-9, said 0.032
inches of precipitation, or about a third of an inch of snow, fell
in the 24 minutes between de-icing and takeoff.
   If all that precipitation had frozen on the wing, it could have
caused problems on takeoff, Brumby said. Ice can change the shape
of the wing, affecting lift.
   Continental responded that the plane was going too fast at the
time of the crash for ice on the wings to have affected it.
   Testimony about possible icing and its effects, and detail on
the efforts to rescue the passengers trapped in the plane after it
crashed, dominated the second day of a National Transportation
Safety Board hearing on the crash.
   Twenty-eight people were killed and 54 hurt when the DC-9
flipped over and broke apart on the runway at Stapleton
International Airport shortly after takeoff during a snowstorm.
   Brumby, under questioning by Continental officials, said that
the amount of precipitation that fell between the time the plane
was de-iced and takeoff was high enough that the plane could have
stalled at about 150 knots, or a little more than 170 mph.
   But Continental officials noted that an NTSB study concluded the
craft had reached 168 knots, or about 193 mph, at some point before
it crashed. Airline spokesman Bruce Hicks said that based on those
findings, ice on the wings could not have caused the crash.
   Continental officials also quizzed Brumby about the possibility
the de-icing fluid failed to keep ice off the wings. He said that
was a possibility but did not elaborate.
   He said there have been three DC-9 crashes in which ice was a
factor during the past 23 years, but in all cases there was no
de-icing before takeoff.
   NTSB investigator Robert Benzon had said Tuesday that officials
want to know why 24 minutes elapsed between de-icing and takeoff
when other planes on the runway took off within 15 minutes.
   Earlier Wednesday, officials testified that rescuers had to cope
with frigid weather, confusion and occasional equipment
malfunctions, but the operation went as well as could be expected.
Some victims were trapped in the wreckage for hours.
   ``We feel fortunate we had that many survivors,'' Dr. Michael
Brunko, the rescue coordinator, testified. ``Obviously, there were
people trapped in the wreckage who we could not do anything for.'
   Brunko said that ``to this day, I do not know what else could
have been done.''
   There were problems with pens that would not write, radio
batteries that failed, confusion created by the number of
Continental personnel at the scene, and the effects of the cold on
rescuers who were not dressed for it, according to Brunko.
   Eldon W. Buller, Denver assistant fire chief, said the
upside-down position of the plane delayed the rescue.
   ``Every time we moved the aircraft on one side, we compromised
people on the other side,'' Buller said. ``People were starting to
get crushed.''
   He said firefighters wanted to drain fuel from one of the
aircraft's wings, but they did not know how and no other airport
officials could explain the procedure.
   ``I was afraid it would drown the people trapped underneath'' if
the fuel began leaking, Buller said.
</TEXT>
