<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Disney-DressCode     03-09 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Disney-Dress Code,0249</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dress Code Adopted By Disneyland Hotel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If Uncle Remus and six of the seven
dwarfs applied for jobs at the Disneyland Hotel, they would be
turned down because of a new dress code. Not even Walt Disney's
pencil-thin mustache would pass muster.
   Disneyland acquired the hotel in January and expanded its
31-year-old dress code to cover its 1,600 employees.
   Under the code, men will have to get haircuts, shave and cover
tattoos. Women will have to abandon slacks, heavy makeup, gaudy
jewelry and wild hairdos.
   Six of the seven dwarfs, Uncle Remus, Captain Hook and
``Pinocchio'' toymaker Geppetto all would be renegades working in
the real-life world of Disney.
   When Disney Co. assumed control of the hotel, previously managed
by the Wrather Corp., its employees fell under the dress code
established for the Magic Kingdom in 1957.
   Some hotel employees said they won't shave, including engineer
Mike Searles, 40, who wears a handlebar mustache.
   ``I don't think it's right, and I'm not going to compromise,''
he said.
   He and others said they will go to their union to fight the
dress code. But workers who rebel may be terminated, said
Disneyland spokesman Bob Roth.
   ``The reason that we are doing this is because the Disneyland
Hotel is becoming part of Disneyland Attractions, and we have an
appearance standard,'' Roth said. ``It is associated with Disney
and is expected by our guests.''
</TEXT>
