<2ND_LINE>AM-Sedition Trial,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Supremacist Changes Mind About Pleading Guilty During Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT SMITH, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A white supremacist changed his mind
Wednesday about pleading guilty to conspiring to overthrow the
government.
   Bruce Pierce, 34, had said Tuesday that he wanted to plead
guilty after U.S. District Judge Morris Arnold ruled that a
confession given to FBI agents after his 1985 arrest was made
voluntarily and is admissible at trial.
   The judge recommended that Pierce wait and discuss the matter
with his attorney.
   In a statement Wednesday, Pierce said he considered entering the
plea ``to avoid further embarrassment over having given a statement
to the authorities. Upon further review and consideration I have
reconsidered.''
   Pierce is among 10 of the 14 men on trial charged with sedition.
Five are accused of conspiring to kill a federal judge and an FBI
agent, and two are accused of interstate transportation of stolen
money.
   Pierce is serving 100 years for racketeering and 150 years for
civil rights violations in the slaying in Denver of Alan Berg, a
Jewish radio talk show.
   Pierce had contended that the confession was not voluntary. He
said that he was told that if he did not talk to the FBI, his wife
would be arrested and his three children would be placed in foster
homes.
