<HEAD>Seven Police Hurt By Bomb As Belfast Riot Protests Gibraltar
Killings</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-5 UPDATE with bomb attack wounds seven police.
Picks up 5th graf pvs, If there ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said a bombing attack
injured seven officers as Roman Catholic youths rioted in Belfast
Wednesday for a third straight night over the killing of three
unarmed IRA guerrillas in Gibraltar.
   A press officer at Belfast police headquarters said the officers
suffered slight injuries when bombs exploded at the rear of
Springfield Road police station in Catholic West Belfast.
   Earlier, police said a grenade was thrown at an army patrol but
exploded harmlessly and that shots were fired at the New Barnsley
police station, which was attacked with gasoline bombs on Tuesday.
   Youths threw gasoline bombs and set vehicles ablaze but no
casualties were reported in those incidents.
   A police official said earlier Wednesday that security forces
will not tolerate Irish Republican Army shows of strength at the
funerals of three guerrillas, who were shot to death by British
commandos last Sunday.
   If there is such a show and ``we move in, we know there is going
to be an unseemly fracas but we simply can't allow the law to be
blatantly defied,'' said a Royal Ulster Constabulary officer. He
spoke anonymously, in accordance with custom.
   Paddy McGrory, lawyer for the three families, arrived in the
British colony on Spain's southern coast to arrange for the return
of the bodies. The funeral date has not yet been set.
   British officials said the IRA members, two men and a woman, had
planned to set off a car bomb Tuesday at a military ceremony in the
center of Gibraltar.
   Spanish police found a car loaded with explosives Tuesday in
Marbella, about 45 miles up the coast from Gibraltar. British
officials believe it was rented by the three slain IRA members.
   The guerrillas killed were Mairead Farrell, 31; Daniel McCann,
30, and Sean Savage, 24, all of west Belfast. The IRA said all were
on ``active service'' at the time of their deaths.
   Police in Madrid said a woman identified as Mary Parkin was
detected in the Gibraltar area in February and was being sought as
a possible fourth member of the IRA team.
   Felix Pizzarello, the Gibraltar coroner, said an inquest will
not be held until May.
   The coroner, who also is a lower-court magistrate, said in a
telephone interview his court ``is fully booked until May and I
can't realisticaly think of having an inquest until then. I don't
consider that the matter requires any urgent treatment.''
   He said Gibraltar police were investigating the shooting and his
inquest would be partly based on documents they would provide
``within two to three weeks.''
   The mostly Roman Catholic IRA has been fighting since 1969 to
unite the overwhelmingly Catholic Irish Republic with British-ruled
Northern Ireland, where Protestants form a majority.
</TEXT>
