<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Panama 2ndLd-Writethru a1109 03-09 0772</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a1109,0793</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Banks to Resume Limited Operations</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERT 2 grafs after 10th graf pvs, Panama keeps ... UPDATING
with Panama-chartered plane searched at Miami. Picks up 11th graf,
The United ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Panama-Future, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Wednesday that
banks can reopen but people still will not be allowed to cash
checks or withdraw money. The banks closed last week because of a
cash shortage and political turmoil.
   The National Banking Commission said banks could accept deposits
from clients, conduct interbank operations and transfer money from
one account to another.
   It did not say when withdrawals and check-cashing would be
permitted. Panama's national currency is the U.S. dollar and the
cash supply has been drying up because of the dispute over who
should control the government.
   No banks in the downtown financial district opened for business
immediately.
   Depositors began a run on domestic banks when President Eric
Arturo Delvalle was ousted Feb. 26 after trying to dismiss Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega, the real power in Panama, as head of the
15,000-member Panamanian Defense Forces.
   On Wednesday, the nephew of the late Omar Torrijos, Panama's
previous strongman, disclosed he broke with the Noriega government.
He said he left his post as chief of Panama's consulate in Los
Angeles and was joining forces loyal to Delvalle.
   Diplomatic sources in Washington, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said the defection of Santiago Torrijos was considered
significant because of the close identification of the his
relatives with the Defense Forces. Omar Torrijos is still
considered a national hero for negotiating the Panama Canal
treaties with the United States.
   The 12 domestic banks closed March 2 in sympathy with a
nationwide general strike called by Noriega's opponents. Late last
week, the government ordered them to remain shut and also closed
more than 100 international banks.
   Commerce has been crippled. With no way to process non-cash
transactions, most businesses refuse to accept checks or credit
cards.
   Panama keeps an estimated $50 million on deposit in American
banks and usually receives remittances, but U.S. judges froze
Panamanian assets in banks in Miami and New York after suits were
filed to prevent Noriega's government from withdrawing funds.
   U.S. Customs Service agents in Miami detained a Boeing 707
chartered by Air Panama for four hours Wednesday to search for U.S.
currency, but no money turned up, customs spokesman Michael Sheehan
said.
   Fifteen agents and inspectors searched cargo unloaded from the
plane after a tip someone might be trying to illegally take U.S.
currency out of the country.
   The United States recognizes Delvalle as Panama's legitimate
president. It has demanded Noriega's removal since he was indicted
in Florida last month on narcotics and money-laundering charges.
   Delvalle went into hiding in Panama after Noriega had the
national legislature dismiss him.
   Because of the cash crunch, Panamanian families have put off
non-essentials.
   Rufina Escobar, a 55-year-old schoolteacher, said she had oil,
noodles and a few eggs _ enough food to make it through the week _
``but if banks don't open next week I'll have to ask friends for a
few dollars just to eat.''
   Panama City was calm Wednesday, unlike a day earlier, when
hundreds of burning trash barricades blocked the streets. The
demonstrations were the largest since Delvalle was dismissed.
   An editorial in the government-run newspaper Critica on Tuesday
said ``all buildings, all institutions in which Americans have any
interest'' should be blown up.
   Its 3-inch-high banner headline said ``Invasion of Panama.'' On
Tuesday, Foreign Minister Jorge Abadia claimed that maneuvers being
conducted by the U.S. Southern Command are ``the prelude to an
armed invasion of Panama.''
   The command, which is based in Panama and is responsible for
U.S. military operations in Latin America, said the maneuvers
involved fewer than 700 soldiers and were ``routine training and
evaluation exercises.''
   The U.S. Embassy issued a communique Wednesday calling Abadia's
allegations ``completely false and tendentious.''
   It also dismissed as ``absurd'' allegations that U.S. Ambassador
Arthur Davis was manipulating funds of the Panama Canal Commission.
   ``The government of the United States has reiterated on various
occasions its faithful compliance with the Panama Canal Treaties,''
the communique said.
   Baltazar Renan Alzpurua, columnist for Critica, said of the U.S.
maneuvers: ``It is time to ... dedicate ourselves to the
organization of volunteers who are ready to fight in the cities,
the mountains, the streets and fields, rifle and machete in hand.''
   Real estate salesman Alexis Alvarez said with a shrug: ``Let the
gringos invade. We can't be any worse off with them than we are now
with this bunch of thieves.''
</TEXT>
