<1ST_LINE>u i AM-DominicanRepublic 1stLd-Writethru a1054 03-09 0545</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dominican Republic, 1st Ld - Writethru, a1054,0557</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Organizers Call Off Strike Protesting Cost of Living</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with strike called off, details.
Picks up 4th graf pvs, Soldiers in ...; SUBS 10th graf pvs, The
strike ... to conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RUDDY GONZALEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Organizers called off a
strike aimed at protesting the high cost of living Wednesday after
a first day of protest shaped up as a failure.
   Most businesses, banks and government offices kept their doors
open on Wednesday, the first day of the planned 2-day walkout, and
activity in the city was normal.
   Virtudes Alvarez, a spokesman for strike organizers, said the
decision was made Wednesday night to give ``the government a short
time'' to talk with the ``those involved in this movement.'' He did
not elaborate.
   Alvarez represents the National Conference of Popular
Organizations, a coalition claiming to have the support of about
200 urban neighborhood and small peasant groups.
   No incidents of violence were reported Wednesday.
   Six people died and about 20 were injured in other protests in
the last two weeks in the Caribbean nation.
   Soldiers in armored personnel carriers and police with automatic
weapons patrolled the streets of the capital of 1.5 million on
Wednesday.
   Bus and taxi drivers stayed home in the early morning and
thousands of people were late for work, but by midmorning most
drivers were back on the job.
   Public and private schools stayed closed as a precaution in the
event of incidents, school authorities said.
   Most labor and church groups and political parties opposed the
strike. However, the nation's largest union, the General Workers
Union with an estimated 40,000 members, had said it would support
the action.
   The coalition has led strikes since February that shut down
several low-income communities in the capital and resulted in
sporadic clashes between residents and police and soldiers.
   Strike organizers demand that the government control the
spiraling cost of basic commodities, improve public services and
carry out capital improvements in their communities.
   About 4,000 supporters of the governing Reformist Party marched
to the National Palace on Tuesday shouting slogans backing
President Joaquin Balaguer and denouncing the strike.
   Tuesday night, the archbishop of Santo Domingo, Nicolas de Jesus
Lopez Rodriguez, termed the strike ``senseless'' and called for
dialogue among government, business and labor.
   Private economists estimated the inflation rate in the Dominican
Republic at 30 percent last year and said it may reach 50 to 60
percent this year.
   The U.S. dollar, to which much of the Dominican economy is
pegged, meanwhile has been rising steadily with respect to the
peso. The peso now is valued at around 19 cents, compared to 26
cents late last year.
   Balaguer this week announced price controls on items such as
plantains, onions, potatoes, rice, but strike organizers say the
measures are insufficient. Other commodities expected to be
regulated include chicken, sugar and tomato paste.
   The police chief, Maj. Gen. Fernando Aristides Sanchez Aybar,
said Tuesday that public disorder would not be tolerated, and the
armed forces minister, Lt. Gen. Antonio Imbert Barrera, said
soldiers would help police keep order.
   Some left-wing and labor groups complained their leaders were
arrested without warrants and were being held without charges.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
