<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PTL-IRS     03-09 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PTL-IRS,0246</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Halts IRS Efforts to Revoke PTL's Tax-Exempt Status</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court judge Wednesday
temporarily halted IRS efforts to revoke PTL's tax-exempt status.
   Judge William Williams of the 4th U.S. Circuit of Appeals in
Richmond, Va., said the TV ministry built by Jim and Tammy Bakker
would suffer irreparable harm if it were determined later that the
IRS overstepped its authority.
   The judge set a March 31 hearing in Greenville, S.C., where PTL
attorneys are expected to argue that loss of tax-exempt status
would be a death blow to PTL, which is trying to reorganize under
bankruptcy court protection.
   On Monday, U.S. District Judge Karen Henderson had ruled that
the Internal Revenue Service could revoke PTL's tax-exempt status.
She overturned a December order by a Bankruptcy Court judge, saying
that court had no authority to stop the IRS.
   As a religious organization, PTL does not have to pay tax on the
donations that finance its religious work.
   PTL is trying to raise about $4 million by May 2 and emerge from
bankruptcy court. If it loses its tax-exempt status now, thousands
of contributors will be frightened off, the ministry said.
   The IRS wants to revoke its status retroactively to 1981 and
seek at least $55.7 million in back taxes. In effect, the IRS has
suggested that Bakker wasn't running a ministry but a profitable
business for himself, relatives and friends.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
