<1ST_LINE>a a PM-ReligionintheNews Adv11   03-09 0746</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Religion in the News, Adv11,0768</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv11</NOTE>
<NOTE>For release Fri PMs March 11 or thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Church Break-in's Remain Mystery Despite FBI Probe Citing Churches</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scores of odd break-ins have occurred over a
period of four years involving groups opposed to U.S. policies in
Central America.
   In many cases, the targets were sanctuary churches providing
haven to Salvadoran and Guatamalan refugees. The burglaries had a
strange similarity. Files and records were ransacked, or taken. But
no valuables were missing.
   ``It's never been solved,'' says David Lerner, spokesman for the
Center for Constitutional Rights, which has documented the puzzling
series of cases. ``The smoking gun has not been found.''
   A House subcommittee investigated the incidents last year, and
determined no perpetrator. Church workers had testified that it
appeared some federal agency was involved, but that fact was not
established.
   The mystery deepened when the constitutional center, through the
Freedom of Information Act, in January obtained more than 1,200
pages of heavily censored FBI files on a five-year investigation of
the Committee in Solidarity with the People of El Salvador
(CISPES), that cited about 25 U.S. religious groups.
   They include Protestant, Roman Catholic and Jewish groups, and
repeatedly mention the sanctuary movement, several of whose leaders
were convicted in 1986 for harboring undocumented aliens.
   But ``the break-ins are not reflected in the documents,'' Lerner
said. ``We just don't have the answer yet.
   ``That doesn't mean the FBI had not participated. We have good
reason to believe there was a connection between the break-in's and
this investigation, and we hope to get to the bottom of it.''
   He said the center, through its lawsuit, still was to receive
other FBI files from regional offices.
   Several of the religious groups mentioned in the FBI reports
strongly protested being brought under surveillance.
   As an example of the references, Lerner cited this passage in a
April 2, 1984, report from the Dallas FBI special agent to
headquarters in Washington:
   ``Investigation has determined CISPES is very closely connected
with the U.S. Catholic Church. The church, which agrees with most
CISPES philosophy, has set aside various sanctuaries to be used to
house illegal Salvadorans in the United States...''
   Actually, various Protestant churches _ Methodist, Episcopal,
Presbyterian, Baptist, Unitarian-Universalist and Lutheran _ as
well as Jewish and Catholic congregations, are among the more than
300 offering sanctuary.
   FBI Director William Sessions has defended the surveilance of
CISPES on suspicion the Washington-based group was subversively
aiding Marxist rebels in El Salvador, which he termed
``terrorist,'' but no criminal activity was found.
   He conceded ``mistakes'' may have been made in the
investigation's mushrooming to other groups. Lerner said about l60
organizations are named in the FBI files, including these religious
groups:
   U.S. Catholic Conference, National Council of Churches, World
Council of Churches, American Friends Service Committee, Friends
Religious Society, Southern Christian Leadership Conference, New
Jewish Agenda, Maryknoll Sisters, Sisters of Bernedict and Sisters
of Mercy.
   Among local religious centers mentioned were:
   Mennonite Church, Pittsburgh; Corpus Christi Catholic Church,
Oklahoma City; St. Williams Roman Catholic Church, Louisville, Ky.;
St. Luke's Presbyterian Church, Minitonka, Minn.; Walker Methodist
Community and Twin-City Friends Meeting, Minneapolis, Thomas Merton
Center, Pittsburgh, and a Milwaukee-based food program run by the
Society of St. Paul.
   The Maryknoll Sisters, based in Maryknoll, N.Y., said in a
statement that the FBI actions ``threaten the rights of all U.S.
citizens and place in jeopardy the democratic principles upon which
this country is founded.''
   The Rev. Arie Brouwer, general secretary of the National Council
of Churches, noted the surveillance involved various groups
differing with U.S. policy in Central America and said:
   ``This sort of abuse of governmental power and authority has
occurred in our society almost invariably when the U.S. is involved
in what is widely perceived in this country as military adventurism
abroad.
   ``Foreign and domestic human rights abuses often go together.''
   The Rev. Joseph Lowery, a United Methodist and president of the
Southern Christian Leadership Conference, said the surveillance
``smacks of the kind of behavior that we accuse the Kremlin of
performing.''
   Sister Linda Rich, a member of the Sisters of Divine Province
and staff member of the Thomas Merton Center in Pittsburgh, said it
had evidence in recent years of ``some FBI surveilance and
informants coming to our meetings.
   ``We conduct our activities and meetings very openly and feel
that simply because we dissent from government policies, that
doesn`t warrant them investigating us.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv11</NOTE>
