<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APonTV-Nature Adv11   03-09 0725</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP on TV-Nature, Adv 11,0741</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv11</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Friday PMs, March 11, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Great Moments from `Nature'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEAN-CLAUDE BOUIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Where can network viewers find unabashed
predatory behavior, bizarre courtship rituals, unreconstituted male
chauvinism, clever deceptiveness and graphic sex scenes (with
closeups)?
   ``Ryan's Hope?'' ``Dallas'' reruns? ``Monday Night Football?''
``L.A. Law?''
   Perhaps. But this Sunday you'll find some of this and much more
in an unlikely place: ``Great Moments from Nature,'' where
scavenging, cavorting and sex take place almost as naturally as in
many network shows. Actually, only a fraction of the two-hour
special deals with animals' mating habits and anyway it's just an
exotic variation on the classic birds and bees routine.
   ``Great Moments'' draws from 30 of the 100 broadcasts in the
five years of the PBS series, ``Nature,'' that eclectic electronic
zoo where animals can be observed closely without being deprived of
their freedom.
   It stars such common predators as the coyote and the osprey,
which is the only bird of prey to feed exclusively on live fish.
There's also the very small, thieving kleptoparasite spider and the
vampire bat, who drinks the blood of sleeping sea lions.
   Courtship scenes feature the exquisite dance of the endangered
Japanese red-crowned crane and the horn-bashing of the Nubian Ibex.
   Dishonorable mention for male chauvinism goes to several
species, including the polar bear, who takes no part in cub-raising
and even attacks his brood.
   The abalone practices its brand of casual sex called broadcast
spawning. We also see a tiny baby octopus coming to life in the
Baja Lagoon and closeups of finned wasps mating in midflight.
   Nothing new if you grew up on a farm, just a bit more exotic. A
kind of healthy voyeurism, and a sign that the wildlife genre on TV
has come a long way.
   ``Filmmakers are more astute about how to film certain scenes
and when to capture things when they happen,'' said series
producer-director Fred Kaufman. ``We're showing things that people
would not normally get a chance to see. We get to see everything
that animals do. In earlier films, you wouldn't see the mating
sequence or the birthing sequence, they would just talk about it.''
   ``Great Moments'' is divided into four sections: environments,
predators and prey, courtship rituals, and animals and their young.
There are other aspects to ``Nature,'' but unfortunately, one of
the best programs on the subject, ``The Volcano Watchers,'' was
left out of this special, perhaps because it didn't fit the
wildlife theme.
   Included are scenes from past shows like ``The Flight of the
Condor,'' ``Kingdom of the Ice Bear'' and ``Sexual Encounters of
the Floral Kind,'' where the hammer orchid mimics the scent of the
female wasp and lures the male to pick up its pollen. The show may
be graphic and grisly at times, but it's no ``Animal House.''
   ``The audience understands what we're trying to do, that we're
not trying to be exploitative by showing a mating scene,'' said
narrator and executive editor George Page.
   ``Personally, I think it's the best way in the world for kids to
learn about sex,'' said Page, who is also director of science and
natural history programming for public station WNET-TV in New York.
   ``It's the best form of sex education. It's the classic one: the
birds and the bees. I think it's a totally harmless way for
children to be exposed to the idea of sex, and a lot of parents
obviously agree with that because we have a lot of children in the
audience,'' Page said.
   Much of the show's photography is incredible, mostly because of
the contributions by such masters as Hugh Miles, formerly of the
BBC, and Wolfgang Bayer, based in Jackson Hole, Wyo. The music by
Broadway show composer Stephen Schwartz in several of the segments
more than makes up for some of the writing, which occasionally
smacks of the ``golly gee'' school of journalism.
   The series is produced in association with The Nature
Conservancy, one of the largest national conservation groups, which
buys property in ecologically endangered areas to save them from
development. An industry organization, the American Gas
Association, provides a grant, but most of the series' annual
budget of $3.4 million comes from Public Television Service
stations and public contributions.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Friday PMs, March 11</NOTE>
</DOC>
