<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 1325EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Thatcher-Revolution Adv20-2Takes   03-09 0808</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Thatcher-Revolution, Adv 20-2 Takes,0828</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv20</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, March 20 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP SPOTLIGHT: Margaret Thatcher _ A 20th Century Revolution</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds, the main story of a five-story package.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   She goes by old values: an honest day's work for
an honest day's pay ... live within your means ... save money for a
rainy day ... support the police. To Margaret Thatcher, that's also
the formula for the success of a nation. It is essentially the
basis for the Thatcher Revolution, which has put a staggering
Britain steady on its feet again. But her critics say it is at a
heavy price.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Far from losing steam after nearly nine years in
office, Margaret Thatcher is marching through her third consecutive
term as prime minister looking more confident and powerful than
ever.
   The 62-year-old Conservative Party leader has become such a
fixture on the political scene, here and abroad, that at times she
seems to be parodying the bossy, schoolmarmish image bestowed on
her by her critics.
   She'll let loose an outburst every so often _ ``I never did
understand men,'' she complained after an argumentative European
summit meeting. She'll chide the United States about balancing its
budget and badger her citizens about littering the streets.
   She advocates a return to ``Victorian values,'' supports the
restoration of the death penalty, has legislated curbs on the
promotion of homosexual lifestyles, and brandishes the Official
Secrets Act with a vigor that makes many critics fear for the
freedom of the British media.
   Now, eight months into a fresh five-year term, the blonde mother
of twins has governed continuously for longer than any other
British prime minister in the 20th century. In the process, she
says, she has wrought a revolution. It's a claim that not even her
severest critics now totally dismiss.
   ``She has taught us that you don't win ... unless you have a
clear ideological position,'' says Roy Hattersley, deputy leader of
the socialistic Labor Party, which went down to its third
successive election defeat by Mrs. Thatcher last June. ``We've made
authoritarianism look respectable _ or, rather, she has.''
   As the Thatcher Revolution surges on with shake-ups in state
education, housing and the once-sacrosanct National Health Service,
authoritarianism is the most frequent charge against her.
   But polls indicate that Mrs. Thatcher retains her trump card: a
feeling among the United Kingdom's 56 million people that, whether
or not they like her policies, no one is offering anything more
credible. The disarray in the left-of-center opposition gives her
an unassailable Parliament majority on just 42 percent of the
popular vote.
   The voting pattern illustrated the divisions and polarization
evident in Mrs. Thatcher's Britain. Tories swept the elections in
prosperous southern England but won not a single seat in the House
of Commons in the north's five major cities, where unemployment and
cuts in government spending are felt most acutely.
   ``She, more powerfully than anyone else, has articulated the
moral doubts and yearnings of her age,'' wrote Peter Jenkins, a
leading liberal analyst, in his recent book, ``Mrs. Thatcher's
Revolution.''
   ``For what people wanted, surely, was an end to decline, release
from the corrosive sense of failure, a government which governed
and a country to begin to be proud of once again.''
   Mrs. Thatcher feels her populist, anti-elitist instincts are
``absolutely in tune with how people feel ... not just in their
pockets, but in their bones, in their hearts and in their minds.
Deep in their instincts they find what I am saying and doing
right.''
   She attributes it all to what she learned from, her father,
Alfred Roberts, a smalltown grocer.
   ``My policies are based not on some economic theory, but on
things that I and millions like me were brought up with,'' she has
said.
   ``An honest day's work for an honest day's pay, live within your
means, put a nest egg by for a rainy day, pay your bills on time,
support the police.''
   Such is the message of her revolution.
   Her laws have curbed the labor unions and nurtured a new breed
of entrepreneurs who, like Mrs. Thatcher, are outsiders to the
establishment.
   Among the 200 richest Britons, self-made chain store
billionaires, computer whizkids and property tycoons outnumber the
landed aristocracy and other old money 2 to 1, according to Money
Magazine, a British publication.
   Britain, the strike-plagued ``sick man of Europe'' in the 60s
and 70s, is now ranked by Ambassador Toshio Yamazaki of Japan as an
Olympics gold-medalist of business with ``one of the great
reforming governments of the century.''
   ``I have noticed not only a genuine economic resurgence but also
a new attitude,'' Yamazaki told the 1988 convention of the British
Institute of Directors. ``The British seem to be enjoying success.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880309-0356 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 1327EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Thatcher-Revolution Adv20-1stAdd   03-09 0701</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Thatcher-Revolution, Adv 20-1st Add,0719</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv20</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, March 20 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>LONDON: enjoying success.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Unemployment is down from a peak 12 percent two years ago to 9.2
percent, lower than West Germany and France; inflation hovers
around 4 percent, down from more than 20 percent in the early
Thatcher years. Britain's economic growth topped the West European
league last year, while reins on state spending have produced a
series of trim, low-deficit budgets.
   Mrs. Thatcher has steadily chopped away at tax rates at the
highest income levels, which had reached 86 percent when she took
over from Prime Minister James Callaghan's Labor government in
1979. Her government succeeded in getting the top rate down to 60
percent and proposes to cut them even more this year.
   Currency exchange controls are gone, and the blossoming of the
City, London's financial district, into a global trading giant is
just one sign of the radically changed business climate.
   But not everybody is better off, and much remains unchanged in
Thatcher's Britain.
   A stubbornly class-conscious society survives with waiting lists
for expensive, private high schools swelled by the children of the
newly prosperous.
   People's accents still matter and are discussed _ including Mrs.
Thatcher's, because it sounds acquired.
   Critics who accuse Mrs. Thatcher of under-funding the National
Health Service in favor of private medicine point to the three
small children who died this year after heart surgery was delayed
for lack of nurses at Birmingham Children's Hospital.
   Nine years after a woman became prime minister, British women
are not noticeably better off. They still do most of the boring
low-paid jobs and earn an average of 145 pounds ($255) a week,
compared with 219.40 pounds ($386) for the average male.
   According to a survey published in February by the state-funded
Equal Opportunities Commission, women comprise 60 percent of bank
employees but only 2 percent of the administrative and managerial
staff. Mrs. Thatcher has never had a woman in her Cabinet.
   Says nurse Rebecca Malby, 24: ``I find her whole attitude
totally out of tune with what young women think ... her references
to the importance of staying home and raising children . .. the
poor pay of women-dominated professions.''
   Everything about the grocer's daughter, from her frilly blouses
and tinted hair to her right-wing views, offends a large section of
the intellectual and cultural establishment.
   ``Her odious suburban gentility and sentimental saccharine
patriotism caters to the worst elements of commuter idiocy,''
charges writer-director Jonathan Miller,
   The novelist Kingsley Amis retorts that the intellectuals are
simply snobs and says he detects resentment among the
intelligentsia that they, like the labor unions, are no longer
consulted by Mrs. Thatcher.
   Instead, she listens to small, right-wing think tanks like the
Institute for Economic Affairs, whose director, Graham Mather,
says: ``There's no doubt the free-market right has been taking the
offensive in recent years and has come to dominate much of the
policy discussion.
   ``The left, the collectivists, the socialists, the believers in
a corporate state, have almost opted out of the policy debate.''
   Internationally, Mrs. Thatcher has turned post-Empire Britain
into what commentator Brian Walden calls ``a medium-sized power _
with clout.''
   She is Washington's staunchest backer in the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization. In Western Europe, her partners in European
Economic Community may dislike her hectoring style and
preoccupation with budgets, but they no longer call Britain the
weakling in the group.
   She is the longest-serving leader in the NATO alliance, and
General Secretary Mikhail S. Gorbachev of the Soviet Union gave her
a red-carpet welcome in Moscow last spring. He stopped off to see
her in December on his way to meet President Reagan in Washington
to sign the treaty limiting nuclear weapons in Europe.
   ``If she sees herself as the de facto leader of the West, that
would give me not the slightest pain,'' former U.S. Secretary of
State Henry A. Kissinger wrote recently in London's Sunday
Telegraph.
   ``I would like that. I have great hopes that even if she is not
the founder of a new Western structure, she can at least do what
the Roman tribunes used to do _ prevent the worst from happening.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, March 20</NOTE>
