<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Thatcher-Milestones Adv20   03-09 0282</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Thatcher-Milestones, Adv 20,0301</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv20</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, March 20 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP SPOTLIGHT: Margaret Thatcher _ The Milestones</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: One of a five-story package.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are milestones in the life of Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher:
   Oct. 13, 1925 _ Born at Grantham, central England, the second
daughter of grocer Alfred Roberts.
   June 1947 _ Graduates from Oxford with a chemistry degree.
   Dec. 13, 1951 _ Marries Denis Thatcher, a wealthy oil executive.
   Aug. 15, 1953 _ Gives birth to twins, Mark and Carol.
   June 1, 1954 _ Qualifies as a barrister (lawyer).
   Oct. 8, 1959 _ Elected to Parliament.
   June 20, 1970 _ Appointed to the Cabinet as Education Secretary.
   Feb. 11, 1975 _ Elected leader of the Conservative Party, then
in opposition.
   May 3, 1979 _ Wins in general election and becomes prime
minister.
   May 15, 1980 _ Britain's inflation hits a record 21.9 percent.
   Jan. 26, 1982 _ Unemployment hits post-depression record of 3
million.
   April 2, 1982 _ Dispatches a task force that recovers the
Falkland Islands from Argentina after a 74-day war.
   June 3, 1983 _ Wins second five-year term.
   Oct. 12, 1984 _ Escapes an Irish Republican Army bombing that
kills 5 people and wounds 32.
   Nov. 15, 1985 _ Signs the Anglo-Irish Accord, granting the Irish
republic a say in Northern Ireland on behalf ot the Roman Catholic
minority.
   April 15, 1986 _ Allows U.S. planes to launch bombing of Libya
from Britain.
   March 28, 1987 _ Gets a red-carpet official visit to Moscow.
   June 11, 1987 _ Wins third five-year term.
   Jan. 3, 1988 _ Becomes Britain's longest continuously serving
prime minister this century.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, March 20</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880309-0358 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 1327EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Thatcher-Winner Adv20   03-09 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Thatcher-Winner, Adv 20,0397</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv20</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, March 20 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP SPOTLIGHT: Margaret Thatcher _ Some are Winners</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: One of a five-story package.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In six years, George Davies has turned a dowdy,
obscure clothing company into Britain's biggest retail success
story of Margaret Thatcher's revolution _ a $1.75-billion empire
for budget-conscious yuppies.
   Raised in a working-class family in Liverpool, Davies is chief
executive and chairman of Next, a chain of nearly 500 stores, and
epitomizes the ``go-getter'' society Prime Minister Thatcher seeks
to create.
   At 46, Davies is not just an entrepreneur but a man eagerly
sought by business experts and the media attempting to assess the
Thatcher Revolution. He typifies the new class of young, self-made
entrepreneurs who have benefited from the lower taxes and improved
business climate of the Thatcher years.
   ``I think the British do produce entrepreneurs, but perhaps the
climate eight years ago didn't let them come through,'' Davies said
in a recent British TV interview, referring to the time before Mrs.
Thatcher's Conservatives took over from the Labor Party.
   ``So if someone like myself who is basically a working-class lad
can start as I did on stock control of ankle socks and come through
and do things I've always dreamed of and have a team that is
equally positive, one's got to say something's going right,'' he
said.
   Davies worked in the clothing trade for nearly 20 years before
his big break.
   In 1981, as a new senior executive with Hepworths, a relatively
little known clothing company, he spotted a gap in the market
between pricy designer clothes and the mass production of the
established chains.
   The first Next store opened in Wales in 1982 and they now cover
Britain. A mail order service Davies launched this year was swamped
with $10.8 million worth of orders in the first three weeks.
   Company headquarters remain in Leicester, an industrial city in
central England town near where Davies lives with his second wife,
Liz, in a 200-year-old rectory.
   He works six days a week, including Saturday evenings when on
his home computer he flips through the weekly takings from stores
around the country.
   In un-British tradition, Next employees call him George.
   ``It's attitudes that are divisive, not money,'' he says.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, March 20</NOTE>
</DOC>
