<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Thatcher-Loser Adv20   03-09 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Thatcher-Loser, Adv 20,0397</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv20</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, March 20 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP SPOTLIGHT: Margaret Thatcher _ Some are Losers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: One of a five-story package</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At 24, Rebecca Malby is professionally a big
success, but she considers herself a loser in Margaret Thatcher's
revolution.
   Miss Malby is a nurse in charge of a 27-bed ward, mainly cardiac
patients, at Whipps Cross hospital in a predominantly working-class
district of the East End of London.
   On a salary of 9,000-pounds ($15,750) a year after seven years
on the job, including gaining a postgraduate diploma, she makes
roughly the same as a rookie policeman and about one-third less
than many London secretaries.
   Her home is a rented room in the house of two young doctors in
London's far-from-gentrified Stoke Newington district and her major
luxury is a second-hand car.
   She sees no prospect of buying her own apartment unless she
gives up the car, vacations and most entertainment.
   But she loves her job, enthuses about being young and in London,
believes passionately in the state-funded National Health Service,
plans to train as a nursing manager _ and thinks Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher simply doesn't care.
   ``We think twice about ordering a brain scan on stroke patients
now because of what it will cost,'' says Miss Malby, one of 515,000
nurses employed by the financially ailing state health service,
which is used by 90 percent of Britons.
   Mrs. Thatcher usually answers such criticism by showing
statistics she says prove spending on health has increased. She
says her aim is not to weaken the service but to streamline it by
shifting funds from the health bureaucracy to the patients.
   ``She (Mrs. Thatcher) has made us think much more about what
we're doing and there's nothing wrong with that,'' says Miss Malby.
``But we're on the edge now ... and she doesn't actually listen to
anybody. She is driven by ideology and just determined we're going
to have a mainly private health service.''
   Miss Malby says she's not tempted into another career and hasn't
seriously considered joining the hundreds of British nurses who
leave annually to double their pay in jobs in U.S. hospitals.
   ``When I think of them (the government) lowering taxes again for
wealthy people, it just seems a crime,'' she says.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, March 20</NOTE>
</DOC>
