<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Thatcher-Arts Adv20   03-09 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Thatcher-Arts, Adv 20,0384</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv20</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, March 20 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP SPOTLIGHT: Margaret Thatcher _ Enemies in the Arts</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: One of a five-story package</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In ``Wetherby,'' a 1985 movie about alienated
English intellectuals, a character ruminates tipsily on what
Margaret Thatcher is doing to his country.
   ``Revenge! That's what she's doing. ... Taking some terrible
revenge. ... And now the whole country is suffering. And yet we've
done nothing to her.''
   The outburst is almost a metaphor for the arts in Britain today
after nearly a decade of Thatcherism: enraged, unfocused, sometimes
venomous to a degree never experienced by a prime minister this
century.
   So deep is Mrs. Thatcher's imprint on society that she often
becomes a stage character in her own right, whether as a
cigar-chomping fascist in the satirical TV revue ``Spitting
Image,'' or as Nanny, leader of the rapacious, authoritarian Money
Party in Pete Davies's novel ``The Last Election.''
   Now she returns in the hit movie ``Sammy and Rosie Get Laid,''
which features a Thatcher speech on slum-clearance over footage of
an urban wasteland.
   Anti-Thatcherism is not confined to left-wing artists.
Conservative novelists also rail against Mrs. Thatcher's
``go-getter society,'' which they claim is drowning Ye Olde
Englande in a greedy money-and-fast-food culture.
   The spate of recent movies with anti-Thatcher messages provoked
an angry article in the Sunday Times by the right-wing historian
Norman Stone of Oxford University in which he claimed that ``the
done thing is to run down Mrs. Thatcher, to assume that capitalism
is parasitism, that the established order in this country is
imperialist, racist, profiteering.''
   Hanif Kureishi, who wrote the award-winning movie ``My Beautiful
Laundrette'' and the ``Sammy and Rosie'' film, responded by
accusing Stone of ``creative impotence and snobbishness.'' Kureishi
insisted the Britain shown in his films is authentic: ``An
intolerant, racist, homophobic, narrow-minded, authoritarian
rathole.''
   The cultural battle, observed the Economist magazine, signifies
``that Mrs. Thatcher is not just the first prime minister of the
century to have an `-ism' attached to her name. She is also
believed by her opponents ... to have so stamped her values on the
country that it has almost become a personal fief.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, March 20</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880309-0361 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 1417EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s w BC-WeeklyFarm Adv13   03-09 0850</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Farm, Adv 13,0871</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv13</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, March 13 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Old Farm Credit System May Be in Intensive Care for Some Time</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The creaky old Farm Credit System is being
rejuvenated, but it'll take a while before the 72-year-old
financial empire starts feeling its oats again.
   It's more than just a face lift, says an Agriculture Department
economist. More like a transplant of key innards, along with $4
billion worth of new blood and muscle.
   The surgery was performed by Congress in the Agricultural Credit
Act of 1987, which was signed into law by President Reagan on Jan.
6. Losses to the system totaled about $4.8 billion over the last
two years and the outlook was grim.
   Although other components came along later, a cornerstone of the
FCS since 1916 has been the federal land banks. Other parts include
intermediate credit banks and banks for cooperatives. Altogether,
some 37 banks and hundreds of local associations have made up the
system's cooperative network.
   In all, the FCS has a $50 billion loan portfolio representing
about a third of the U.S. farm debt.
   ``While federal assistance allows the FCS to operate in the
shortrun, the help is not cheap,'' says Merritt Hughes of the
department's Economic Research Service. ``Changes included a
reorganization of the system, additional rights for its borrowers,
and additional measures to ensure the institution's future.''
   Structurally, the FCS won't be the same. For example, within six
months the federal land banks and the federal intermediate credit
banks must merge. Other mergers between FCS institutions and
districts may follow, she said. The banks for cooperatives must
also decided whether to consolidate.
   The Farm Credit Administration (FCA), the federal agency that
oversees the cooperative system, will have expanded regulatory
responsibilities and powers ``along the lines of those already
existing for other types of financial institutions,'' Ms. Hughes
said.
   Newly created components will include an insurance corporation
to insure debt obligations of the system. A separate Farm Credit
Assistance Board has been formed to administer the federal bail-out
of the system and ensure that units getting aid take necessary
steps to reduce costs.
   A secondary market for agricultural real estate loans and
certain rural housing loans will be handled by a new autonomous
institution within FCS called the Federal Agricultural Mortgage
Corp., which already has been dubbed ``Farmer Mac,'' she said.
   ``Reorganizing the FCS will reduce overhead cost as the number
of FCS entities declines,'' Ms. Hughes said. ``Farmer Mac is
expected to bring in additional income.''
   Although there will be added costs associated with the new
administrative parts of FCS, the changes overall ``should result in
a more efficient implementation and delivery of loans'' to farmers,
she said.
   Insurance against operational failure will be targeted to a
number of areas, Ms. Hughes said. An internal fund will be created
to guarantee against default on system debt issuances.
   ``The new act requires FCS institutions to build up equity in
order to decrease interest rate exposure and stabilize net
income,'' she said. ``Banks will be able to charge loan origination
fees and issue non-voting, at-risk stock to raise the capital to
meet FCA-determined standards. Borrowers will not be allowed to
withdraw stock as their loans are repaid, and non-borrowers will be
able to purchase non-voting stock.''
   Ms. Hughes' analysis was reported in the March issue of
Agricultural Outlook magazine published by the USDA agency.
   The FCS's recent troubles resulted from two simultaneous
developments: the near-collapse in the farm economy, and the
system's issuance of long-term bonds with high interest rates, Ms.
Hughes said.
   How would the system react in the future under repeat
circumstances?
   ``The FCS will likely be more capable of coping with a
recurrence of the first or these problems as capital is rebuilt,''
she said. ``If proportionately more income is generated from loan
origination fees and the sale of non-insured stock, the adverse
consequences of borrower default will be less of an issue.''
   In the case of unanticipated high interest rates, the impact on
the FCS ``may not be substantially reduced'' by the new
legislation, Ms. Hughes said. The new requirements call for a high
level of capital that can be easily drawn on during downswings.
   `` The level of capital is probably not as important as the
stability of capital (immunity from investor flight), since prior
to the mid-1980s the system had developed very large capital stock
without legislative prompting,'' she said.
   One of the problems in the old FCS was an inability to shuttle
financial help from one bank to another.
   The former Capital Corporation mandated by a 1985 law, for
example, was able to assess about $300 million from the various
banks but was able to collect only $175 million and actually
dispensed only $10 million, Ms. Hughes said. Formerly, the sharing
of capital among FCS institutions was in conflict with
reponsibilities to stockholders.
   ``The 1987 act permits a more flexible organizational structure
while at the same time requiring continues, rather than sporadic,
shared financial responsibility,'' she said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, March 13</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880309-0362 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 0142EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   03-09 0510</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0531</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   R.H. Macy & Co. Inc. has begun its $6.1 billion
tender offer for Federated Department Stores Inc. and has gone to
court in hopes of torpedoing the competing $6.18 billion offer by
Campeau Corp.
   Macy filed suit Tuesday in federal court in Manhattan seeking an
injunction to bar Campeau from proceeding with its tender offer on
the grounds that Campeau's amended bid was actually a new offer and
as such must remain open beyond its scheduled expiration at
midnight March 15.
   Extending Campeau's bid would reduce the pressure on Federated
shareholders to decide between the rival Macy and Campeau offers,
effectively putting the Macy offer _ which expires April 4 _ on
better footing.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Higher stamp prices won't take effect until
next month at the earliest, postal officials say.
   The board of governors of the U.S. Postal Service decided
Tuesday to postpone a final decision on the effective date of the
new rates, and scheduled a special meeting for March 22 to discuss
putting the new rates into effect, effectively delaying the
increase until April 3 at the earliest.
   The new prices, recommended by the independent Postal Rate
Commission last Friday, would boost the first-class rate to 25
cents from 22 cents.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LANDOVER, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dart Group Corp. has abandoned its $1.03
billion takeover bid for Stop & Shop Cos. and says it will return
all tendered shares to Stop & Shop stockholders.
   Stop & Shop announced on Feb. 29 it had agreed to be acquired in
a $1.23 billion leveraged buyout by the investment firm of Kohlberg
Kravis Roberts Inc.
   Dart's tender offer expires at midnight Wednesday and will not
be extended, Dart said Tuesday in a one-paragraph announcement.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appellate panel has upheld a lower
court's finding that there was no evidence General Motors Corp.
knowingly sold 1.1 million 1980 X-cars with alleged brake defects.
   The panel of the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals on Tuesday
affirmed U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson's 1987
rejection of government claims that the cars had an inherent defect
that caused rear brakes to lock up prematurely and spin out of
control under certain circumstances.
</TEXT>
