<1ST_LINE>r f PM-EconomyRdp     03-09 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Up; Dollar Falls</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A key stock market indicator has risen to its highest level
since the October market crash, even as the dollar slipped further
against foreign currencies.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 24.70 points to
close Tuesday at 2,081.07, its highest level since the Oct. 19
crash.
   Other market indices also rose, as two stocks advanced for every
one that fell on the New York Stock Exchange.
   Wall Street analysts said the rally partly reflected a desire by
managers of institutional investment funds to put unused money to
work as the first quarter draws to a close at the end of this month.
   Others said the increased interest in stocks reflected true
buying interest and waning anxiety by investors over the impact of
the October collapse, along with optimism over indications that the
economy is thriving.
   But many professional strategists were reluctant to declare that
the underlying post-crash nervousness has evaporated.
   In the currency markets, the dollar continued to slide as the
British pound soared and other major currencies took their cue from
sterling. Analysts said the British currency was buoyed by high
interest rates and the strength of the country's economy.
   Sterling rose to $1.8425 on Tuesday in New York from $1.8180
late Monday and has gained nearly 7 cents against the dollar in two
days.
   In the credit markets, bond prices finished little changed with
the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond ending the day barely below
where it ended Monday's trading session.
   Oil futures prices rose slightly in response to calls for
meetings among oil-producing nations over production and price
issues.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, contracts for April
delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the U.S. benchmark crude oil,
settled at $15.45 per 42-gallon barrel, up 8 cents from Monday's
close.
  
</TEXT>
