<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 0144EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     03-09 0241</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0251</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Firm on Reports for Meetings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil prices have firmed slightly in response to
calls for meetings among oil-producing nations.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, contracts for April
delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the U.S. benchmark crude oil,
settled at $15.45 per barrel Tuesday, up 8 cents from Monday's
close.
   Among refined products, wholesale heating oil gained 0.08 cent
to 43.49 cents a gallon. Near-term contracts for wholesale gasoline
dipped 0.23 cent to 43.71 cents a gallon.
   Analysts said longer-term contracts for both crude and the
products were stronger, reflecting sentiment that key world oil
producers may yet agree on ways to limit production and stabilize
prices.
   In gasoline, for example, the September contract gained 0.41
cent to 43.70 cents a gallon on hopes for firmer prices and a
strong summer driving season.
   Helping support prices Tuesday was Egypt's announcement that
non-OPEC oil producers would meet today in London. Venezuela also
reportedly called for more future meetings of the 13-nation
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries, analysts said.
   Members of both groups appear anxious to address the problem of
price discounting by some oil producers, said Bob Baker, an analyst
for Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   But analysts said meetings alone would not dissolve the world's
oil glut.
   ``There will have to be some kind of results or we'll continue
to see these kinds of prices,'' said John Hill of Merrill Lynch
Energy Futures.
</TEXT>
