<DOCNO> AP880309-0367 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 0149EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Dart-Stop&Shop Bjt   03-09 0426</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dart-Stop & Shop, Bjt,0436</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dart Drops Stop & Shop Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LANDOVER, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dart Group Corp.'s decision to drop its
hostile $1.03 billion takeover offer for Stop & Shop Cos. marks the
latest of Dart's series of unsuccessful but profitable attempts to
acquire a major retailing chain.
   Dart said in a brief statement Tuesday that it would let its $37
a share tender offer expire at midnight EST tonight return all
tendered shares to Stop & Shop stockholders.
   Stop & Shop, a supermarket and discount department store
operator, said Feb. 29 it had agreed to be acquired in a $44 a
share, $1.23 billion leveraged buyout led by the investment firm
Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co.
   A Dart spokesman, who did not wish to be identified, said the
Landover, Md.-based company felt it was ``uneconomic to bid
further.''
   Dart, which owns about 2.7 percent of Stop & Shop's 27.9 million
common shares outstanding, nevertheless stands to profit from its
abortive takeover try.
   Dart reportedly acquired its 730,000 Stop & Shop shares at
prices below $20 a share, giving them a potential pre-tax gain of
at least $17.5 million if it tendered its shares under the
company's buyout.
   Stop & Shop closed at $43.50 a share Tuesday on the New York
Stock Exchange, down 12{ cents from Monday's close.
   Dart, which had launched its takeover bid with a $31 a share
offer on Feb. 1, in recent years has developed a reputation as a
corporate raider that launches hostile takeover bids and later
pockets huge profits by selling its stock to another suitor or to
the target company.
   Dart since 1985 has been spurned in takeover bids by several
major retailers, including Safeway, Beatrice Cos., Supermarkets
General Corp. and Dayton Hudson Corp.
   The company, which owns the Crown Books and Trak Auto Parts
retail chains, has maintained it wanted to acquire a major retail
chain as part of its long-term strategy.
   In addition to the Kohlberg Kravis buyout agreement, Dart faced
another obstacle in Stop & Shop's federal lawsuit to block the
hostile tender offer. Stop & Shop accused Dart of failing to
disclose that its purpose in making the bid was to boost the stock
price of the target company in order to make a speculative profit.
   Boston-based Stop & Shop owns 113 Stop & Shop supermarkets and
169 Bradlees discount department stores. In a leveraged buyout,
investors borrow heavily to buy out a company and then pay off the
debt with the target company's cash flow or the sale of its assets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
