<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Firestone     03-09 0215</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Firestone,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge To Review Ohio Takeover Law In Firestone-Pirelli Battle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has set a hearing for next week
to review the constitutionality of Ohio's anti-takeover law, but
has refused to immediately prevent Firestone Tire & Rubber Co. from
using the law to thwart a $1.86 billion buyout bid from Italian
tiremaker Pirelli.
   Judge Alice Batchelder rejected Pirelli's request for a
temporary restraining order against the law and set a hearing for
next Monday to review the statute's constitutionality.
   Attorneys for Pirelli Societe Generale SA went to U.S. District
Court in Cleveland on Monday in an effort to prevent Firestone from
using provisions of the Ohio Takeover Act, which attempts to hinder
hostile buyouts.
   Firestone rejected an earlier merger proposal from Pirelli in
favor of a venture under which it will sell 75 percent of its core
tire business to Bridgestone Corp. of Japan. That rejection led the
Italian tiremaker to launch its unsolicited tender offer for
Firestone on Monday.
   John J. Nevin, chairman of Firestone, stated late Monday that
the company's board was reviewing the offer and asking shareholders
to await its recommendation before deciding whether to tender their
stock to Pirelli, which is based in Milan.
   The board will complete its review by March 18, Nevin said.
</TEXT>
