<1ST_LINE>d f PM-FordProfit-Sharing     03-09 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ford Profit-Sharing,0477</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ford Workers Receive 1987 Profit-Sharing Checks</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DT3 of March 8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIVONIA, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mark Peabody's share of Ford Motor Co.'s
profits will go into a house he is building for his family. Mike
Heaslip is taking his to Las Vegas and Josephine Aftanas plans to
use hers for her daughter's May wedding.
   Many of the 4,500 Livonia Transmission plant employees already
had plans for their portion of the $635 million in profit-sharing
checks that Ford distributed Tuesday to 156,479 U.S. workers.
   Ford earned an industry-record $4.6 billion in 1987 and
distributions to workers jumped by 70 percent to an average of more
than $3,700, up from $2,100 in 1986 when Ford earned a
company-record $3.29 billion.
   Most Ford workers received their checks Tuesday morning. But
Peabody and his colleagues on the main transmission assembly line
at the Livonia plant agreed to wait until Ford Vice Chairman Harold
Poling arrived for a Tuesday afternoon ceremony.
   ``It's not only the politicians who can call this Super
Tuesday,'' Poling told a crowd of cheering workers. He noted that
the plant's 4,500 employees received $17.6 million, or an average
of $4,450 each.
   ``You helped make 1987 one of the most remarkable years _ and
certainly the most profitable _ in the history of Ford Motor Co.,''
Poling said before he and a retinue of reporters and executives
walked to the assembly line.
   The Livonia Transmission workers' checks were larger than the
company average because most workers have high seniority and few
new, younger workers have been hired there, said Ford Vice
President Peter Pestillo.
   Workers on that line assemble transmissions for
front-wheel-drive cars such as the popular Taurus-Sable and the new
Lincoln Continental.
   Most of them said they are lucky to be there at all. Most were
on layoff from other plants and had enough seniority to be called
to work at Livonia when Ford added the line three years ago.
   Ford withheld the checks of about 2,244 workers under a court
order for payment of delinquent child support. All but 50 of those
workers live in Michigan. The others live in Jefferson County, Ky.,
Ford spokesman Mike Moran said.
   More than 160,250 Ford workers in the United States received
profit-sharing checks in 1986. Ford workers took home an average
$2,100 in profit-sharing for 1985, $2,000 for 1984 and $400 for
1983, when the company distributed the first checks.
   General Motors Corp. workers received no share of GM's $3.56
billion in 1987 profits, though the corporation said it would
distribute $184.6 million in stock bonuses to executives.
   GM, the nation's largest automaker, switched to the Ford
profit-sharing formula for 1988, but said that formula would have
generated no profit-sharing distributions had it been used for 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
