<HEAD>P&G, Syntex In Joint Pharmaceutical Venture</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Procter & Gamble Co. has entered a joint
venture with Syntex Corp. of Palo Alto, Calif., increasing the
Cincinnati-based consumer products company's involvement in the
pharmaceutical industry.
   The companies will work to bring Naprosyn, Syntex's popular
prescription arthritis treatment, to the over-the-counter market.
   P&G officials have joined Syntex's talks with the Food and Drug
Administration concerning wider distribution of Naprosyn, Kathleen
Gary, Syntex vice president of public affairs, said Tuesday.
   Once the venture is under way, Syntex will benefit from P&G's
expertise in marketing over-the-counter drugs, she said.
   Syntex and P&G have indicated their work on Naprosyn would be
the first of several joint projects. The companies said they are
``engaged in a series of other broad ranging discussions regarding
further collaboration.''
   Neither P&G representative Pam Sussman nor Ms. Gary could
provide details on what kind of ventures the companies might be
planning.
   Naprosyn and a related product called Anaprox are Syntex's
biggest sellers, accounting for more than half of its $1.3 billion
in annual sales. Naprosyn is sold in more than 80 countries.
