<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 0819EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-EEC-Trade     03-09 0212</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EEC-Trade,0220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kohl Warns Against U.S. Protectionism</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STRASBOURG, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl on
Wednesday called upon the U.S. Congress to recognize Europe's
contribution to liberalizing world trade and refrain from
protectionist legislation.
   In a speech to the European Parliament, Kohl said the European
Economic Community's recent decisions to cut back farm production
set an example for Washington to follow.
   ``We are confident the Congress will understand our measures and
therefore should refrain from all protectionist legislation,'' he
said.
   Kohl referred to a decision by the leaders of the 12-nation EEC
last month to cut spending on agricultural subsidies as a means of
curbing the production of food Europe can neither consume nor sell.
   Speaking as the current EEC president, Kohl hailed the Feb. 13
decision of the Brussels summit as a turning point in the EEC's
31-year history.
   He also outlined to the Parliament a long list of measures his
government plans to push through before the end of its EEC
presidency on June 30. Among them were plans for complete
liberalization of capital movements, opening of the insurance and
financial services to international competition and harmonization
of technical standards.
   ``The internal market will develop only if we coordinate our
economic, financial and monetary policies,'' Kohl said.
</TEXT>
