<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 1019EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Federated 1stLd-Writethru   03-09 0700</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Federated, 1st Ld-Writethru,0720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Macy, Beginning Its Tender Offer, Sues To Block Campeau Bid</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS final 5 grafs with 8 grafs to update with Macy SEC
filing, stock price.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   R.H. Macy & Co. Inc. has taken its battle for
Federated Department Stores Inc. to the marketplace and to the
courts.
   Macy, which last week agreed to a $6.1 billion buyout of
Federated, on Tuesday began a tender offer for 80 percent of the
Cincinnati-based retailer's common stock.
   Macy also asked a federal court for an injunction to block the
rival $6.18 billion buyout offer from Campeau Corp., contending
Campeau's bid _ which was revised from an earlier offer _ actually
constituted a new offer and as such must remain open beyond its
scheduled expiration at midnight EST March 15.
   Extending Campeau's bid would reduce the pressure on Federated
shareholders to decide between the rival Macy and Campeau offers,
effectively putting the Macy offer _ which expires April 4 _ on
more equal footing.
   Campeau, a Toronto-based real estate developer and retailer, is
offering $75 in cash per share for 80 percent of Federated's stock
and $44 in cash per share for the remaining 20 percent. The Campeau
bid, which has an aggregate value of $68 per share, totals $6.18
billion.
   Until March 2, when Campeau officially announced its two-tier
bid, the company had offered $68 in cash outright for each of
Federated's 89.6 million outstanding shares.
   ``In order to increase the pressure on Federate's stockholders,
defendants have unlawfully treated their new two-tier offer as a
`mere' amendment to their prior tender offer,'' Macy contended in
court papers.
   Because of the two-stage price structure, Campeau's latest
proposal bears little resemblance to its original bid and should
therefore be treated as a new offer, Macy argued.
   Under federal law, a new offer would have to remain open for at
least 20 business days after publication or submission to
stockholders. If Campeau's bid is considered a new offer, it could
not legally expire on March 15 as scheduled.
   Macy asked the court to block the Campeau offer from closing
before stockholders had a sufficient amount of time to review
materials and to evaluate the changes included in the new bid.
   Macy's tender offer will pay $74.50 per share in cash for up to
70.43 million shares, or approximately 80 percent of Federated
common stock. Macy plans to swap shares in a new company,
Macy's-Federated Inc., for the remaining 20 percent of Federated's
shares.
   The Macy offer expires at midnight EST April 4. Analysts
estimate it is worth $6.1 billion.
   Macy revealed in a filing with the Securities and Exchange
Commission Tuesday that under the Macy-Federated agreement,
Federated executives have the option of being paid in cash for all
of their shares in the company, instead of the cash-and-stock offer
being made to the public. The price to be paid for the executives'
stock was $73.80 per share, slightly less than the cash price in
the tender offer.
   Federated stock was up 37{ cents to $66.37{ a share in early New
York Stock Exchange trading today.
   In a separate SEC filing Monday detailing its latest bid,
Campeau revealed that Federated had received six offers for its
Ralphs supermarkets division in California. The bids ranged from
$800 million to $990 million, including a $955 million offer by
Ralphs management, Campeau said.
   Macy also said in its SEC filing that it expected Ralphs to be
sold.
   Whoever ends up acquiring Federated is also likely to sell the
company's other non-department store divisions, Gold Circle
discount stores and Main Street and Children's Place specialty
stores.
   Campeau announced last week it had agreed to sell Federated's
Foley's and Filene's department store divisions to the May
Department Stores Co. if its tender offer succeeded.
   Federated, the nation's fifth-largest retailer, also owns
department stores including Bloomingdale's, Lazarus, Rich's,
Abraham & Straus, Bullock's and Burdine's.
   In its SEC filing, Macy said it expected some department store
divisions would be sold, but it did not elaborate. Analysts expect
Macy, which has nearly 100 department and specialty stores of its
own, to sell Federated Rich's and Abraham & Straus divisions.
</TEXT>
