<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Belgium-Takeovers     03-09 0218</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Belgium-Takeovers,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Belgian Government Seeking Anti-Takeover Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government is trying to push
legislation through the Belgian Parliament to control corporate
raiders in the wake of the takeover battle for Societe Generale de
Belgique SA, officials said Wednesday.
   The law would make it mandatory for an investor to disclose a
shareholding in a publicly-listed Belgian company once the stake
reaches 10 percent of the total voting stock. Further disclosures
would be required for each increment of 5 percent.
   If approved, the law would be effective from March 1, 1988
through Dec. 31, 1989 and would apply to Belgian companies with a
minimum equity of 200 million francs, the equivalent of $5.71
million.
   The bill will be examined by a committee on Thursday and be put
to a parliamentary vote next week, Marc De Backer, a Finance
Ministry spokesman, said.
   The absence in Belgium of legislation to control raiders allowed
the Italian investor Carlo De Benedetti to build up a direct and
indirect stake of 18.6 percent in Societe Generale before
announcing his bid on Jan. 18 for effective control of the firm,
which is Belgium's largest holding company.
   In the ensuing battle, the other major Societe Generale
shareholder, Cie. Financiere de Suez of France, bought its stake of
20 percent in similar secrecy.
</TEXT>
