<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet11am     03-09 0251</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 11am,0265</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market edged upward today, struggling
to extend Tuesday's rally.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up 24.70 on Tuesday,
gained .66 to 2,081.73 by 11 a.m. today on Wall Street.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 3 to 2 in the overall tally
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 788 up, 528 down and
461 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 72.23 million shares at
midmorning.
   Confidence has continued to spread lately on Wall Street that
the economy remains healthy nearly five months after Black Monday
on Oct. 19.
   In addition, stock prices have been less volatile lately than
they were as recently as early January, suggesting that investors'
mood is less subject to sudden change.
   Analysts say investing institutions have grown more eager to put
some of their cash reserves into stocks, in order to show in their
first-quarter reports to clients that they participated in the
recent market rally.
   Still, many observers wonder how much stock might be for sale at
higher prices by investors sitting with paper losses and waiting
for an opportune time to get out of the market.
   Japanese stocks were mostly higher following an up day in the
Tokyo market. Matsushita Electrical climbed 4} to 200{ and Honda
Motor gained 2~ to 129~.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.31 to 151.93. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up 1.65 at 297.69.
