<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 1136EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s f BC-ForeignBosses Adv13   03-09 1155</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Foreign Bosses, Adv 13,1194</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 13</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday March 13 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Gradually Foreign Bosses Are Learning American Ways</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto, LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   C. Robert Powell ought to be taking orders from
Tokyo. Last year, the 60-year-old chief executive became one of the
first Americans to see his company seized by the Japanese in a
hostile takeover.
   So why is Powell still telling his Japanese bosses how he
intends to run things at Reichhold Chemicals Inc.? Simple, he says.
He knows the American market and they don't.
   ``In Japan they have `harmony': a closed industry; you don't cut
prices. I told them `harmony' in the U.S. is six years in
Leavenworth.''
   More than 3 million Americans work for businesses that have at
least 10 percent foreign ownership, and their numbers are rising
rapidly as foreigners snap up U.S. properties with the dollars
earned from their huge trading surpluses.
   The bosses include Italians in Indiana, Swedes in Georgia,
Canadians in Vermont and West Germans in California. The businesses
range from cars to cement.
   But people like Robert Powell in White Plains, N.Y., prove that
working for a foreign boss doesn't necessarily mean giving up the
American way of life.
   After one tough discussion with a superior from Dainippon Ink
and Chemicals Inc., Powell says he was told by a lower-level
Japanese, ``Mr. Maeda doesn't like to argue with you.''
   ``I said, `Fine, tell him not to argue with me.'''
   Foreign companies such as Dainippon are learning to adapt to
American ways, a lesson in flexibility learned years ago by U.S.
companies such as International Business Machines Corp. when they
went global.
   ``We're really babies at working with each other,'' said
Clifford Clarke, president of IRI International Inc. in Redwood
City, Calif., a consulting firm specializing in U.S.-Japanese
management issues.
   The first step in a corporate relationship is denial of
differences. The second step is ``throwing names at each other.''
The third step is understanding, and the final step is taking
advantage of the differences, Clarke said.
   ``Out of the diversity comes the best decisions,'' Clarke said.
``That's as American as apple pie.''
   Fretting about foreign bosses seems to be more common among
people who don't have them _ presidential candidates, for example _
than people who do have them, such as Wayne Hancock, who works for
a Bridgestone Corp. tire plant in La Vergne, Tenn.
   ``It's been real enjoyable working with the Japanese,'' Hancock,
an accounting manager, said recently. ``It's not like an American
company. There's a lot more emphasis here on the quality of the
product. ... They're more people-oriented.''
   Bridgestone's relations with the union are so good that the
United Rubber Workers flag flies next to the Bridgestone flag in La
Vergne.
   Some problems do arise when the boss lives in another country.
Differences in language and culture can inhibit communication, and
there are ceilings at some companies on how high Americans can
advance.
   In Barre, Vt., David Cuttler was worried that his way up at
Quebec-based Bombardier Inc. was blocked by his trouble learning
French. Now his worries have eased.
   ``After you work together for a while, you tend not even to
distinguish Americans and Canadians. You're all part of the same
team,'' said Cuttler, production manager for a factory that builds
train cars. ``It's nice to speak French, but it's not necessary.''
   The leading states for foreign employers are California, New
York, Texas, New Jersey and Pennsylvania, according to 1985 figures
that are the most recent available.
   Japanese employers get most of the publicity even though they
ranked only fifth in U.S. employment in 1985, behind British,
Canadians, West Germans and Dutch.
   Japanese ranked far ahead of British, West Germans and Arabs in
a poll asking which were the best U.S. employers. The poll was
released this past week by Smick-Medley & Associates Inc., a
Washington-based consulting firm.
   One reason for Japan's high profile _ think of the movie ``Gung
Ho'' _ is that Japanese are likely to mold companies in their own
image. Europeans often remain at arm's length from their U.S.
holdings.
   Italian executives of Ferruzzi Group have paid only two visits
to the Fort Wayne, Ind., headquarters of food processor Central
Soya Inc. since buying the company last year. And that suits David
Swanson just fine.
   ``It would be foolish of Americans to try to implant certain of
their systems on Europeans _ and vice versa,'' said Swanson,
Central Soya's president and chief executive.
   Europeans are not always so invisible: West Germany's BASF AG
has had labor problems in West Virginia, Michigan, New York and New
Jersey, and chemical workers in Geismar, La., are just now
trickling back to work after a company lockout that began in 1984.
   BASF says its labor policies in the United States are set
locally, but the Oil, Chemical and Atomic Workers union charges
that the decisions are made in Ludwigshafen.
   ``In West Germany, it's illegal to lock your employees out. What
they've been able to do here they would not have been able to do in
their own country,'' said Ernest Rousselle, a union representative.
   Both Europeans and Japanese have elaborate employment guarantees
at home _ the Europeans by law, the Japanese more by tradition.
Americans sometimes feel cheated when the companies are not as
protective when they do business in the United States.
   More than 130 people in the San Diego area sued Japan's Kyocera
International Inc. after they were laid off in 1980, claiming they
had been promised lifetime employment. They lost but have appealed.
   More typical are complaints from ambitious American executives
that their road to the top has been blocked, such as the pending
lawsuit by Thomas McDannold and Edward Neubauer against NEC America
Inc. in Mountain View, Calif.
   Potential for cultural conflict is probably greatest on Wall
Street, where buttoned-down Japanese managers try to deal with
freewheeling American recruits, and vice versa.
   ``You need a kind of cowboy mentality,'' said Gregory V.
Coggiano, an executive with Nomura Securities International Inc.,
``but you've got to be a team player as well.''
   A consensus is developing among management experts that foreign
owners would be wise to adapt their homegrown methods to the ways
of Americans. At Bridgestone, for example, Japanese stopped doing
early-morning exercises in the parking lot when only a few
Americans joined in.
   The result, as Bridgestone's human resources adviser Seiji Ohtsu
describes it, may be a ``third approach'' _ a blending of good
ideas, foreign and domestic.
   As such things as quality circles and flexible job
classifications become standard operating procedure here, having a
foreign boss may no longer seem quite so unusual.
   In Japan's case, said labor analyst Harley Shaiken of the
University of California at San Diego, ``The real, key issue isn't
so much how Japanese companies are different, it's the enormous
influence they have had on U.S. firms.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday March 13</NOTE>
</DOC>
