<DOCNO> AP880309-0381 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 1145EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s f BC-ForeignBosses-Bar Adv13   03-09 0570</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Foreign Bosses-Bar, Adv 13,0585</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 13</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday March 13 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>In Manhattan Hideaway, Japanese Execs Unwind And `Affiliate'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Foreign Bosses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It is a place few Americans ever see, a plush
lounge where Japanese executives spend $100 an evening to sip
whiskey, flirt with pretty hostesses and maybe take a turn singing
to the accompaniment of a baby grand piano.
   The piano bar _ ``pianoba'' in Japanese _ is the one place where
Japanese executives lower their reserve, speak frankly and
consolidate working relationships with their colleagues and
customers.
   ``In the office, nothing moves. In the piano bar, everything
moves,'' a Japanese executive said late into a recent Friday
evening at one club in midtown Manhattan.
   Americans other than ethnic Japanese are generally not welcome
at a piano bar unless they are in the company of Japanese. Piano
bars do not advertise. The only way to get in is to know where one
is _ and then to be able to read the message in Japanese on a small
piece of paper telling customers to ring three times for admittance.
   Americans are accustomed to being the outsiders when they go to
Japan to do business. But at a piano bar, Americans are outsiders
in the middle of New York City.
   ``If you're not invited, you're being cut out of something,''
said a young American who speaks Japanese, works for a Japanese
trading company and occasionally goes to piano bars.
   ``More business is done after 5 o'clock in these bars than is
done during business hours. Because that's when people can have a
couple of drinks and really say what's on their minds,'' the
American said, speaking on condition that he not be identified.
   The piano bar does not start to fill up until after 9 p.m. or
so, when executives drift over after work and dinner. The $100 does
not pay for food, except for light snacks. It doesn't even cover
drinks: Regulars have bottles of expensive scotch kept for them in
a closet.
   The $100 does cover the attentions of the hostesses, young women
who sit on stools and light guests' cigarettes, freshen their
drinks and engage in flirtatious small talk. Most are from Japan or
elsewhere in the Far East; others are Americans or Europeans.
   Lest the guests become too bored or too bold, the hostesses are
shuttled from table to table by the mama-san, who is dressed in a
traditional kimono.
   When their names are called out, men stride up to the microphone
and sing the song of their choice, usually in Japanese. Among songs
in English, a favorite is ``My Way,'' a la Frank Sinatra.
   The importance of the piano bar to Japanese business should not
be underestimated, said Clifford Clarke, president of IRI
International Inc., a Redwood City, Calif-based consulting firm
specializing in U.S.-Japanese management issues.
   While Americans prize achievement above all, Japanese give the
most weight to personal relationships, which are forged in piano
bars and their less-expensive cousins, the karaoke bars, Clarke
said.
   ``We talk about after 5 in the bars as being social. They don't
separate private life and work life,'' Clarke said. ``It's not felt
that after-hours time is play time.
   ``A lot of Americans feel that Japanese never give direct
feedback. Well, that's what the evenings are for,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday March 13</NOTE>
</DOC>
