<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 1214EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   03-09 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0329</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices opened mixed
today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Soybean futures opened higher but quickly turned lower in
response to reduced spot market prices for soybeans, soybean oil
and soybean meal, analysts said.
   Wheat futures opened lower on follow-through selling from
Tuesday but soon turned higher as the reduced prices brought in
buyers.
   Wheat futures prices have been trending lower recently due to
uncertainty about future U.S. export sales, especially large
shipments under the government's Export Enhancement Program,
analysts said.
   ``We've got some business but we're in need of some new EEP
business,'' said Dale Gustafson of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   Corn futures weakened on increased farmer selling, Gustafson
said. But Algeria and South Korea both had purchase bids pending,
and sales of U.S. corn to those countries could boost corn futures,
he said.
   In early trading, wheat was \ cent to 1 cent higher with the
contract for delivery in March at $3 a bushel; corn was 1\ cent
lower to \ cent higher with March at $2.00\ a bushel; oats were \
cent to } cent lower with March at $1.91} a bushel; soybeans were {
cent to 2{ cents lower with March at $6.14{ a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mixed while pork futures were mostly lower
in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .25 cent lower to .15 cent higher with April at
72.92 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent lower to .08 cent
higher with March at 81.05 cents a pound; hogs were .28 cent lower
to .03 cent higher with April at 43.75 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .40 cent to .77 cent lower with March at 53.32 cents a
pound.
   Cattle and hog futures closed higher Tuesday while frozen pork
belly futures retreated.
</TEXT>
