<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Grumman     03-09 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Grumman,0230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grumman Announces 700 Layoffs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BETHPAGE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grumman Corp. today announced that it will
lay off about 700 employees and eliminate another 1,900 jobs due to
declining business in aircraft engineering and manufacturing.
   In an open letter to employees, Grumman President John O'Brien
said the reductions were prompted by the loss of a recent
competition for a new aircraft program, production delays caused by
defense budget reductions, and uncertainty about the funding of the
A-6 aircraft.
   However, O'Brien said, ``The airplane business is the backbone
of our company, and we're in it to stay.'' He said the company was
investing millions of dollars in research for future aircraft.
   Six hundred employees will lose their jobs at the Aircraft
Systems, Aerostructures, Data Systems and Electronics Systems
divisions on Long Island, N.Y.; another 100 layoffs are planned for
Aircraft Systems facilities in Milledgeville, Ga., and Stuart,
Fla., and the Systems Division in Melbourne, Fla.
   An additional 1,900 jobs will eliminated nationally through
attrition, coupled with a reduction in part-time and temporary
workers, the company said.
   The largest part of the layoff will occur by the middle of
April, with the remainder spread over the remaining months of the
year, Grumman said.
   Grumman said hiring has already been sharply curtailed and is
now essentially limited to people with specialized skills.
</TEXT>
