<DOCNO> AP880309-0387 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 1351EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-HousingConstruction     03-09 0267</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Housing Construction,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Housing Construction Falls Sharply In 1987</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing construction plunged 14 percent in 1987
from the previous year as rising interest rates and high apartment
vacancies took their toll on the industry, a survey released
Wednesday showed.
   The report by the F.W. Dodge Division of McGraw-Hill Information
Systems Co. said nationwide housing starts fell to 1.58 million
units from 1.84 million units in 1986.
   It noted that only three of the nation's top 10 metropolitan
areas _ Washington, D.C., Detroit and Philadelphia _ showed any
pickup in construction activity last year.
   ``High vacancy rates and high mortgage rates took a heavy toll
of apartment and one-family building alike last year,'' said George
A. Christie, chief economist for F.W. Dodge.
   Christie said the apartment surplus, which he describes as ``a
hangover from early '80's tax shelters,'' was likely to persist
this year but that a drop in interest rates after the Oct. 19 stock
market crash has improved the outlook for construction of
single-family homes.
   Leading the nation in 1987 housing construction was Washington,
with 52,045 units, up 1 percent from 1986. The Los Angeles-Long
Beach area ranked second with 50,052 units, although activity
decreased 32 percent from the previous year.
   The rest of the nation's top 10 housing areas for 1987 were:
Atlanta, 46,333 units, down 12 percent; Riverside-San Bernadino,
Calif., 41,282, down 20 percent; Chicago, 30,189, down 6 percent;
Phoenix, Ariz., 27,216, down 37 percent; San Diego, Calif., 27,011,
down 34 percent; Minneapolis-St. Paul, 26,219, down 5 percent;
Detroit, 26,009, up 1 percent; and Philadelphia, 25,366, up 1
percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
