<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 1853EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Sweden-Merger     03-09 0562</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sweden-Merger,0582</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Swedish Companies Discussing Takeover Worth $990 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stora AB, a forestry products company,
offered Wednesday to pay the equivalent of $990 million for Swedish
Match AB, the world's leading manufacturer of lighters and wooden
matches.
   The offer of 5.94 billion kronor was the biggest cash takeover
bid ever in Sweden, but was widely criticized as being far below
the value of Swedish Match, which also has major interests in home
interior and consumer products.
   Both companies are dominated by investment companies controlled
by the wealthy industrialist Wallenberg family. One group controls
85 percent of Swedish Match, and the other holds a major voting
holding in Stora, which has Peter Wallenberg, the family patriarch,
as its board chairman.
   A merger would create one of Sweden's largest companies, with
annual sales of 36 billion kronor, or about $6 billion, and more
than 55,000 employees.
   Analysts said Stora wants to diversify its paper, pulp and power
operations and improve its access to the European Economic
Community.
   Brian Knox, a Scandinavian specialist at Kleinwort Grievson, a
London brokerage, said the bid was far below the range of what
Swedish Match is worth.
   ``If Match were a London company, it would be putting up a
vigorous defense,'' he said. ``But because of the huge (Wallenberg)
position, there will be a tendency for people to just shut their
eyes and enjoy it.''
   Peter Wallenberg conceded after a news conference that the price
was disputed at meetings of the two companies' boards, but he said
it reflected a fair value for Swedish Match.
   Both companies released 1987 financial results Wednesday showing
strong gains in profit. Stora said its pre-tax profit climbed 39
percent to 2.57 billion kronor from 1.85 billion kronor the
preceding year. Swedish Match had a 26 percent rise in profit to
628 million kronor from 500 million.
   Swedish Match was taken over by the Wallenberg family, along
with several other companies, after financier Ivar Kreuger's empire
collapsed and he committed suicide in Paris in 1932. Swedish Match
had created a virtual monopoly in the market for wooden matches and
now also dominates in lighters.
   It later expanded into consumer products and housing products.
Its Tarkett group is the world's second largest producer of
flooring material.
   Analysts noted that Sweden's two other major forestry product
companies recently diversified their operations through
acquisitions. Svenska Cellulosa AB bought the French diaper company
Peaudouce, and Mo-Och Domsjoe AB acquired Holmens Bruk AB, a
Swedish newsprint producer.
   Hans Larsson, chief executive of Swedish Match, said adding the
financial strength of Stora would help in future acquisitions.
   ``We will now have a very rich parent company,'' he said.
``We'll be on the offensive now, as we have been.''
   Among Swedish Match's latest major recent acquisitions are the
$230 million purchase of Wilkinson Sword, a major British producer
of matches, shaving products and household goods, and the $190
million purchase of the West German flooring group Pegulan.
   Those acquisitions are part of what makes the company
attractive, because of the access they offer to the European
Economic Community, Peter Wallenberg said.
   Stora, like other Swedish, Norwegian and Finnish groups, is
eager to expand into the member countries of the trade bloc to
avoid being shut out in 1992 when a single internal market is
scheduled to be created. None of the three belongs to the group.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880309-0395 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 1640EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-UAW-Chrysler Bjt   03-09 0671</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UAW-Chrysler, Bjt,0693</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chrysler Workers Support Early Talks But Questions Remain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. and the United Auto Workers union
could be meeting over a bargaining table as soon as next month if
140 local union leaders meeting here Thursday agree to a request
for early contract talks.
   Local union leaders said Wednesday they favor early talks and
UAW Vice President Marc Stepp has said ``the earlier the better,''
but one issue must be settled first: Will Chrysler also agree to an
early strike deadline?
   ``Our preference would be to actually start the clock ... a real
strike deadline as opposed to an artificial bargaining deadline,''
UAW spokesman Peter Laarman said.
   Chrysler's three-year national contract, which governs wages and
benefits for 71,700 workers, expires Sept. 14. Talks normally would
begin in July, but Chrysler asked for early talks last week.
   Chrysler made the request after it succumbed to UAW pressure and
decided against selling its 28,000-worker Acustar Inc. parts
subsidiary. As an alternative, the company said it would close four
Acustar plants if it could not sell them in the next 18 months.
   Angry workers had threatened a series of plant-by-plant strikes
over local issues and had stopped cooperating in union-management
programs essential to improving quality and production efficiency.
   The No. 3 automaker doesn't appear willing to let the union set
a deadline before Sept. 14, after which workers could legally
strike the company if no settlement were reached, Laarman said.
   Chrysler's chief negotiator and vice president for human
resources, Anthony St. John, told The Detroit News on Tuesday that
the company doesn't want an early strike deadline, but the company
would not comment Wednesday.
   St. John and Stepp both were in Milwaukee on Wednesday for
negotiations on a plant closing agreement for 5,500 workers at the
former American Motors Corp. assembly and stamping plants in
Kenosha, Wis.
   Stepp has said he would recommend early talks when he meets
Thursday with the UAW's national Chrysler bargaining council, which
represents workers at 49 local unions. The council will make its
decision Thursday afternoon.
   Local union leaders said they would support early talks because
it would increase chances of protecting jobs and of ironing out
mounting difficulties in plant-level labor relations.
   ``I'm positive our membership would be 100 percent in favor of
that. As long as we're talking about jobs they would be more than
willing,'' said Fred O'Brien, an official with Local 1264 at
Chrysler's key Sterling Heights stamping plant.
   If talks begin early on the national contract, local unions
would follow suit on plant-level contracts, which govern working
conditions and other issues specific to them, Laarman said.
   Chrysler is expected to agree to the job-protecting pattern
contract established last fall at Ford Motor Co. and General Motors
Corp.
   Chrysler's contract lacks protections included in the GM and
Ford pacts and workers said they want to sign a similar contract as
soon as possible.
   The GM and Ford contracts forbid layoffs except when production
is cut because of slow sales, make it harder for the companies to
move production outside the company or country and forbid plant
closings that were not announced before talks started.
   O'Brien said going to the table early would limit the time
Chrysler has to announce further plant closings and make it easier
for the union to battle the possible closings of the four Acustar
plants.
   In addition, Chrysler already buys the largest percentage of
outside parts of any Big Three maker _ 70 percent compared with 30
percent at GM and about 50 percent at Ford.
   O'Brien said workers are anxious to sign a contract that keeps
Chrysler from moving more parts work to outside non-union ``scab
shops'' or ``we'll all be on welfare.''
   Chrysler also has no profit-sharing program. Stepp said last
week that he would particularly like to see the Ford profit-sharing
formula included in the Chrysler contract.
   Ford workers Tuesday received profit-sharing checks averaging
more than $3,700 from Ford's industry-record 1987 profits of $4.6
billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880309-0396 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 1925EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Grumman     03-09 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Grumman,0301</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Announces 700 Layoffs, Nearly 2,000 Job Eliminations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BETHPAGE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grumman Corp., wounded by defense cutbacks
and the failure to win a major aircraft contract, announced
Wednesday it would lay off 700 employees and eliminate 1,900 more
jobs this year.
   The reductions amount to 7.7 percent of Grumman's 33,700
employees. Of the 700 employees who will be laid off, 600 work on
Long Island. The others work at Grumman facilities in
Milledgeville, Ga., and Stuart and Melbourne, Fla.
   The other job reductions will be made by attrition, coupled with
a cut in the number of part-time and temporary workers. Officials
said 1,700 of those 1,900 jobs are located on Long Island.
   Grumman President John O'Brien, in a letter to employees
published Wednesday, said recent reverses forced the reductions.
   He cited production delays caused by cuts in the defense budget,
and questions about the status of the A-6 plane. Congress must
reconcile the budget, which calls for production of 12 advanced
A-6Fs, and a budget authorization, which calls for production of 11
of the old A-6E planes.
   He also noted that Grumman had lost a competition for a contract
to build the Navy's advanced tactical aircraft. The contract,
valued at more than $4 billion, was won by McDonnell Douglas Corp.
of St. Louis.
   O'Brien noted that other Grumman planes, like the F-14D, E-2C
and EA-6B, will remain in production, and ``we are continuing to
invest millions of dollars in the development of technologies for
future aircraft.''
   ``The airplane business is the backbone of our company, and
we're in it to stay,'' O'Brien insisted.
   Most of the layoffs will occur by the middle of April, with the
remainder spread over the remaining months of this year, the
company said.
</TEXT>
