<1ST_LINE>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   03-09 0503</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0523</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market's recent rally bogged down
Wednesday as blue chips gave up some of their gains from the day
before.
   Smaller issues, however, showed more of the strength they have
been displaying since late last year.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 big-name industrials, up 24.70
points on Tuesday, dropped back 6.80 to 2,074.27.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 4 to 3 on the New
York Stock Exchange, with 872 up, 654 down and 460 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 210.90 million shares, against 237.68
million in the previous session. The NYSE's composite index lost
.14 to 151.48.
   Confidence has continued to spread lately on Wall Street that
the economy remains healthy nearly five months after Black Monday
on Oct. 19.
   In addition, stock prices have been less volatile lately than
they were as recently as early January, suggesting that investors'
mood is less subject to sudden change.
   Analysts say investing institutions have grown more eager to put
some of their cash reserves into stocks, in order to show in their
first-quarter reports to clients that they participated in the
recent market rally.
   Still, many observers wonder how much stock might be for sale at
higher prices by investors sitting with paper losses and waiting
for an opportune time to get out of the market.
   Japanese stocks were mostly higher following a gain in the Tokyo
market. Matsushita Electrical, up 5 at 200}; Honda Motor, up 2} at
129}; Pioneer Electronics, up 1 at 52{, and Sony, up ] at 41], all
hit record highs.
   Facet Enterprises jumped 3] to 27. Prospect Group said it
planned a $26-a-share tender offer for all of the company's stock.
   Johnson & Johnson added 1} to 85\. Analysts said buying was
prompted by renewed enthusiasm over sales prospects for a J&J skin
treatment product that has received considerable publicity of late.
   Losers among the blue chips included International Business
Machines, down 1 at 116|; McDonald's, down ] at 46}; Exxon, down |
at 41~; Ford Motor, down | at 45[, and Eastman Kodak, down } at 42~.
   Charles Schwab Corp., a discount brokerage firm that recently
announced an increase in commission rates, rose { to 9{. Schwab
stock traded as high as 17 after the company went public last
September, and as low as 5} in the wake of the crash.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market increased $0.69 billion, or 0.03
percent, in value.
   Nationwide turnover in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in
those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter
market, totaled 240.13 million shares.
   Standard & Poor's index of 400 industrials rose .04 to 312.46,
and S&P's 500-stock composite index was down .37 at 269.06.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
gained 3.35 to 380.28. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index closed at 299.58, up 3.54.
