<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Women-Management 1stLd-Writethru   03-09 0596</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Women-Management, 1st Ld-Writethru,0613</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wharton Study Says Women's Leadership Patterns Changing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS 3rd graf by rewording to include men and women in
the responses; picks up 4th graf: Webber studied...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE OWEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Women business students are more eager for
leadership positions than they were in the 1970s and men are more
likely to accept the change, a Wharton School study concludes.
   ``The improvement in relations between the sexes is dramatic,''
Ross A. Webber, management professor at the elite Pennsylvania
business school, wrote for the latest issue of Human Resources
Management journal of the University of Michigan business school.
   He acknowledged, however, that the improvement apparent from
responses about the roles of women in mixed-gender study groups may
be slightly suspect because of 1980s expectations about men's
attitudes toward women.
   Webber studied behavior of men and women business graduate
students at the Wharton and Columbia schools in group projects from
1969-75 and at Wharton from 1980-84.
   ``Women are much more likely to exercise leadership whether in
the majority or the minority; conflict levels have sharply declined
on predominantly female teams; and males appear to be much less
threatened when working with women,'' Webber wrote.
   ``Clearly significant social change has occurred during the 10
years separating the two investigations.''
   The study examined four-person study groups formed from 420
students in the 1969-75 period and 268 in the later period. Course
instructors gave neither leader designations nor instructions on
how to organize to perform assigned tasks.
   Of the 688 students overall, 120 were in groups of four males,
392 in groups of three males and one female, 164 in groups of three
females and one male and 12 in groups of four females.
   In the male-majority groups, 51 percent of the men claimed to be
leaders, compared with 13 percent of the women, in the earlier
sample. By the 1980s, the disparity disappeared, with 57 percent of
the men and 61 percent of the women claiming to be group leaders.
   Group members' ideas toward others also changed, with the
percentage of men being called leaders falling from 48 to 36, and
the percentage of women considered group leaders rising from 7 to
56.
   ``The results suggest that when working with women, men feel
less compelled to play the macho, dominating role,'' Webber said.
   Among women in female-majority groups, claims of being the
leader rose from 35 percent to 61 percent over the decade. In the
1970s, all 21 men in those female-dominated groups considered
himself the group's leader, but in the 1980s, 70 percent claimed
that status.
   Leadership status in those groups was attributed to the sole
male member 83 percent of the time in the 1970s, falling to 60
percent in the 1980s. As women's views of themselves as leaders
rose to 61 percent in the 1980s, the perceptions by all group
members of other women as leaders fell from 53 percent to 35
percent.
   ``Women appear to be much more willing to compete for
leadership, even as a lone female on a predominantly male team,''
Webber wrote.
   Webber cautioned that expected attitudes may have influenced
some men's responses in his most recent sample.
   ``Even among our younger male graduate students, with their
appearance of greater comfort with mixed sex teams, one can ask
whether actual behavior has changed as much as claims and
attributions,'' Webber said.
   ``For example, today it may not be as permissible for a male to
be critical of female behavior as in the past, so the 1980s
questionnaire responses could be a bit suspect.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
