<1ST_LINE>u f AM-OilMeetings     03-09 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Oil Meetings,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Non-OPEC Producers Meet To Debate Price Strategy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of non-OPEC oil producers met in London Wednesday to
debate moves to halt plunging prices, while members of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries considered similar
talks.
   Results of the London session weren't disclosed, but oil prices
edged upward in response to hopes that producing nations inside and
outside of the cartel would move quickly to stem the recent erosion
of the market.
   The meeting of non-OPEC officials was called by Egypt and was
held at the Mexican Embassy in London, even though Britain, which
rejects group pricing policies for its North Sea oil, wasn't
invited.
   Another European producer, Norway, declined to attend.
   Apart from Egypt, the other invited participants were the Soviet
Union, China, Angola, Malaysia, Brunei, Oman, Mexico and Colombia.
   ``The meeting is at expert level with no ministers involved,''
said a Mexican official, who declined to be identified. ``They just
want to talk about the situation in the market, although obviously
they are not in any position to take a decision.''
   Oil prices have declined by an average of about 20 percent over
the past few weeks amid reports of production excesses and price
discounting by OPEC members.
   On Tuesday, Egyptian oil minister Abdel-Hady Kandil said the
London meeting was not aimed against the 13-nation cartel, ``but is
an attempt by non-OPEC producers to help save the world oil market
from further deterioration.''
   There also was continued speculation that OPEC would convene its
own emergency meeting. Venezuela initiated calls for such a
conference, which were supported by Saudia Arabia and Indonesia,
among others. But sources said the Saudis preferred to hold
preliminary, informal talks to set an agenda for a meeting.
   Nigeria, whose oil minister Rilwanu Lukman is president of OPEC,
has yet to respond to the proposal. Sources said it was unlikely a
date would be set before Nigeria replied.
   The pricing committee is empowered by OPEC to hold an emergency
meeting of all 13 members of the cartel when prices drop
dramatically below the official price of $18 per barrel.
   The price slide was interrupted when reports of official concern
surfaced Tuesday. On the New York Mercantile Exchange Wednesday,
contracts for April delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the U.S.
benchmark crude oil, settled at $15.49 per 42-gallon barrel, up 4
cents from the Tuesday close. The contract had gained 8 cents
Monday.
</TEXT>
