<1ST_LINE>u f AM-NorthwestAirlines     03-09 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Northwest Airlines,0392</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Northwest Will Impose Contract With Flight Attendants</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY LAURA WILKINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EAGAN, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northwest Airlines said Wednesday it would
impose a contract on the carrier's 6,700 flight attendants April 1,
despite a stalemate over wage demands that nearly triggered a
strike last month.
   Northwest said a provision of the Railway Labor Act allowed it
to implement contract changes unilaterally following a 30-day
cooling-off period that ended Feb. 26.
   Flight attendants have voted to strike since then, but have
continued to work while pursuing negotiations with the airline
through their Teamsters union local.
   Union spokesman Jeffrey Musto said he had no immediate comment
on the airline's latest move because Teamsters lawyers were still
studying it.
   Terry Erskine, the airline's vice president of law and labor
relations, said the contract did not include a union proposal to
limit the number of years needed to elevate attendants to higher
salary levels.
   The main obstacle to reaching an agreement between the airline
and the Teamsters union local representing the attendants has been
a demand by the union to raise lower-paid B-scale attendants to
A-scale wages.
   Northwest has proposed extending the B-scale from five years to
eight years, meaning lower-wage flight attendants would have to
wait an additional three years before earning top-scale wages.
   But B-scale flight attendants say the airline is trying to break
a promise that they would earn A-scale wages after five years.
   The union also has objected to two-tier wage agreements, saying
they pit junior workers against senior workers.
   The issue has intensified since Northwest acquired Republic
Airlines in 1986. Roughly one-third of the 2,600 Republic
attendants work for B-scale wages and the other two-thirds have
said they wouldn't get enough out of Northwest's latest wage offer.
   Erskine told a news conference Wednesday that there are some
changes in the contract that will be imposed April 1, but they are
minor.
   Under the contract proposal that will be implemented, the
entry-level wage will go from more than $13,000 a year to $15,000 a
year and the top base wage will go from the current $32,000 up to
$35,000 a year, Erskine said.
   Erskine said the airline has not talked with the union about its
plan to impose the contract.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
