<DOCNO> AP880309-0405 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 2049EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Douglas-MD-11     03-09 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Douglas-MD-11,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Douglas Begins Assembly of New Generation Jumbo Jet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONG BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McDonnell Douglas Corp. executives,
using a symbolic gold-plated rivet, Wednesday began assembly of the
first MD-11, the company's entry into a fierce competition to
provide a new generation of jetliners.
   The action soothed concerns that were expressed about whether
the new airliner would ever get off the ground after the company
earlier this year scaled back the number of orders it had received
for the plane.
   During a ceremony at the company's Douglas Aircraft Co. plant in
Long Beach, Douglas President James Worsham announced that two more
carriers had ordered a total of six MD-11s. Identity of the new
carriers wasn't disclosed.
   The new orders brought the total to 16 customers and 99 of the
jetliners, which sell for between $90 million and $100 million
each. If all the planes are purchased, it would create $9.9 billion
in revenue for Douglas, a division of St. Louis-based McDonnell
Douglas.
   Douglas spokesman Don Hanson said Wednesday that 31 of the
orders are firm, 45 are conditional or options and 23 are listed as
``reserves,'' which the company defines as falling into ``various
categories of intent to acquire the airplane.''
   The MD-11 is a roomier, longer-range and more fuel-efficient
version of its current jumbo jet, the DC-10.
   However, the MD-11 faces a tough fight with Seattle-based Boeing
Co. and the Airbus Industrie, the European consortium, to provide
the new generation of passenger jetliners in what is likely to be a
shrinking market.
   Analysts say there is room in that market for only two
manufacturers and it is a toss-up as to which will survive.
   In what is generally seen as a weakness for the MD-11, the maker
has yet to land an order from a domestic commercial passenger
airline. The only domestic order it has received is from Federal
Express, the parcel-delivery service.
</TEXT>
