<HEAD>Toolmaker Rejects Offer to Enter Talks In a Takeover Cease-Fire</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to recast, CLARIFY that Black & Decker
characterized proposed standstill agreement, UPDATE with further
American Standard response, closing stock prices, edit to tighten.
No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOWSON, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Black & Decker Corp. on Wednesday refused to
enter talks proposed by its target American Standard Inc. over the
toolmaker's $2.26 billion hostile buyout offer.
   Black & Decker said American Standard had asked it to enter into
a standstill and confidentiality agreement under which it would
provide Black & Decker with non-public corporate information.
   Such an agreement would prohibit Black & Decker from taking
additional action to pursue its hostile bid for the New York-based
plumbing and air conditioning maker.
   Nolan D. Archibald, Black & Decker chairman and chief executive,
called the conditions of the proposal ``excessively restrictive and
totally unacceptable.''
   He said Black & Decker would continue to ``pursue aggressively''
its $73-a-share bid.
   American Standard rose 37{ cents to $73.37{ a share on the New
York Stock Exchange. Black & Decker rose 25 cents to $18 in heavy
trading.
   American Standard on Tuesday announced it would continue
developing a recapitalization plan aimed at thwarting Black &
Decker's hostile buyout offer, but said it expected to engage in
discussions and negotiations with Black & Decker and other
potential acquirers.
   On Wednesday, American Standard denied asking for a standstill
agreement, saying it only sought to uphold ``shareholder values.''
   ``We have just requested that they not drop their tender offer
and conduct a street sweep...thereby preempting higher bids for the
company,'' said spokeswoman Linda King. ``We were puzzled to see
Black & Decker's release. We are trying to pursue a reasonable
course and are talking to Black & Decker's legal counsel to resolve
the situation.''
   In a street sweep, a bidder tries to gain a controlling interest
in a target company by buying huge blocks of the target company's
stock rapidly in regular market transactions.
   In a prepared statement, Black & Decker said it had a right to
the same information on the same terms that American Standard had
made available to third parties supporting the recapitalization.
   Those parties include banks who have agreed to let American
Standard borrow nearly $2 billion to finance its plan and Emerson
Electric Co., which has agreed to buy $160 million in American
Standard junk bonds.
   Thomas T. Taylor, president of Towson-based Chesapeake
Securities Research Corp., said American Standard was trying to buy
time to find a ``white knight'' friendly suitor in proposing a
truce with Black & Decker.
   On Friday, Black & Decker sweetened its offer for the fourth
time _ to $2.33 billion _ just hours after American Standard had
increased its own competing offer to shareholders.
   American Standard said Monday it would pursue other ways to
boost its recapitalization plan before it accepted Black & Decker's
takeover bid.
   Analysts estimate the American Standard plan, paying
shareholders a combination of cash, debt, and stock in the
recapitalized company, is worth slightly more than $2 billion.
</TEXT>
